<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PoliceTrial     06-30 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Trial,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opening Arguments Begin in Boston Police Corruption Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven past or present detectives went on trial
Thursday on charges of extorting money and favors from nightclubs
and restaurants, with the defense arguing they did little more than
accept gifts from friends.
   In return for the alleged payoffs, the officers are accused of
having fixed citations, overlooked violations, protected
establishments from inspections and and received money for details
that were never performed.
   Prosecutor Diane Kottmyer, in opening arguments in U.S. District
Court, called the detectives greedy and shameless in their
shakedowns and were almost flamboyant in the favors they provided
for powerful friends.
   Kottmyer said former Detective Thomas J. Connolly arranged for
employees of Cafe Budapest to be taken to make their nightly bank
deposits in police vehicles free of charge.
   In return, Kottmyer said, Connolly dined with friends at Cafe
Budapest and ``at the conclusion of his meal, no bill would be
paid.'' Connolly ``would be seen just strolling out of the
restaurant,'' she said.
   Attorney Robert Muse, representing retired Detective Francis X.
Sheehan, described his client as a ``damn fine cop'' whose
``deeply-rooted'' friendships with some club owners resulted in
gifts, not payoffs.
   The detectives are charged with 50 counts of conspiracy, bribery
and extortion. They are accused of extorting favors and $18,000 in
money from 1975 to 1986.
   Besides Sheehan and Connolly, the defendants are former
Detectives John E. Carey and Peter Boylan and Detectives John F.
McCormick, Kenneth J. Nave and Matthew A. Kilroe.
</TEXT>
