<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presser     06-30 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presser Reported Alert, Undergoing Tests in Cardiac Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters union President Jackie Presser,
battling cancer, was described as alert and breathing on his own as
he underwent tests in a hospital's cardiac care unit.
   Presser, 61, was listed in serious condition Wednesday night at
Lakewood Hospital in suburban Cleveland, said hospital spokesman
David Hopcraft. He was admitted Tuesday after complaining of
weakness and dizziness.
   ``Further treatment will be determined after the conclusion and
interpretation of the tests,'' Hopcraft said. Presser has been able
to communicate with doctors, nurses and his family, the spokesman
said.
   Presser had a brain tumor removed May 17 at the Barrow
Neurological Institute in Phoenix, Ariz., and later was treated for
a smaller tumor affecting his pituitary gland.
   Three weeks ago, a federal judge, citing Presser's health,
delayed the union leader's July 12 embezzlement and racketeering
trial in U.S. District Court here.
   The charges allege that Presser took $700,000 from his Cleveland
local's union office and paid it to ``ghost'' employees who
performed no work.
</TEXT>
