<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Farmworker-Pesticides     06-30 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farmworker-Pesticides,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposed New Rules Deal With Farmworker Exposure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New rules proposed by the Environmental
Protection Agency to protect farmworkers from pesticides are
satisfying neither farm owners nor labor groups concerned about
when sprayed fields can be re-entered safely.
   Shelly Davis, an attorney for the Migrant Legal Action Program,
said Wednesday she will submit comments so critical of the plan
they will ``burn up the page.''
   Mark Maslyn, pesticide specialist for the American Farm Bureau
Federation, said the new rules still had ``problem areas that
hopefully will be addressed'' in the 90-day public comment period
starting with publication sometime next week.
   The new regulations, 55 pages accompanied by 220 pages of
explanation, would replace a one-page regulation in effect since
1974. They cover pesticides that have not yet been the subject of
specific worker regulations in EPA's review of all 650 active
pesticide ingredients.
   Compliance by farmers and manufacturers could cost $170 million
in the first year and less after that, EPA said. The average grain
farm would have to spend an estimated $167 in the first year, the
average vegetable farm $611 and the average greenhouse $3,515.
   Louis True, head of program management and support in EPA's
pesticide program, told reporters Wednesday that a reduction of
one-half percent to 1 percent in poisonings would make the cost
worthwhile. He did not explain the calculation.
   Estimates of poisonings have ranged from 12,000 up to 300,000.
   Some 2.5 million farmworkers could be affected by the proposals
if they take effect as expected next year, including about 300,000
not now covered in commercial forestry, greenhouses and nurseries.
Exemptions would apply for home use, non-commercial forest use, as
by a park agency, use on rights of way, use in research and for
chemicals injected directly into plant tissue.
   Major provisions of the new regulations establish general
re-entry intervals during which no one normally may enter fields
after spraying.
   For the most toxic pesticides, the field would be closed for 48
hours, warning placards would have to be posted and oral warnings
would be required for any workers on that farm.
   Other provisions deal with the legal responsibility for
accidents and require the farmer to see to it that any contractors
hired are aware of the rules. Still others specify warnings that
must be given, emergency equipment that must be kept on hand,
protective clothing that must be worn and when blood tests for
professional pesticide applicators must be undertaken.
   Ms. Davis faulted the agency for using only acute toxicity to
set re-entry levels, ignoring chronic effects such as cancer. ``I
would establish a long interval for anything that's an actual or
suspected carcinogen in animals _ like a week,'' she said.
   A requirement that the oral warnings contain information on the
medical effects of exposure would sharpen workers' and farmers'
concern about their own health, she said.
   Maslyn said he feared that the re-entry intervals could not be
enforced against farmers anxious to get their crops to market.
   Some provisions of the regulations appear to hold the farmer
responsible for accidents even if a worker has refused to use
safety equipment, he said.
   ``I don't know what you do'' about a provision forbidding
farmers to require workers to work in chemical-resistant suits when
it is too hot, he said. ``There's a potential for abuse there.''
   ``It's been our concern all through this that they don't have
specific hard information that shows we have a problem with
re-entry levels and it needs to be fixed in this way,'' Maslyn said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Long-RangeForecast Bjt   06-30 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Long-Range Forecast, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Cheer in Store for Dry Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH. E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hot, dry weather plaguing America is
likely to shift East and South in the next month, and forecasters
offer little hope that the widespread drought will be broken.
   The 90-day outlook issued by the National Weather Service on
Wednesday does indicate a chance of more rain than normal in some
western sections of the Great Plains by the end of September.
   But in the nearer term, the watchwords were for more of the same
weather that has been parching fields and reservoirs, stalling
river traffic and baking crops and livestock.
   The 6- to 10-day outlook is ``very close to holding stationary
the pattern of the last few weeks,'' Donald L. Gilman, head of the
Long Range Predictions Group at the National Weather Service, said
at a news conference.
   And the 30-day prediction shows ``only subtle changes,'' Gilman
added.
   ``Unfortunately, reliable predictions of the drought's end, its
geographic spread, or changes in severity, cannot be made today,''
the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration cautioned in an
accompanying statement.
   The agency noted that while the current drought is severe, it is
not yet comparable to the damaging dry spells of the 1950s and
1930s. This dry period is ``neither unprecedented nor unexpected
from a climatological perspective,'' the agency said.
   Nonetheless, Dr. Michael Hudlow, director of hydrology for the
weather service, said: ``It's likely to get worse before it gets
better.''
   The river level at Memphis, Tenn., where Mississippi barge
traffic is already stalled, could drop another foot in the next 10
days, he warned.
   High-altitude jet stream winds that normally sweep across the
northern tier of states have split, to the north and south, Gilman
said, holding the drought conditions in place between them.
   Gilman's 6- to 10-day outlook calls for much above normal
temperatures in Montana, Wyoming, the Dakotas, Nebraska, Wisconsin
and Iowa.
   In addition, above normal readings are expected in much of the
rest of the nation except the Columbia River valley, West Texas and
along the Atlantic Coast from North Carolina through Georgia and
northern Florida.
   In the short range the rain forecast is ``patchy'' said Gilman.
He said no precipitation is likely in Oregon, California, Nevada,
southern Idaho, western Utah, western Arizona and Texas.
   There is a chance of some scattered moisture from the Gulf of
Mexico causing rain here and there in the Midwest, but only Kansas,
South Carolina and Georgia seem likely to have more rain than
normal for the period.
   In July, above normal heat is expected throughout most of the
northern Plains and upper Midwest, Gilman said, while the outlook
for rain is ``very uncertain.''
   The greatest chance of hot weather is in Illinois, Indiana,
Ohio, Kentucky and Tennessee, Gilman said. He gave that region a 65
percent chance of being hotter than normal for July, an unusually
high ranking for a summer forecast. Typically, the 30-day outlooks
are considered only 55 percent likely in summer.
   In addition, July has a chance of warmer than normal weather
from Pennsylvania west through the Great Lakes states to Montana,
south to Oklahoma and Arkansas and east to the Appalachian
Mountains.
   The rest of the country should expect near normal readings in
July except the Puget Sound region, where is it expected to be
cooler than normal.
   The outlook for rain in July shows below normal precipitation
expected for California, Michigan, Illinois, Indiana, Ohio and
Kentucky. Above normal is expected only in Puget Sound and along
the Arizona-New Mexico border.
   Other regions are likely to be close to normal, Gilman said,
with the added warning that the below normal region could expand
back into the plains.
   If this were earlier in the year, he would have predicted a
larger dry area, Gilman said, but there may be breaks in the jet
stream which could allow some rain to move north from the Gulf of
Mexico.
   Finally, he issued a long-range 90-day forecast for July, August
and September.
   That outlook anticipates above normal temperatures along the
Pacific Coast, in southern Arizona and in Iowa, Missouri, Arkansas,
Louisiana, Illinois, Indiana, Ohio, Pennsylvania, West Virginia,
Kentucky, Tennessee, Virginia, Maryland, Delaware, the Carolinas,
Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia and Florida.
   Below normal temperatures are expected in Idaho, Montana,
Wyoming, Colorado, Utah and New Mexico, with near normal readings
elsewhere.
   The three-month rain outlook is for below normal in California,
Maryland, Virginia, the Carolinas, Georgia and parts of West
Virginia, Tennessee and Kentucky.
   The lone bit of good news may be the chance of above normal
precipitation for Montana, Wyoming, southern South Dakota,
Nebraska, Kansas, Colorado, New Mexico, West Texas and western
Oklahoma over the 90 days.
   For the rest of the nation, the chances are too close to call
over such a long period.
</TEXT>
