<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Democrats-Veep Bjt   06-30 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats-Veep, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegates Appear Content To Let Dukakis Call The Shots On Running
Mate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's contention that he deserves to
be offered the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket is supported by
few Democratic National Convention delegates other than those
pledged to support him for president, an Associated Press survey
found.
   Other delegates appear content to let Michael Dukakis pick his
own running mate.
   ``Dukakis won fair and square, and it's his call,'' said Joseph
Courtney, a Dukakis delegate from Connecticut.
   Roughly half the delegates surveyed said they had no preference
for the No. 2 spot on the party's ticket, while the other half
scattered their support among nearly three dozen potential
candidates, mostly favorite sons.
   Many of those responding to the survey said they were willing to
go along with whomever Dukakis asks to join him on the ticket.
   ``It's entirely up to Michael Dukakis to make those choices,''
said Laura Past, a delegate and Democratic National Committee
member from Nevada.
   The delegates will be asked to ratify Dukakis' choice on the
final night of the four-day convention.
   Nearly all of Jackson's vice presidential support is coming from
delegates pledged to support him for president, according to the AP
survey.
   Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn and Jackson drew the most support in the
survey, followed by Sens. John Glenn of Ohio and Albert J. Gore Jr.
of Tennessee. Further back were Sens. Bill Bradley of New Jersey,
Dale Bumpers of Arkansas and Lloyd Bentsen of Texas.
   AP bureaus throughout the United States are polling all 4,161
delegates to the Democratic National Convention, which opens July
18 in Atlanta. With replies tabulated from more than 1,300 of those
delegates thus far, the trend was clear: The delegates are not
looking at anyone in particular.
   ``Dukakis, by winning more delegates than Jackson, has earned
the right to select whomever he wants, regardless of how any of the
other candidates did in the process,'' said Maine delegate John
Diamond, who backs Glenn.
   Of those tabulated, 611 said they had no preference when asked
whom they supported for the vice presidential nomination, and 174
supported Nunn, who said Wednesday he told Dukakis he is not
interested in the job.
   Jackson was named as vice presidential choice by 148 delegates,
132 of whom already were supporting him for president.
   Jackson has said that because of his second-place finish in the
race for the presidential nomination, he deserves to be offered the
No. 2 spot on the ticket. He has not said whether he would accept
the post if it is offered.
   But Jackson's argument found little support outside his own
delegates.
   ``I think that Dukakis needs someone who has foreign policy or
national experience and I don't think Jackson has either,'' Maine
delegate Dana Trattner said.
   However, Lawrence Lewis, a Jackson delegate from Vermont, said
the vice presidential spot on the ticket should be offered to
Jackson ``because in the last 10 years, Jackson has done more to
bring back enthusiasm ... than any other candidate _ the small
person with little or no voice.''
   But support for Jackson is not universal, even among his own
delegates.
   Barbara Maddox, a Jackson delegate from Michigan, said she is
still undecided about who should fill the second spot on the
Democratic ticket but is sure that it should not be offered
automatically to Jackson.
   ``Tradition has been that the presidential nominee of the party
selects his running mate,'' Ms. Maddox said. ``I think it should
continue that way at least for this convention. If they want to
change the rules, they should do it at the beginning of the game,
but they've got to start a new game next year.''
   ``I don't think he should be the vice presidential nominee,''
Tom Mason, a Dukakis delegate from Oregon, said of Jackson. ``I
think we would lose the South.''
   And Lawrence Katz, a Dukakis delegate from Arizona, said Jackson
should be denied the spot on the ticket because of a Jewish
backlash over a 1984 remark in which he referred to New York as
``Hymietown'' and his past association with Nation of Islam leader
Louis Farrakhan.
   Dukakis spent Wednesday on Capitol Hill, talking to senators,
some of whom are potential running mates.
   Among the tabulated delegate replies, Glenn was supported for
the vice presidential spot by 114 delegates, while 94 backed Gore.
Bumpers and Bradley were supported by 28 and 31, respectively, and
Bentsen had 25.
   Dukakis himself was listed as the vice presidential choice of 28
delegates. Twenty-seven of them were Jackson supporters.
</TEXT>
