<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Kean-Keynote Bjt   06-30 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kean-Keynote, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Keynote Speaker Better Known For His Politics Than
Oratory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The keynote speaker for the Republican
National Convention isn't known as a fiery orator. He stuttered so
badly as a child that he used to break into a cold sweat when he
was called on in class. And he has a hybrid New Jersey-New England
accent that earns him a good deal of ribbing.
   But New Jersey Gov. Thomas H. Kean will be in the spotlight
nonetheless at the GOP convention Aug. 15 in New Orleans, selected
from among hundred of other prominent Republicans.
   ``I am flattered by the honor, excited about the opportunity,
and a bit humbled,'' Kean said during a news conference to announce
he was accepting the offer from Vice President George Bush, the
expected Republican presidential nominee.
   ``I am going to go back home, I guess, sit for awhile and think
about what I am going to say,'' the governor said.
   Republican Party sources had told The Associated Press on
Tuesday that Kean had been picked to give the leadoff speech at the
convention. Kean said he was told of his selection on Tuesday, and
that Bush called him Wednesday to thank him for accepting.
   Bush called the governor ``one of the nation's most respected
leaders of either party.''
   ``We are extremely excited that the same voice of leadership
that has inspired the people of New Jersey will be in New Orleans
to send our troops out into battle,'' said Bush, in a statement
released by Kean's office.
   Kean's selection provoked at least one Republican, however. New
Hampshire Sen. Gordon Humphrey, the Senate's leading opponent of
legalized abortion, threatened to stage a convention walkout if a
right-to-life partisan doesn't get equal time.
   Humphrey said Kean is ``an outspoken advocate of abortion.''
Aides to the New Jersey governor say Kean is personally opposed to
abortion, but does not support a constitutional ban, something
Humphrey has long sought.
   Kean spokesman John Samerjan said the governor would not comment
on Humphrey's complaint.
   Kean gained national prominence after his lopsided re-election
gubernatorial victory in 1985. He captured nearly 60 percent of the
black vote and two-thirds of the blue-collar vote.
   When asked the reason for the landslide victory in an industrial
northeastern state, Kean uttered the four-word dogma for which his
political autobiography is named _ ``the politics of inclusion.''
   Kean has long urged the Republican Party to expand its appeal
beyond its traditional bloc of supporters _ the affluent, and
middle-class whites _ to groups normally aligned with Democrats
such as blacks, Hispanics, other minorities, the poor and the
blue-collar community.
   Kean said that over the next several weeks he will be developing
themes and ideas for his speech and will draw upon the expertise of
close aides and other Republicans.
   But he got a bit of encouragement from someone on the other side
of the political aisle _ New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, who delivered a
much-acclaimed keynote address at the 1984 Democratic National
Convention. Kean said he received a congratulatory call from Cuomo
on Wednesday.
   Kean noted, however, that he felt no pressure to measure up to
Cuomo's rousing speech to Democrats in 1984, a monumental address
that brought Cuomo into the national spotlight.
   ``Mario Cuomo is a better speaker than I am,'' said Kean. ``But
I'll do my best. What I want to do, obviously, is present a message
and do what I can to help George Bush and the party. ... You've got
to do your own speech.''
   Born into one of New Jersey's most distinguished families, Kean
wrote in his autobiography of a lonely childhood and a stuttering
problem so bad that it was an ordeal to speak up when he was called
on in school.
   He graduated from Princeton University and holds a graduate
degree from Columbia University. He taught prep school, served as a
camp director and was president of a real estate company before
entering political life in 1968, when he served the first of 10
consecutive years in the state assembly. Kean was speaker of the
House in 1972 and 1973 and was elected governor in 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
