<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Humphrey-GOPConvention     06-30 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Humphrey-GOP Convention,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator, Angered by Keynote Selection, Threatens GOP Convention
Walkout</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Kean-Keynote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, protesting the selection
of New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean as keynote speaker at the Republican
National Convention, is threatening to stage a walkout unless a
right-to-life partisan gets equal time.
   Humphrey, the Senate's leading opponent of legalized abortion,
said the selection of Kean to give the high-profile,
convention-opening address was ``a terrible mistake, a blunder, an
affront to the right-to-life movement.''
   Humphrey said Kean is ``an outspoken advocate of abortion.''
Aides to the New Jersey governor say Kean is personally opposed to
abortion, but does not support a constitutional ban, something
Humphrey has long sought.
   Kean spokesman John Samerjan said the governor would not comment
on Humphrey's complaint.
   Humphrey said Vice President George Bush, the Republican
nominee-apparent, also needs to ``assure us that his vice
presidential running mate will be someone who shares George Bush's
opposition to abortion.''
   The New Hampshire senator said it was up to the Bush campaign to
settle the dispute before the convention, which opens Aug. 15 in
New Orleans.
   ``I'm going to try to organize a walkout from the convention
during the governor's speech unless between now and then the Bush
campaign seeks to make amends for this affront,'' said Humphrey,
who is a delegate to the convention.
   Humphrey said he wasn't opposed to Kean being allowed to speak
at the convention, but objected to his giving the major address.
``He's done an outstanding job as governor,'' Humphrey said, but
``it's a colossal blunder to have him give the keynote speech.''
   ``I think this decision is just another further indication of
the inability of the Bush campaign to understand the kind of
coalition it must put together if it hopes to have the support of
conservative Republicans and Democrats,'' Humphrey said.
   ``I've spoken to about a dozen members of the Senate and the
House who are very upset,'' Humphrey said.
   ``There is incredulity that George Bush would choose an even ...
more-blueblood figure than he is,'' Humphrey added, noting Kean's
aristocratic background.
   Kean, the son of a congressman and grandson of a senator,
attended prep school and graduated from Princeton University before
becoming a banker and teacher.
</TEXT>
