<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SexualHarassment-Feds Bjt   06-30 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sexual Harassment-Feds, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Sexual Harassment `Pervasive' In Federal Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Over half the female State Department
employees in a survey said they were harassed sexually at work,
giving the department the worst record in a study of the problem in
the federal workplace.
   But the department is by no means alone in having a dismal
record. The survey by the U.S. Merit Systems Protection Board said
sexual harassment is ``pervasive, costly and systemic'' in the
federal workplace.
   In a report issued Wednesday, the board said 42 percent of women
and 14 percent of men who responded to its survey of federal
employees experienced some form of sexual harassment from May 1985
to May 1987. That figure was virtually identical to findings in the
board's 1980 survey.
   The board, an independent, quasi-judicial agency that decides
federal employee appeals from personnel actions, found that the
problem cost the United States an estimated $267 million over the
two-year period in paying sick leave to employees who missed work,
replacing employees who left their jobs and in reduced individual
and group productivity.
   However, the report noted that the respondents generally did not
consider the problem any worse in the federal government than in
the private sector.
   ``I don't think the federal government is somehow a hotbed of
sexual harassment that stands out from the rest of the country. ...
This is a problem in the rest of the country,'' John M. Palguta,
the project supervisor, said in an interview.
   The survey was sent in March 1987 to a representative sample of
about 13,000 full-time permanent federal workers, and 8,523
employees responded.
   Palguta said the survey was checked carefully to make sure those
who responded were representative, and did not, for example,
represent a high percentage of people who had reported problems.
   The survey found that the State Department had the highest
percentage _ 52 percent _ of women respondents who said they
experienced some form of uninvited sexual attention. The Veterans
Administration had the highest percentage of men respondents _ 21
percent _ claiming sexual harassment.
   The Department of Health and Human Services had the lowest
percentage of women respondents who claimed harassment, 29 percent,
and NASA had the lowest percentage of men who said they were
harassed, 10 percent.
   A wide range of behavior was considered to be sexual harassment.
It was generally viewed as uninvited and unwanted attention,
including: letters, telephone calls or materials of a sexual
nature; touching; sexually suggestive looks or gestures; pressure
for sexual favors or dates; sexual jokes or questions; actual or
attempted assault or rape.
   The most frequently experienced type of uninvited attention is
``unwanted sexual teasing, jokes, remarks or questions,'' the
report said.
   Women were more likely than men to be victims. They were likely
to be working in a non-traditional job in a predominantly male
environment, have some college education, be single or divorced and
between the ages of 20 and 44. Male victims were more likely to be
divorced or separated, age 20 to 44, in clerical or trainee
positions in a predominantly female work group.
   The board said victims are most often harassed by co-workers and
by people of the opposite sex. Twenty-two percent of male victims,
however, reported in the 1980 survey that they were harassed by one
or more men. The question was not asked in the 1987 survey.
   Only 5 percent of both female and male victims said they took
some kind of formal action, usually in the form of requesting an
investigation by the employing agency.
   The report recommended that federal agencies and departments
provide training on sexual harassment to all employees, quickly and
thoroughly investigate allegations, and exercise strong sanctions
against offenders. Existing guidelines detailing specific
prohibited practices and penalties should be updated annually, the
report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Ethiopia-US     06-30 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethiopia-US,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Skeptical Of Ethiopian Call For Better Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopian leader Mengistu Haire
Mariam has renewed a call for improved relations with the United
States, but U.S. diplomats are skeptical of the offer.
   Mengistu, who transformed pro-Western Ethiopia into a Marxist
state after the military toppled Emperor Haile Selassie in 1974,
told a May news conference: ``We are not really pleased with our
relations with the United States. We will do everything of our best
to improve relations. I am sincere ... about this.''
   But U.S. Charge d'Affaires James Cheek, referring to a series of
such overtures in the past three years, said, ``It's been a history
of occasional words and no action.''
   ``Words are always welcome. But they don't get you far if they
are not accompanied by actions.''
   U.S. officials said that Mengistu, at short notice, canceled
planned meetings three times in the past six months with Chester
Crocker, the U.S. assistant secretary of state for African affairs.
   In the latest incident, Crocker was at Frankfurt airport in
January, awaiting a flight for Addis Ababa, when the Ethiopians
said the meeting was off.
   An angry Crocker told Voice of America: ``President Mengistu and
his Politburo are not interested in pursuing the possibilities of
broadening their international options and are quite comfortable
where they are _ out of step with the rest of Africa, but in a cozy
relationship with the Soviets and the Cubans.''
   Some diplomats based in Addis Ababa believe Mengistu may face
opposition from hard-liners in his government who prefer to see
even greater distance between Addis Ababa and Washington.
   Ethiopia has close ties with the Soviet Union, and receives
substantial military aid from Moscow in the government's battles
against separatist guerrillas. It is the only African nation with
Soviet combat troops. It also has 2,500 Cuban soldiers.
   Under Haile Selassie's rule, the United States was Ethiopia's
firmest foreign friend.
   Today, the United States is a vocal critic of Mengistu's Marxist
reforms and his failure effectively to come to terms with rebel
uprisings and persistent food shortages.
   ``We are not saying (for them to) give up relations with the
Soviet Union,'' said Cheek in an interview, ``but we are saying
pursue a truly nationalist and non-aligned policy.''
   Ethiopian leaders resent the branding of their country as a
client state of Moscow. Neutral diplomats contend Mengistu is
fiercely independent-minded, but grudgingly forced to embrace the
Soviets to fight off guerrilla armies seeking autonomy or
independence in Eritrea and Tigre provinces.
   In his news conference last month, Mengistu's tone toward the
United States wavered from anger to admiration.
   ``Simple hatred,'' he asserted at one point, might have prompted
Washington to label Ethiopia a communist country.
   But he also declared: ``We have respect and admiration for the
American people ... Once upon a time, we were close friends.''
   The once-warm relations between Washington and Addis Ababa
deteriorated when the Soviet Union became Ethiopia's biggest patron
in 1977.
   Washington suspended development aid and downgraded its
diplomatic representative from ambassador to a charge d'affaires.
   There was little contact until the 1984-1985 famine, when the
United States was the biggest donor of emergency food to the
nation. This year, Washington again is the biggest donor, as a
drought threatens more than 7 million Ethiopians, nearly half of
them in the war-torn north.
   There has been friction over the delivery of food supplies,
however, with Washington accusing Mengistu of trying to keep food
from reaching the northern rebels, and the United States diverting
some supplies for Ethiopia to Sudan, for distribution by rebel
organizations.
   Cheek believes that despite the acrimony, the two countries
could begin a rapprochement.
   ``At least we could talk about getting the legal obstacles out
of the way, though the policy obstacles would stick,'' said Cheek.
``The Angolans are trying, the South Africans are trying, but these
people have not tried.''
   In 1985, Ethiopia resolved one of several legal problems by
paying $7 million in compensation to U.S. companies for
nationalized property.
   U.S. economic assistance still is restricted by laws that deny
development aid to countries accused of human rights abuses and
which owe money for arms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
