<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--ArrowWounds     06-30 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Arrow Wounds,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10 Wounded By Arrows in Election Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tribesmen supporting rival
candidates in provincial elections fought with bows and arrows and
axes, leaving 10 hospitalized with serious arrow wounds, national
radio said today.
   The fighting in Timbu province, 150 miles north of the capital,
followed the announcement of election results this week, the Papua
New Guinea National Broadcasting Commission said.
   It said supporters of victorious and defeated candidates fought
with traditional weapons along tribal lines.
   The commission said the violence was worst in the town of
Gumine, where houses, a hospital and police station were damaged by
rampaging groups. There was no indication of how many people were
involved.
   Papua New Guinea, north of Australia, is one of the most
primitive countries on earth. About 89 percent of of the population
of 3.2 million lives in rural areas without road access.
</TEXT>
