<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FairHousing     06-30 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fair Housing,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fair Housing Legislation Goes To Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A compromise bill aimed at putting teeth into
the nation's basic fair housing law goes to the Senate after
winning overwhelming approval in the Democratic-controlled House.
   The House voted 376-23 Wednesday evening in favor of the
legislation to broaden protections against housing bias and speed
review of complaints. All the ``nays'' were cast by Republicans.
   The Senate is expected to take quick action on the measure,
which amends the 1968 Fair Housing Act. The act barred
discrimination based on race, color, religion, or national origin
in the sale or rental of housing. A 1974 law prohibits housing
discrimination on the basis of sex.
   President Reagan has said he supports the legislation, which
broadens the power of the Department of Housing and Urban
Development to enforce discrimination complaints.
   As part of the political compromises necessary to get the
original law enacted, HUD was given the power to resolve disputes
only through mediation.
   The new proposal would empower HUD officials to institute legal
proceedings against parties they believe are guilty of
discrimination. But in a major concession to real estate interests,
those accused of discrimination would have the choice of taking
their cases before an administrative law judge or a trial court.
   Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., a civil rights leader in the South in
the 1960s, said the legislation ``breaks another link in the chains
that have bound our society in the ravages of discrimination.''
   ``What we do here today will be a meaningful and significant
step on the long and continued journey on the road to an open
society,'' Lewis said in a floor speech. ``We are saying to the
American people that we must look out for the common good, that we
are one nation, one community, one house, the American house.''
   The legislation represents a compromise between the civil rights
groups and realtors' associations, whose bitter dispute over
enforcement of housing discrimination laws had stalled
congressional action for nearly 11 years. The two sides finally
reached an agreement last week.
   The House also approved, 241-159, an amendment by Rep. Robert K.
Dornan, R-Calif., to ban discrimination against women who are
pregnant.
   Those voting against the overall fair housing bill were:
   Reps. Bill Archer, R-Tex., Richard K. Armey, R-Tex., Steve
Bartlett, R-Tex., Joe Barton, R-Tex., Beau Boulter, R-Tex., Dan
Burton, R-Ind., Larry Combest, R-Tex., Philip M. Crane, R-Ill.,
William E. Dannemeyer, R-Calif., Tom DeLay, R-Tex., David Dreier,
R-Calif., Jack Fields, R-Tex., James V. Hansen, R-Utah;
   Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., Bob Livingston, R-La., Donald E.
Lukens, R-Ohio, Alfred H. McCandless, R-Calif., Bob McEwen, R-Ohio,
Clarence E. Miller, R-Ohio, Howard C. Nielson, R-Utah, Norman D.
Shumway, R-Calif., Bob Stump, R-Ariz., and Patrick L. Swindall,
R-Ga.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
