<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ferrets     06-30 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ferrets,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black-Footed Ferret, Near Extinction, Believed Found in Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERTON LAKES NATIONAL PARK, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small number of
black-footed ferret, one of the rarest animals in North America,
may be living in the Canadian portion of the Waterton-Glacier
International Peace Park, a naturalist says.
   If verified, the find ``may have all the significance of the
return of the whooping crane,'' Duane Barrus, the park's chief
naturalist, said this week.
   The only known population of the weasel-like animals is in a
captive breeding program at the Sybille Wildlife Center near
Wheatland, Wyo. The ferrets, believed extinct for years, were
discovered near Meteetse, Wyo., in 1981, and now number 62.
   ``We believe among ourselves that we have a small wild
population, not too small, we hope, to reproduce,'' Barrus said of
the Waterton ferrets.
   Information about the sightings was relayed to park officials
this spring by Frank Goble, a retired Waterton businessman who
lives in Cardston, Alberta, Barrus said.
   Goble said his son, David, a physics professor at a Nova Scotia
university who summers in Cardston, first saw a ferret in 1983 but
did not know what it was until he returned to school and saw a
photograph in a National Geographic magazine.
   ``It was about six feet from him,'' the elder Goble said. ``He
thought it was a funny-looking weasel.''
   ``They're out there,'' he said. ``My wife saw one last night.
I'm inclined to think that there's a fair population, but they're
scattered.''
   Barrus said researchers had not looked for black-footed ferrets
inside the park because they were believed to live only alongside
prairie dogs, their primary food source, and Waterton has no
prairie dogs.
   Barrus said the animals may have adapted to feed on Columbian
ground squirrels, which are plentiful in the park, and perhaps on
the Richardson's ground squirrel or common gopher.
   Park officials have persuaded the Canadian Wildlife Service to
begin a study inside the park, across southern Alberta and into
Saskatchewan, to get photos and determine the population and range
of the ferrets, Barrus said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
