<2ND_LINE>PM-Soccer Rowdies,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two British Soccer Fans Sentenced For Attacking Italians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STUTTGART, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A juvenile court has sentenced
two British soccer fans to two weeks in jail for a drunken attack
on four Italian fans during the European Soccer Championships.
   But a court spokesman, who asked not to be identified further,
said the men were freed after Wednesday's sentencing because they
had already spent 19 days in jail awaiting trial.
   Court officials identified the men as Gary Webb, 19, and Steven
Peckham, 18, both of Kent.
   According to testimony in the case, the men were among 10
British fans who attacked four Italian fans in downtown Stuttgart.
   Witnesses said one Italian was knocked unconscious, another
struck with a beer mug and a third thrown into a flower bed.
   Several hundred English soccer fans were arrested in six West
German cities during the two-week championships.
   The violence prompted British government officials to ask West
Germany to punish rowdies severely with jail terms.
   Fifteen other British soccer fans are still awaiting trial in
Stuttgart on a variety of charges ranging from assault to
disorderly conduct.
</TEXT>
