<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirForceReactors Bjt   06-30 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Force Reactors, Bjt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Looking for New Power After Scrubbing Local Nukes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force says it is looking for other
emergency power sources after scrubbing a program that would have
placed small nuclear reactors at bases around the country.
   ``We continue to be concerned about secure power and secure
energy for our Air Force bases,'' Gary S. Flora, associate director
of Air Force engineering and services, told a House Government
Operations subcommittee Wednesday.
   His testimony came after an official of the General Accounting
Office criticized the four-year reactor development program, which
cost about $3.75 million, as ill-conceived and poorly managed. The
program was terminated in May 1987.
   Flora said the Air Force is pursuing other options including
additional feeder cables from the commercial power grid and
installation of more auxiliary power generators at bases.
   ``Key facilities currently have backup generators,'' he said,
but in most cases they can supply only a fraction of total power
needs.
   The local reactor project was prompted by the need to provide
Air Force bases with auxiliary power supplies that would be more
secure against disruption in the event of natural disasters,
sabotage, terrorism or wartime attack.
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., chairman of the subcommittee on the
environment, energy and natural resources, said that while such
concern was understandable, ``the logical approach would seem to
call for assessing all the options and choosing the one best suited
to each individual base.''
   ``Instead, DOE (the Department of Energy) pressed ahead with a
plan to put cloned `mini-nukes' at bases around the country at a
cost which could ultimately approach $20 billion,'' he said.
   As a start, the program envisioned locating 10-megawatt reactors
at seven bases: Tinker Air Force Base, Okla.; McClellan AFB,
Calif.; Kelly AFB, Texas; Robbins AFB, Ga.; Hill AFB, Utah;
Mountain AFB, Idaho, and Shemya AFB, Alaska.
   Initial work on the project was done at Los Alamos National
Laboratory for DOE's Office of Defense Programs. Then, before the
Los Alamos feasibility study was complete, the project was
reassigned to DOE's Office of Nuclear Energy and the work was
transferred to the department's Idaho National Engineering
Laboratory.
   Air Force responsibility for the project also was shifted, from
an office at Tyndall Air Force Base, Fla., to another at Bolling
AFB in Washington, D.C., before the plan was dropped.
   Keith O. Fultz, senior associate director of the GAO's
resources, community and economic development division, told the
subcommittee that despite the time and money spent, the program
``made little progress toward its intended goal.''
   He said the GAO, a congressional watchdog agency, viewed the
project as ill-conceived because ``the choice and feasibility of
using nuclear power was never clearly established and documented
prior to the decision to proceed.''
   Flora emphasized in his testimony that the service had decided
to kill the small reactors project before it proceeded beyond an
early stage.
   ``Phase One of the project was a feasibility study only,'' he
said. ``We decided the concept to be too costly. It may have turned
out that cost would have been outweighed by environmental concerns,
even if nuclear plants would have proved cost-effective.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ColorizedMovies     06-30 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colorized Movies,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Would Discourage but not Ban Colorized Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood actors and directors are coming up
short in their efforts to win congressional approval of an outright
ban on computer colorization of black-and-white movies.
   In the first Capitol Hill floor vote on the issue, the House on
Wednesday approved legislation that would merely discourage
colorization of classics such as ``Casablanca'' and ``The Maltese
Falcon.''
   The vote came on an amendment tacked by Rep. Sidney Yates,
D-Ill., onto an Interior Department spending bill. The amendment
would establish a 13-member National Film Preservation Board
composed of film-related officials such as heads of the actors,
writers and directors guilds and of the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences.
   Operating with a $100,000-a-year budget in the Interior
Department, the board would recommend movies for inclusion in a
National Film Registry, with up to 25 movies to selected for the
registry each year by the interior secretary
   A registered film would be given a special seal to denote its
status, and the seal could be used to promote any version of the
movie that has not been materially altered, a term that includes
colorization and heavy editing.
   Materially altered versions of registered films would have to
carry labels to that effect in their advertising and on boxes
containing videocassette versions.
   The bill containing the film board amendment was sent to the
Senate by a 361-45 vote, with Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., objecting
to the amendment on constitutional free-speech grounds.
   ``Establishing a national film commission to pass on the merits
or values of films is an unprecedented and unwarranted extension of
federal power over privately produced works of art,'' Edwards said.
``This is content-based government regulation of speech. In simple
terms, that is censorship.
   ``We should not have a government body deciding that some films
are worthy and some are not. Politics will enter into the
decisions.''
   Hollywood figures such as actor James Stewart and director Fred
Zinneman have been lobbying Congress for months, objecting to
increasing numbers of movies colorized for television through a
computer process.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0300EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-InteriorMoney     06-30 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interior Money,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Opposing Bill to Cut Clean Coal Technology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House is making veto threats against
a House-passed spending bill that President Reagan's budget
director says threatens U.S. promises to Canada to combat acid rain
pollution.
   James Miller, director of the Office of Management and Budget,
is criticizing the $9.69 billion package to finance the Interior
Department, U.S. Forest Service and key energy research programs in
fiscal 1989.
   Miller says unless changes are made, he will recommend a veto of
the bill, which was sent to the Senate on Wednesday by a 361-45
vote _ a margin far larger than what would be needed in the House
to override any veto.
   Miller said the House bill would jeopardize the commitment
Reagan made to Canada to combat acid rain from U.S. sources by
developing technology to reduce pollution from coal-burning plants.
   He said Congress is backtracking on its agreement last year to
spend $525 million on clean coal research in fiscal 1989, which
begins Oct. 1. Instead, the House plan would spend only $100
million in 1989, with $225 million earmarked for 1990 and $200
million for 1991.
   Although Miller blamed Congress exclusively, the $425 million
cut in fiscal 1989 resulted from an agreement between the White
House and Congress to reduce the massive federal budget deficit.
   Miller also complained about the continuation of moratoria on
leasing federal oil tracts off the coasts of northern California
and Massachusetts and the resumption of such a ban off southwestern
Florida. The moratoria are for a year.
   He said the administration strongly opposes a related provision
that would require at least 50 percent U.S. labor and materials to
be used for petroleum facilities in other parts of the outer
continental shelf.
   Miller contends that the buy-U.S. language would delay needed
exploration, drive up its costs and violate international trade
agreements, inviting retaliation by other nations.
   The veto-threat message delivered to lawmakers also cited
opposition to giving states $157 million for energy conservation
programs, which Miller says states should finance themselves;
spending $156 million on discretionary construction; and earmarking
$64 million for Indian health facilities when existing facilities
have a 50 percent vacancy rate.
   The House was unmoved by the warning, and the administration got
no help from Republicans. Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio, called the
legislation a ``peoples' bill,'' and ranking Appropriations
Committee Republican Silvio Conte of Rhode Island urged colleagues
to vote for the measure, calling it a ``good bill.''
   Because of the tight money situation, the legislation is
proposing no major new initiatives and would grant mainly modest
spending increases.
   The National Park Service, for example, would get $960 million,
up from $900 million but well above the $780 million proposed by
the White House. The service and other interior agencies would get
$167 million for land acquisition, more than eight times what
Reagan proposed.
   Overall, the Interior Department would get $4.484 billion next
year, compared to $4.427 billion this year and the administration's
request of $3.973 billion.
   The Forest Service would get $1.81 billion, $200 million above
the administration's proposal and about $56 million more than in
fiscal 1988. The House approved the service's plan to harvest more
than 11 billion board feet of lumber on public land, but it cut $5
million from the current $166.8 million road-building budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
