<DOCNO> AP880630-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TradeReport     06-30 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade Report,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: U.S. Faces `Time of Reckoning' Over Deficit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US Debt Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America faces ``a time of reckoning'' when
foreign sources will no longer be willing to loan the money
necessary for the nation to sustain its deficit-ridden trade
habits, says a congressional report.
   The report, prepared by the Office of Technology Assessment and
released Wednesday by Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., says, ``No nation,
not even one as rich as the United States, can go on forever paying
its current account deficit with foreign capital.''
   The current account is the most important of all the government
trade statistics because it covers not only trade in merchandise,
but also trade in the so-called services category, which reflects
primarily the flow of investment earnings between nations.
   The account has showed a deficit since 1981, as Americans have
handed over billions of dollars to foreigners in exchange for
imported goods. The U.S. deficit has been sustained by loans and
investments from abroad.
   ``As the United States sinks further into debt, foreign
investors and creditors _ central banks, individuals and firms _
will be less inclined to commit ever-increasing amounts of capital
to a $4 trillion economy on a spending spree,'' OTA said.
   When that happens, it said, the United States will be forced to
decrease government spending, business investment or consumption _
or all three. One way that could happen is through a recession.
   But OTA said the nation could minimize its economic woes by
getting better at manufacturing, with the government's help.
   ``That is the most constructive way to recapture some of our own
markets and raise exports,'' the report said.
   Another way to boost exports is through a devalued dollar, but
that also increases the cost of imported cars, video cassette
recorders and other imported goods, the report noted.
   OTA did not predict when the ``time of reckoning'' would occur.
It said the trade patterns of the 1980s ``are a significant
departure from any past experience.''
   The report rejected the notion that service industries such as
banking, engineering or software design can replace manufacturing
industries, or cut the deficit on their own.
   ``To speak of services as taking the place of manufacturing is
to overlook the strong interdependence of the two kinds of
activities and the blurring of distinctions between them,'' OTA
said.
   ``Many service industries depend heavily on manufacturers for
business. And some manufacturing industries could hardly exist
without allied services _ for example, the manufacture of computers
and design of software, often by an independent firm,'' it said.
   Of the $161 billion trade deficit in 1987, 85 percent was in
manufacturing such as motor vehicles and parts, textiles, shoes and
electronics, OTA said.
   The report was released at a news conference by Heinz, who said
it demonstrated that ``manufacturing is the key'' and that bringing
down the dollar to make American exports more attractive ``will not
be enough.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
