<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Diner Bjt   06-30 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Diner, Bjt,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmer's Digest Drought With Diner's Coffee And Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOORHEAD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When dawn breaks in the pale blue prairie
sky, the pickup trucks arrive at the Fryin' Pan Restaurant with
farmers hungry for breakfast and thirsty for rain.
   Their day starts anytime after 5 a.m. at the Fryin' Pan, a place
to catch up on farm news and trade ideas. Somehow, the farmbelt's
worst drought since the Dust Bowl seems easier to digest over
coffee, eggs and sausage with friends facing the same troubles.
   ``I'm an old bachelor. I can take quite a beating,'' said cattle
rancher Walt Engsetter, 54, his meaty hand wrapped around a mug of
black coffee.
   ``If I had a wife and kids, I'd be jumping out of my socks. I've
never seen it this dry.''
   Engsetter has 120 Hereford cows with calves on a 1,200-acre
spread in Spring Prairie Township on Minnesota's western edge. A
22-acre plot of oats to feed the cattle is doing poorly, the
pastures are worn down and the watering holes are getting low.
   ``They're the sorriest oats I've ever seen. It's close to a game
of shutout,'' said the blue-eyed, wiry-haired Engsetter, born of
tough Norwegian stock. ``The pasture is pretty well worked. And I
am nervous about the water.
   ``There ain't much you can do about it though,'' he said.
   This is the heart of America's upper breadbasket.
   Breakfast attire can consist of Big Mac bib overalls, dungarees,
blue work shirts, clodhopper work shoes, Caterpillar belt buckles
and baseball-style mesh caps that advertise everything from seeds
to tractors to fertilizers.
   The restaurant's wallpaper is a pattern with spears of wheat.
Farm sales and auctions are posted on a bulletin board near the
cash register.
   The men speak in measured tones about how their crop is faring
and ask their colleagues how they're doing.
   ``You can talk to your neighbors and exchange ideas, maybe pick
up something that you can give a whirl,'' said Jim Regstad, 46, of
Georgetown.
   Regstad has 100 acres of sugar beets that seem to be weathering
the hot, dry weather so far. His wheat and barley crops aren't
doing as well.
   ``We're hoping for more rain. The grain is pretty much shot,''
said Regstad. ``We're looking to next year already. To be a good
farmer, you got to be an optimist.''
   Regular customers show up almost everyday, and bodies fill the
counter seats and cushioned booths when the weather isn't so dry.
   ``You can tell when it rains. A lot of our business is
weather-related,'' said Scott Christenson, manager of the 24-hour
restaurant.
   Melvin Nyberg of Arthur, N.D., stopped for a bite to eat while
seeking repairs on a cultivator that had blown a cylinder. He
figures the wheat yield on his 1,120-acre farm will be half of
normal.
   ``I think we've lost a crop,'' said Nyberg, 62, wearing a
digital watch with the Case tractor logo on it. ``There's always
adversity in farming. But if you sit here and worry about it, it
will drive you crazy.''
   One extra headache he has is grasshoppers. The insects don't
have enough plants to munch on, so they've been settling in his
crops. He's paying $17 an acre to have them sprayed by air.
   ``They're eating what little's out there. There's so darn many,
you have to control them or you'll have more next year if you
don't,'' Nyberg said.
   ``You hate to spend that kind of money, but we have to do it.
It's survival.''
   Nyberg does some plumbing on the side to make extra money. His
son, Rand, also works the farm and does some accounting.
   ``We'll survive. It won't kill us,'' said Nyberg. ``We're not in
debt and we don't vacation in the winter in Arizona. Anybody that's
borrowing money to put into crops is in tough shape.''
   Waitress Mary Ward hears a lot of the farmers' gripes and
marvels at their pluck and independence.
   ``You got to be crazy to do anything that depends on the
weather,'' she said while carrying a tray of food. ``Even though
farming's a nice life, it would give me ulcers.''
</TEXT>
