<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Drugs Bjt   06-30 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Drugs, Bjt,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Reagan's Drug Task Force Going Nowhere</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan misread the hourglass when he
challenged Congress to take politics out of the national drug
policy debate.
   Whatever sands of goodwill that existed had already slipped away
by the time Reagan used a mid-May Coast Guard Academy address to
urge creation of a joint executive-legislative branch task force.
   ``As I finish my final year in office and look ahead, I worry
that drug politics might undermine effective drug policy,'' Reagan
said in the speech. ``That's why today, I'm calling on both houses
of the Congress, both sides of the aisle, to join with my
representatives in a special executive-legislative task force to
advance America's unified response to the problem of illegal drug
use.''
   A month and a half later, Reagan has only two-thirds of the task
force _ the executive branch members and the representatives
selected by Republican congressional leaders.
   The Democrats have never sent the White House their task force
lineup. And this will not happen, say those close to House Speaker
Jim Wright of Texas, House Majority Leader Tom Foley of Washington
and Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia.
   Simply put, Reagan had an idea whose time had passed. There's
the ongoing presidential campaign, not to speak of the separate
task forces already set up by the House and Senate when Reagan
proposed the joint effort. Finally, there's the reality that
precious little time remains for lawmaking before Congress goes
into recess.
   The clear confluence of politics and this city's great political
debates is rarely out of sight, and it's seldom been more stark
than in the drug issue during this presidential election year.
   Reagan violates the spirit of his own proposal when he puts in a
plug for Vice President George Bush's anti-drug efforts _ as he has
done on more than one occasion. In fact, the presidential campaign
crossfire between Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis makes
bipartisan approaches even less likely.
   Jeff Biggs, a spokesman for Foley, said, ``We already have a
task force. My guess is that there's not going to be any
appointments.''
   House Minority Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill., said, ``I would sure
hope they would because they can give a sense of direction to it.
But in the absence of that, I think we in the legislative branch
have got to move ahead as aggressively as we can.''
   The unwillingness of Democrats to name members to Reagan's task
force has left White House officials grousing about political
motives, with tongue-in-cheek expressions of shock.
   ``Gee, I know Jim Wright's a partisan but I certainly would
never suggest that Congressman Wright would want to be playing
politics on the drug issue. There must be some other explanation,''
said domestic policy adviser Gary Bauer.
   Reagan may have been hoping to find the same kind of bipartisan
cooperation that marked the joint executive-legislative agreement
on a congressional budget-reducing package in the wake of the Oct.
19 Wall Street collapse, when investors sent a vote of
no-confidence to Washington political leaders.
   Or maybe he was looking for the kind of pull-together consensus
the administration enjoyed in Congress when it decided to bomb
Libya in mid-April 1986 in reprisal for a surge of terrorism that
U.S. officials laid at the feet of strongman Moammar Gadhafi.
   What the drug task force fiasco likely proves is that only
perceived emergencies slice through the partisanship of Washington
politics, and that the drug problem did not fit that criterion, its
perils notwithstanding.
   The drug issue will still be here after Election Day.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Hartson covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
