<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vatican-Schisms     06-30 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vatican-Schisms,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Has Had Many Splits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Cardinal Robert of Geneva in 4th graf cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Rebel Archbishop, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic Church has suffered ruptures for
centuries. Here, at a glance, is a look at the major schisms:
   _The Old Catholics, led by German clergy and laymen, split from
the Holy See in 1870 when they rejected the decrees of the First
Vatican Council, particularly the dogma of papal infallibility. By
1874, they set up a new church which, among other things, allowed
priests to marry and made confession optional.
   _The Great Schism, or the Schism of the West, occurred from 1378
to 1417. It involved not a dispute over faith or practice but a
conflict between two parties each claiming to support the true pope.
   The schism began with the death of Pope Gregory XI in 1378.
Under pressure from Romans who feared that the papacy might move
back to Avignon, France, the cardinals elected Urban VI as the new
pope. A few months later, the cardinals declared the election
invalid and elected Cardinal Robert of Geneva as Pope Clement VII,
and he moved to Avignon. Urban retorted by naming 28 new cardinals.
The schism lasted through two lines of popes, ending in 1417 with
the election of Martin V. Today, it is generally agreed that the
Urbanist popes were the true ones.
   _The East-West Schism marked the split between the Holy See and
the Orthodox Eastern Church after centuries of doctrinal disputes
and diverging traditions. The break began in 1054 when Michael
Cerularius, the patriarch of Constantinople, split with Pope Leo
IX. The breach gradually widened, becoming definitive in 1472.
   In a recent split with Rome, China cut ties with the Vatican in
1957 and established its own breakaway Catholic church, which now
claims 3 million members. An unknown number of other Chinese
Catholics remain secretly loyal to the pope.
   Cardinal Rosalio Jose Castillo Lara, the Vatican's leading canon
law expert, said Tuesday that the Chinese split is not considered
schismatic because it is assumed the Catholics were not acting on
their own free will.
   The Catholic Encyclopaedic Dictionary defines schism as ``the
refusal to submit to the authority of the pope or to hold communion
with members of the church subject to him.'' The sacraments may not
be administered to schismatics, even those in good faith, according
to the dictionary.
   The case of Martin Luther (1483-1546), German leader of the
Protestant Reformation, was not one of schism but of heresy, in
that he was seen as rejecting a truth that the Catholic Church
proposed as revealed by God.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PlantClosing     06-30 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Closing,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Maneuvers Mark Plant-Closing Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress will have to cut short
their July 4th campaign plans because of a struggle for political
one-upmanship on the issue of giving workers advance notice of
plant closings and layoffs.
   Democrats had hoped to win passage of a mandatory notice bill in
both the Senate and House before the Independence Day break so they
could vote on overriding an expected veto from President Reagan
before the party's national convention in three weeks.
   Republicans thwarted those ambitions Wednesday, stalling final
action this week by saying they would make Democrats vote first on
a Massachusetts voluntary notice law touted by Democratic
presidential candidate Michael Dukakis.
   With Dukakis at the Capitol most of the day Wednesday, Democrats
balked at allowing a vote that would have enabled Republicans to
claim victory either way: as a rejection of Dukakis or as a
rejection of mandatory notices.
   Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd pulled the bill from the floor
saying, ``We're not going to sit around here and fiddle-faddle with
these little amendments that don't mean anything.''
   Byrd had promised lawmakers earlier that they could spend all of
next week campaigning for re-election in their home states if the
Senate could get final passage of the bill Wednesday and allow
House action on it today.
   Instead, he and House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, agreed to
reconvene Congress July 6 in another attempt to win passage of the
plant-closing measure next week.
   Still, the delay effectively precludes any chance of Congress
overriding a veto before the Democratic convention opens July 18 in
Atlanta, assuming Reagan will use all 10 working days he has under
the Constitution to exercise it.
   With polls showing more than 80 percent of Americans in favor of
advance layoff notices, opposition to the mandatory 60-day notice
proposal from Reagan and Vice President George Bush has become a
top campaign issue for Democrats.
   Dukakis boasted through the primaries that because of his
efforts Massachusetts is ``the one state that has a comprehensive
plant closing law'' even though labor leaders and other critics say
that it is toothless.
   The 1984 Massachusetts statute requests but does not require
employers to give 90 days advance notice of a plant closings, which
is defined as a layoff involving at least 90 percent of a
facility's work force.
   And the only sanction that it provides the denial of state
economic aid to troubled companies that decline to sign a
non-binding pledge to provide the notices.
   ``Let's vote on the Dukakis plan; let's see how many votes he
has,'' Senate Minority Leader Robert Dole, D-Kan., said Wednesday.
``He's for giving notice in his state, but he wants to give it
voluntarily.''
   Dole said Reagan would sign a substitute bill modeled on the
Massachusetts plan that seeks only voluntary rather than mandatory
notices and offers incentives rather than fines as an inducement.
   Vice President George Bush also has endorsed voluntary notices
and conditioning federal contracts and tax incentives on pledges by
companies to provide them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
