<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-30 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This isn't Gotham City, and Scott
Chinery isn't the caped crusader, but that's the Batmobile he's
been cruising around town in.
   Chinery, a 27-year-old entrepreneur who collects expensive and
unusual cars, bought the car for $180,000 from Fantasy Cars, a
California company that deals mainly in vehicles used in movies and
TV shows. It was delivered Monday.
   ``I started my car collection with Matchbox cars when I was 5
years old,'' he said. ``As my income grew, so did my car
collection.''
   Chinery, who founded a sports nutrition company based in Brick
Township, is about to open a stereo store. The Batmobile will be
used to promote that store and various charities, he said.
   The Batmobile that Chinery bought is actually one of two
functioning all-metal versions built in 1964 for stunts and driving
sequences in the television program ``Batman.'' The car has a
2,000-pound body.
   ``It doesn't really go that fast, maybe 100 (mph) tops,'' said
Chinery, who also bought the Batcycle, the original motorcycle and
motorized sidecar used by Batman and Robin, the Boy Wonder.
   But he says that compared to the rest of his car collection, the
Batmobile ``is a piece of history that is the most famous car in
the world.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lover's pop-lyric lament that all
he has to do is dream may have some basis in scientific fact,
according to research presented at an international conference on
dreamwork.
   The vast landscape of dreams is in fact a form of thinking that
could be used to diagnose illness, change neurotic behavior and
enhance artistic creativity, according to scientists meeting
Wednesday at the Fifth Annual Conference for the Study of Dreams.
   Researchers, including a world authority on nightmares, are
investigating topics that include women's dreams, and why some
people recall dreams and others don't.
   The dreamworkers are collecting thousands of dreams from
classrooms, clinics, tribes and diaries into a library that will be
used to study how dreams vary, or don't vary, from decade to decade.
   ``They will become a vast `dreams archive,''' said Bill Domhoff,
professor of psychology at the University of California at Santa
Cruz, where the conference will continue through Saturday.
   ``People 100 years from now will know what we were dreaming in
the '50s and the '80s,'' he said.
</TEXT>
