<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Drought-Congress     06-30 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Congress,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Capitol Hill Deluged with Drought-Fighting Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blazing sun may be baking the midcontinent,
but proposals for fighting the drought are raining down on Capitol
Hill.
   ``This is certainly the worst drought that this country has
suffered since the droughts of the 30s,'' Sen. John Melcher,
D-Mont., said Wednesday in calling for stepped-up federal aid.
``Our farmers are staggering.''
   Proposals ranged from cancellation of a 50-cent cut in dairy
price supports to an evangelist's ``haylift'' of livestock feed to
South Dakota.
   Democratic presidential nominee-to-be Michael Dukakis huddled
with farm Democrats at the Capitol on Wednesday to discuss the
plight of farmers.
   ``I think the governor's attitude was very reassuring to all of
us,'' said Rep. Thomas Foley, D-Wash., after the session. ``He
doesn't come with a lot of preconceived technical proposals. He's
there to get our counsel and advice.''
   Meanwhile, Sens. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., and David Pryor, D-Ark.,
lent their support to a ``haylift'' designed to feed 2,000 to 3,000
head of cattle in South Dakota for a month.
   The Rev. Larry Jones, an Oklahoma City evangelist, developed the
plan to load hay onto 15 railroad cars for transport to South
Dakota, where livestock producers are desperate to replace feed
burned away by the sun.
   A lottery might be needed to determine who gets the feed, said
Dallas Tonsager, president of the South Dakota Farmers Union, since
3,000 head represent only a small fraction of the South Dakota
herd. He expressed gratitude, though, to Jones for his effort.
   ``They say that a rising tide raises all boats,'' Jones
declared. ``But everybody does not have a boat and those who do not
have a boat when the tide rises drown. Rural America is drowning.''
   Livestock producers are being forced to sell their herds for
lack of feed, creating a buyer's market and thus driving down
prices.
   ``The situation is going from bad to worse,'' Daschle said.
``Each day additional herds are shipped south and out of state.''
   An hour later in the same Senate committee room, Melcher
unveiled a wide-ranging drought relief bill at another news
conference.
   It would guarantee income-support payments to farm program
participants whose crops fail, and provide payments for growers of
crops not covered by a USDA program. It also would authorize the
secretary of agriculture to make irrigation grants.
   Federal officials would be directed to transport cattle out of
drought-stricken areas hit by shortages of livestock feed. The bill
also would cancel an expected 50-cent cut in dairy prices supports
set for next year.
   Melcher's plan received support from Sens. Howell Heflin,
D-Ala.; Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y.; Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, and Kent
Conrad, D-N.D.
   Elsewhere, Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich met with lawmakers on
drought-fighting strategy and then headed down Independence Avenue
to the Agriculture Department to try the plan on Secretary Richard
E. Lyng.
   It was Perpich's second trip to Washington in recent weeks. Last
time, he urged Lyng to allow hay cutting and grazing on
Conservation Reserve Program acreage. The secretary balked but a
few days later relented under heavy pressure from Congress.
   ``We have to send a signal that we are going to keep farmers on
the land over this difficult period,'' Perpich said.
   His latest proposal would delay the 50 cent dairy price-support
reduction and allow farmers to keep government payments they have
received in advance, even if the effect of the drought would
otherwise shrink the amount.
   It also would provide special benefits for farmers who donate
hay from Conservation Reserve Program acreage and assure
income-support payments later in the season even if crops are wiped
out.
</TEXT>
