<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Poll     06-30 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Poll,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: Reagan Good with Soviets but Bungled Iran, Central America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national poll shows public support for
President Reagan's dealings with the Soviet Union but disapproval
of his policies in Central America and the Mideast.
   Three-quarters of Americans surveyed approve of Reagan's
handling of Soviet relations, but only 46 percent like his overall
foreign policy, according to the nonpartisan ``Americans Talk
Security'' poll released Wednesday.
   Sixty-two percent think he mishandled Iran; 63 percent disagree
with his Central America policies, and 63 percent think he has done
too little to solve conflicts in the Mideast, according to the
survey.
   The poll results also reflect heightened concern over
international trade and drug trafficking. For example, 63 percent
of those surveyed said Reagan should do more to combat
international drug dealing.
   Improved U.S.-Soviet relations probably have helped those issues
come to the fore, one pollster said.
   ``Reagan has sapped political concern on the issue'' of
U.S.-Soviet relations, said John Martilla, who conducted the survey
as part of a bipartisan series. Martilla also conducts polls for
Michael Dukakis, the apparent Democratic presidential nominee.
   Another pollster taking part in the series, Fred Steeper, said
Reagan's success in dealing with Moscow ``has removed from the
Republican bag of tricks the ability to run against the Soviets.''
Steeper also conducts polls for Republican presidential candidate
George Bush.
   The survey was based on interviews with 1,003 voters before the
Moscow summit, May 29-June 2, and had a margin of error of 3.1
percentage points, according to Martilla and Steeper, who presented
it at a news conference.
   The survey also showed disagreement with the U.S. policy to use
nuclear weapons if the conventional armies of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization are not able to stop a Soviet invasion of
Western Europe.
   Only 8 percent of those surveyed said nuclear weapons should be
used if the ``Soviets have successfully invaded Western Europe
without nuclear weapons.''
   The poll also showed that the public holds some contradictory
attitudes about foreign affairs.
   For example, even though 57 percent of the public agreed that
``it's only a matter of time before Japan becomes the number one
economic power in the world,'' 56 percent said `the U.S. will
continue to be the greatest economic power well into the next
century.''
   The U.S. gross national product is far larger than that of
Japan, although the Japanese GNP is slightly higher on a per capita
basis.
   Americans thought Reagan has done a good job on traditional
national security issues: 75 percent liked him for ``standing up to
the Soviets;'' 73 percent thought he has kept America out of war;
75 percent liked his arms control policies; 71 percent thought he
had developed a sound national defense; 61 percent commended him
for an ``appropriate use of military power;'' 59 percent thought he
had promoted the spread of democracy; 58 percent thought he had
prevented the spread of communism; 61 percent liked his policy in
the Persian Gulf; and 54 percent thought he had won respect for the
United States.
   ``Yet, despite these truly impressive ratings, only 46 percent
of the American people ``approve of the way Ronald Reagan is
handling foreign policy,'' while 47 percent disapprove, according
to the survey.
   Also, 48 percent approved and 48 percent did not approve of his
efforts in fighting terrorism; 51 percent thought he had not helped
make the United States a strong competitor on the international
market, versus 48 percent who thought he had; and 29 percent did
not approve of his handling of relations with Panamanian leader
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
</TEXT>
