<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe-Glance     06-30 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Glance,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Purchasing Chief Backs Away from Defense of Memo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD></HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the major developments in the
investigation of Defense Department procurement practicies.
   
   HALTING CONTRACTS=
   
   The Pentagon's top purchasing official, Robert B. Costello, said
he would talk with Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci today about
a suggestion to halt contracts with companies involved in the
criminal investigation. Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., said Carlucci
should order ``absolutely no contracts signed for 60 days (or) six
weeks'' with those companies.
   
   DESTROYED DOCUMENTS?=
   
   In Brooklyn, court papers filed by the U.S. attorney heading the
investigation said he has learned of several instances of documents
being destroyed by people implicated in the probe.
   Henry Hudson provided no details on who destroyed documents, how
they were destroyed or how they might have been related to the
investigation.
   
   CHANGE OF VIEW=
   
   Costello, the Defense Department undersecretary for acquisition
policy, told the House Armed Services Committee he no longer backs
the position he took in a May 5 memo that Pentagon officials should
be empowered to block fraud investigators from searching defense
contractor facilities.
   Costello repeatedly defended the Defense Department procurement
policies of the Reagan administration. Congress can enact new laws
and the Pentagon can pass new regulations, but there is no way to
ensure against greed, Costello said.
   
   LEVIN-PAISLEY=
   
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., asked the FBI to give Congress its
file on Melvyn Paisley, a former Pentagon procurement official
under investigation in connection with alleged fraud and bribery in
defense purchasing.
   
   INSPECTOR GENERAL=
   
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., said the Pentagon inspector
general's office has reopened its investigation into a disputed
contract in the wake of the separate criminal investigation of
bribery and fraud in Defense Department weapons purchases.
   
   CONGRESS-MONEY=
   
   Leading defense contractors contributed more than two-thirds of
the honoraria received by members of the House and Senate
committees responsible for defense-related legislation, said Common
Cause, a liberal lobby organization.
</TEXT>
