<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MiniskirtBan     06-30 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miniskirt Ban,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miniskirts Banned At Regatta, Thigh-Spotters On Duty</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   HENLEY-ON-THAMES, England (AP) _ Miniskirts may be high fashion,
but if they're more than two inches above the knee they will keep
you out of the exclusive enclosure for ticket-holders at the Henley
Royal Regatta.
   ``Henley has retained its Victorian-Edwardian style in almost
every respect, including its standards of dress and adherence to
the rule book,'' a spokesman said Wednesday, the first day of the
149th annual rowing event.
   Stewards, or race organizers, will not examine all of the
250,000 people who attend the prestigious four-day regatta on the
Thames River, a highlight of Britain's summer social season.
   But they will inform women who enter the stewards' enclosure
with ``inappropriate'' hem height of their objections, the
spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   The enclosure, with bar and dining facilities, is reserved for
stewards and their guests.
   Regatta officials said ``a number'' of women were turned away
from the enclosure for wearing short skirts Wednesday, but did not
specify how many.
   ``If you go with women's fashion you end up with middle-aged
women displaying thighs they should have kept secret for years,''
said Peter Coni, chairman of the Regatta Committee.
   ``You have got to have strict rules which don't place a burden
on people at the gates having to make judgments on whether someone
is sexy or not.''
   The regatta's strict dress code also requires men entering the
enclosure to wear suits or a jacket and pants and a tie. Women are
not permitted to wear short skirts, slacks or culottes.
   No one is admitted to the enclosure wearing shorts, jeans or
anything made of denim.
</TEXT>
