<DOCNO> AP880630-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PLOMission     06-30 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO Mission,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO And UN Hail U.S. Court Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations and the PLO hailed a
federal court decision that blocks a congressional attempt to ban
the PLO's U.N. Mission from the United States.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said Wednesday he was
``gratified by this judgment, which demonstrates the respect of the
U.S. courts for the international obligations of the country.''
   Zehdi Labib Terzi, the Palestine Liberation Organization's
ambassador to the U.N., called the ruling a victory for
international law.
   ``The United Nations now has no fear that the host country, or
any host country, can violate its legal obligations and get out
scot-free,'' he said.
   U.S. District Judge Edmund Palmieri ruled that the 1947
agreement that brought the United Nations to the United States
prohibits the government from closing the Palestine Liberation
Organization's observer mission.
   He also said the Anti-Terrorism Act passed by Congress does not
supersede U.S. obligations under the 1947 Headquarters Agreement.
   Palmieri said the language of the Anti-Terrorism Act, which
branded the PLO a terrorist group, does not indicate Congress meant
to abandon America's obligations to the U.N.
   The U.S. Mission to the United Nations said it would have no
comment on the ruling.
   Judge Palmieri dismissed the government's suit with prejudice,
meaning it can't be brought again. It can be appealed to a higher
court.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani, who argued the government's case
before Palmieri earlier this month, said the decision was being
studied ``and we will make a decision as to further proceedings as
soon as possible.''
   State Department spokesman Dennis Harter in Washington said his
department also was reading the decision and consulting with the
Justice Department. The State Department had opposed the attempt to
close the PLO mission.
   The Justice Department filed suit in March seeking to close the
PLO mission, citing the Anti-Terrorism Act passed by Congress and
reluctantly signed by President Reagan last year.
   The law, which took effect March 21, labeled the PLO and its
affiliates ``a terrorist organization and a threat to interests of
the United States.''
   The law barred the PLO from operating its U.N. Mission or any
other office in the United States and also barred the PLO from
funding any activities in this country to further its aims.
   Dr. Clovis Maksoud, the Arab League's permanent observer to the
United Nations, said his organization considered the ruling ``a
victory for the United States over the recklessness of the Israeli
lobby and their unquestioning supporters.''
   ``We welcome this decision and believe that this will facilitate
the work of the U.N. (General) Assembly,'' he said. ``It shows
judicial respect for United States' treaty obligations and the
healthy independence of the judiciary.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
