<DOCNO> AP880630-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Jonsson     06-30 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Jonsson,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swedish-Born Trapper Dies After Six Decades In The Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE PAS, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ragnar Jonsson, a Swedish-born trapper
who lived in a tent in northern Manitoba and spent more than 60
years in the Canadian bush, has died at the age of 88.
   Jonsson, who died last Saturday, will have his ashes scattered
over an island that bears his name in the middle of Neultin Lake
after a funeral today, Manitoba, the Canadian Press news agency
reported. It did not say how he died.
   The Swede came to Canada in 1923 and made his living cutting
wood and fishing around Big River, Saskatchewan, before starting
his trapping career in the 1930s.
   For more than 40 years he lived off the land near Neultin Lake.
His shelter was a small tepee, just big enough for an oil drum
converted into a stove, an oil lamp and sleeping bags.
   He once praised the benefits of sleeping in cold weather. ``It
keeps you healthy. I haven't had a headache in 50 years.''
   Jonsson occasionally met Cree and Chipewyan Indian trappers or
sport fishermen and hunters at a nearby lodge, but his only steady
companions were his husky sled dogs.
   Mail reached him once or twice a year and every decade or so, he
ventured into a city.
   In 1982 he went to Winnipeg after an absence of 59 years to have
a cataract removed.
   ``Now I could see a moose or a caribou moving 50 miles away,''
he said before heading back into the bush, where his favorite foods
included lake trout, ptarmigan and pancakes made with the blood of
a caribou or moose.
   ``If you've ever tasted it, you'll never ever want any other
kind of pancake,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
