<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     06-30 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Suggests Fewer Blood Transfusions May Be Needed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Institutes of Health panel,
concerned about the spread of AIDS through donated blood, is
recommending that doctors keep blood transfusions ``to a minimum.''
   The panel of experts says doctors should also reevaluate
traditional uses of blood in surgery in light of AIDS and improved
surgical techniques.
   The chances of contracting acquired immune deficiency syndrome
from donated blood is still considered ``miniscule,'' said Tibor
Greenwalt, a University of Cincinnati researcher and chairman of
the NIH committee. But he warned Wednesday that blood transfusions
do carry ``documented risks of infection and immune changes.''
   He and other committee members issued a report that said,
``Blood transfusions were once believed to be relatively safe, but
more recently many physicians and patients have come to regard them
as potentially dangerous.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Club Born Of Suffrage Movement Gives Men Right To Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Born 66 years ago of the women's suffrage
movement, the Woman's National Democratic Club has made men equal
members of the organization.
   The club voted Wednesday to grant its male members the right to
vote in what outgoing club President Jean R. Jensen called an
ironic turn for an organization founded to give women a say in what
once was the male world of politics.
   ``Perhaps it is a measure of our success that women's clubs are
being asked to include men,'' she said.
   The organization has nearly 2,000 members, of whom 85 are men.
As associate members, the men could participate in all ways except
that they could not head committees, become officers or vote.
   The club's decision to grant men full membership status comes on
the heels of votes by Washington's exclusive Metropolitan and
Cosmos clubs to end their men-only policies.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kids At Loose Ends Over Dads' Failure To Buckle Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mothers are more likely to buckle up than
fathers, and a new survey says the behavior of parents can have a
strong influence on whether their children use seat belts.
   The survey of 1,118 children, released Wednesday, showed 58
percent said they wear seat belts all or most of the time, while 57
percent said their mothers regularly wear seat belts and only 38
percent said their fathers buckle up.
   The children were interviewed by Louis Harris and Associates for
the American Coalition of Traffic Safety, which was set up by the
U.S. auto industry in 1986 to support safety belt use.
   Results of the survey, which has a margin of error or 3
percentage points, were released at a news conference that included
37 children who survived accidents because of seat belts.
   Susan Akin, Miss America for 1986, accompanied the children, and
recounted that a seat belt saved her life in a 1987 Mississippi
crash involving her car and an 18-wheel truck.
</TEXT>
