<DOCNO> AP880630-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cambodia     06-30 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Military Command Pull Out From Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vietnamese said they
withdrew their top military command from Cambodia today, turning a
nine-year-old guerrilla war over to Cambodian officers.
   For the first time, Vietnamese officials also disclosed their
casualties in the war. They said 55,000 Vietnamese soldiers have
been killed since 1977, when Vietnam began clashing with the Khmer
Rouge regime, which then ruled Cambodia.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia the next year, replacing the
pro-Beijing Khmer Rouge with a pro-Hanoi government.
   The top Vietnamese commander in Cambodia, Gen. Le Ngoc Hien, and
about 300 other top officers and their staffs returned to Ho Chi
Minh City from Cambodia's capital of Phnom Penh aboard Soviet-made
military helicopters and airplanes.
   They are among 50,000 Vietnamese troops Hanoi says it will bring
home by the end of the year in the largest of seven annual pullouts
from Cambodia. Anti-Vietnamese guerrilla groups claim the
withdrawals are nothing but troop rotations.
   Vietnamese officials said the latest move completes the transfer
of the military command to the Phnom Penh government.
   ``We think the Cambodian armed forces can shoulder their
responsibility themselves,'' Lt. Gen. Le Kha Phieu, deputy
commander of Vietnamese forces in Cambodia, told a news conference
in Ho Chi Minh City.
   About 100,000 Vietnamese soldiers are helping the Cambodian
government fight a three-party guerrilla group backed by many
Western nations and China.
   Phieu said about 13,000 Vietnamese soldiers have already
returned home this year. Hanoi says 50,000 are being withdrawn this
year and the remaining 50,000 will come home by 1990.
   He also disclosed Vietnamese casualties in the war, saying
30,000 Vietnamese died in border clashes in 1977-78 with the Khmer
Rouge, who killed more than a million Cambodians during their
bloody rule from 1975 to 1978.
   Another 25,000 Vietnamese troops have died in Cambodia since the
1978 invasion, Phieu said.
   Vietnamese forces in Cambodia have been taking fewer casualties
in recent years, indicating that the guerrilla forces were becoming
weaker, Phieu said. He said that this year and last, only 500
Vietnamese soldiers were killed in Cambodia and another 2,500 were
wounded.
   The ultra-radical Khmer Rouge ``remain a force in Cambodia but
are in decline because they receive no support from the Kampuchean
(Cambodian) people,'' Phieu said.
   Thousands of Vietnamese crowded into the international airport
of Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon, to greet the returning
officers and advisers. They arrived after a sendoff in Phnom Penh
by thousands of Cambodians waving Vietnamese and Cambodian flags
and saffron-robed monks offering blessings for a safe journey home.
   Cambodian Defense Minister Koy Buntha pledged to strengthen his
forces to replace the Vietnamese, whom he thanked at an airport
ceremony for ``your blood and sacrifice.''
   United Nations special envoy Rafee Uddin Ahmed was to arrive in
Phnom Penh later today for talks with Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen on settling the Cambodian issue. It would be the first time for
a U.N. envoy to hold formal talks on the issue with the Cambodian
government, which the United Nations does not recognize.
   Instead, the U.N. recognizes the tripartite coalition made up of
the communist Khmer Rouge, non-communist Khmer People's National
Liberation Front and forces loyal to Prince Norodum Sihanouk.
   In Bangkok, Thailand, meanwhile, a U.S. official appeared on a
television broadcast and said the United States will not accept the
return to power of the Khmer Rouge.
   Gaston Sigur, U.S. assistant secretary of state for East Asia
and Pacific Affairs, said today that the United States supports
efforts by Sihanouk to resolve the Cambodian conflict.
   The telecast from Washington was organized by the United States
Information Agency as a preview to a July visit to Asia by
Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
