<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Ambush     06-30 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Ambush,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Attack Leftist University President, Kill Three Aides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen with a grenade launcher and
automatic rifles attacked a leftist university president today,
killing three aides and wounding the educator and five other aides,
police said.
   A pedestrian was slightly injured in the ambush, the second in
seven months on Dr. Nemesio Prudente, president of the
government-run Polytechnic University of the Philippines.
   No group claimed responsibility. The first attack, in 1987, was
blamed on right-wing extremists.
   ``This second attempt on the life of Dr. Prudente is brutal,
brazen and contemptible,'' President Corazon Aquino said in a
statement read by spokesman Teodoro Benigno. She ordered a ``speedy
solution.''
   Police said Prudente and his aides, including several
bodyguards, were approaching the university campus at 8:45 a.m.
when they were ambushed. His party was traveling in a van followed
by a security car.
   Prudente suffered shrapnel wounds in the left arm and both legs,
police said, adding that none of the other six wounded were in
critical condition.
   Reporters looking through a hospital's emergency room windows
said they saw Prudente, both arms and left shoulder bandaged,
sitting on a bed and talking to investigators.
   Roger Pureza, a university security guard in the van with
Prudente, said the gunmen sprayed it with bullets, then hurled a
grenade. He suffered shrapnel wounds in the left arm and face.
   Jejomar Binay, a nephew of Prudente and mayor of the Manila
suburb of Makati, told reporters police believe there were at least
six gunmen.
   He said the gunmen could be the same who wounded Prudente and
killed a university lawyer in an unsolved Nov. 11, 1987 ambush.
   Human rights groups blamed right-wing death squads for the first
ambush, which occurred a week after soldiers and policemen chanted
``Kill Prudente'' during a funeral for a police captain and three
other people killed by communist assassins.
   The military and police had accused Prudente, an outspoken human
rights activist, of using his school to shelter communist urban
guerrillas. Prudente denied the charge.
   Students from the university and other colleges said they would
protest today's ambush.
   Sen. Ernesto Maceda, chairman of the Senate's defense committee,
condemned the attack and criticized police for failing to keep
peace and order in the Manila area.
   The capital has been rocked during the past few years by
killings attributed to leftist and right-wing extremists.
</TEXT>
