<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Illinois Dems Chief Targets Jackson-backed Platform Plank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans are underway to strip the
Illinois Democratic Party's platform of a controversial plank
backed by supporters of Jesse Jackson which advocates an
independent Palestinian homeland.
   State party Chairman Vince Demuzio, a senator from Carlinville,
said Wednesday that the position taken by delegates at the recent
state convention here was wrong and will be changed.
   ``I've polled the state party and they support our traditional
position on the Middle East,'' Demuzio said. ``The position taken
at the convention is not supported by Michael Dukakis and it will
not be in the national platform.''
   Demuzio said he found no support for the position when he polled
the 44 members of the Democratic state central committee last week.
   Delegates to the Democratic state convention June 18 adopted a
plank calling for self-determination for the Palestinian people and
establishment of an independent Palestinian state. The plank also
defended Israel's right to exist.
   It is supported by Jesse Jackson, who had bus loads of
supporters at the convention.
