<HEAD>Jackson Plans Week Off Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson says he plans to leave the
campaign trail for most of the next week to resume personal efforts
to free U.S. hostages held in Lebanon and map out his strategy for
the Democratic National Convention.
   Jackson said Wednesday he will also use the time to deliberate
``in great detail'' with his family about whether to seek the vice
presidential nomination.
   There are no meetings scheduled between Jackson and certain
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis, but Jackson said
the attitude of those closest to him might be the most important
factor in his own decision to seek the vice presidential nomination.
   Dukakis was meeting in Washington this week with congressional
leaders considered potential running mates.
   ``Unlike other persons who are under consideration, I have taken
every test that Dukakis has taken,'' said Jackson.
   Jackson declined to provide many specifics on his efforts to
free U.S. hostages, but said he plans to make several audio and
videotapes for distribution in the Middle East over the next few
days, appealing to the hostages' captors for their safe release.
   He said he has kept in contact with unnamed people in the Middle
East and ``instincts and certain conversations'' convinced him the
timing was right to again seek the hostages' release.
   ``We must not give the impression that we have given up on the
Americans who are there,'' Jackson said. ``And we need to exhaust
all efforts to get them out.''
   He said he was prepared to make another personal trip to the
region if necessary, but added, ``We've got no timetable.''
   Jackson also announced the filing in Washington of a political
action committee, ``Keep Hope Alive,'' to advance the themes of
fairness and economic justice that were the centerpieces of his own
presidential campaign.
   ``There are some targeted areas in congressional campaigns and
state legislative campaigns where we can help elect officials who
believe the future of this party is in integrated slate-making,''
he said.
