<HEAD>Poll Shows Dukakis Ahead in Colorado</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colorado voters, who have a strong record of
voting Republican in national elections, favor likely Democratic
nominee Michael Dukakis over George Bush by nearly a double-digit
margin, a new poll shows.
   The telephone poll, conducted by The Denver Post and KCNC-TV,
shows Dukakis with the support of 45 percent of the 553 people
randomly surveyed across the state. Bush, the all-but-certain GOP
choice, has the backing of 36 percent of the voters, while 19
percent remain uncommitted.
   Colorado voters have not supported a Democratic candidate in 24
years.
   The poll was conducted June 5-7 by Talmey Research & Strategy of
Boulder. It has a margin of error of 4 percentage points.
