<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-30 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a slight fall, the dollar held its ground
against the Japanese yen today, and share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange added to its previous day's gain.
   After opening at 132.90 yen, up from Wednesday's close of 132.40
yen, the dollar crawled up further to peak at 133.00 yen before it
dropping to finish the day at 132.20 yen, down 0.20 yen from the
previous day.
   The dollar fell because ``market participants are closing their
positions prior to the Fourth of July holiday in the United
States,'' said a dealer a major local securities firm, speaking on
condition of anonymity. U.S. markets will be closed Monday for
Independence Day.
   ``Those who were buying the currency at the 133-yen level at the
start of trading moved down to 132 yen because of the upcoming
holiday,'' he added.
   King Ogino, a dealer at Goldman Sachs, said local city banks at
one point tried to push the dollar above the 133-yen level, but had
to fall back after meeting market resistance.
   But buying pressure is still intact and the dollar will soon
consolidate its position, Ogino said. He added however that
``people are cautious.''
   The securities dealer said ``the dollar will be bought up in the
upcoming week,'' adding that ``there is a rumor of it reaching even
the 135-yen level.''
   He said however that the movement depended on the nation's
central bank, which since last week refrained from intervening in
the market to stem the dollar's rise.
   This lack of intervention has been primarily responsible for the
dollar's appreciation against the yen. Monetary authorities have
ruled out stepping into the market, and Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa earlier this week said the market changes were ordinary
fluctuations.
   In September 1985, the dollar was trading as high as 242 yen
when the seven major industrialized nations agreed to push the
currency down to help reduce the massive U.S. trade deficit. A
lower dollar theoretically makes U.S. goods cheaper and more
competitive abroad.
   Meanwhile, on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the main market
barometer added another 162.07 points, or 0.58 percent, to close at
27,769.40 points. The index had gained 209.24 points, or 0.76
percent, on Wednesday.
   Traders said the rise in the Nikkei index was led mainly by
heavy electricals and automakers.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at a heavy 2.5 billion
shares, unchanged from Wednesday.
</TEXT>
