<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-SovietUnion     06-30 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Soviet Union,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Says Soviet Union Faces Big Hurdles In Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's official news agency today said the
Soviet Union faces major hurdles in its attempt to revamp its
economic and political systems.
   The Soviet Communist Party conference taking place in Moscow
``is entrusted with the formidable task of seeking ways to deepen
reforms,'' Xinhua News Agency said in a signed commentary from
Moscow.
   ``But big hurdles have to be overcome before the process can
become irreversible.''
   The commentary did not mention the many obstacles China has
faced since pioneering market-oriented economic reforms in 1979 and
more recently tackling political restructuring.
   But it spoke from experience in cautioning that the Soviet road
to reform will not be easy.
   It noted that ``practices are lagging behind theory'' in the
Soviet Union and quoted Valentin Falin, head of the Novosti Press
Agency, as saying old practices must be done away with for economic
and social reforms to succeed.
   Xinhua said Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev is calling for
solutions to chronic food shortages and that well-stocked markets
``will help strengthen the hand of the Soviet leader in convincing
people of the correctness of reforms.''
   Xinhua also noted that Gorbachev had stressed political reform,
particularly the clear separation of party and government functions
and an enhanced role for legislative assemblies. China too is now
striving to end Communist Party interference in government and
economic affairs and make its legislatures more democratic.
   The report said many at the conference agreed that
``self-criticism of mistakes will prove more important than
legislation because laws may be violated or annulled by rulers if
no one stands up to raise an objection.''
   The commentary concluded: ``People here now are wondering how
far the conference will go in its efforts to make reforms
irreversible. One thing is almost certain: the task requires more
time and unremitting endeavor.''
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing, asked about the
conference at a weekly briefing today, said: ``The holding of such
a conference by the Soviet Communist Party under the current
circumstances has naturally drawn people's attention and we are
also following the developments of the conference.
   ``We have noted that a major topic of the current conference is
reform and we hope that the reform in the Soviet Union will be a
success.''
   China and the Soviet Union split over ideological differences in
1960 and political relations remain strained.
   But economic ties between the two countries have grown steadily,
and it is believed that the Soviet Union has watched closely
China's experiments in reducing the role of central planning,
allowing the value of goods to be determined by market forces and
encouraging private enterprise.
</TEXT>
