<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MuscularDystrophy     06-30 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Muscular Dystrophy,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Studies Hint at Cause of Muscular Dystrophy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Studies of a protein linked to the most serious
form of muscular dystrophy suggest the disease may kill muscle by
weakening muscle cell walls, an idea that may help lead to
treatments.
   The protein is absent from muscles of people with Duchenne
dystrophy, and the studies suggest that may result in abnormally
weak cell walls.
   Scientists are trying to determine the function of the protein,
called dystrophin, so they can tell just why its absence is so
destructive in Duchenne. That knowledge is expected to guide
development of treatments.
   The studies do not directly demonstrate dystrophin's function,
but hint at it by showing where the protein appears within the
muscle cell. The results support the cell-wall hypothesis, proposed
before dystrophin was discovered last year.
   Today's British journal Nature published one of the studies,
co-authored by Louis Kunkel of the Howard Hughes Medical Institute
at Children's Hospital in Boston, with colleagues at the hospital
and Harvard Medical School.
   Similar conclusions were published this month by Canadian
researchers, including Elizabeth Zubrzycka-Gaarn and Ronald Worton
of the Hospital for Sick Children in Toronto and the University of
Toronto.
   Duchenne muscular dystrophy appears in about one in 3,500 male
births in the United States. It causes progressive weakness and
wasting of voluntary muscles, requiring patients to use wheelchairs
by age 12 and killing most in their early 20s. No cure is known.
   When Kunkel and collaborators announced the discovery of
dystrophin last December, they suggested it may play a role in
regulating muscle contraction. But the new work makes that
hypothesis less likely, Kunkel said this week in a telephone
interview.
   His team's research, which involved examining extremely thin
slices of muscle tissue under an electron microscope, found that
dystrophin appeared just inside the flimsy, fatty membrane that
makes up the cell walls.
   It appears to be part of the cytoskeleton, a mesh of proteins
that maintains the structure of the cell, he said. That fits in
with previous work showing that it resembles other proteins in the
cytoskeleton, he said.
   If dystrophin is part of the cell's structural support, muscle
cells that lack dystrophin may be unusually susceptible to being
torn and destroyed as the muscle works, he said.
   Zubryzycka-Gaarn, senior author of the other paper, said her
team found a similar location for dystrophin and reached the same
hypothesis about what its absence might do. But scientists are
still a long way from knowing dystrophin's function in detail, she
said.
   Similar caution was voiced by Donald Wood of the Muscular
Dystrophy Association.
   The studies show dystrophin is ``in some way associated with the
(cell wall) membrane. We don't know what that way is now,'' he
said. ``I think we're at the point where it's best to keep an open
mind'' about what dystrophin does.
   In a separate report in Nature, Japanese researchers said they
have found another protein absent in muscle from patients with
Duchenne and other forms of muscular dystrophy. Its location in
normal cells resembles that of dystrophin, they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0070 </DOCNO>
