<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-GardenTheft     06-30 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Garden Theft,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Guarding Garden With Shotgun After Early Harvest Theft</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Diner, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTLEY, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evelyn Cameron, who nurtured her vegetable
garden through the drought, has her shotgun cocked in case the
bandits who raided her patch last week come back looking for more.
   ``If they come back ... I'll be ready for them,'' she said
Wednesday. ``I'm not scared of anything.''
   The first harvest had just ripened when about 1{ bushels of
butter beans, cucumbers and purple hull peas were stolen, said Mrs.
Cameron, who has lived in this central Louisiana town 29 years.
   That's not much, but it was all that was ripe, she said.
   ``They took everything, right down to the little bitty ones,''
said Mrs. Cameron. ``It's really disheartening because you plant a
garden and take care of it through the drought and then they steal
your vegetables.''
   More vegetables have begun to ripen. And until they're
harvested, she's not going anywhere. Her shotgun is at the ready in
case anyone gets a late-night urge for corn on the cob, okra or
cucumbers.
   ``I guarantee you I'll shoot it,'' she said. ``I'll scare the
daylights out of 'em, if nothing else.''
   Mrs. Cameron said she did not call the Grant Parish Sheriff's
Office about the theft because there's not much deputies can do
unless the thieves are caught in the act.
   Even if the booty isn't cooked and eaten, it would be hard to
prove the vegetables were Mrs. Cameron's.
   It's not that Mrs. Cameron is unwilling to share her bounty. Her
three garden plots and dozen chickens provide more than enough
vegetables and eggs for her.
   ``If they want something, why don't they come and ask? I'd have
given them eggs, too, if they needed 'em,'' she said. ``They were
just out to steal something. People do some strange things.''
</TEXT>
