<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0533EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-PLO     06-30 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-PLO,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Israelis Sentenced To Prison For Meeting PLO Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAMLE, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a landmark decision, a magistrate court
today sentenced four Israeli left-wing activists to six-month
prison terms for violating a law that bars contacts with the PLO.
   They were the first Israelis to be jailed on the basis of the
1986 law barring ``unauthorized'' contacts with members of
terrorist groups. Israel views the PLO as a terrorist group.
   A judge in this city near Tel Aviv also gave each of the four a
one-year suspended sentence and ruled that each should pay $2,500
in fines and court expenses. The law carries a sentence of up to
three years imprisonment.
   ``They seemed thunderstruck when they heard the ruling,'' one
witness told The Associated Press.
   The leftists were convicted on June 2 for violating the law by
meeting with a 15-member Palestine Liberation Organization group in
Costinesti, Romania, in November 1986.
   Israel army radio quoted Judge Avraham Baiser as acknowledging
in his ruling that the law was disputed in Israel.
   ``However, the law should be respected even if it is not
accepted by the public,'' Baiser wrote. ``The court is not to
decide whether a law is bad or good. The accused have committed an
offense in front of the eyes of the whole world and now they should
be punished.''
   The judge noted that the four sentenced were ``good citizens''
and suggested they serve their sentences doing public service and
not in prison.
   The implementation of the sentence was postponed until Aug. 4 to
enable the four to appeal.
   Amnon Zichrony, an attorney for the four, said that his clients,
Latif Dory, Yael Lotan, Reuven Kaminer and Eliezer Feiler, would
appeal the decision.
   ``I hope the severe sentence will give rise to public campaign
against this Draconic law,'' the radio quoted Dory as saying.
   Police prosecutor Raanan Ben-Yosef said the sentence would lead
to indictments against 16 other members of the group that met with
PLO officials in Romania.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
