<2ND_LINE>PM-Lightning Deaths,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man, Horse Killed by Lightning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKEECHOBEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lightning struck and killed a man and
the horse he was riding while rounding up cattle, authorities said.
   The death of 62-year-old Henry E. Lee Jr. was one of two in
Florida caused by lightning this week.
   Jason Cranmer, 10, was killed Sunday as he rode his bicycle
through a campground near Orlando.
   Lee, of Lake Wales, was a third-generation Floridian who always
wanted to be a cowboy, said his brother Alvin.
   ``He was a good Florida cracker cowboy and we liked him,'' said
Pat Wilson, president of the Latt Maxcy ranch property, which
covers thousands of acres in Okeechobee and Osceola counties.
   Lee, who was a ranch foreman and lived on the property, was on
open ground next to a drainage ditch leading to the Kissimmee River
when he was killed, authorities said.
   Wilson's son, Coot, who was working nearby, found Lee with his
feet still in the stirrups, authorities said.
   Lee's clothes were torn from the force of the lightning hitting
him, Medical Examiner Frederick Hobin said.
   Lee's brother said he loved horses and cows and had performed in
rodeos in his earlier years.
   ``He was an easy-going, lovable guy and he never got rowdy
unless you crossed him,'' he said. ``He died doing what he loved to
do.''
</TEXT>
