<DOCNO> AP880630-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-USBombers     06-30 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-US Bombers,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jane's Says U.S. Bombers With Cruise Missiles Coming To Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will deploy 51 F-111 bombers
armed with cruise nuclear missiles in Britain to replace land-based
missiles banned under the superpower arms control agreement, Jane's
Defense Weekly reported.
   Britain's Defense Ministry acknowledged in a statement, without
elaboration, that NATO was considering transferring U.S.-based,
long-range aircraft to Western Europe.
   But it said the deployment of air-launched cruise missiles in
Western Europe ``is not under consideration.''
   Lt. Col. Ed Neunherz, spokesman at U.S. Air Force European
headquarters at Ramstein, West Germany, said plans to adapt F-111s
to carry cruise missiles have been under consideration for several
years, but NATO has not given the final go-ahead.
   Jane's reported that Gen. William Kirk, commander-in-chief of
the U.S. Air Force in Europe, said the 51 F-111s ``would augment
the capability of striking targets deep in the Soviet Union from
their new bases in the U.K. (United Kingdom) when armed with
nuclear cruise missiles.''
   It was the first confirmation of NATO plans to update its
nuclear arsenal following the Intermediate Nuclear Forces treaty in
December, the magazine said in its issue to be published today.
   The treaty, ratified last month, provides for elimination of
1,800 Soviet and 800 Allied medium-range missiles over three years.
   Jane's said a fleet of F-111s will be transferred from Strategic
Air Command bases in New York and New Hampshire in late 1989 or
early 1990 to ``bolster NATO's flexible response strategy.''
   The U.S. Air Force keeps about 150 of the swing-wing supersonic
F-111s at Lakenheath and Upper Heyford air force bases in England.
   The F-111s are capable of carrying a wide range of nuclear
weapons. Such dual-capable aircraft and air-launched cruise
missiles are not prohibited by the INF treaty, which covers only
land-based missiles with a range from 300 miles to about 3,100
miles.
   The U.S. Air Force said Wednesday that Kirk confirmed in a June
2 interview with the Omaha, Neb., World-Herald that the 51 F-111s
will be transferred on the basis of a one-for-one swap with aging
F-111s already in Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
