<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0551EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-Torture     06-30 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Torture,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>44 Policemen Acquitted of Torture Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A criminal court today acquitted 44 police
officers of charges they tortured Moslem fundamentalists held in a
case linked to the assassination of President Anwar Sadat.
   It was the first time in Egypt's modern history that torture
charges were brought against policemen by a government that was in
power when the offenses were alleged to have taken place.
   The officers, ranging in rank up to brigadier, held posts in the
Interior Ministry's Prisons Administration and the State Security
Service. They were suspended for the duration of the trial that
began in December 1986.
   The defendants, relatives, friends and officers on duty in the
courthouse broke into applause and cheered after Suleiman Ayoub,
president of the three-man tribunal, read out the judgment. They
shouted ``Long live justice'' and ``Long live President (Hosni)
Mubarak.''
   The defendants would have faced penalties of three to 10 years
in prison if convicted.
   The case grew out of the 1982 trial of 300 Moslem
fundamentalists belonging to an underground group called Jihad, or
holy war.
   They were charged with an abortive attempt to overthrow the
government in the wake of Sadat's assassination by Moslem
extremists at a military parade in Cairo on Oct. 6, 1981.
   Mubarak succeeded Sadat.
   Jihad members were tried for riots and armed raids on police
installations in the southern city of Assiut that left 87 people
dead, 66 of them policemen.
   The disturbances occurred two days after Sadat's slaying and the
government said the riots were part of a coup attempt.
   Jihad members, in custody throughout their trial, claimed in
court they had been tortured by prison officers and state security
interrogators.
   In 1984, a state security court sentenced 107 Jihad members to
prison terms up to life at hard labor and acquitted the rest.
   In handing down that ruling, presiding Judge Abdel-Ghaffar
Mohammed Ahmed publicly demanded an investigation of torture claims
by the defendants.
   An investigation began in December 1984 and ended with the
indictment of 44 officers.
   Judge Adly Hussein, a member of the tribunal, told reporters
after today's session that the court had ``more than 130 reasons
for deciding on acquittal, foremost among them superficiality of
investigations and lack of evidence.''
   The court also threw out damages claims made by 26 of the
fundamentalist prisoners who alleged they had been tortured.
</TEXT>
