<2ND_LINE>PM-News Stand,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYC Errs in Razing Blind Vendor's News Stand; Refuses to Replace
It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's Sanitation Department accidentally
destroyed a news stand that a blind man has operated for 12 years,
and is refusing to build a new one in its place.
   The stand belonged to 68-year-old Rosario Civello, who served
about 500 customers a day from his spot in Brooklyn.
   The Sanitation Department had been sent to tear down an
abandoned stand across the street, but demolished Civello's by
mistake on Tuesday night, according to today's Daily News.
   ``It's tough to lose something I've had for so many years,''
Civello said. ``It's like somebody broke into my house.''
   Gary Walker, a spokesman for the Department of Consumer Affairs,
which licenses news stands, said: ``We cannot apologize enough.''
   However, city officials maintain that Civello's stand was
blocking a subway entrance anyway, and say he can take the
abandoned stand across the street, which would be moved to a new
site, the News said.
   Civello said his stand did not block the subway entrance. And he
said he doesn't want to work elsewhere because he'll lose business.
</TEXT>
