<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TVALayoffs 1stLd-Writethru a0503 06-30 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TVA Layoffs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0503,0731</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TVA To Lay Off 7,500 Workers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to include that 8 million people are served by
TVA.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SHARP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees streamed from the Tennessee
Valley Authority in a sea of pink clothing, symbolizing the slips
many of them carried as the nation's largest supplier of
electricity slashed its workforce by nearly a quarter.
   ``It's an awful day,'' said Deedra Sluder, a worker in the
employee relations office who, like many, had expected the layoffs.
``Our branch manager called us in one-by-one. He did it as best he
could. It was hard on him.''
   TVA Chairman Marvin Runyon on Wednesday announced that TVA will
lay off 7,500 of its 34,000 workers, or 22 percent, by October. He
said the cutbacks are necessary for the survival of the federal
utility, which operates in seven states and serves 8 million people.
   ``We look at our operation as one that's in very bad trouble
financially,'' Runyon said. ``The steps we're taking are the kind
of steps that you would expect someone who had a real financial
problem to take.
   ``I wish they could all keep their jobs. ... But the fact is,
we're starting a new way of doing business, and we had to make some
very tough, hard decisions.''
   Runyon, who became TVA chairman in January after serving as
chief executive officer of Nissan Motor Manufactur
new jobs.
   ``It does appear that the layoffs have been distributed among
all levels of TVA's employees,'' a statement from the senators
said. ``However, TVA has a responsibility to go all out to help
those employees.''
   Although employees have known about the layoffs for three
months, it was still a sad time for many at TVA's headquarters in
Knoxville and elsewhere. Many wore pink to represent the pink slips
they carried.
   Robert Stone in the office of nuclear power said the layoffs
were handled fairly well.
   ``The only thing was, they said they had been very communicative
toward the employees, and I feel like maybe we haven't heard quite
as much as our managers knew,'' he said.
   According to Runyon's announcement, about 4,000 full-time
salaried TVA employees were laid off, or 15.3 percent of the total.
   He said 1,800 contract employees, or 47 percent, were
eliminated, which should cut TVA's cost for contract services by
$143 million next year. And 1,700, or 23 percent, of the jobs paid
on an hourly basis were cut.
   Runyon said 889 managers would be laid off, reducing the ratio
of supervisors to employees from 1-to-7 to about 1-to-13.
   TVA was created in 1933 during the New Deal as a way of making
the Tennessee River more navigable, controlling floods and bringing
electricity and economic growth to a poor region. In addition to
Tennessee, it operates in Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, North
Carolina, Virginia and Kentucky.
   TVA embarked on an ambitious nuclear power program in the late
1960s and early 1970s, with plans to build 17 reactors. Five of
those reactors have operated, but all were shut down for more than
two years over management and safety concerns. Only one is
operating. Four others are under construction, and eight have been
mothballed at a cost of some $8 billion to TVA's ratepayers.
   The board also modified its contracts with TVA power
distributors and restructured its energy conservation program, and
changed the pay and benefits package for management level
employees. Managers' salaries will be frozen.
</TEXT>
