<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Scotus-Preschool     06-30 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Preschool,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Decision Raises Specter of New Round in McMartin Child Molest Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Supreme Court decision dealing with
testimony of young victims in sex abuse cases will likely spark a
new legal skirmish in the marathon McMartin Pre-School molestation
trial, a defense attorney said.
   A prosecutor disagreed, however, saying Wednesday's ruling in
Coy vs. Iowa, which held that victims and defendants must confront
each other in court, should have little impact on the year-old
trial.
   The McMartin trial is on a summer recess, and jurors are
scheduled to resume hearing testimony July 18.
   Raymond Buckey, 30, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 61,
are charged with 100 child molestations at their now-defunct
McMartin Pre-Schoool in Manhattan Beach. The case has been in the
Los Angeles courts for five years.
   The prosecution, which once involved 41 children, now focuses on
14 youngsters who have grown from toddlers to preteen-agers in the
years of legal proceedings. Nine children have testified at the
trial. One alleged victim is not expected to testify and four
others are scheduled to take the stand before the prosecution rests
its case, probably by September.
   Prosecutors dropped charges against five other teachers at the
school in 1986.
   The disagreement over significance of the Supreme Court decision
will surface in court July 11 when a hearing is scheduled on a
motion by prosecutors to allow use of videotaped preliminary
hearing testimony in place of a child who refuses to testify in
person at the trial.
   ``We will vigorously oppose that,'' defense attorney Danny Davis
said. ``We have a real confrontation problem. ... If a mother says
the child doesn't want to testify because they're frightened, does
that reduce the trial to a video show?''
   ``As far as I understand, it should not affect our case,''
Deputy District Attorney Roger Gunson said of the high court's
ruling, which severely limited state efforts to shield child
witnesses in sexual abuse trials.
   The high court overturned the conviction of a man who was
shielded by a one-way screen, which prevented child witnesses from
seeing him.
   Iowa, California and many other states have passed laws intended
to prevent children testifying at sex abuse trials from being
intimidated by the sight of defendants.
   The ruling ``casts serious doubt on the constitutionality'' of
California laws that allow children in molestation cases to testify
by videotape on closed-circuit television, said Steve White, the
state's chief assistant Attorney General.
   In the McMartin case, closed-circuit TV testimony was used
during the appearance of a single child at the preliminary hearing.
But the trial, which has been under way for more than a year, has
not used that device. All witnesses have testified in person.
   ``We have not at trial presented any witnesses where the
defendants could not see them or they could not see the
defendants,'' Gunson said, ``and we do not intend to use such
devices with the remaining children.''
</TEXT>
