<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Suriname-Clash     06-30 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Suriname-Clash,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels, Soldiers Clash, Threatening Peace Negotiations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEO MORPURGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-government guerrillas attacked
a military post in eastern Suriname, killing three soldiers and
wounding three others, the Suriname News Agency reported.
   The clash could threaten a cease-fire agreement between rebels
and government representatives, who met in neighboring French
Guiana on Tuesday.
   The soldiers were ambushed Wednesday near the eastern town of
Patamacca as they were drawing water at a pump, the state agency
reported.
   Rebel leader Ronny Brunswijk told a radio station and friends in
Paramaribo by radio on Wednesday that heavy fighting was still
going on since the army attacked his troops in Patamacca last
Friday. He said government soldiers had surrounded his troops,
wounding several.
   Army spokesman Commander Badressein Sital said Tuesday similar
allegations made by Brunswijk Monday were ``a big lie.''
   Brunswijk and government delegates signed an agreement that may
put an end to the guerrilla war that has ravaged this former Dutch
colony for nearly three years. The talks were mediated by the head
of the Council of Christian Churches, Roman Catholic Bishop
Aloisius Zichem.
   Army Commander Desi Bouterse repeated last week that the army
would not negotiate with terrorists but would not prevent the
government from doing so.
   Brunswijk, a former army private, began his attacks on military
and economic installations in the summer of 1986, when Bouterse was
president.
   Bouterse took power by coup in 1980. President Ramsewak Shankar
was elected president last November.
   Shankar's government is treating Brunswijk as a rebel against
the former regime, rather than as a terrorist and criminal, as
Bouterse had done.
   ``The president (Shankar) is also our president and we put our
trust in his government,'' Brunswijk said after the talks in French
Guiana, where he claims to have the support of an estimated 10,000
Surinamese refugees.
   After meeting with representatives of the Council of Christian
Churches to receive their report of the peace talks, President
Shankar met Wednesday with Bouterse. No information on their
meeting has been released.
</TEXT>
