<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NBC-Writers     06-30 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NBC-Writers,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Announces Contingency Plans for `Writer-Proof' Fall Schedule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC says it will dust off scripts from
old shows and refilm them with new actors this fall, but striking
writers warned that the strategy would fail because ``there's no
such thing as a writer-proof script.''
   The network will use recycled scripts, rejected pilots, foreign
and ``writer-proof'' work as part of a four-point plan to deal with
the strike, NBC Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff said
Wednesday.
   ``We at NBC have worked too hard dragging ourselves out of the
ratings cellar to sit back and let our efforts be dashed because of
the strike,'' Tartikoff said at a news conference that was sent by
satellite to NBC affiliate stations. ``We have been sitting back
patiently watching the negotiations but today we are taking
action.''
   The network will announce a revised fall schedule within 10
days, he said.
   ``We want to let both the public and our advertisers know that
come hell or high water we're going to deliver original shows in
the fall,'' Tartikoff said.
   But a spokeswoman for the 9,000-member Writers Guild of America
questioned that resolution.
   ``They're not going to fill their fall schedule without WGA
members,'' Cheryl Rhoden said. ``Even scripts that are already
written take rewrite work. There is no such thing as a writer-proof
script.''
   The guild struck the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television
Producers on March 7.
   Tartikoff noted that NBC was in better shape than the other
networks because its coverage of the Summer Olympics in Seoul,
Korea and baseball's World Series would delay its fall schedule
anyway.
   But NBC was fast approaching the time when, without contingency
plans, it would be unable to put a fall schedule on the air,
Tartikoff said.
   The four-point plan would include:
   _Original shows of existing series that have signed interim
agreements with the striking writers, such as ``The Cosby Show,''
``A Different World,'' ``Highway to Heaven'' and ``ALF.''
   _``Writer-proof'' programming such as ``Unsolved Mysteries'' and
a presentational variety show that does not require writers.
   _The purchase of British and Canadian comedy scripts and
passed-over pilot scripts in which additional episode scripts had
been ordered but never filmed.
   _The revival of old shows that are recast and filmed again using
the original scripts.
   The NBC programming department was sifting through nearly 500
properties looking for possible shows that could be put on the air,
Tartikoff said.
   He defended the plan to revive old shows and said they were not
junk.
   ``It would be much easier to simply buy the golden oldie reruns
than to film the new shows,'' he said.
   ``The example I've been giving to the studios is suppose that
Bruce Willis had not gone into `Moonlighting.' You could get eight
to 10 old Richie Brockleman'' scripts, a short-lived spinoff of
``The Rockford Files,'' and re-do them with Willis, he said.
   ``We all know that a lot of recycling goes on in this business
anyway. Look at Broadway. Without revivals half of Broadway would
be dark. The `Alfred Hitchcock Presents' show we revived two years
ago had 75 percent of the old original scripts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0082 </DOCNO>
