<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Prisoners     06-30 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Prisoners,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Releases 46 Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today released 46
political prisoners and promised that the status of other
imprisoned dissidents would be reviewed later.
   Along with 453 other ordinary criminals, prison authorities
said, the 46 prisoners were released from various prisons.
   The release came on the first anniversary of President Roh
Tae-woo's promise to undertake democratic reforms. Ever since it
came to power, Roh's government has been trying to deflate
controversy over political prisoners.
   Among those freed today was prominent dissident Kim Kun-tae, who
recently received the Robert F. Kennedy Award for Human Rights. He
was sentenced to five years imprisonment in 1986 for inciting
unrest. International human rights groups have campaigned for his
release.
   Kim was released from a prison in the southern city of Kimchon
as about 30 relatives and friends welcomed him. ``Release all
political prisoners,'' they chanted.
   The Justice Ministry said the dissidents were released ``in line
with the government's continuing efforts to promote democracy in an
atmosphere of national harmony.''
   But opposition groups, which claim there are more than 600
prisoners, demanded the immediate release of other dissidents,
charging President Roh with failing to carry out some of his
promises for broad reforms.
   The opposition said the dissidents were imprisoned for political
beliefs or anti-government activity. But the government contends
they committed violent crimes or violated national security laws.
   Today the three opposition parties agreed to move a resolution
urging the release of all political prisoners. The opposition
stripped the government party of its parliamentary majority in
elections in April.
   Among others released today were five labor activists, a number
of radical students and five people arrested in December on charges
of leading violent protests against alleged government vote rigging
in presidential elections.
   Also released were 11 Koreans from Japan, convicted of spying
for communist North Korea. The 11 were arrested while visiting
South Korea in the late 1970s.
   Today's action left only 81 political offenders in prison,
government officials said. They said there also are about 480
others awaiting trial on similar charges.
   The parole coincided with the first anniversary of the so-called
``grand declaration for democracy'' made by Roh on June 29, 1987,
when nationwide protests forced the government to accept demands
for democratic reforms. He subsequently won the presidential
election.
   Since last year, hundreds of political prisoners have been
released in several amnesties.
   Ministry officials said the cases of dissidents still in jail
would be reviewed on a monthly basis, and they might be released
later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
