<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-30 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls But Off Early Lows, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in European trading this morning
but was recovering from its early lows as the market waited to find
out whether the West German central bank will raise interest rates.
   Gold prices were higher in moderate trading.
   The dollar dropped in East Asian trading on profit-taking on the
dollar's recent gains, dealers in Europe said.
   Traders said they expected the market to remain quiet until the
Deutsche Bundesbank's top policy-making body, the central bank
council, decides whether or not to raise its official discount
rate, the rate it charges to commercial banks.
   Dealers said they expect the council to vote to lift the
discount rate by half a percentage point to 3 percent and to
increase domestic money market rates by a quarter percentage point.
   ``All eyes are on the Bundesbank, and there's going to be little
activity until the decision is announced or not announced,'' said a
Frankfurt trader.
   One senior trader with an Italian bank in Milan said the dollar
could fall in reaction to a rise in West German interest rates.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.20 yen to a closing 132.20 yen. Later, in
London, it rose to 133.40 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates:
   _ 1.8205 West German marks, down from 1.8290
   _ 1.5098 Swiss francs, down from 1.5155
   _ 6.1375 French francs, down from 6.1635
   _ 2.0492 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0545
   _ 1,349.50 Italian lire, down from 1,350.75
   _ 1.2150 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2173
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7075, stronger
than $1.7060 late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $436.80 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $436.85, both up from Wednesday's late bid of
$433.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $436.75, up from $433.50 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 86 cents to close at a bid
$439.18.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.64 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's $6.66.
</TEXT>
