<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Musavi     06-30 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Musavi,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Reinstates Musavi As Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Hussein Musavi was
re-elected by Parliament today and warned that Iran must prepare
for ``all-out struggle'' against Iraq and its other enemies, Iran's
official news agency reported.
   He was reinstated for a fourth term with an overwhelming vote of
confidence by the Majlis, or Parliament, the Islamic Republic News
Agency said.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said 204 of the 217 deputies
present in the Majlis voted for Musavi. Eight voted against him and
five abstained.
   The remainder of the 270 members apparently did not attend the
session.
   The radical Musavi's re-election had been expected following
Parliamentary elections in April and May in which his supporters
and their allies made sweeping gains at the expense of conservative
factions.
   Musavi, 44, has been prime minister since 1981. He said he will
introduce members of his new cabinet in the Majlis next week,
though he said last week that he would be making few changes.
   In a speech before today's vote, Musavi declared that a
``massive mobilization by Iran's enemies is a warning that we must
prepare for an ... all-out struggle against them.''
   He stressed: ``We are faced with an historic confrontation, the
most important manifestation of which has emerged in the
warfronts'' with Iraq.
   He did not elaborate. But he was clearly referring to a string
of Iraqi victories since mid-April in which the Iranians have been
driven out of three of their four bridgeheads on Iraqi soil in a
dramatic turnaround in the nearly 8-year-old conflict.
   The Iranians also claim the United States is actively helping
the Iraqis. The U.S. Navy sank or crippled six Iranian naval craft
in a series of clashes April 18.
   The main objective of the Iraqi-U.S. campaign is to destroy the
Iranian revolution, Musavi said.
   But he declared that Iran is ``potentially capable of putting up
a durable resistance against an all-out economic and arms embargo
by the Great Satan,'' Iran's catchword for the United States.
   Without mentioning any figures, Musavi said the government's
financial and foreign exchange resources ``are limited.'' But he
said that if they are not being used ``to full capacity at present,
they will be in the future.''
   Iran's foreign exchange holdings are estimated at around $5.5
billion.
   They were about $7.5 billion in 1986. But Tehran had to draw on
them heavily to compensate for the collapse of oil prices that year.
   Musavi said Iran's arms industry, built up over the last two
years to sidestep arms embargoes, now produces enough hardware and
ammunition to save the country $50 million a year, IRNA reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
