<DOCNO> AP880630-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0802EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugTesting     06-30 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Testing,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Testing Proposed For Mass Transit Workers, Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mandatory, random drug testing of transportation
workers is ``the only effective, reliable method'' for weeding out
drug abusers, says Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley, but unions
disagree.
   At a news conference Wednesday, Burnley announced a
Transportation Department proposal for such testing among more than
350,000 mass transit workers, merchant seafarers and pipeline
industry workers. The proposal is in line with Burnley's earlier
call for testing in the airline, railroad and trucking industries.
   Burnley said he hoped to have rules imposed in all six sectors
by the end of the year.
   If enacted as proposed, the rules would require workers
throughout the transportation industry to submit to drug tests
before they are employed, at random intervals while they are
working, whenever there is probable cause to believe they are
abusing drugs, and whenever they are involved in an accident.
   ``Nobody has a right in this country ... to have a job in which
they can put the lives of other people in mass transportation at
risk through narcotics ingestion,'' Burnley said Wednesday.
   But transportation unions denounced the proposal as overkill.
   ``Obviously, nobody who's taking drugs and drinking on the job
should be operating a train or a bus,'' said Jim Gannon, spokesman
for the Transport Workers Union representing 100,000 mass transit
workers. ``But I think the percentage of those people is so low
that just to approach it in a Gestapo-type manner is not right.''
   Gannon said the TWU supports mandatory drug testing before
employment, during annual medical examinations and when there is
probable cause to suspect drug use.
   A spokesman for the Seafarers International Union, which
represents 18,000 deep-sea sailors, said he couldn't comment on
Burnley's proposals until he had seen them. But, he said,
``generally, we have not supported mandatory, random testing.''
   Burnley called mandatory, random testing ``the only effective,
reliable method'' of enforcement, and said the benefits outweigh
the loss of privacy to workers.
   The department's proposal will be subject to 60 days of public
comment before final rules are drafted, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
