<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0831EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Gangs-Drugs     06-30 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gangs-Drugs,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gang Members Tell Task Force That Death Penalty is Not a Deterrent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police sweeps and threats of the gas chamber
cannot stop street gangs from killing to protect their highly
profitable drug trade, two gang members testified.
   ``When I'm out there doing my thing, I don't think about the
consequences. I won't think about the death penalty at the time
because I'm just thinking about getting away,'' a gang member
identified by the pseudonym John told a state task force meeting
Wednesday to plot a war on gangs and drug trafficking.
   Testimony from John and another member of the city's
predominantly black Crips gang, identified by the pseudonym Jack,
highlighted the first day of a two-day hearing.
   The meeting followed a night of violence in which 11 people were
wounded in shootings, many of them gang-related.
   The testimony was piped by loudspeaker into the hearing room at
the County Hall of Administration, while the two men remained
concealed in an adjacent room. The two said they were arrested more
than 10 times each on such charges as robbery and illegal firearms
possession.
   John, 28, became a gang member at age 10 and has spent three
years in state prison and four years in California Youth Authority
facilities.
   His death penalty comment was in response to a question by task
force chairman Robert Philibosian, former county district attorney.
   John also said the Police Department's anti-gang sweeps were
useless, although they have resulted in 16,000 arrests so far this
year, 8,000 of whom were gang members.
   ``As soon as you arrest one, it will be replaced with another,''
John said.
   Other witnesses said gangs had become so sophisticated they hold
out-of-state seminars on expanding their drug empire.
   Jack and John said they were enticed by a narcotics business
that can net them $1,000 a day, but that competition had become so
fierce in Los Angeles that gang members were exporting their
illegal trade elsewhere.
   ``Bakersfield, Sacramento, Seattle, Texas, Dallas and Houston.
It's really going on up there, that's where it's at. Texas is the
hot spot,'' John said. ``You take $100 worth of dope, make $600 or
$700 off of it.''
   Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl Gates suggested incarceration as
a solution to the gang problem.
   ``Let's take those old (military) bases, put some barbed wire
and land mines outside it. Why not?'' he said.
   The chief said the LAPD has found gang members living in
million-dollar houses, while Lt. Larry Carter of the suburban
Inglewood Police Department said a local gang member was arrested
in Seattle with $35,000 in his pocket.
   Called urban terrorists by Philibosian, county street gangs
accounted for 387 slayings in 1987 and more than 140 murders
already this year. Authorities said gangs are using such
military-style weapons as Uzi machine guns, AK-47s and AR-15
assault rifles.
   ``They go out like cowards and shoot little kids and innocent
people. They have no conscience and concern. It's a hideous thing
like you found in Nazi Germany. And we have it here. And our people
have to live with it,'' Gates said.
</TEXT>
