<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Egyptian-Weapons     06-30 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egyptian-Weapons,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Indicted on Illegal Weapons Technology Export Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rocket scientist, a marketing
representative and an Egyptian army colonel have been indicted on
charges of illegally exporting technology used in sophisticated
missile weapons, authorities said.
   Federal grand jury indictments were handed up Wednesday against
Aerojet Solid Propulsion Co. rocket specialist Abdelkader Helmy,
40, of El Dorado Hills; James Huffman, 46, of Lexington, Ohio, the
Midwest marketing representative of Teledyne, McCormick, Selph, a
defense aerospace company based in Hollister; and Egyptian army
Col. Hussam Yossef of Salzburg, Austria.
   The indictments followed the arrests Friday of Helmy and Huffman.
   Huffman, arrested in Indian River, Md., posted $100,000 bond
Wednesday and was released from custody.
   Helmy was ordered held without bail Wednesday by U.S. Magistrate
Esther Mix in Sacramento, who cited the serious nature of the
alleged offenses, Helmy's ties to Egypt, and the strength of the
evidence against him.
   California U.S. Attorney David Levi said his office plans to
seek extradition of Yossef from Austria. A spokesman for Levi said
she didn't know if Yossef was in custody.
   The indictments charge the three with illegally exporting about
430 pounds of a carbon composite material to Europe and Egypt
without obtaining the necessary licenses.
   The special carbon material has a low visibility level to radar
and is used extensively in high-speed aircraft, missiles and
rockets. It is on the federal restricted list and requires special
licenses to be exported.
   The suspects also were charged with money laundering because
they allegedly wired funds into the United States for the purpose
of promoting an unlawful activity, Levi said.
   If convicted, each of the accused face maximum prison sentences
of 95 years and possible fines totaling several million dollars,
said Levi.
</TEXT>
