<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gephardt-Veep     06-30 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gephardt-Veep,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Once A Rival, Now A Prospective Running Mate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0447 to correct category code to `p'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri rode a
$48,000 Hyundai and a message of economic nationalism to fleeting
stardom in the Democratic presidential campaign.
   To the suprise of many, Gephardt transformed himself from a
congressman little known outside of Capitol Hill to winner of the
Iowa caucuses. Now he is among those mentioned as possible running
mates for Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   But Gephardt, 47, says he doesn't think he'll be asked to join
the ticket and predicts the nominee will ``look to the South to
fill that bill.''
   ``I don't expect to be asked, but if I were asked I would do it
because I want to help Gov. Dukakis win the presidency and the
Democrats win the presidency in 1988. And if he feels I can help in
that way, I'll do it,'' says Gephardt.
   He declines to say whether he has discussed the No. 2 spot with
Dukakis or any of his campaign aides.
   Those who point to Gephardt suggest he could provide Dukakis
with needed strength in the midwestern Farm Belt. They also say his
skills as a campaigner, one who demonstrated he could excite voters
with his populist ``It's your fight too'' oratory, would offer a
counterbalance to the governor's staid demeanor.
   But Dukakis and Gephardt clashed on issues during the campaign,
particularly on trade, and some political professionals say that
those differences could hurt the Democratic ticket by providing
Republicans with plenty of ammunition for the general election.
   It was the Dukakis camp that broadcast perhaps the most pointed
attack on Gephardt. A television commercial pointed to Gephardt's
``flip-flops'' on issues, including abortion, and showed an
acrobat, who looked like Gephardt, doing somersaults.
   Some Democrats also worry that Dukakis could anger supporters of
the Rev. Jesse Jackson if he fills the No. 2 spot with one of his
former rivals and doesn't offer it to Jackson.
   Gephardt, serving his sixth term in the House representing a
mostly blue-collar district in St. Louis, wears a Capitol Hill
reputation as a leader among a new generation of House Democrats.
He is known as a legislator's legislator, who excels in the molding
of compromises.
   He also has demonstrated a knack for positioning himself on the
cutting edge of issues. He and Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., were
early advocates of an overhaul of the federal income tax system.
   But Gephardt made his mark on the campaign trail for his tough
talk on trade.
   He championed a proposal for mandatory retaliation against
foreign competitors failing to lower their trade surpluses with the
United States. Critics, including Dukakis, denounced it as
protectionism. The proposal, initially approved by the House, was
ejected from the trade bill eventually passed by Congress and
vetoed by President Reagan.
   Gephardt won the Iowa caucuses after bouncing back from
single-digit, fourth place standings in opinion polls six weeks
before the contest.
   His prescription for recovery was a sharply anti-establishment
theme in his speeches and a television blitz featuring an
advertisement with Gephardt criticizing Korea's tariffs on American
automobiles. The candidate vowed in the ad to retaliate if trade
barriers didn't disappear: ``How many Americans are going to pay
$48,000 for one of their Hyundais?''
   But Gephardt's victory in farm country proved to be his
brightest moment in the political sun. He finished second in New
Hampshire, received a brief boost with a victory in South Dakota,
but ran low on money and was buried in the Super Tuesday primaries
and caucuses on March 8. He abandoned the race on March 28, after
limping to a third-place finish in the Michigan caucuses.
   Before entering the presidential race, Gephardt was known as a
centrist or moderate, even conservative on some social issues. He
once backed anti-abortion constitutional amendments and sponsored
legislation to prohibit busing of school children for
desegregation. He no longer supports either, however, saying there
are more effective ways of achieving the same results.
   Critics say Gephardt has become more liberal because of his
national political aspirations. Gephardt says the changes reflect
growth and flexibility.
   He arrived in Congress in 1977 after coming up through the ranks
in St. Louis politics, where he was one of several activist
Democratic aldermen called the ``Young Turks.''
   He earned a coveted seat on the tax-writing Ways and Means
Committee as a freshman. Since 1985, Gephardt has served as the
chairman of the House Democratic Caucus, the No. 4 leadership spot.
