<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IntegratedPool     06-30 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Integrated Pool,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blacks, Whites Swim Together As Town Reopens Pool After 23 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-three years after this town closed
both its swimming pools rather than integrate them, a single pool
for everyone was opened to the cheers of blacks and whites alike.
   ``This pool is going to get integrated in a few minutes. George
and I are going to integrate it,'' said Fred Edwards, who is white
and served as an alderman in 1954 when the Redbud Park pool was
constructed specifically for blacks.
   The Redbud Park pool in southwest Canton and another pool in the
northwest part of town were closed in 1965 when black residents
tried to integrate the public facilities.
   Edwards and 77-year-old George Washington, who is black, jumped
into a new pool at Redbud Park simultaneously Wednesday.
   ``It was a long time coming. It was something we had to do and
was needed,'' Alderman Jewel Williams said. ``We had pools, and
they were closed. That should never have happened.''
   As city officials gave their speeches, Edwards and Washington
waited poolside for their symbolic dive. Edwards wore black socks
as protection against the concrete, made almost unbearable by the
105-degree heat.
   The 25-meter pool was built on the site of a trash dump, about
20 yards from the old pool site.
   The dedication plaque for the old pool still stands. It reads:
``Dedicated to the colored citizens of Canton. Project of the Negro
Chamber of Commerce.''
   ``It's bringing people together,'' Alderman John Taylor said
about the new pool. ``I think we are doing something for everybody.
I'm so proud of this pool.''
</TEXT>
