<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Armenia     06-30 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disputed Region Might be Turned Over to Gorbachev's Home District</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials are considering turning disputed
Nagorno-Karabakh over to Mikhail S. Gorbachev's home region until
the demands of two ethnic groups can be resolved, a delegate to the
Communist Party conference said today.
   Eduard M. Dzhrbashyan, director of the Institute of Literature
of Armenia's Academy of Sciences, said the proposal was one of
three under consideration.
   Armenians, who make up the majority of Nagorno-Karabakh's
population, have been demanding since February that the region be
taken out of the republic of Azerbaijan and be annexed to
neighboring Armenia. The Armenian parliament endorsed the demand,
but Azerbaijan rejected it.
   Nagorno-Karabakh's legislature proposed a compromise June 21 in
a move to calm tensions between Armenians and Azerbaijanis that
have led to strikes, demonstrations and riots. The legislature
suggested turning the region over to the central government in
Moscow until a long-term solution is found.
   At a Moscow news conference, Dzhrbashyan offered another
temporary compromise. He said Nagorno-Karabakh, classified as an
autonomous region of Azerbaijan, should be put under the control of
the Russian republic, specifically of the Stavropol region of
southern Russia.
   Dzhrbashyan did not make clear who was considering the
compromise, but his mention of it as a conference delegate
indicated it had some official support.
   Gorbachev was born in a farming village in the Stavropol region
in 1931. After completing law school in Moscow in 1955, he returned
to his home district along with wife Raisa and worked there for 23
years, serving successively as head of the Communist youth league,
city party boss and party chief in the region, which is about the
size of South Carolina.
   Sergei A. Ambartsumyan, head of Yerevan University in Armenia's
capital and a conference delegate, also mentioned at the news
conference the possibility of temporarily transferring
Nagorno-Karabakh to the Russian republic.
   Grant M. Voskanyan, Armenia's president, told the news
conference he is on a commission of the conference that is drafting
the resolution and that it contains no specific proposals for
resolving the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute. But he said the party's
Central Committee recommended the conference discuss ``perfecting
federation of the country'' and expanding the rights of republics.
   Voskanyan refused to endorse any of the proposed solutions to
the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute.
   ``The question is extremely complicated because two union
republics have taken practically opposite decisions,'' Voskanyan
said. ``In such a situation, governmental wisdom to resolve the
issue ... in the interests of all people is demanded of our
republic and all of us.''
   The Communist Party conference is scheduled to adopt a
resolution outlining policy toward the country's more than 100
ethnic groups.
</TEXT>
