<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Pipeline     06-30 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Pipeline,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Become Involved in California Dispute Over Oil
Pipelines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to become
involved in a California dispute over the power of cities to charge
fees to companies that operate oil pipelines under city streets.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that Santa
Monica, Calif., may charge Shell Oil Co. $237,000 a year to carry
crude oil through 3.9 miles of underground pipeline within the city.
   While a lower court ruling in the case largely favored the city,
Santa Monica officials as well as Shell asked the high court to
intervene because one important aspect of the lower court decision
exposed the city to suits for restricting interstate commerce
unlawfully.
   Santa Monica has permitted Shell Oil and its former owners to
use the portion of the pipeline within the city limits since 1941.
The 3.9-mile segment is part of a pipeline stretching 82 miles from
Ventura County to Shell's Wilmington refinery in Los Angeles County.
   Shell transports more than 32,000 barrels of crude oil each day
through the pipeline.
   Shell had been paying Santa Monica $1,029 a year to use the
pipeline within the city until the company's lease expired in 1981.
   Since then, the company and city officials have disagreed over
the fee.
   Shell at one point agreed to pay up to $12,500 a year. But the
city insisted on $237,000 with annual adjustments for inflation.
   The oil company has been permitted to use the pipeline for
around $10,000 a year pending the outcome of the court battle.
   Shell filed a federal lawsuit that said the $237,000 fee
violates the Constitution because it ``places an unreasonable
burden on interstate commerce.''
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last October dismissed the
company's lawsuit. But the appeals court, stopping short of a
complete victory for Santa Monica, said cities are subject to the
Constitution's commerce clause restrictions in such cases.
   The appeals court rejected the city's argument that it should be
immune from attack under the commerce clause because the city is
acting as a ``market participant'' rather than ``market regulator.''
   The fact that Santa Monica has a contractual relationship with
Shell does not make the city a market participant insulated from
commerce clause scrutiny, the appeals court said.
   ``In deciding whether, or on what terms, to grant a franchise
for the use of public streets the city may not burden interstate
commerce in a manner that violates the commerce clause,'' the
appeals court said.
   But the appeals court said the franchise fee the city seeks to
charge Shell is reasonable because it ``is based on an evenhanded''
appraisal of the value of the property adjacent to the pipeline.
   The cases are Shell vs. Santa Monica, 87-1685, and Santa Monica
vs. Shell, 87-1841.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
