<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0472 06-30 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,740</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Dukakis economic speech; pick up 7th
graf pvs bgng ``On Wednesday...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McCOOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today blamed the Reagan
administration for economic policies that have left average family
income ``right where it was 20 years ago.''
   Dukakis told employees at a Reynolds aluminum plant that the
average weekly wage for jobs lost between 1979 and 1985 was $440,
while the average weekly pay for new jobs during that period was
only $270. The numbers that Dukakis used did not take into account
the last three years of economic recovery.
   ``Today there are more Americans working than at any time in our
history, but average family income in America is right where it was
20 years ago, even though there's been a huge increase in the
number of families where both parents work,'' the certain
Democratic presidential nominee said in remarks prepared for
delivery at the plant, the largest manufacturing facility under one
roof in Illinois.
   ``Too many of our families are struggling to hold on, challenged
by change, anxious about their jobs, burdened by the rising costs
of health care and housing and college tuition, troubled by the
lack of quality affordable child care,'' Dukakis said.
   As Dukakis began a second day of campaigning in the troubled
Midwest, he kept his counsel on his search for a vice presidential
nominee.
   ``I can't say at this point if I'm close or not so close,'' the
Democratic presidential candidate said Wednesday after meeting with
members of Congress, including four senators often mentioned as
potential running mates.
   At a farm in Norwalk, Iowa, Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois, one of
Dukakis' defeated rivals in the fight for the Democratic
presidential nomination, offered this praise for the Massachusetts
governor:
   ``There's not a phony bone in Mike Dukakis' body. He's genuine.''
   On Wednesday, Dukakis told farmers gathered at the 160-acre farm
of Howard Hughes, ``It's good to be home.'' Dukakis recalled the
months he spent campaigning before the Iowa caucuses last winter
only to finish third behind Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri and
Simon.
   Hughes and other Midwest growers face heavy losses from a
prolonged drought.
   But as Dukakis spoke the sky was obscured by thick dark clouds
and the ground was damp from rain the night before.
   The corn Dukakis inspected in one of Hughes' fields towered at
least a foot above the head of the 5-foot 8-inch governor.
   ``That corn looks awfully good over there,'' said Simon. ``You
can't judge that by it's being green, that doesn't mean it will
produce anything. Don't get any false impression even though that
looks better than a lot of corn in Illinois and South Dakota and
everywhere else.''
   But this healthier looking corn was only four miles from the end
of the runway at the Des Moines airport, making it a convenient
stop on the candidate's five-state Midwest swing.
   Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said Midwest farmers have lost 10
percent to 15 percent of their corn crop and stand to lose much
more if the drought continues.
   ``In North Dakota and some parts of South Dakota, it's the worst
drought since 1934,'' said the senator, who, along with Simon and
Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa, flew to the Midwest with Dukakis.
   One of the senators Dukakis met with on Wednesday was Sam Nunn
of Georgia, a favorite of many Southern Democrats who believe Nunn
would help Dukakis throughout their region.
   But the senator told Dukakis he wasn't interested in the second
spot on the Democratic ticket.
   During an hour-long meeting during which they discussed other
possible choices, Nunn said he told Dukakis ``I was still not
interested in the vice presidency.''
   The Georgian, who is chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, said his feelings about the vice presidency ``had
absolutely nothing to do with Gov. Dukakis.''
   Others with whom Dukakis met privately were Sens. John Glenn of
Ohio, Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, and Bob Graham of Florida, all of
whom have been mentioned as among the most prominent potential
choices.
   ``Things have a way of sorting themselves out,'' said Dukakis.
``We're making progress.''
   During his Midwest campaign tour, Dukakis was expected to be
joined by Glenn in Ohio and Rep. Lee Hamilton of Indiana in his
home state. Hamilton also is considered a top contender to join
Dukakis on the Democratic ticket.
</TEXT>
