<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-CableCopyright     06-30 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Cable Copyright,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Way Cable TV Operators Pay Copyright Royalties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand the way
cable television operators pay copyright royalties for
retransmitting broadcast programming.
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments that
the the U.S. Copyright Office is overcharging the cable industry by
at least $40 million a year.
   The payment system had been challenged by Cablevision Co., a
cable television operator in New York and New Jersey, and the
National Cable Television Association.
   Under the Copyright Act of 1976, cable television systems are
entitled, under a ``compulsory license,'' to retransmit copyright
broadcast programming to cable subscribers. In return, the cable
systems must pay royalties into a Copyright Royalty Tribunal for
distribution to copyright owners who file claims.
   Failure to pay a government-established fee by a cable operator
retransmitting programs from over-the-air television stations is
deemed a copyright infringement.
   Each cable system must pay a fee equal to a ``specified
percentage of the gross receipts ... for the basic service of
providing secondary transmissions of primary broadcast
transmitters.''
   At issue in the dispute acted on today is the definition of
``gross receipts'' under the 1976 law.
   Cablevision sued in 1983, contending that the royalties fee
should be based only on revenue from retransmission of local
broadcast signals _ and not on revenue from cable-originated
stations such as ESPN and CNN and so-called superstations such as
WTBS in Atlanta and WGN from Chicago that may be included in a
cable system's ``basic service.''
   Cablevision had been threatened by the Motion Picture
Association of America, a group of copyright owners, with possible
infringement lawsuits for underpaying royalty fees.
   The MPAA filed counterclaims, contending that Cablevision had
infringed on the copyrights held by the association's members.
   U.S. District Judge June L. Green here rejected the
interpretation of ``gross receipts'' that was favored by the MPAA
and had been adopted by the Copyright Office.
   But the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here reversed the judge's
ruling last Jan. 5. The appeals court ruled that the Copyright
Office's interpretation was entitled to judicial deference, and
ordered Judge Green to restudy the MPAA's claims for higher royalty
fees from Cablevision.
   In its Supreme Court appeal, lawyers for Cablevision argued that
the Copyright Office lacks the authority to issue a binding
regulation on how royalty fees should be calculated.
   The National Cable Television Association's appeal made the same
argument.
   The appeals said annual copyright royalties paid by the cable
industry exceed $100 million, and that the Copyright Office's
regulation on calculating royalty-fee liability ``cost the cable
industry an additional $40 million in this past year alone.''
   The Federal Communications Commission recently approved a policy
that could alter significantly copyright considerations for cable
operators.
   The policy would let local, over-the-air television stations buy
exclusive rights to syndicated programs. Cable systems that
transmit the same programs in a local station's viewing area would
have to black out the shows or substitute other programs.
   The cases are Cablevision Co. vs. Motion Picture Association of
America, 87-1642, and National Cable Television Association vs.
Columbia Pictures Industries, 87-1814.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0112 </DOCNO>
