<2ND_LINE>PM-Captive Women, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0521,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accused Killer Beaten While Jury Deliberates Fate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The jury ...,' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
deliberations resuming. SUBS 7th graf, `Heidnik and ...,' with 1
graf to CORRECT that assailant was murder suspect, not convicted
murderer. Contents of 6th graf may be offensive.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of murdering two of six
kidnapped women he imprisoned in a basement ``house of horrors''
was attacked by two other inmates while a jury deliberated the
charges against him, officials said.
   Gary Heidnik, 44, suffered only bruises in Wednesday's attack,
which occurred in a holding cell one floor above where the jury was
meeting.
   ``The guards told me he took the fetal position when they
knocked him down and he didn't fight back,'' said Heidnick's
attorney, A. Charles Peruto, who argued in court that his client
was insane. ``He's upset. But he's going to have to get used to it
if he gets sent to a prison.''
   The jury Wednesday spent 3{ hours deliberating before Common
Pleas Judge Lynne Abraham sent them back to their hotel ``to get
some rest and come back refreshed'' this morning. The panel resumed
work shortly before 9 a.m.
   Heidnik was arrested in 1987 after a captive escaped and alerted
police. He is accused of luring women to his basement, where he
chained them and raped them repeatedly in hopes of breeding a
``superior race.''
   He used a chain saw to cut up one corpse and then fed the
remains mixed with dog food to the other women, according to police
and trial testimony. The body of the second woman was found in the
woods in New Jersey.
   Heidnik and his assailants were together at lunchtime when he
was punched several times, said Sheriff's Office spokeswoman Janet
Pina. No charges against the men _ a murder suspect and a robbery
suspect _ were filed.
   On Wednesday, the judge took nearly three hours to outline the
19 charges against Heidnik to the jury, and explained all the
possible verdicts, among them innocent by reason of insanity and
guilty but mentally ill. The charges included murder, kidnapping,
rape, aggravated assault and involuntary deviate sexual intercourse.
   The panel was chosen in Pittsburgh because the judge said
pretrial publicity here hampered the selection of impartial jurors.
   The prosecution said it would seek the death penalty if it gets
a first-degree murder conviction.
   After Wednesday's attack, the judge advised sheriff's deputies
to keep Heidnik in a room designated for psychiatric prisoners and
to try to keep him segregated.
   It was the second time Heidnik has been attacked since his
arrest in March 1987, when one of his captive women escaped and
brought police to the so-called ``House of Horrors.''
   Heidnik later tried to commit suicide and since then he has been
kept in isolation and on a suicide watch.
</TEXT>
