<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Vatican-Lefebvre 1stLd-Writethru a0553 06-30 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vatican-Lefebvre, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0553,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Confirms Excommunication of Lefebvre and Bishops</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with explanation of excommunication, reax,
quotes. No pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican today announced the
excommunication of Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre and four bishops he
consecrated.
   A statement read by Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro cited
church law for the excommunications, noting the prohibition on
consecrating bishops without papal approval.
   In such cases, the excommunication is automatic, requiring no
formal act by the Vatican. Only the pope can lift the sanction,
Navarro said.
   The statement, made shortly after Lefebvre carried out the
consecrations in Econe, Switzerland, said it was a schismatic act
carried out expressly against the wishes of the pope.
   A schism is a formal rupture with the Holy See.
   Excommunication puts a Roman Catholic outside the church and
unable to receive its sacraments, such as communion and extreme
unction, or last rites.
   Earlier this week, Lefebvre's traditionalist movement challenged
the excommunications, claiming that church law permits such
ordinations in an ``emergency.''
   The Vatican said the only ``necessity'' in the case was raised
by Lefebvre ``to conserve an attitude of division in the Catholic
Church, despite the offers of communion and concessions made by the
Holy Father John Paul II.''
   Navarro said a statement would be issued in coming days on the
position of Lefebvre's lay followers.
   The communique identified those excommunicated as Lefebvre and
the four bishops: Bernard Fellay, Bernard Tissier de Mallerais,
Richard Williamson and Alfonso de Galarreta.
   Brazilian prelate Antonio de Castro Mayer, bishop of Campos,
assisted at the rites in Econe. Navarro said the Vatican was
awaiting clarification on his role in the ceremony before making a
decision on excommunication.
   John Paul carried out official duties as usual today, including
receiving five Soviet journalists, but Lefebvre's action provoked
considerable bitterness at the Vatican. A symphonic concert
scheduled for Thursday evening was canceled to express ``deep
pain'' over the schism.
   The Italian Bishops' Conference immediately called for prayers
for the pope.
   Archbishop Albert Decourtray of Lyon and president of the French
council of bishops, said: ``It is a day of mourning for the
Catholic church, for all those who are attached to Christian
unity.''
   Navarro has estimated that Lefebvre's traditionalist movement
has 80,000 to 100,000 followers, although other Vatican officials
have said as many as half a million lay people turn to his priests
for various church functions.
   Navarro said the Vatican plans to announce Friday the legal
position of the priests and lay supporters of Lefebvre.
   The Vatican spokesman estimated that relatively few Catholics
incur excommunication and that many of the cases today involve
Catholic doctors who perform abortions. However, he noted that
these are matters of individual conscience and no records are kept.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
