<HEAD>Wounded Palestinian Dies, Army Closes Schools</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Palestinian shot; Picks up
4th pvs, `The military...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old Palestinian who was shot during
a clash with Israeli soldiers died today, and the army closed six
more Palestinian schools, Arab reports said.
   Arafat Awad Hanani died of injuries suffered in a clash June 16
in Beit Furik, near the West Bank city of Nablus. One other Arab
was killed and 18 were wounded in the fighting which erupted after
the army blew up an Arab-owned home.
   His death brought to 213 the number of Palestinians killed in
the nearly 7-month-old uprising against Israeli rule of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip. Four Israelis have died.
   Also today, troops opened fire at Arab youths throwing rocks in
Nablus' old city, wounding a 17-year-old in the leg, said officials
at the city's Al Ittihad Hospital. Army officials said they were
checking the report.
   The military administration closed six West Bank and east
Jerusalem schools, the daily Arabic newspaper Ashaab reported.
   Fifty-three schools have been ordered closed again after the
army reopened West Bank schools on June 6, according to the
Palestinian-run Jerusalem Media and Communications Center.
   The army shut down more than 1,000 schools in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip on Feb. 2, but schools in Gaza have been operating
on-and-off since. Israeli officials have hoped that the reopening
of schools in the West Bank would help restore normal life in the
area.
   Also today, 19 Arabs charged in connection with an April 6 clash
in the West Bank village of Beita went on trial. A 15-year-old
Israeli girl was killed during violence between Arab villagers and
Jewish teen-agers.
   The army determined that Tirza Porat was killed by a bullet
accidentally fired by an Israeli guarding the teen-agers.
   The Arabs were charged with attacking and injuring the Israeli
guard, causing bodily harm, throwing stones and seizing and
concealing weapons.
   On Wednesday, Israeli troops shot and killed a 15-year-old
Palestinian in a clash that Arab witnesses said erupted after a
Jewish settler torched olive trees near the boy's village in the
occupied West Bank.
   Ibrahim Ghassan Aranka was fatally shot in the pelvis and
abdomen during protests in the village of Taiyiba near Ramallah,
said offiials at Jerusalem's Mukassad Hospital.
   The army said an officer opened fire in Taiyiba after Arabs
pelted troops with stones and bottles, and two soldiers were
slightly injured. An army official said the circumstances of
Aranka's death were under investigation.
   The incident began when residents spotted a Jewish settler
setting fire to olive trees near the village, said Salem Suleiman
Khoriyeh, the son of Taiyiba's village elder.
   Hundreds of villagers rushed to the grove and battled the blaze,
which destroyed about 15 acres of olive trees, said Khoriyeh, 42.
   Soldiers in five jeeps watched the two-hour battle but did
nothing to help douse the flames, Khoriyeh said.
   Angered by the indifference of the troops, villagers began
stoning the soldiers, who responded by opening fire, Khoriyeh said.
   Army officials said they had no reports of arson by Jewish
settlers in the area.
   Palestinian nationalists are believed to be responsible for more
than 100 cases of arson in Israel since January. Arabs have blamed
Jewish settlers for arson in the occupied territories.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, troops shot and wounded two
Arabs near the open-air market, area hospital officials said.
   The officials said the clash erupted when youths threw empty
bottles and rocks at troops accompanying Israeli tax officials on a
tax check of Arab shops.
   The army confirmed one Palestinian was wounded and said it was
checking the report of the second shooting.
</TEXT>
