<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0458,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Suggests Dukakis Weak On National Security</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Bush speech; pick up 2nd graf pvs bgng
``At the same...; Delete final 3 grafs to shorten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said today that after
eight years of Republian rule in the White House ``some good people
yearn for a change'' and that's why the GOP ticket faces an uphill
struggle.
   ``It's our job to let them know that this time, in this case,
change and improvement come from the Republican Party,'' Bush said
in remarks prepared for a GOP fundraising luncheon.
   The vice president, the certain Republican presidential nominee,
also accused liberals of ``champing at the bit to raise taxes
again'' and said, ``the trouble with the Democrats in Congress is
that they haven't learned to `just say no.'''
   Bush praised the current economic recovery, the longest
peacetime expansion in history, and took a swipe at economists for
being pessimistic.
   He said that as recently as 1986, 60 percent of the members of
the National Association of Business Economics predicted a
recession in 1988.
   ``Wrong, wrong, wrong,'' Bush said. ``No wonder it's called the
`dismal science.''
   Referring to polls showing him in a tough race against Democrat
Michael Dukakis, Bush said, ``It's an uphill fight for our
Republican team this year. After eight years of one party in the
White House, no matter how successful, some good people yearn for a
change _ hoping that change will mean improvement.''
   Bush compared himself with former President Harry Truman, noting
that Democrat Truman too had been the underdog when he ran in 1948.
   ``The crowds would yell, `give 'em hell.' And he'd shout back,
`I don't have to give 'em hell. I just tell the truth and they
think it's hell,''' Bush said.
   ``In the final analysis, liberals promise compassion but they
deliver misery,'' Bush said. ``We promise hope, growth and
opportunity and we deliver hope, growth and opportunity.''
   On Wednesday, Bush criticized Dukakis for ill-founded ideas
about the Soviet Union and arms control, and he said ``it would be
ridiculous'' to proceed with the nuclear weapons cuts Dukakis wants.
   At the same time, Bush spoke cautiously about the sweeping
reforms advocated by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, including
a redistribution of power in the Soviet Union.
   Bush said the changes would be ``revolutionary'' and
``historic'' if they were implemented.
   However, he said, ``We've got to remember, the cold war is not
over.'' In contrast to the upbeat tone adopted by President Reagan
after the Moscow summit, Bush said the West should be prepared for
a protracted conflict with the Soviet bloc.
   Bush, certain to be the Republican presidential nominee,
stressed foreign policy in a speech Wednesday in San Francisco and
in an interview on Air Force Two as he flew back to Washington.
   He stopped in the farming community of Marion, Wis.,to talk
about the drought.
   While announcing no new initiatives, Bush said, ``I want to say
that, leave aside the politics of the moment and my ambitions for
the fall _ what we want to do as a part of the administration is do
as much as possible under the circumstances.''
   The vice president's message Wednesday was that Dukakis, who is
virtually assured the Democratic presidential nomination, is weak
on national security and foreign affairs and particularly fuzzy
about why the Soviet Union has been willing to negotiate nuclear
arms agreements.
   Dukakis has voiced opposition to the MX missile and Midgetman
missiles, and also has said he would replace the administration's
Strategic Defense Initiative with a buildup in conventional forces.
   ``He wants to do away with a lot of these systems and I think _
to negotiate an arms control agreement with the Soviet Union _ it
would be ridiculous to do that,'' Bush said.
   The vice president said it was the United States' refusal to
make unilateral concessions on arms that persuaded the Soviets to
sign an agreement to abolish U.S. and Soviet intermediate-range
nuclear missiles.
   Bush said Dukakis' emphasis on conventional, or non-nuclear,
forces ``leads you inextricably to the question: `Is he proposing
the winnability of a conventional war?' And leads you to ask the
question: What about the United States? What's going to happen in
defense of the United States?''
   The vice president said, ``In fairness, I don't know really what
his approach is yet. But if (the conventional force buildup) is his
approach towards dealing with the Soviet Union, I have a distinct
difference with him.''
</TEXT>
