<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Acid Rain, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0567,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acid Rain Destroying Tourist City and Former Capital</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Corrects spelling of Zhejiang in 2nd graf. Picks up 3rd graf,
`In Nanking...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acid rain is destroying vegetation in the tourist
city of Hangzhou and in the former capital of Nanking, official
reports say.
   Acid rain has destroyed foliage and damaged ancient statues and
stone tablets in the city of Hangzhou, the official China News
Service said in a report seen in Beijing today. Hangzhou is in
coastal Zhejiang province.
   In Nanking, capital of the Nationalist government until the
Communist takeover in 1949, acid rain is also causing serious
problems, the report said. Nanking is in Jiangsu province.
   In May 1986, leaves of 400 snow pines planted in Hangzhou's
parks and hotel grounds turned yellow and withered as a result of
acid rain.
   Around Hangzhou's famous West Lake, stone statues and stone
tablets bearing inscriptions by historical figures are being eroded
by the rains, as are stone Buddha images at the Monastery of the
Spirit's Retreat, the city's best-known monastery.
   Experts say the problem is caused by pollution from industries,
which burn low-quality coal that has a high sulphur content, and by
the city's thousands of boilers and tens of thousands of family
coal stoves that release sulphur dioxide into the atmosphere, the
report said.
   Earlier news reports said acid rain is a major problem in
Sichuan province in southwestern China and neighboring Guizhou
province, in the southern provinces of Hunan and Guangxi, and in
Shanghai.
   The problem is most serious in the south, where the soil is
basically acidic. In the north, the alkaline soil neutralizes the
acid in the rain, experts said.
   China started its research into acid rain in 1981 and last
September passed the country's first air pollution prevention law.
</TEXT>
