<HEAD>Police Say Owners Burned Their House Rather Than Clean It Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KERNERSVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A brother and sister burned their
filthy, $70,000 house, which allegedly had a stronger odor than
fresh asphalt, rather than clean up garbage that had accumulated
for years, police say.
   Although the house, owned by Terry W. Key, 41, and his sister,
Barbara J. Key, 54, was paid for and was not insured, police said
the two can be charged with willfully burning their own house, a
felony that carries a penalty of up to 10 years in prison.
   ``I think his temper got to him,'' said Officer C.C Perdue III,
who questioned Key on Wednesday. ``He just figured, `Hey, we can't
clean it up, there's no way to clean it up, let's burn it up.'
That's the way he was thinking. That's strange.''
   Perdue said Key told investigators he doused the brick house
with gasoline Monday and set it afire. Key was treated for burns on
his face, ear and arms.
   ``He said that he just wanted to get out of the neighborhood,''
Perdue said. ``He didn't think about selling the house, he didn't
think about anything but just eliminating the problem.''
   Although neighbors said they had been enduring the stench of the
house for years, the events that led to Monday's fire began last
Friday when police investigated a complaint from a crew paving
streets in the rural neighborhood.
   The road crew told police they could smell the house through the
odor of freshly laid asphalt.
   Perdue told the Greensboro News & Record that he and another
officer went to the house and found sewage soaking the back yard
from a broken septic tank and mounds of garbage festering in ripped
plastic bags under the carport.
   ``When they opened the door, you felt like you just wanted to go
behind a tree or something, it smelled so bad,'' Perdue said.
``Both had to kick the trash out of the doorway to get out. They
couldn't even open the door all the way.''
   The officers told the Keys their house posed a health risk and
that it must be cleaned up by Monday or the Forsyth County Health
Department would be called to investigate.
   Perdue said the Keys made excuses for the house's condition,
that his night job and her recent knee surgery had kept them from
getting the garbage to the curb. They had lived in the house for
more than 20 years.
   ``But this problem was building up for several years,'' Perdue
said. ``This didn't just happen.''
   Gary Almond, who lives across the street, said the Keys' house
has been an odorous eyesore ever since he moved to the neighborhood
in 1980. He said neighbors had called the Health Department many
times seeking relief, but got nowhere.
   ``I don't understand how anyone could live in something like
that,'' he said. ``They used to feed the cats inside and then throw
the cans out the door. The cans would be piled up on each side of
the steps.''
   ``We're going to try to charge them,'' said agent Curtis Douglas
of the State Bureau of Investigation. ``It may have been their own
property and they may not have had any insurance on it, but the
danger they created with that explosion and fire in a neighborhood
with kids and everything, we can't let that go.''
   The Keys could not be reached for comment; Perdue said they had
gone to live with a relative.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
