<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NunAbducted     06-30 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nun Abducted,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother Says Abducted Nun Has Mailed Her Habit Back to Convent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was abducted from a convent by her
family doesn't want to go back, one of her brothers says. However,
the spiritual leader of the convent said he doesn't believe it.
   Mary Susan Greve, 22, took off her habit Tuesday and mailed it
back to the convent, Dave Greve said from the family's home here
Wednesday.
   ``One of their rules is that by taking off the habit, it means
you don't want to be a part of it. She gave up wanting to belong to
that order. She didn't give up wanting to be a nun,'' Greve said.
   But the spiritual adviser, the Rev. Clarence Kelly, said the
order had not received any package or message from the woman, known
as Sister Mary Cecilia.
   ``I can't believe the kidnappers, quite frankly,'' Kelly said in
an interview in New York Wednesday. ``The only thing that disturbs
me is for the family to impose what they believe on (Mary Susan)
and do it illegally.''
   Police in New York and Ohio have been looking for the woman
since her father, James, and brothers Dave, Mark and John pushed
her into a waiting car Sunday as she walked with two nuns on a
street near St. Joseph Novitiate Convent in Roundtop, N.Y., in the
Catskill Mountains.
   New York state police have said they would not press charges
unless the woman wants to file them. It was the second time Miss
Greve had been abducted by her family.
   Dave Greve said his sister and parents were at a Catskills
motel, which he would not identify, when he left them Tuesday. He
said he did not know when they plan to return to Cincinnati.
   Sister Mary Cabrini, the order's secretary-general and senior
sister, arrived in Cincinnati on Wednesday to try to contact the
woman's family. She said she spoke with the FBI.
   ``We are sincerely concerned about our sister,'' she said. ``We
want to establish she is safe and free. We have to know it from
her. And thirdly, we want to establish that this will not happen to
anyone ever again, or nobody will be safe.''
   The St. Joseph Novitiate Convent calls itself a traditionalist
Roman Catholic convent, said the Rev. Michael A. Farano, chancellor
of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Albany, N.Y. However, he said
it is not recognized by the Catholic Church. Its services are in
Latin and it has rejected all of the teachings of the Second
Vatican Council of the 1960s.
   John Greve said the family opposed his sister's decision to
become a novice at the convent after the family broke with a
traditionalist Catholic church in the Cincinnati suburb of
Sharonville.
   Dave Greve said the family abducted his sister because of the
family's suspicions of Kelly. Kelly heads an ultra-traditionalist
Catholic sect called the Society of St. Pius V, which broke from
the traditionalist Catholic Society of St. Pius X in 1983.
   Miss Greve first joined St. Joseph's in September 1986. In
April, her mother drove to the convent and tricked her into getting
into the car, then brought her back to Cincinnati. The convent's
mother superior persuaded Miss Greve to return to the convent.
   Dave Greve said his sister still wants to become a nun and that
the family is searching for a convent for her to join.
</TEXT>
