<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-FizzledFourth 1stLd-Writethru a0481 06-30 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Fizzled Fourth, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0481,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Douses Many Fireworks Celebrations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf pvs, `Restrictions vary...' to
UPDATE with Indiana governor banning unsupervised fireworks today.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Diner, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   There won't be any rockets' red glare or bombs bursting in air
this Fourth of July in many drought-devastated communities across
the Midwest, Plains and South, where tinder-dry conditions have
sparked fears of a conflagration.
   Scores of towns and counties in Iowa, Ohio, Illinois, Missouri,
Kansas, Indiana, Nebraska, North Dakota, South Dakota and Tennessee
have canceled or limited Independence Day displays of rockets,
sparklers and other fireworks.
   ``Right now is not the time to be shooting fireworks,'' said
Dwight Barnett, a spokesman for the state forestry division in
Tennessee, where authorities are encouraging localities to ``save
it for the rain.''
   ``We're creatures of habit, and we're used to shooting fireworks
on the Fourth of July, but this Fourth of July is different.
There's a high degree of risk out there,'' Barnett said.
   Restrictions vary and are widespread in some states, with some
officials wavering because of recent rain. In North Dakota, one of
the most drought-ravaged states, 19 of 53 counties have banned the
use and or sale of fireworks while the danger remains.
   Indiana Gov. Robert Orr announced today that he had banned
unsupervised fireworks displays on state properties such as parks
and urged Hoosiers to attend supervised public displays. He said he
had wanted to declare a complete ban on private fireworks during
the holiday weekend, but that state law was so complex such a
restriction would likely be unenforceable.
   In Wisconsin, Gov. Tommy Thompson signed an order Tuesday
banning private fireworks displays. Local governments and the state
may make exceptions and community displays are exempt if they take
fire precautions.
   ``Things are so dry that we are seeing grass and brush fires in
cities and villages,'' Thompson said. ``We have to do what is right
and necessary to protect lives and property.''
   The National Safety Council also issued a warning Monday saying
fireworks, which are linked to 11,000 to 12,000 injuries each year,
will be even more dangerous this year because of parched forests
and fields.
   In Tennessee, a fire that scorched three to four acres at
Lavergne on Tuesday night was blamed on fireworks. More than 150
firefighters were called to fight the blaze.
   ``We think it was possibly started by juveniles shooting
fireworks,'' said John Goodrum, a rescue worker. ``We found a lot
of bottle rockets.''
   Though the bans have prompted a few lawsuits, the head of a
fireworks group said he doesn't oppose the restrictions. ``If they
make a decision their local conditions are that bad, we're
certainly not going to take issue,'' said John Conkling, executive
director of the American Pyrotechnics Association.
   However, he said, cancellations will be a blow to the $170
million-a-year industry, which has about 80 percent of its business
tied to the holiday.
   ``Fireworks companies are very likely to be additional
casualties of the drought,'' Conkling said. ``It very likely will
have impact on every fireworks company in this country.''
   The largest in the nation, Zambelli Fireworks Internationale,
said this is the first time in 40 years drought has affected
business. ``The Midwestern states are backing out the fastest,''
George Zambelli Sr. said Wednesday.
   Some towns have planned alternative celebrations or have
postponed events. The Chicago suburb of Addison will have a
fireworks show in September. Independence, Mo., and Hoffman
Estates, Ill., are planning laser light shows.
   Other towns going ahead with fireworks are taking special
precautions. In Champaign-Urbana, Ill., for example, workers at the
University of Illinois stadium will water the area heavily before
July Fourth and firefighters will stand by, erecting sandbags to
prevent stray sparks from catching fire.
   Iowa State Fire Marshal Wilbur Johnson is advising towns that if
they proceed with fireworks shows they should make sure a firetruck
is standing by.
   But even with safety measures, some officials say fighting a
fire would further deplete water supplies and conditions are just
too risky.
   ``I don't know who would take the responsibility if anything
happened,'' said Dennis Ballou, fire chief in Exira, Iowa.
``Everything is so dry now. Lawns are so cracked it hurts to walk.''
</TEXT>
