<1ST_LINE>u i PM-1812Soldiers     06-30 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-1812 Soldiers,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Canada Honor Remains of American Soldiers Who Died in War of
1812</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT ERIE, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a lawn where their predecessors
traded musket fire, U.S. and Canadian soldiers today honored 28
American servicemen who died during the War of 1812 in the first
repatriation ceremony between the two nations.
   Although the repatriation and burial of the servicemen is more
than a century and a half overdue, they are being treated as if
they died only yesterday, said Lt. Col. Robert Trotter.
   ``This is the day these men waited 174 years for,'' said
Trotter. ``They are coming home.''
   U.S and Canadian military details stood by as cannon saluted the
fallen men.
   Fort Erie Mayor Heinz Hummel told the crowd of about 500 that
the soldiers' sacrifice paved the way to an undefended border
between the two nations.
   ``Their death was the beginning of our peace,'' he said.
   The remains of the servicemen were discovered during a
construction project in Fort Erie in October 1987 and taken to a
Toronto laboratory for study.
   Archaeologists were able to determine that the skeletons were
American, but could not come up with individual identifications.
They are believed to have been killed during a British siege on an
American position at Snake Hill in 1814.
   George Hees, Canadian minister of veterans affairs, transferred
possession of he remains to Thomas Niles, U.S. Ambassador to
Canada, saying, ``There can be no finer expression of the good
relation between our countries than the reverence we show for these
men.''
   Before the ceremony, an honor guard of U.S. and Canadian
soldiers stood vigil over the 28 caskets, draped with American
flags and lined up in rows on the lawn at old Fort Erie, in the
early morning chill.
   Though the bones are being treated with reverence now, the dead
were given a hasty burial at the time, said Ronald Williamson, head
of the team in charge of the excavation. The soldiers dodged
British artillery and patrol attacks to bury the soldiers in
separate but unmarked graves.
   The victims ranged in age from mid-teens to about 40, and at
least 12 of the men showed evidence of severe injuries, presumably
from musket or cannon fire, Williamson said.
   After the ceremony, 28 hearses carried the caskets over the
Peace Bridge into Buffalo. They were to be buried at Bath National
Cemetery in Steuben County.
   The ceremony marked the beginning of the annual Friendship
Festival between the United States and Canada, which celebrates
continuous peace between the two nations since 1814.
   ``We could not ask for a more symbolic gesture,'' said Patrick
Mines, a festival organizer from Fort Erie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
