<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz 2ndLd-Writethru a0609 06-30 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0609,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Arrives in El Salvador With Promises of U.S. Support</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs with Shultz comments. Picks up 2nd pvs,
`In Guatemala...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P.
Shultz today pledged continued U.S. support to this Central
American nation, but he expressed concern about an increase in
politically motivated killings of civilians.
   During a four-hour visit, Shultz signed a $125 million balance
of payments agreement. He urged the couuntry to reject the
challenge of the ``guerrillas and their communist allies.''
   ``They don't want democracy; they don't want freedom,'' Shultz
said in a statement shortly after his arrival from Guatemala. He
planned to fly to Honduras from El Salvador.
   After a meeting with Acting President Rodolfo Castillo
Claramount, Shultz conferred with commanders of the Salvadoran
armed forces.
   U.S. officials said Shultz expressed concern about an increase
in killings of civilians to an average of 34 a month. Last year,
the average was 27 civilian slayings each month.
   The administration is worried that a major setback in human
rights performance could jeopardize congressional support for U.S.
aid to El Salvador. The country is receiving $400 million in
economic and military aid this year.
   Speaking of the leftist insurgency, Shultz said, ``They want to
achieve with bullets the power that the people of El Salvador
refuse to give them by the ballot.''
   In Guatemala on Wednesday night, Shultz set the tone for his
four-nation Central American journey by contrasting Nicaragua's
performance with that of the region's democracies.
   He said the democratic countries have been making political and
economic progress with U.S. help, while hopes raised by Nicaragua's
1979 revolution had given way to ``repression and stagnation'' and
``deepening misery.''
   ``The economy is a bust,'' Shultz said. ``Ideology is plentiful
but milk is rationed. The standing army has grown from 6,000 to
80,000 men.''
   Shultz signed a $75 million balance of payments support
agreement with Guatemalan officials and met with President Vinicio
Cerezo. Cerezo is now in his third year as the country's first
elected civilian president since 1970.
   While criticizing Nicaragua, Shultz said the picture is
different elsewhere in the region.
   ``In the last decade, three countries _ Guatemala, El Salvador
and Honduras _ have each made significant progress, more than most
believed possible,'' he said.
   ``Ten years ago, Costa Rica was Central America's only
democracy; today, Nicaragua is Central America's only
dictatorship.''
   Despite Shultz' upbeat assessment, El Salvador and Guatemala
both face potential instability. There have been signs of military
unrest in Guatemala and the political situation in El Salvador is
becoming increasingly polarized.
   Shultz said U.S. support will continue for Central America's
democracies regardless of who wins the U.S. presidential election
in November, because the policy enjoys bipartisan support.
   Shultz returns to Washington on Friday night after a visit to
Costa Rica.
   Shultz said his visit is not focusing on administration plans to
seek additional aid for the rebels fighting Nicaragua's leftist
government.
   In his lengthy arrival statement Wednesday night, Shultz made
only scant reference to the rebels, perhaps reflecting the
Guatemalan government's steadfast coolness to the Contra cause.
   Under questioning from reporters during his flight here, Shultz
acknowledged that the military effectiveness of the Contras has
``lessened substantially'' since U.S. military aid ended in
February.
   He accused the Sandinistas of compiling a record of ``evasions
and non-compliance'' in negotiations dating back to the 1979
revolution.
   The Sandinistas, he said, continue to support subversion in
neighboring countries.
   ``Theirs is not a record of honest negotiations. It is a record
of negotiations corrupted by the Sandinistas' efforts to destroy
those who do not agree with them,'' he said.
   Negotiations between the Sandinistas and the Contras broke down
earlier this month and no new talks have been scheduled. Each side
has blamed the other for the breakdown of the negotiations over an
end to their 6{-year-old war.
</TEXT>
