<DOCNO> AP880630-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Child-WelfareLawsuit     06-30 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child-Welfare Lawsuit,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ACLU Sues Illinois Child-Welfare Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court-appointed overseer should take over the
Illinois Department of Children and Family Services because
officials of the child-care agency are leaving thousands of young
people at risk, according to a lawsuit.
   The suit, filed Wednesday in federal court by the American Civil
Liberties Union on behalf of 14,000 wards of the state, charges
that the department is overburdened and often houses youngsters in
overcrowded, violent shelters or sends them to foster homes where
they are abused.
   ``Thousands of them (wards) are consigned to a life of drift,
disruption and despair,'' according to the lawsuit.
   The department had to deal with 91,715 abuse complaints last
year, up 30 percent from the previous year, officials said. The
1988 total is expected to be higher.
   Department Director Gordon Johnson, named as the defendant, said
a lack of money is the problem.
   ``I am in charge of the department and the buck stops here,''
Johnson said. ``But I am not the one who appropriates money to the
department or raises money in taxes. That is for the Legislature to
do.''
   He said that despite shortcomings, the department is ``one of
the best agencies in the country.''
   Johnson also disputed the need for appointment of an overseer.
   ``Is the federal overseer going to bring federal dollars?'' he
asked.
   The lawsuit charges the agency with violating the children's
constitutional rights of due process and equal protection under the
law.
   ACLU attorney Benjamin Wolf said the agency's shortcomings were
the result of ``10 years of (Gov.) James Thompson's cruelty.''
Thompson is not named as a defendant.
   Wolf said the four-term governor has consistently failed to
provide sufficient funds to manage the agency and other human
services, and has never asked for enough money to address the needs
of the children in his care.
   Dave Fields, a spokesman for the governor in Springfield, said
today that ``Mr. Wolf is engaged in demagoguery.
   ``The fact is that the governor has given DCFS money to vastly
increase the network of child abuse reporting in this state over
the last 10 years. This year, under the tax increase proposal he
submitted, DCFS would have gotten $48 million more'' than the $334
million it got this year.
   Thompson declared his tax increase proposal dead Tuesday because
of opposition in the Legislature.
   Johnson said appropriations for his agency have increased by
$100 million since he took over in 1983.
   The lawsuit contends caseworkers routinely have three times the
number of cases the department itself considers manageable, that
staffing at state facilities is short of adequate levels, that the
agency does not have enough foster homes in which to place
children, and that the agency does not make adequate attempts to
reunite families.
   Wolf said the department's shortcomings have long been apparent,
but Johnson ``never addresses serious problems until they appear on
the front page.''
   ``We respond to children's needs, not newspaper stories,''
Johnson said.
   Wolf said the lawsuit was unusual but warranted.
   ``We only do something like this,'' he added, ``when the whole
system has collapsed.''
</TEXT>
