<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Romania-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru   06-30 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Romania-Hungary, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0525,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romania Orders Closing of Hungarian Cultural Center</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Grosz's comments, summoning
of Romanian charge d'affaries. Pick up 3rd graf pvs: `On
Tuesday...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania ordered Hungary's cultural center
in Bucharest closed and told the embassy to leave the building, a
Hungarian diplomat said today.
   The move was the latest in a diplomatic war prompted by
Hungary's contention that Romania is mistreating ethnic Hungarians
who live within its borders.
   In Budapest, Premier Karoly Grosz said tensions between the two
countries were only temporary and that he still intended to visit
Romania as planned.
   Grosz was invited to visit Romania as government leader, before
he was appointed party leader last month. The visit will be the
first to Romania by a Hungarian Communist Party chief since 1977.
No date has been set.
   ``I am convinced that if we don't talk to each other, we cannot
understand each other,'' Grosz said, speaking through an
interpreter.
   The Hungarian Foreign Ministry summoned the Romanian acting
charge d'affaires and expressed its ``regret'' at Romania's
expulsion of Hungarian diplomats.
   Relations between the two Soviet bloc neighbors have been
strained for years over what Hungary maintains is Romania's
discrimination against the 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians in
Romania. Bucharest has accused Hungary of interfering in its
internal affairs.
   On Tuesday, in an unprecedented action involving two Warsaw Pact
allies, Romania ordered Hungary's consul general in the
Transylvanian city of Cluj to leave the country and declared the
consulate closed.
   The Romanian Foreign Ministry told the Hungarian Embassy on
Wednesday that the cultural center, which never opened to the
public, must be vacated within 48 hours, the diplomat said in a
telephone interview from Romania's capital.
   Both decisions apparently came in retaliation for a rally Monday
night of about 50,000 Hungarians in Budapest who protested
Romania's plans to destroy 7,000 Romanian villages, including
hundreds of Hungarian communities.
   Romanian Communist leader Nicolae Ceausescu was angered over
what he said was Hungarian government support for the protesters,
who filed past the Romanian Embassy. He hinted in a speech Tuesday
that he may order the Hungarian missions' operations scaled down.
   Hungarian newspapers and government officials said the
village-demolition scheme would destroy the 1.7 million Hungarians'
cultural heritage in the Romanian province of Transylvania.
   Romanian officials said the villages to be razed by the year
2000 would be replaced by modern agricultural-industrial centers
and remove differences between country and city dwellers.
   The decision to open cultural centers in Bucharest and Budapest,
the Hungarian capital, was made in 1977 at a meeting between
Ceausescu and former Hungarian party chief Janos Kadar.
   Hungary rented a bulding in downtown Bucharest where it planned
to open the center, complete with a library and a projection room.
But Romania never used its reciprocal right to do the same in
Budapest and has not said why.
   The Hungarian cultural center was never issued a permit to start
operation, the diplomat said. In recent years the building was used
as a storage for the Hungarian Embassy.
   The United States, France, West Germany, Czechoslovakia, Great
Britain and Italy have received permission and opened similar
centers in Bucharest in the past 20 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Military     06-30 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Military,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Ruling Forcing Defense Contractor to Pay Damages
for Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that forced a defense contractor to pay damages for an on-duty
accident involving a Navy pilot.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Grumman
Aerospace Corp., ordered to pay $840,556 to the pilot's family who
died when his plane crashed off the California coast in 1979.
   The court's action comes just three days after the justices
ruled that government contractors enjoy sweeping legal immunity
from personal injury lawsuits.
   In Monday's ruling, the court said contractors cannot be sued if
they designed the equipment according to government specificiations
and notified the government about any hazards they knew about.
   It appears a federal appeals court's ruling in the Grumman
Aerospace case focused on the Navy's lack of notification about any
hazards.
   The death of Navy Lt. Gary S. Shaw of Fort Lauderdale, Fla., was
blamed on a design defect in Grumman's A-6 plane. The plane crashed
within seconds after taking off from the aircraft carrier
Constellation about 100 miles off the coast of San Diego.
   Navy investigators said the most likely cause of the crash was
the loss or failure of a bolt in the plane's system for controlling
its up-and-down movement.
   Although the A-6 is the mainstay of the Navy's carrier-based
attack fleet, there have been at least six other accidents
involving the plane's flight control mechanism since the 1960s.
   In 1981, Shaw's father, Edwin Lees Shaw, sued over his son's
death.
   Last December, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the
$840,556 jury award against Grumman.
   The appeals court said military contractors in such cases are
not exempt from liability.
   Grumman contended that forcing it to pay undermines the
military's independence and violates the separation of powers by
giving courts too much power.
   But the appeals court said, ``Although the Navy did formally
approve Grumman's A-6 specifications and design changes, that
approval did not constitute the sort of informed military decision
to accept the risk of a dangerous product to which this court must
defer under separation of powers doctrine.''
   In such cases, the appeals court said, the defense contractor
has more information about risks and ``the military may simply be
working in the dark.''
   The appeals court added: ``Our central concern is whether or not
the military actually made a decision to use a product that it knew
to be dangerous to servicemen.''
   Since the military was not sued by the Shaw family, it was up to
Grumman to prove it followed very specific orders in designing the
A-6, the appeals court said, adding that the company failed to do
so.
   Grumman had argued that allowing monetary damages in such
lawsuits would undermine servicemen's confidence and give comfort
to enemies of the United States.
   ``If anything persuades pilots to tremble and the enemy to
rejoice, it will be the A-6's accident record itself _ not this
court's recognition of it,'' the appeals court said.
   In the appeal acted on today, Grumman's lawyers said four other
federal appeals courts have disagreed.
   Most of the nation's defense industry joined in support of
Grumman, arguing the 11th Circuit court ruling undermines military
independence.
   But lawyers for the Shaw family said the companies were trying
to deceive the Supreme Court into believing the government was the
defendant in the case.
   ``Neither the United States nor the Navy are on trial,'' they
said.
   The high court has ruled that members of the armed services may
not sue the government over injuries suffered in connection with
their military service.
   The case is Grumman vs. Shaw, 85-1529.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Movies     06-30 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Movies,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Only Two Prime-Time Movies a Week on French TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French television stations will be limited to
showing two films a week in prime time in a bid to boost attendance
at movie houses, the government announced Thursday.
   Culture Minister Jack Lang said on France's annual ``Cinema
Day'' that he also would be putting together an ``emergency plan''
to provide $12 million for promoting films and movie houses.
   The Culture Ministry said in a statement that the heads of
France's six television networks had agreed to cut back film
broadcasts during the prime-time hours from 8:30 p.m. to 10:30 p.m.
Regulations giving the limit the force of law are being drawn up.
   ``It is a first step, and other measures will have to be taken
to assure a new balance among the media,'' the statement said.
   The networks currently are forbidden from showing movies in
prime time only on Wednesdays and Saturdays. Some channels have
scheduled films on the other five nights.
   The French are the most active moviegoers in Europe, but cinema
admissions have been falling in recent years as film buffs stay
home to watch TV.
   Bernard Vidal, spokesman for the National Federation of Cinema
Halls, said about 500 movie houses have closed since January 1987.
He said the proliferation of movies on TV was the prime culprit,
with 1,300 films broadcast last year.
   ``This situation, without precedent in France, does not have an
equal anywhere in the world,'' he said.
   On Cinema Day, an annual event started in 1985, anyone who buys
a single cinema ticket at full price can then go from one movie to
the next all day long, paying just one franc (about 16 cents) per
ticket.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
