<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Voter Registration,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Register Through New State Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 85,000 Minnesotans have returned
voter registration forms that were mailed with their income tax
booklets.
   Voter registration forms for the first time were mailed out in
tax booklets this year as part of a program to increase
participation in elections.
   People applying for or renewing driver's licenses also receive
voter registration information, and Secretary of State Joan Growe
said Wednesday that the state has received about 55,000 forms back
from that effort.
   An additional 40,000 to 50,000 forms filled out by driver's
license applicants are believed to have been sent directly to
county auditors, Growe said. About 2,000 voter registration forms
obtained during visits to other state agencies also have been
returned, Growe said.
   According to the secretary of state's office, about 2.5 million
of Minnesota's estimated 3.1 million eligible voters are registered.
