<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Colombia-Guerrillas     06-30 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Guerrillas,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Captures Guerrilla Base, Destroys Narcotics Facilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers captured a major leftist
guerrilla base and destroyed several narcotics laboratories and
36.5 tons of drugs, Colombian military officers announced today.
   The leftist National Liberation Army guerrilla base was
discovered Tuesday night in a wooded area near the town of San
Alberto, 230 miles north of Bogota, Gen. Farouk Yanine Diaz
reported.
   Diaz, commander of the Second Army Division, said the guerrillas
fled when a network of alarms was activated.
   Guerrillas have blown up the country's main oil pipeline 79
times since last year. Diaz said his troops captured 90 pounds of
dynamite.
   The pipeline carries 215,000 barrels of oil daily from the Cano
Limon field to port Covenas on the Caribbean. The guerrilla attacks
deprived Colombia of $200 million of oil export income this year,
Ecopetrol, the state oil company, says.
   Diaz said arms, communications equipment and uniforms were
captured at the base, as well as notebooks containing details of
rebel activities. He said these included account books of sums
extorted from landowners in the area and plans to continue dynamite
attacks.
   ``The information will make it easier for us to destroy this
gang,'' Diaz told reporters.
   Gen. Harold Bedoya Pizaro, commander of the Seventh Army
Brigade, said in a communique his troops had destroyed 84 cocaine
processing laboratories in a joint operation with police in the
Guaviare area of southwestern Colombia. He said they had also
rendered inoperable 18 clandestine airstrips and destroyed 20.5
tons of coca base and 16 tons of coca leaves.
</TEXT>
