<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Italy-F-16s 1stLd-Writethru a0619 06-30 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-F-16s, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lower House Approves Transfer of U.S. Jets to Italy</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 7 grafs to details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lower house of Parliament today overwhelming
approved the government's decision to accept 72 U.S. F-16 fighter
jets being evicted from their base in Spain.
   The Chamber of Deputies, in a secret ballot, voted 298-196, with
24 abstentions, to back the plan to move the jets to Crotone, in
the Puglia region of southern Italy.
   In his appeal to the legislature before the vote, Foreign
Minister Giulio Andreotti called acceptance of the fighter wing ``a
decision in tune with the politics of peace that our country has
always pursued.''
   Italy's government on June 4 announced that it had accepted a
NATO request to accept the jets, which Spain has had at the orrejon
air base. Spain has decided that the jets must go within three
years.
   A coalition of Communists, Italy's second-largest party, and
smaller leftist groups, had opposed accepting the jets. But Premier
Ciriaco De Mita's five-party coalition has a comfortable majority
in Parliament.
   The vote on whether to accept the jets came on the opposition's
request.
   The opposition has also asked for a vote in the Senate but no
date has been set for it. The government coalition also has a
majority in the upper house.
   The coalition had viewed keeping the jets in the Mediterranean
an essential key to guaranteeing security in NATO's southern flank.
   Opposition parties in the lower house argued on Wednesday,
during the first day of debate, that Italy's acceptance of the
planes would upset the strategic balance between East and West and
hamper efforts to ease tensions between the two blocs.
   Andreotti addressed those concerns today, saying that the F-16
issue ``certainly has not damaged the relations between our
government and Moscow.'' He noted that Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze, in recent talks with Italian officials, did
not raise the subject.
   Andreotti told the chamber that basing the planes at Crotone
would serve to keep the balance between NATO and Warsaw pact forces.
   Outside Parliament, several members of the small leftist
Proletarian Democracy party, including one parliamentarian, joined
by members of Communist Party youth groups and some independent
peace activists, demonstrated peacefully against the basing of the
missiles, the Italian news agency ANSA reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
