<HEAD>Freight Plane Makes Rough Landing At Sea-Tac Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Emery Air Freight DC-8 with hydraulic problems
blew out four tires when it landed at Seattle-Tacoma International
Airport today, forcing one of airport's two main runways to close,
authorities said.
   A small fire broke out because of the rough landing, but airport
crews quickly extinguished it and the five-member crew was
evacuated with no injuries, Port of Seattle officials said.
   Port spokeswoman Vicki Schmitz said the flight to Seattle from
Dayton, Ohio, warned the control tower of the plane's hydraulic
problems. Emergency crews were on hand for its landing.
   The DC-8 was diverted from the main runway after landing, Ms.
Schmitz said, and the flat tires would be changed before the plane
was unloaded.
   No delays were reported because of the shutdown runway three
hours after the landing.
