<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-Bias     06-30 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Bias,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Study Alleged Race Discrimination in Alaskan Salmon
Canneries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 13th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to study
alleged race discrimination in Alaskan salmon canneries, setting
the stage for an important sequel to a one-day-old ruling that
makes it easier for workers to prove their bosses are guilty of
illegal bias.
   The justices said they will hear an appeal by two companies
based in Washington state and Oregon that operate canneries in
Alaska.
   The court will review a ruling that the companies must stand
trial on bias charges by non-whites, primarily Filipinos, Alaskan
natives and Asians who say they are relegated to the lowest-paying
jobs.
   A ruling by the justices is expected sometime in 1989.
   By an 8-0 vote Wednesday, the justices said employees can use
statistical evidence to prove that some subjective decisions made
by their employers violate federal law. The court reinstated a suit
by a black woman who charged a Texas bank with discrimination.
   But only four justices in the Texas case agreed on how difficult
it should be to prove, with statistics, that subjective decisions
are illegally discriminatory.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, the newest member of the court, did
not take part in reviewing the Texas dispute.
   By agreeing to study the Alaskan cannery case, the justices will
have the opportunity to elaborate on some of the guidelines it
provided Wednesday. Their eventual ruling could have widespread
impact for job-bias claims.
   Non-whites charged discrimination against Wards Cove Packing Co.
Inc. of Seattle, Wash., and Castle & Cooke Inc. of Astoria, Ore.
   The companies operate salmon canneries in remote areas of Alaska
during the summer salmon run.
   The non-whites said that while they hold nearly half the jobs at
the canneries, the jobs are racially stratified with whites
dominating in the higher-paying positions such as machinists,
carpenters and administrative slots.
   The non-whites also said that discrimination is so pervasive
that mess halls and bunkhouses are racially segregated.
   Even the salmon-butchering machine at one of the canneries has a
name with racial overtones _ the ``Iron Chink,'' they said.
   But lawyers for the cannery companies said any racial divisions
are caused by legitimate business-related reasons. They said, for
example, that most of the higher-paying jobs require skill and
prior experience that it is difficult for the non-whites to acquire
because they are seasonal workers from remote regions of Alaska.
   Moreover, the companies' lawyers said, the lower paid cannery
workers are hired through a union which is primarily non-white.
   The companies said statistics showing non-whites hold most of
the seasonal cannery worker jobs should not be allowed as proof of
discrimination. The companies said what is relevant is that they
hire for the higher-ranking positions from a labor market that is
only 10 percent non-white. The companies said they have filled
those better jobs with more than 20 percent non-whites.
   A federal judge ruled in favor of the companies in 1983. But the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated the bias suit by the
non-whites last September.
   The appeals court said statistics showing a concentration of
non-whites in the lower-paying jobs can be used as evidence of
discrimination in the better jobs. The appeals court also gave the
non-whites broad leeway to cite a host of company employment
practices to support their discrimination claims, placing a heavy
burden on the company to disprove those claims.
   For example, the non-whites said the firms are guilty of
nepotism _ hiring relatives for the better jobs. The federal judge
who ruled in favor of the companies said any nepotism was
permissible because those hired had greater skills and were not
given jobs because they are relatives of other employees or bosses.
   But the 9th Circuit court, in reviving the suit, said the
companies must prove that any nepotism was a ``business necessity.''
   The case is Wards Cove vs. Antonio, 87-1387.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
