<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Cambodia-Fears Bjt   06-30 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia-Fears, Bjt,0889</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Pullout Haunted By Violent Specter Of Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The withdrawal of Vietnamese forces
from Cambodia has conjured fears of a comeback by the dreaded Khmer
Rouge, one of the most brutal regimes of modern times.
   Although it has been nearly a decade since the Khmer Rouge were
toppled by the Vietnamese invasion, there is a fear in southeast
Asia of a reprise of their 1975-78 reign of terror in Cambodia.
According to some estimates, up to 3 million people died.
   ``One has to be either naive or an idiot to believe that the
Khmer Rouge in the '80s can be different from the Khmer Rouge of
the '70s,'' Prince Norodom Sihanouk, Cambodia's former leader, said
recently.
   Having been both their prisoner and their ally, few outsiders
know the Khmer Rouge as well as Sihanouk.
   Similar apprehension is being voiced in the now bustling capital
of Phnom Penh, whose citizens died by the tens of thousands in a
forced march into the countryside during the Khmer Rouge rule.
   And, somewhat ironically, alarms are being sounded in countries
that in recent years have called for the withdrawal of the
Vietnamese and tried with considerable success to brand Hanoi an
international pariah because of its late 1978 invasion of Cambodia.
   ``We cannot preclude the possibility that a Vietnamese
withdrawal might create conditions in which the Khmer Rouge could
return to power,'' said U.S. Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y. and
chairman of the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on Asia.
   Solarz recently described a Khmer Rouge comeback as ``morally
unthinkable and politically unacceptable'' and called for an
international conference to face this dilemma.
   There have been other proposals, such as holding internationally
supervised elections, disarming warring parties, and creating a
United Nations peacekeeping force to prevent Khmer Rouge domination
of a post-war Cambodia.
   ``I would like people to know who really is the obstruction to
peace in Cambodia: the Vietnamese or the Khmer Rouge,'' said former
Thai prime minister and elder statesman Kukrit Pramoj.
   Thailand has been a vocal opponent of Hanoi and allows Chinese
arms to flow through its territory to the Khmer Rouge.
   Such concern was set off by Hanoi's partial withdrawal Thursday
of some of its 50,000 troops. Vietnam, apparently with some Soviet
urging, has promised to pull out all its remaining forces by 1990
and said it would enter talks to find a political solution to the
protracted conflict.
   In the absence of a Vietnamese military shield, the
35,000-member army of the People's Republic of Kampuchea would be
left alone to face the three-party coalition of the Khmer Rouge and
two non-communist groups, Khmer People's National Liberation Front
and Sihanouk's followers.
   Despite Hanoi's claims that the Phnom Penh regime can stand on
its own, virtually all western analysts regard its army as
substandard.
   Western analysts and the two coalition partners themselves have
pointed out that the Khmer Rouge have done little fighting but have
stockpiled much weaponry in recent months. The conclusion drawn is
that the guerrillas are trying to put themselves in the strongest
position possible in the event of a ceasefire.
   China, the prime backer of the Khmer Rouge, is key to their
future. Although denying recent American newspaper reports that it
was prepared to grant asylum to the top Khmer Rouge leaders, says
Beijing appears ready to show some flexibility on the Cambodian
issue, the U.S. State Department says.
   Some analysts speculate that if peace comes the Khmer Rouge will
have difficulty retaining their rank and file, who may rally to the
side of Sihanouk.
   Still widely popular, the 65-year-old Sihanouk has been
Cambodia's king, head of state and nominal chief of a front, which
included the Khmer Rouge, that fought the U.S.-backed Phnom Penh
government in the 1970-75 war.
   After victory, Sihanouk became a prisoner of the Khmer Rouge,
who released him as Vietnamese troops moved into Cambodia so he
could plead the country's case before the world community.
   During their rule, Khmer Rouge leaders turned Cambodia into a
vast labor camp and charnel house
   By conservative estimates, hundreds of thousands were killed;
Phnom Penh says three million perished. Schools were closed,
Buddhist temples destroyed, all private property was abolished and
millions were forced to labor in the fields on near-starvation
diets.
   The top Khmer Rouge leaders, including Pol Pot, Ieng Sary and
Khieu Samphan, reverted to being guerrillas after the Vietnamese
invasion and admitted only to ``some mistakes'' during their rule.
They claimed to have renounced communism.
   The Khmer Rouge dropped the harshest aspects of their rule but
human rights groups and defectors have consistently reported severe
punishments in areas of the Thai-Cambodian border under their
control.
   The United Nations recently said it might cut off aid to a
second Khmer Rouge border camp because its leaders have blocked
outside aid efforts and reportely prevented refugees from being
evacuated for medical treatment.
   A U.N. official cited ``bizarre violations of human rights.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Denis D. Gray, bureau chief for The Associated
Press in Thailand, covered Cambodia during the Indochina War and
visits the country from his base in Bangkok.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
