<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Spy,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court To Hear Convicted Spy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court agreed Thursday to
grant a retrial in the case of an air force officer whose spying
conviction was based on circumstantial evidence.
   His attorney said he was confident the court would clear the
officer, Lt. Col. Bertil Stroberg, who maintained he was innocent.
   Stroberg completed half his six-year sentence and was released
on parole in 986.
   Stroberg said he was doing a favor for an acquaintance when he
went to a post office to pick up a letter indicating he offered to
sell military secrets to Poland.
   The letter was planted by police who earlier were alerted to a
spy operation by another letter sent to the Polish Embassy
containing military secrets and offering more information for
payment.
   ``There was no direct evidence that Stroberg had written the
letter to the embassy nor that he had delivered it,'' said his
lawyer, Ulla Jacobsson.
   The 1983 case received notoriety in part because Stroberg
continued to receive 90 percent of his military salary while he was
in jail.
</TEXT>
