<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Cambodia     06-30 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Cambodia,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Sees Chances Improved for Cambodian Solution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conditions for a political solution to the
long Cambodian conflict have improved with a Vietnamese troop
withdrawal and plans for discussions among all sides in the
conflict later this year in Indonesia, administration officials
said Thursday.
   ``Recent events in Indochina suggest reasons for being
cautiously optimistic about ending the seemingly intractable
conflict in Cambodia,'' said Karl D. Jackson, deputy assistant
secretary of defense for East Asia.
   Jackson and David Lamberston, a deputy assistant secretary of
state for the region, cited the withdrawal of 50,000 Vietnamese
troops from Cambodia that began this month and the prospect for
informal talks among Cambodian factions, Vietnam and other
interested parties in Indonesia in late July.
   ``We do not expect concrete decisions to result from these
initial talks, but we believe that they reflect increasing momentum
in the direction of a political settlement of the conflict,''
Lamberston told the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on East Asia.
   Both officials reiterated U.S. concern that the withdrawal of
Vietnamese occupation troops could create an opening for the
resumption of power by the Khmer Rouge, which was responsible for
the genocide of more than a million Cambodians in the 1970s under
the ruthless leadership of Pol Pot.
   Also testifying at the hearing was Kitty Dukakis, wife of the
apparent Democratic presidential nominee, Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis. Mrs. Dukakis asked for a greater U.S. commitment
to improving the lives of the 300,000 or more Cambodian refugees
now living in camps along the Thai-Cambodian border.
   Living conditions in the camps have deteriorated, she said.
Residents have no space in which to grow fresh vegetables, and the
60 percent of their inhabitants who are children have no place to
play. Rapes and brutality have increased, and Thai officials are
failing to provide adequate security, she said.
   While some education is available to the refugee children, it is
of poor quality, Mrs. Dukakis added. ``It is a tragic loss of the
future of Cambodia ... We must provide a sense of hope.''
</TEXT>
