<HEAD>Savimbi Says Reagan Backs Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6 grafs new material for 2nd graf pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan guerrilla leader Jonas Savimbi today
met with President Reagan and said afterward that Reagan agreed
with a new plan intended to bring ``peace and reconciliation to my
country.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said after Sabimvi spoke
with reporters that ``generally speaking'' Reagan supports
Savimbi's plan. Fitzwater did not go into detail.
   In a speech to the National Press Club following his White House
meeting, Savimbi listed the four points of the plan:
   _U.S. military assistance should continue for UNITA as long as
the Soviet Union and Cuba continue to provide military assistance
to the Angolan government his guerrillas are battling.
   _The United States should maintain contact with the governments
of Angola, Cuba, the Soviet Union and South Africa to ``force the
withdrawal of all foreign troops from Angola as soon as possible.''
   _The United States and key African states should promote a
dialogue between UNITA and the Angolan government to discuss the
formation of an interim government leading to free elections.
   _The United States and African countries should obtain
agreeement from both UNITA and the Angolan government on a date for
free elections.
   The United States says Cuba has about 45,000 Cuban troops in
Angola backing that nation's Marxist government. Savimbi's UNITA
organization receives about $16 million in U.S. aid, including
shoulder-fired anti-aircraft missiles, a year.
   Savimbi, who has said he is satisfied with the U.S. aid, said he
did not mention the subject to Reagan.
   But he said he did support U.S.-sponsored negotiations between
the Angolan government, South Africa and Cuba intended to gain the
withdrawal of the Cuban troops as well as South African soldiers
who support Savimbi's guerrillas.
   Many U.S. civil rights leaders oppose Savimbi because of his
South African support. Democrats in Congress are calling for a new
ban on U.S. aid to UNITA.
   Today, however, he was accompanied to the White House by Ralph
David Abernathy of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference and
several prominent black Republicans who vouched for Savimbi's
opposition to South African apartheid.
   The White House said Savimbi met privately with Reagan and they
were joined later by Abernathy and the black Republicans, who
included Charles Evers, mayor of Fayette, Miss., and Maurice
Dawkins, candidate for the Senate in Virginia.
   Abernathy said Savimbi deserved U.S. support from ``the black
people of America and the world, and white people of goodwill and
all mankind'' in his effort to bring peace to Angola.
   Before coming to Washington this week, Savimbi toured the
southern United States in an effort to build support in
predominantly black churches.
   On Wednesday, Savimbi said in a speech that UNITA would accept
support from wherever we get it.''
</TEXT>
