<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-TaxBreak     06-30 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Tax Break,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Common Cause Assails Proposed Tax Break On Lawmakers' Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government watchdog group on Thursday urged
members of the House tax-writing committee to reject a proposal to
give lawmakers a bigger deduction on their homes.
   ``This action would ... enhance preferential tax treatment for
members of Congress that is available to no other taxpayer,'' said
Fred Wertheimer, president of Common Cause, a group which advocates
higher ethics standards in goverhment.
   ``We strongly urge you to resist any efforts to repeal or
increase the deduction for living expenses for members of
Congress,'' he said in a letter sent to committee members.
   Ways and Means Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., has
proposed to repeal the current $3,000 limit on deductibility for
members' Washington living expenses as part of a plan allowing
higher congressional salaries in exchange for banning acceptance of
speaking fees.
   The committee is currently drafting a catch-all bill of changes
to the 1986 income tax law, and could include Rostenkowski's
proposed tax break in that legislation.
   Rostenkowski argues that his plan would treat lawmakers in the
tax code the same as businessmen and women who travel frequently.
Wertheimer said that argument was false, since Washington becomes
the normal residence for most lawmakers.
   ``Because of this special provision, members of Congress ...
(are) eligible to take business deductions for what are actually
the normal everyday costs of living at home,'' Wertheimer said.
</TEXT>
