<DOCNO> AP880630-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1341EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeamsterDissidents     06-30 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamster Dissidents,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Goals Echo Those Of Longtime Dissident Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1976, a knot of dissident Teamsters agitating
against multiple salaries, jet air fleets and other abuses by some
union leaders were showered with verbal abuse by union President
Frank Fitzsimmons.
   Twelve years later the Teamsters for a Democratic Union is a
minority party within the giant union with its own constitution,
bylaws and annual conventions. TDU goals were echoed by the reforms
the federal government sued this week to try to force on the 1.6
million-member International Brotherhood of Teamsters.
   The 11,000 members of TDU have won little more than abuse and
busted heads for their efforts.
   At the Teamsters convention in 1976 in Las Vegas, Nev., dock
worker Peter Camarata, representing the fledgling TDU, urged
changes from the convention floor. He was met with jeers, power was
cut to his microphone, and he later was beaten up at a convention
party.
   In 1983, a crowd loyal to current Teamsters President Jackie
Presser shoved its way into a Romulus, Mich., hotel where the TDU
was meeting. They trashed the meeting room but missed the
dissidents, who slipped out a side door.
   TDU influence may be wider than its 11,000 members, according to
Frank DePirro, a national organizer of the Detroit-based group. He
said he mails about 50,000 copies of the group's 10-times-yearly
newsletter Convoy Dispatch, of which he is editor.
   In the U.S. Justice Department suit filed this week, the
government proposes taking over the union and setting up direct
election of officers.
   ``If you beat your head against a stone wall for long enough,
either your head gets bloody or the wall gets a chink in it. Maybe
this is a little bit of both,'' said Washington attorney Arthur
Fox, who represents the TDU.
   The TDU agrees that direct elections are needed, but DePirro
said the rank and file doesn't trust the government to run the
union.
   Fox said TDU grew out of a meeting of truck drivers sponsored in
1971 by consumer advocate Ralph Nader, who urged members to
petition the government for protections their union did not provide
_ such as limits on driving hours.
   In 1976, Fox and a law student published ``Teamsters Democracy
and Financial Accountability,'' a book that rocked the union with
accounts of officers drawing two, three or more salaries, abuses of
the union jet fleet and widspread nepotism.
   Fox treasures a tape of a radio interview that year in which
Fitzsimmons berated him and the 6,000 Teamsters then in the
dissident group.
   ``Frank Fitzsimmons called me lots of names. ... He said we
weren't fit to sweep the floors of the Teamsters union,'' Fox said.
   Camarata voiced the TDU's positions at the 1976 convention,
proposing direct election of officers, and limiting officers to ``a
reasonable salary not to exceed $100,000.''
   Then, as now, top union officers were chosen through a delegate
system that put power in the hands of 16 regional vice presidents.
They make up the convention, said Camarata, now a driver for a
Detroit trucking company.
   ``When I went down there I walked into a total snake pit,'' he
said. ``They are just not open to any kind of opposition. They just
hated my guts.''
   Camarata was shouted down on the floor of the convention. Later
at an International Executive Board party, he was jumped and beaten
up. Camarata left the convention under the protection of hotel
security guards.
   At the Teamsters next convention, in 1981, TDU members nominated
Camarata for union president. ``I got about 10 votes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
