<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ERA     06-30 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ERA,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New ERA Drive Set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Feminists and lawmakers launched a new drive
Thursday to add an Equal Rights Amendment to the Constitution,
vowing to introduce the measure as soon as the 101st Congress
convenes in January.
   ``My dream today is that 1989 will be the last time they swear
in a president of the United States under a constitution that does
not treat women as equals,'' Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., told
about 300 people at a Capitol rally sponsored by the National
Organization for Women.
   Schroeder and Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., said they will
introduce the new ERA next year with the backing of the House
Democratic leadership and, according to Edwards, ``even some
Republicans who have seen the light.''
   Schroeder said petitions containing hundreds of thousands of
signatures, collected by NOW members across the country, would be
delivered to appropriate House delegations in order to build
advance support for the new ERA bill.
   NOW scheduled the rally for June 30 because the most recent
drive for the ERA ended on that day in 1982, when an insufficient
number of state legislatures had met the deadline for ratifying the
measure.
   Women wearing green T-shirts that said ``Put women in the
Constitution'' cheered as Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., and a
string of House members exhorted them to keep ERA alive.
   ``Watch out, all of you. ERA is coming. All the signs are
here,'' said Edwards, chairman of the House Judiciary subcommittee
on civil and constitutional rights.
   Edwards cited the congressional override of President Reagan's
veto of a major civil rights bill earlier this year and the House
vote Wednesday in favor of a fair housing bill that bans
discrimination against families with children. He also cited the
``gender gap'' afflicting the Republican Party, and suggested it
stems from GOP opposition to the ERA.
   The ERA says that ``equality of rights under the law shall not
be denied or abridged by the United States or by any state on
account of sex.'' Other sections of the brief amendment give
Congress the power to enforce it and say it shall take effect two
years after ratification.
</TEXT>
