<1ST_LINE>u i PM-F-16Crashes 3rdLd-Writethru   06-30 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-F-16 Crashes, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0634,0748</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Investigators Examine Wreckage of Crashed F-16s</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Air Force statement. Pick
up 6th graf pvs: `Two of...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BODENHEIM, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military investigators today
examined debris of two jet crashes that killed an American pilot
and destroyed three U.S. Air Force F-16 fighter planes in one day.
   A newspaper report said cracks were found in the engine blades
of some F-16s and were the likely cause of the crash of one of the
jets in April.
   The accidents Wednesday brought to five the number of F-16
fighter jets that have crashed in West Germany in the past three
months.
   A leader in Chancellor Helmut Kohl's coalition government called
for the immediate grounding of F-16 fighter jets stationed in West
Germany.
   ``If the F-16, which has recently piled up a number of crashes,
has a technical fault, it must be temporarily grounded,'' said
Werner Hoyer, a military expert and member of the Free Democratic
Party.
   The Air Force said in a statement later that it had halted all
routine flight operations to prepare for a ``safety day'' on Friday
to ``review all flying, ground and weapons safety operations.''
   The statement made no mention of the F-16 crashes.
   Two of the jets collided in the air Wednesday, and a third
crashed and exploded in the Black Forest 90 minutes earlier.
   Tracy Burnett, a spokeswoman for the 50th Tactical Fighter Wing
at Hahn Air Base, said one pilot was killed after the F-16s
collided during a training maneuver near this small town about 35
miles west of Frankfurt.
   Burnett identified the dead pilot as Capt. Michael A. Crandall,
30. His hometown was not available.
   The pilot of the other aircraft ejected to safety before his
plane plunged into a field and exploded. He was identified as Capt.
Robert McCormack, 31, of Delmar, Calif.
   McCormack was being treated for minor back and neck injuries at
an Air Force hospital in Wiesbaden, she said.
   No one was injured in the crash in the Black Forest.
   Following crashes of F-16s in March and April, the West German
Defense Ministry asked that the single-engine jets be grounded.
However, U.S. Air Force European Commander Gen. William L. Kirk
said at the time the move would be premature before determining
what caused the crashes.
   In a report from its Washington bureau, the military's
unofficial Stars and Stripes newspaper said today the U.S. Air
Force had replaced the engines of 31 F-16 jets ``because of
potential cracks in high-speed engine blades.''
   It said blade cracks found in some General Electric F110 engines
that are used in some F-16s were ``the likely cause'' of an April
18 crash near Erzberg, West Germany.
   Citing an interview with General Electric Co. spokesman Bill
Schumann, the newspaper quoted him as saying the Erzberg crash was
caused by an engine problem, ``and, as far as I know, that engine
problem was believed to have been caused by one of these blade
cracks.''
   The newspaper said the Air Force had found cracks in several GE
F110 engines, and ``as a precaution, 23 engines were removed in
Europe and eight from planes in Japan and Korea.''
   Lt. Col. Ed Neunherz, spokesman for the U.S. Air Force European
headquarters at Ramstein Air Base, declined immediate comment on
the cracked blades or possible grounding of the F-16s following the
latest crashes.
   A U.S. Army OH58 observation helicopter crashed into Lake
Starnberg in Bavaria on June 14, critically injuring the pilot and
killing the co-pilot.
   On June 9, a U.S. Army helicopter crashed after hitting power
lines near a busy highway in Bavaria state, killing the three-man
crew.
   A British Chinook helicopter on May 6 hit a loading ramp with
its rear rotor at the Hanover air show, throwing debris over a wide
area and killing two people on board. Twelve people were injured on
the ground.
   On April 18, a U.S. Air Force F-16 crashed near an ammunition
depot and hospital south of Trier near the Luxembourg border. The
pilot was slightly injured when he ejected.
   On March 31, a U.S. Air Force F-16 crashed into the town of
Forst north of Karlsruhe, killing the pilot and a resident.
   The crash came one day after a French military Mirage jet
fighter crashed in southern Bavaria near a nuclear power plant.
</TEXT>
