<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-PrizeCrops Bjt   06-30 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Prize Crops, Bjt,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought May Stunt Prize Vegetables</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROMEO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   County and state fair time is coming up but
the hot, dry summer over wide areas of the nation may be drying up
farmers' hopes of displaying plump, prize-winning cattle, pigs,
squash and pumpkins.
   And with grain crops in jeopardy, 4-H members face rising prices
for feed for their would-be blue-ribbon heifers, pigs and lambs.
   Animal exhibitor registrations for the Michigan State Fair, Aug.
26-Sept. 5, are lagging behind last year. Farmers may be hesitant
about putting their animals through the rigors of hot-weather
transport, a fair official said.
   Watering helps the ``fooling-around garden'' that produced the
largest pumpkin and the tallest sunflower at last year's state
fair, but Joe Malburg Jr. says his potential prize vegetables still
are feeling the drought.
   Malburg's sunflower last year stood 12 feet 10 inches. If he has
an entry this year, he said, ``It could still be the largest. But
it might be five feet shorter than last year.''
   The drought creates problems for Michigan's 9- to 19-year-old
4-H Youth Program exhibitors, who entered 3,704 swine, 3,615 cattle
and 2,919 sheep in county fairs last year, said Ken Geuns, 4-H
livestock youth specialist at Michigan State University.
   Feed corn and hay prices are rising in anticipation of short
harvests. Out in drought-stunted hayfields, Geuns said, ``A lot of
people are harvesting whatever forage they can.''
   But many of the youths have no hayfields, he said. ``Where it's
going to affect the kids right now is in terms of buying feed. A
reasonably high percentage of the kids, their families are not
full-time farmers.''
   Geuns said about 200 head of cattle were entered in the recent
Michigan Youth All Breed Beef and Sheep Show at Ionia, down 50 from
last year.
   The show may have lost exhibitors to a competing show in
Maryland, he said, but ``I think some of it was due to the
weather.''
   Many youths may have to put off their fall or early winter
purchases of cattle to fatten for next year's exhibits, Geuns said.
   With a month before the Aug. 1 deadline for entering livestock
in the state fair, Joanne Schwedt of the fair's entries office said
registrations, particularly of heat-sensitive swine, seem to be
trailing last year's.
   Part of the problem is general, Schwedt said. ``It's no secret
farmers are not doing well. The fewer farmers, the fewer exhibits
there are.''
   But she said farmers who do want to enter probably are waiting
for a break in the heat.
   ``It's extremely expensive to bring your animals down to the
state fair to show them. In these weather conditions, they just
won't do it,'' she said. ``And the vegetables will be hurt. I don't
think you will see a lot of big pumpkins and so on.''
   Malburg raised his sunflowers and his wife, Pam, raised last
year's largest pumpkin, 182 pounds, on a one-acre plot on the
180-acre farm of Joe's parents in Romeo.
   Their plot with potential prize pumpkin plants, squash and
Indian and other decorative corn varieties gets some special
treatment, said Malburg's mother, Clara. ``We have it right by our
house here. We've been keeping it going with the sprinkler from the
house.''
   But that is no substitute for a wet summer, she said.
   ``It's so windy and dry and hot that even if you irrigate, the
next morning it's gone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
