<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Environment     06-30 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Environment,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ecological Issues Hit at Party Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A steelworker harangued government leaders
Thursday for their failure to deal with ecological problems he said
have reached ``the level of a Chernobyl-like catastrophe.''
   Veniamin A. Yarin, a middle-aged mill operator at a huge steel
mill in the Ural Mountains, was one of several delegates to the
nationwide Communist Party conference who raised the problem of the
environment either at the rostrum or in written suggestions to the
forum.
   But Yarin's speech hit home particularly hard because he comes
from the city of Nizhny Tagil, 10,000 of its 403,000 inhabitants
took to the streets earlier this year to protest pollution caused
by two 45-year-old coke-burning furnaces at a steel mill.
   Soviet media accounts in April quoted a crying woman at the
demonstration demanding, ``Who will answer for 54 stillborn
children in 1987?''
   Yarin dramatized his plea for urgent action by telling the 5,000
delegates that an old Bolshevik had told him to go before this
week's conference and sing a line from a popular song where pigeons
fly over town roofs.
   ``At our works, we've long had no pigeons. We don't even have
crows,'' Yarin said. ``We look up at the sky and we are horrified.''
   But city inhabitants were just as shocked when they studied the
text of a national government resolution for action to clean the
air in their town.
   ``Our hair stood on end at how little action was going to be
taken,'' he said.
   Yarin said he believed there were 50 to 100 cities in the Soviet
Union where ecological damage had become a serious health threat.
He demanded an immediate government resolution on a group of these
cities and funds to resolve their problems within two years.
   ``I'm not afraid to say that this problem has reached the level
of a Chernobyl-like catastrophe,'' Yanin said, referring to the
explosion and fire at a Ukrainian nuclear plant on April 27, 1986,
that led to at least 31 deaths.
   A $14 billion program was launched to clean up the contamination
caused by the accident and to rehouse an estimated 135,000 people
who were evacuated.
   Environmental problems ``have a huge social resonance,'' Yanin
said. ``They should be discussed at this conference.''
   Also Thursday, the Communist Party chief of the Central Asian
republic of Uzbekistan addressed one of the nation's most serious
ecological catastrophes, the drop in the water level of a vast
inland sea, the Aral Sea.
   A newspaper account in 1983 said excessive tapping of the sea
for irrigation in Central Asia had halved its depth in a decade and
caused its shoreline to recede 40 miles in just a few years.
   That account was ahead of its time in sounding the alarm on
ecological problems, which in the past two years have received
increasing attention in the media and from intellectuals.
   In 1986, an active campaign by well-known writers led the ruling
Politburo to overturn a potentially catastrophic decision to
reverse the flow of several northward-flowing rivers to the arid
south for irrigation.
   But the media still are full of ecological horror stories like
the one from Nizhny Tagil. In December, the Communist Party daily
newspaper Pravda quoted intellectuals in the Urals city of Ufa as
saying their city was no longer fit for human habitation because of
chemical pollution.
   All three Baltic republics have brought written resolutions to
the conference about the urgent need to deal with ecological damage
in their areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
