<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   06-30 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students, Soldiers Clash In East Jerusalem; Seven Schools Closed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab students threw stones and smashed
windshields during protests in Jerusalem on Thursday, and
authorities shut down seven Palestinian schools.
   A 17-year-old Arab was shot and wounded in a clash with soldiers
during a funeral in the occupied West Bank.
   An Arab teen-ager shot by soldiers two weeks ago died in a West
Bank hospital, bringing to 213 the number of Palestinians killed
since the ``intefadeh,'' or uprising, began Dec. 8. Four Israelis
also have been killed.
   In Jerusalem, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told reporters that
Israel was ``closer to the end'' of the uprising against the
21-year occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Dozens of high school girls staged rock-throwing protests in
several parts of Arab east Jerusalem, and police responded with
tear gas, Israel radio reported. It said several car windshields
were smashed and two girls were arrested.
   Two male students were arrested after throwing stones at police
from a high school in the walled Old City, the radio said. It said
police closed the Dar El Aytam School.
   In the West Bank, the army closed six schools following violent
protests in the past few days against the Israeli occupation, said
Olivier Rafowicz, spokesman for the military government in the West
Bank.
   Rafowicz said Thursday's closures brought to 38 the number of
schools shut since June 6 when classes on the West Bank resumed
after a four-month suspension that began in February.
   ``If the disturbances are not going to be stopped, we will be
forced to close all the schools and we will not allow students to
take final exams,'' Rafowicz said.
   The army shut down more than 1,000 schools in the West Bank on
Feb. 2. Israeli officials had hoped that the reopening of schools
in the West Bank would help restore normal life in the area.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus on Thursday, soldiers shot a
17-year-old in the left leg, officials at Al Ittihad Hospital said.
   Soldiers opened fire when youths, some wearing masks, threw
stones and tried to incite a riot among people taking part in a
funeral of a heart-attack victim, an army spokesman said. One youth
was wounded and several were arrested, he said.
   The Palestinian youth who died Thursday, Arafat Awad Hanani, was
shot by soldiers June 6 in the village of Beit Furik near Nablus.
Villagers began throwing stones after soldiers blew up an Arab home.
   Shamir talked to reporters after delivering a speech to the
Washington Institute for Near East Policy. He said the army
reported a drop in the past few days in violent incidents in the
West Bank and Gaza.
   Asked if the uprising was at an end, Shamir replied: ``I can't
determine that. There is no doubt that we are getting closer to the
end.''
   Shamir told the American group that the uprising wasn't about
land at all.
   ``The experience of the last few months should have taught all
that the problem is not of territories, but of Arab refusal to
recognize the legitimacy and permanence of the state of Israel,''
he said.
   Shamir repeated he saw no reason to negotiate with the PLO
``because they oppose peace with Israel.''
   A magistrate's court sentenced four Israeli leftists to
six-month jail terms for violating a law that forbids contact with
the PLO. They were the first Israelis sentenced under the 1986 law.
   The four were convicted June 2 in the court in Ramle, near Tel
Aviv, for violating the law by meeting with 15 PLO members in
Costinesti, Romania, in November 1986. The jails terms were
postponed until Aug. 4 to allow an appeal.
   Also Thursday, a trial opened in a military court for 19
Palestinians accused of taking part in a clash with hikers from a
Jewish settlement. A 15-year-old Israeli girl was killed in the
April 6 clash in the West Bank village of Beita.
   The incident caused a furor among Israelis after Jewish settlers
said the villagers shot the girl, Tirza Porat. But an army
investigation later determined she was accidentally shot by one of
the guards accompanying the hikers.
   Among the charges against the Arab defendants are
stone-throwing, causing serious bodily harm, making threats, and
trying to seize and conceal the weapons of the two guards.
</TEXT>
