<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1409EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     06-30 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Attack Leftist University President for Second Time in
Seven Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen with a grenade launcher and
automatic rifles attacked a leftist university president Thursday,
the second attempt against him in seven months, police said. Three
bodyguards were killed.
   The educator, five aides and a pedestrian were wounded, but none
seriously, police said.
   The ambush occurred as Nemesio Prudente and his party approached
the campus of the government-run Polytechnic University of the
Philippines.
   No group claimed responsibility. The first attack, in November,
was blamed on right-wing extremists.
   ``This second attempt on the life of Dr. Prudente is brutal,
brazen and contemptible,'' President Corazon Aquino said in a
statement read by spokesman Teodoro Benigno. She ordered a ``speedy
solution.''
   Shortly before the attack, three suspected communist urban
guerrillas shot and killed a policeman in the Manila suburb of
Malabon.
   Sen. Ernesto Maceda, chairman of the Senate's defense committee,
criticized police for failing to maintain order in the capital,
which has been rocked in recent years by killings blamed on
left-wing and right-wing extremists.
   ``It seems easy for anybody to shoot and kill anybody in this
country,'' Maceda said.
   Police said Prudente and his aides were ambushed as they
approached the university campus at 8:45 a.m. The group was
traveling in a van followed by a security car.
   Four gunmen waited for Prudente's party to pass under a concrete
bridge and then opened fire with grenades and automatic rifles,
police said. Two others acted as lookouts, police said.
   Prudente suffered shrapnel wounds in the left arm and both legs,
police said.
   The military and police have accused Prudente, an outspoken
human rights activist, of using the school to shelter communist
urban guerrillas. Prudente denied the charge.
   On Nov. 11, suspected rightwing extremists sprayed his car with
bullets, wounding the educator and killing a university lawyer.
   No arrests have been made in that attack. But human rights
groups blamed right-wing death squads for the first ambush, which
occurred a week after soldiers and policemen chanted ``Kill
Prudente!' during a funeral for a police captain and three other
people killed by communist assassins.

