<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     06-30 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Begin's Son, Netanyahu Chosen at American-Style Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of former Prime Minister Menachem Begin
and former U.N. ambassador Benjamin Netanyahu were among the
parliamentary candidates chosen Thursday by the main faction in the
right-wing Likud bloc.
   The political newcomers in the Herut Party election won more
votes than most of the veterans in Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
Cabinet, including Industry Minister Ariel Sharon and Deputy
Premier David Levy.
   Herut is the senior partner of Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc,
which shares power in a shaky alliance with the left-leaning Labor
party. Also in the Likud is the Liberal Party.
   Herut was founded by Begin as an outgrowth of his Etzel
underground militia that fought the British rulers in Palestine in
the 1940s.
   The results of the secret balloting by 2,092 central committee
members do not determine the place any of the 35 candidates will
hold on the party list for the November election.
   The nominees will be ranked July 7, with Shamir assured the top
spot. Only about 30 of the nominees are likely to be elected.
   But the showings made by Netanyahu and Benjamin Begin meant they
were likely to be ranked high. They also boosted Shamir's standing
in his fractious party while dealing a blow to his rival, Sharon.
   During the convention at a country club in Herzliya, north of
Tel Aviv, many of the 104 candidates used American-style gimmicks
to attract the attention of the Central Committee members.
Candidates showered delegates with buttons, stickers, balloons,
wine and perfume _ campaign methods new to Israel.
   It also was an attempt to keep up with the Labor party, whose
convention earlier this month was marked by carnival-style antics.
   Netanyahu and Begin, among 14 new faces on the party's list, are
expected to enhance Likud's chances of defeating the Labor party,
which elected a slate of young, new candidates earlier this month.
   Shamir, pleased by the results, told reporters: ``We have an
excellent list which will also give the public incentive to vote
for us.''
   Pollsters predict a close race between the two parties, and the
latest survey shows Labor with a slight edge of Likud.
   Begin, a 44-year-old geologist, is the first offspring of an
Israeli prime minister to enter politics successfully.
   Begin said his victory showed party members were repaying his
father ``with extraordinary love.''
   His father, a recluse since he resigned in 1983, issued a
statement broadcast on Israel army radio, saying he was happy with
his son's victory.
   The younger Begin became active in the party shortly after his
father resigned, but refrained from declaring himself a legislative
candidate until just before the convention.
   Netanyahu, 39, and son of a Cornell University professor, spent
most of his teen-age years in the United States. He went to high
school in Philadelphia and studied business administration at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
   He made Arab terrorism a chief target of his speeches in his
four years as U.N. ambassador. He stepped down this year to run for
parliament.
   ``It is very flattering to see this kind of support,'' a beaming
Netanyahu said on Israel television.
   Netanyahu won the highest number of votes with 1,408.
Iranian-born Moshe Katsav, a labor minister in Shamir's Cabinet,
was second with 1,324, while Begin finished third with 1,233.
Sharon came in fifth; Levy seventh.
   In the balloting, committee members had to cast votes for 21 of
the 104 candidates. The top 35 made the slate, but only about 30
have a realistic chance of being elected to parliament.
   Under Israel's electoral system, voters choose a party, not
individual candidates. The party is apportioned seats in the
120-member parliament according to the number of votes it gets.
  
</TEXT>
