<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     06-30 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Renews Amnesty Offer to Tamils</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has renewed its offer
of general amnesty for Tamil rebels if the dominant militia agrees
to surrender its weapons and stop fighting for a separate homeland,
a communique said Thursday.
   The government also promised to free all Tamil political
prisoners in jails and military detention camps. More than 600
Tamils are believed still in custody.
   In addition, it pledged to complete arrangements for an election
for a new regional council in Tamil-dominated areas by the end of
July. The council would give Tamils a greater voice in their own
affairs.
   According to reports, the dominant rebel group, the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, is close to an agreement with India to end
the 5-year-old insurgency for a separate homeland in north and east
Sri Lanka.
   ``If the Tamil militants would lay down arms and support the
Indo-Sri Lankan agreement, the detenus will be released and all
Tamil militant groups would be granted general amnesty and would be
allowed to return to the mainstream of the democratic process,''
said the statement issued by the Presidential Secretariat.
   The statement appeared aimed at assuring the Tigers that the
terms of the peace accord would be carried out despite the Tigers'
intransigence.
   The peace accord, brokered by India, was signed July 29, 1987,
by President Junius R. Jayewardene and Indian Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi. It included amnesty for the guerrillas and a pledge to
release all prisoners.
   The Tigers at first accepted the accord, but later resumed
fighting. The Sri Lankan government withdrew the amnesty promise,
and India moved an estimated 50,000 troops to the island to put
down the insurgency.
   Talks between the Tigers and members of the Indian Research and
Analysis Wing, an intelligence branch of the Indian government,
have been under way in recent weeks in southern India.
   The top Indian diplomat in Sri Lanka, High Commissioner J.N.
Dixit, was called to New Delhi last weekend for talks with Gandhi
on the negotiations with the Tigers. Dixit returned to Colombo on
Wednesday and briefed Jayewardene, according to officials at the
Indian High Commission, or embassy.
   The statement issued by the government Thursday said that Gandhi
informed Jayewardene that the Tigers militia ``has given
indications of their williness to lay down their arms and cooperate
in the implementation of the Indo-Sri Lankan agreement.''
   It gave no clues on when a final deal with the Tigers might be
reached.
   Tamils are mostly Hindus and make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million population. They claim they are discriminated against by
the majority Sinhalese Buddhists, who control the government.
   Militant Tamils began fighting for an independent homeland in
July 1983. Authorities have said at least 8,000 people have died.
   India became involved because it is the dominant power in South
Asia and its own 60 million ethnic Tamils are sympathetic to their
Sri Lankan brethren.
</TEXT>
