<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Lefebvre-Americans 1stLd-Writethru a0632 06-30 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lefebvre-Americans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0632,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Archbishops Followers Sticking With Him</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 19th graf, `Internationally, the...' to include higher
estimate of rebel group.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Lefebvre Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American followers of rebel Archbishop Marcel
Lefebvre say they are sticking with his movement rejecting Roman
Catholic reforms despite his break with the official church.
   His consecration of four bishops in Switzerland on Thursday in
defiance of Rome brings his automatic excommunication and marks the
first split in the church in 118 years.
   ``I don't know of a single priest or seminarian who is leaving
because of this so-called excommunication,'' said the Rev. Charles
Ward of St. Louis, administrator of the movement's U.S. district.
   ``We're holding fast to the faith, which is what a true Catholic
does. We know he (Lefebvre) is teaching the truth.''
   Other American adherents of the Lefebvre revolt, organized
internationally as the Priestly Society of St. Pius X, expressed
the same determination.
   ``There's no dissenion in our ranks,'' said Jason Huvar of
Victoria, Texas, one of about 15 seminarians refurbishing new
quarters for their St. Thomas Aquinas Seminary near Winona, Minn.
   ``It's a dire situation,'' he said in a telephone interview.
``But what is being done had to be done.
   ``It's a matter of life and death for the faith, of keeping
traditional priests. You can't have them without bishops to ordain
them.''
   Lefebvre, 82, under suspension since 1976 for condemning key
reforms of the 1962-65 Second Vatican Council, has continued to
ordain priests and celebrate other sacraments.
   But the further step of consecrating new bishops to perpetuate
his revolt beyond his lifetime formalizes the breach with Rome,
marking failure of recent Vatican negotiations for reconciliation.
   ``He is taking measures to insure continuation of the Catholic
priesthood, the traditional Mass and survival of the church,'' said
Timothy McDonnell, a seminarian from Manitowoc, Wis.
   He said other U.S. priests and bishops ``are no longer teaching
the faith,'' and Lefebvre is consecrating new bishops ``to maintain
the faith. Most of us have been openly for it.''
   He and others followers echoed charges by Lefebvre that Rome's
embrace of religious liberty, ecumenical relations with other
churches and the vernacular liturgy violated Catholic tradition and
were ``democratizing'' it.
   McDonnell said the changes parallel those of 16th-century
Protestant reformers Martin Luther, John Calvin and Thomas Cranmer.
   Other than Ward, top officers of the Lefebvre's U.S. movement
were in Switzerland for the consecrations, including the movement's
superior, the Rev. Francois Laisney of St. Louis, and its seminary
rector, the Rev. Richard Richardson.
   Ward compared Lefebvre's excommunication to the fourth-century
papal excommunication of Alexandrian Bishop Athanasius, later made
a saint. Lefebvre, Ward said, ``can't truly be ecommunicated. He
will be by the letter of the law, but not by the spirit of the
law.''
   The U.S. wing of the Lefebvre movement has 29 priests, about 95
centers across the country for worship in the traditional
Tridentine Latin Mass, an estimated l0,000 lay participants, and
various substantial properties.
   Those listed include St. Vincent's Church in Kansas City, Mo.;
Immaculate Conception Church and a grammar school at Post Falls,
Idaho; Queen of Angels Church and printing press for its magazine,
Angelus, at Dickinson, Texas; and a grammar school, high school and
two-year college at St. Marys, Kan.
   Internationally, the movement has 220 priests and an estimated
100,000 followers, with seminaries in Switzerland, Argentina,
Australia, Germany and France, enrolling about 250 seminarians.
Some Vatican officials have said the movement has as many as a
half-million followers.
   Kenneth Novak of Downers Grove, Ill., one of about 40
seminarians in this country, said the society is ``the only
institution organized to perpetuate the faith. Rome is no longer
defending the faith and tradition.''
   He said most people in the Lefebvre movement ``had already made
up their minds beforehand'' and would stick with him despite
excommunication.
   ``If any leave, it will be the weaker types, the fringe,'' he
said.
   ``It's a bad thing that we're being condemned for being what
Catholics should be,'' said Huvar. ``Thirty years ago, we'd be
considered good. Now we're considered schismatics, outcasts and
rebels.''
</TEXT>
