<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1458EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Sinatra     06-30 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Sinatra,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Friar's Club Elects First Women Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Friar's Club elected its first female
members Thursday, none of whom should need membership cards to be
recognized at the door.
   Barbara Sinatra, Lucille Ball, Carol Burnett, Eydie Gorme,
Barbra Streisand, Elizabeth Taylor, Dinah Shore, Phyllis Diller and
Martha Raye all were elected to honorary membership after the
club's board of governors changed its constitution to allow female
members.
   Liza Minnelli, who had applied for regular membership, was
approved, according to Friar's spokesman Al Rylander.
   The 84-year-old club's decision to admit women followed a U.S.
Supreme Court ruling that upheld a New York City
anti-discrimination law. The law prohibits private clubs from
banning women.
   The California Friar's Club, in Beverly Hills, voted last year
to admit women. A member of the California club, Los Angeles
attorney Gloria Allred, was admitted to the New York club for lunch
last week following the court's ruling.
   The Friar's Club has more than 1,300 members in New York, most
of them active in the performing arts. Frank Sinatra is its top
officer, the abbot.
</TEXT>
