<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 2ndLd-Writethru a0579 06-30 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0579,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Jets Bomb Iranian Gas Plant; Iraq Claims Victories On Land</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with new victory claimed. Picks
up 6th pvs, `Earlier, the...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Musavi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its warplanes bombed Iran's
biggest gas production plant and attacked an offshore oil field
today, and it claimed major victories in the northern and central
sectors of the war front.
   State-run Baghdad Radio interrupted programming to announce that
Iraqi troops, backed by tanks and helicopter gunships, recaptured
four ``strategic'' border heights along the Shehabi ridge, in the
central sector of the 733-mile front.
   ``The enemy is collapsing,'' Baghdad Radio declared. ``The four
heights were purged of the filthy enemy.''
   Earlier, Baghdad Radio reported that the northern Mawat basin,
in the Kurdistan mountains, was ``liberated'' after fierce battles
with the Iranians.
   It said the Iraqi flag was hoisted on 24 strategic heights
overlooking the town of Mawat town at 2:45 p.m. It said two border
outposts occupied by the Iranians also were seized.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said the Iraqis launched the
offensive at 7:30 p.m. Wednesday. There was no immediate reaction
from Tehran.
   The Iraqis have been inching into Iranian-held territory in
northern Sulaimaniyeh province for several weeks. But they have not
totally dislodged their enemy from the strategic mountain region,
inhabited mainly by pro-Iranian Kurds who are fighting the Iraqi
government for autonomy.
   Earlier, the official Iraqi News Agency said its aircraft bombed
the gas plant on Sheik Sho'eyb Island in the southern Persian Gulf
and the Cyrus oil field in the northern gulf.
   It said all the planes returned safely to their bases.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said Iraqi jets
bombed ``an industrial-labor complex'' on its southern gulf coast,
killing or wounding an unspecified number of workers and causing
some damage.
   The Iranians also claimed their air force fighters shot down an
Iraqi warplane over the gulf at 8.29 a.m., 30 minutes before the
Iraqis said their fighter-bombers hit Sheik Sho'yeb.
   The Iranian news agency, also monitored in Nicosia, said a
second Iraqi jet was shot down over western Iran by anti-aircraft
fire.
   The Iraqi News Agency quoted a military communique as saying
``large numbers'' of Iraqi warplanes were involved in the two gulf
raids and left their targets ``engulfed with fire and smoke'' after
penetrating Iranian air defenses.
   ``The Iranian regime today received a strong blow which will
have an extreme effect on its economy and oil resources,'' the
communique said.
   The raids came several days after Iraqi forces drove the
Iranians out of their last major bridgehead in southern Iraq, the
Majnoon islands in the oil-rich Howeizah marshes.
   The Iraqis recaptured the southern Faw Peninsula on April 18,
two years after the Iranians had seized it and a month later drove
them from a position east of the port city of Basra.
   These battlefield defeats dramatically swung the military
balance in the nearly 8-year-old war in Iraq's favor after years of
Iraq being on the defensive.
   The military setbacks have badly jolted Tehran. Prime Minister
Hussein Musavi said today when he was re-elected by Parliament that
Iran faces ``a historic confrontation'' with its enemies and must
``prepare for an all-out struggle against them.''
   The Iraqi communique declared: ``The Iranian regime must realize
that after the successive victories of the Iraqi army and air force
that it has to accept peace and nothing but peace.''
   The Iraqi air force's last major raids against Iranian oil
installations were June 23, when 10 targets in the southwestern
Ahwaz, Bibi Hakimah and Sarran oil fields were bombed.
</TEXT>
