<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--CubaReforms     06-30 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cuba Reforms,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Ends Hated `Watchdog Committee' Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba's hated vigilance committees will no longer
inform anonymously on neighbors with suspect attitudes, according
to a government radio broadcast monitored here Thursday.
   The so-called Committees for Defense of the Revolution are being
``perfected,'' according to the broadcast.
   Until the change, the secret, anonymous committee reports had
been necessary for a variety of activities including entrance to
universities and obtaining certain jobs.
   Reports on ``neighbors' attitudes and behavior'' have generated
problems and complaints, and ``have not been accurate in all
cases,'' said the radio report.
   In the future, the committee reports must be public and can be
filed only with the previous authorization of the Communist Party
or specific government agencies.
   The announcement was made at a meeting of the vigilance
committees' national directorate.
</TEXT>
