<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FlightLawsuit     06-30 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flight Lawsuit,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmental Groups Sue Over Air Guard Flights Over Wilderness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three environmental groups have filed a
lawsuit to block what they contend are illegal low-level flights by
Air National Guard jets over the Boundary Waters Canoe Area
Wilderness in northeastern Minnesota.
   In the lawsuit filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court, the
environmentalists contend the flights over the million-acre area
violate federal law, disrupt the area's solitude and harm wolves
and other wildlife.
   They contend the Air Guard and the Federal Aviation
Administration have failed to assess the environmental impact of
the flights.
   Since 1949, the federal government has banned flights over the
BWCA lower than 4,000 feet above sea level. The environmental
groups contend military jets have flown below that level, which in
most places is 2,000 to 2,500 feet above the ground.
   Suing are the national Izaak Walton League, Friends of the
Boundary Waters Wilderness and Friends of Animals and Their
Environment. Named as defendants are the top officials of the FAA
and the National Guard Bureau, which oversees the Air Guard.
   Don Leyden, an FAA spokesman in Washington, D.C., said Wednesday
the agency could not comment.
   The environmentalists were joined in complaints about the
flights last year by the U.S. Forest Service. Air Guard officials
challenged the contentions, saying no military flights are flown
below 4,500 feet in the area. They also said perhaps 80 percent of
Guard flights over the area were more than 8,000 feet above the
ground.
   Brian O'Neill, a lawyer representing the environmentalists, said
low-level military flights also are a problem at other wilderness
areas and national parks.
</TEXT>
