<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0677 06-30 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Liberals, Economists Trying to Hide Nation's Financial
Upturn</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng, `We're in,' with 2 grafs new to
UPDATE with Bush changing statement in delivering speech, event
raising $2 million, moves up reference to proceeds; EDITS 3rd graf
to delete now-redundant first reference to Dukakis.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush blamed liberals and
economists Thursday for seeking to cloak the good news about the
U.S. economy and compared his presidential candidacy to the 1948
come-from-behind effort of Democrat Harry Truman.
   ``We're in for a real battle in the fall. Everybody knows
that,'' the vice president told a $10,000-a-couple GOP fund-raising
luncheon that raised $2 million toward a fund to be used by the
Republican National Committee for the fall election, according to
organizers.
   The $8.3 million fund is exempt from the $2,000-a-person limit
on direct campaign contributions to a candidate, according to
federal election laws that also prevented Bush from mentioning his
Democratic rival Michael Dukakis in his speech.
   Although recent public opinion polls show a narrowing of
Dukakis' early lead, Bush said Republicans still face an uphill
struggle _ in part because a Republican has been in the White House
for two terms.
   ``After eight years of one party in the White House, no matter
how successful, some good people yearn for a change _ hoping that
change will mean improvement,'' the likely nominee told the GOP
audience. ``And it's our job to let them know that this time, in
this case, change and improvement come from the Republican party.''
   The vice president also accused liberals of ``champing at the
bit to raise taxes again'' and said, ``the trouble with the
Democrats in Congress is that they haven't learned to `just say
no.'''
   ``They rush to enact every soft-hearted idea that crosses their
desks, eyes closed to the social and economic consequences,'' Bush
said.
   He praised the current economic recovery, which began in late
1982, as the longest peacetime expansion in history, and took a
swipe at economists for being pessimistic.
   ``Economists aren't any help,'' he said, noting that leading
economists have been projecting a recession since 1984 and two
years ago, 60 percent of the members of the National Association of
Business Economics predicted a downturn in 1988.
   ``Wrong, wrong, wrong,'' Bush said. ``No wonder it's called the
`dismal science.'''
   ``I'm feeling like Harry Truman,'' Bush added. ``Forty years
ago, he was fighting against the odds and when he went out to
speak, the crowds would yell, `give 'em hell.' And he'd shout back,
`I don't have to give 'em hell. I just tell the truth and they
think it's hell,''' Bush said.
   Bush also reiterated his call for tougher sentences for drug
abusers in a speech to the National Organization of Black Law
Enforcement officers.
   ``Only 14 percent of the drug felons convicted in New York City
last year were sentenced to as much as a year with no probation,''
he said in prepared remarks.
   He said that states should make more use of ``habitual
offender'' laws that make repeated conviction on felony charges a
separate crime _ and proposed providing ``federal jail space for
them when needed.''
   Bush was scheduled to leave Thursday night for his vacation
resort in Kennebunkport, Maine, where he will spend most of the
holiday weekend. On the Fourth of July, Bush planned to visit four
cities, including Detroit and St. Louis, to participate in
Independence Day events.
</TEXT>
