<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1933EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lefebvre-Issues     06-30 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lefebvre-Issues,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican II Reforms Are Major Issues of Contention</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lefebvre, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre has challenged
some of the most important reforms in the modern history of the
Roman Catholic church.
   The French prelate contests the reforms of the Second Vatican
Council of 1962-65, which he charges have led to ``neo-modernist
and neo-Protestant tendencies.''
   Major points of contention with the Vatican include:
   _ Vatican II documents on ``the church in the modern world'' and
on ``religious freedom,'' which Lefebvre refused to sign as a
council member.
   _ The 16th century Tridentine Mass. Lefebvre continues to
celebrate this Mass, which the council replaced with a simplified
and modernized liturgy to be said in the modern local language,
rather than in Latin. Lefebvre has described the modern Mass as
``bastard rites.'' A few years ago, the Vatican said the Tridentine
Mass could be celebrated with special permission.
   _ Ecumenism, or the opening to other churches and faiths. The
Second Vatican Council formally recognized that other faiths have
elements of truth and that their members stand in the love of God.
Lefebvre objects to the concept of religious freedom as a
``horrible apostasy'' because it put the church on equal footing
with all other, including non-Christian, churches. He condemned as
``appalling'' Pope John Paul II's meeting with leaders of other
religious faiths in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
