<DOCNO> AP880630-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1520EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Gorbachev 1stLd-Writethru a0693 06-30 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gorbachev, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,a0702,a0713,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Addresses Conference Again With Personal Plea</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: COMBINES urgent series. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev appealed to
delegates of the Communist Party conference on Thursday to adopt
his proposed overhaul of the Soviet system and said that socialism
will die if they don't.
   Taking the floor for the second time at the conference he called
to assess his 3-year-old reform program and set a course for the
future, Gorbachev recalled that previous attempts in the 1950s and
1960s to reform the Soviet economy all were ``swallowed up'' by the
system.
   In an impassioned 40-minute speech broadcast later on national
television, Gorbachev told the 5,000 delegates assembled in the
Kremlin he had decided to address them again because he felt there
was a ``certain lack of understanding'' of the proposals he made
Tuesday at the conference opening.
   Gorbachev, the general secretary of the party and the nation's
most powerful leader, proposed to redistribute political power,
investing authority in a president to be elected by a new
2,250-member Congress of Deputies. He has not indicated whether he
would seek the new presidency.
   He said executive power should be similarly transferred to local
and regional governing councils that would be headed by local
Communist Party chiefs.
   The new national congress would meet annually to set policy and
would elect a considerably smaller full-time legislature to conduct
government business.
   On Thursday, Gorbachev argued that the failure of earlier reform
efforts made clear that this time there must be change in the
political system itself.
   ``Socialism, Lenin, that is the creative activity of the
masses,'' Gorbachev said in an emotional speech punctuated by
frequent sweeping gestures with his hands and only occasional
glances at his notes. ``But that activity will die unless we reform
the political system.''
   He noted that some of the 40 or so delegates who have spoken at
the conference so far had complained there were no real results yet
from the three years of reform since he became party leader in
March 1985.
   Getting overnight results would be ``the simplest, shortest but
most mistaken way'' to pretend successful reform had already taken
place, Gorbachev said.
   Without naming names, the Soviet leader noted some party members
want to fix percentages of representation or administer the economy
by directives from the seat of power.
   ``No, comrades,'' he said. ``We have to give a general
direction. We have to work out a political line.''
   The nation, he said, is faced with critical problems in ethnic
relations and youth affairs, and he noted that all were agreed that
something should be done about them.
   ``These are all questions of the fate of the country,'' he said,
``and that's why it is necessary to free the party of other
functions.''
   Very few of the speakers in the closed-door debate so far have
specifically addressed Gorbachev's proposals for structural
overhaul.
   Excerpts shown on television or reported in the state-run media
have reflected lively discussion of concrete problems such as food
shortages, ecology or ethnic questions.
   Talking about his proposal to make Communist Party chiefs the
heads of their local governing councils, known as soviets,
Gorbachev stressed, ``we have to give full power to the soviets.''
   Gorbachev's intervention at the end of the morning session on
the third day of the conference had the tone of a personal appeal
to the delegates to understand what he wants from them.
   At least three times, Gorbachev noted the need to return to the
principles of Vladimir I. Lenin and make the Communist Party the
``political vanguard'' of Soviet life.
</TEXT>
