<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Fireworks-UPS     06-30 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fireworks-UPS,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Orders UPS To Resume Fireworks Deliveries _ After July 4th</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a masterpiece of timing, a government
agency this week told United Parcel Service it had to transport
shipments of fireworks, then said three days later the order won't
take effect until July 8.
   The Interstate Commerce Commission gave no reason for
effectively reversing itself except to say it was acting on a
petition by UPS. The package delivery service had wanted out of the
fireworks hauling business because of the difficulty of obeying all
the different local, state and federal laws.
   ``It was a great administrative burden,'' said Bob Kenney, a
spokesman for UPS in Greenwich, Conn. He said that while UPS had
been one of the leading shippers of fireworks _ which can't go
through the U.S. mail _ it was only a minor part of its business.
   Last year UPS asked the ICC to be let out of shipping fireworks
and the commission said OK. In March, four fireworks manufacturers
asked that the decision be reversed, and on Monday the ICC did.
   The commission ruled that the UPS action ``is unreasonable
discrimination and therefore unlawful.'' It gave the parcel
delivery service two days to reinstate the service it had stopped
on Jan. 8.
   The commission's action was not unanimous. Chairman Heather J.
Gradison dissented, saying it was ironic that in ``its overweening
zeal to use regulatory intervention to keep the `bang' in the
Fourth of July'' the commission showed the fragility of the
liberties being celebrated.
   ``For business reasons ... UPS has made the deicsion that it no
longer wishes to invest its time, labor and capital carrying
fireworks,'' she wrote. ``The commission is in effect taking from
UPS its right to exercise its control over its property.''
   ICC Vice Chairman Frederick Andre also dissented:
   ``UPS is now being ordered to ... immediately transport
fireworks for the upcoming Fourth of July holiday,'' he wrote. ``In
return for such a radical readjustment, UPS is merely offered the
promise of an adequate explanation to be issued at a later date.''
   UPS filed its objection on Tuesday and the fireworks companies
objected to the objection.
   The last word was the commission's. ``Our prior decision is
stayed until July 8, 1988,'' said the order on Thursday.
</TEXT>
