<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp Bjt   06-30 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims Key Land Victories, Bombing Raids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its jets bombed an Iranian
natural gas plant and an offshore oil field Thursday during raids
in the Persian Gulf, and claimed its land forces drove Iranian
troops from key border regions.
   Baghdad Radio said Iraqi forces recaptured four border points
along Iraq's Shehabi ridge in the central sector of the 733-mile
war front.
   It said troops also recaptured Iraq's Mawat basin region in the
northern Kurdistan mountains after an offensive launched late
Wednesday. It said the Iraqi flag was raised on 24 strategic
positions in the region.
   It also said two other border outposts were recaptured from the
Iranians.
   ``The enemy is collapsing,'' Baghdad Radio declared.
   It said the offensive in the central sector lasted more than 12
hours and ended when the Iranians retreated to the pre-war border,
``leaving their dead littering the battlefield.''
   Tehran had no immediate comment on the reports.
   But Tehran radio said Iranian warplanes strafed troop positions
in Iraq's northern Sulaimaniyeh province Wednesday night and
inflicted ``heavy losses on the enemy.''
   Iraq had claimed its forces retook Mawat two weeks ago.
Thursday's communique claimed the entire Mawat basin, two miles
west of the border, has been recaptured.
   The official Iraqi News Agency also said its aircraft bombed a
natural gas plant on the Iranian mainland in the southern gulf and
the Cyrus oil field in the northern gulf. It said all the planes
returned safely to their bases.
   Tehran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored
in Nicosia, said Iraqi jets bombed ``an industrial-labor complex''
on its southern gulf coast, killing or wounding an unspecified
number of workers and causing some damage.
   It said Iran's air force fighters shot down an Iraqi warplane
over the gulf at about the same time Iran reportedly raided the gas
plant.
   Iraq said the gas plant, which it called Iran's biggest, was on
the mainland across from the island of Lavan, also known as Sheik
Sho'yeb.
   The Iranian News Agency said a second Iraqi jet was shot down
over western Iran.
   Baghdad's official Iraqi News Agency denied any plane was downed
during the two gulf raids. The agency quoted an unnamed spokesman
as saying ``large numbers'' of warplanes were involved in the two
raids and left their targets ``engulfed with fire and smoke.
   ``The Iranian regime today received a strong blow which will
have an extreme effect on its economy and oil resources,'' he said.
   The Iraqi air force's last major raids were June 23, when 10
targets in the southwestern Ahwaz, Bibi Hakimah and Sarran oil
fields were bombed.
   The Iraqi spokesman declared: ``The Iranian regime must realize
that after the successive victories of the Iraqi army and air force
that it has to accept peace and nothing but peace.''
   Last week, Iraqi forces drove the Iranians out of their last
major bridgehead in southern Iraq, the Majnoon islands in the
oil-rich Howeizah marshes.
   They also recaptured the southern Faw Peninsula April 18, two
years after the Iranians had seized it.
   The battlefield defeats dramatically swung the military balance
in the nearly 8-year-old war in Iraq's favor after years of being
on the defensive.
   An authoritative oil source said the apparent target of one of
the Iraqi raids was the Kangan natural gas plant.
   Meanwhile, Iran's parliament re-elected Prime Minister Hussein
Musavi on Thursday, Iran's official news agency reported.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said 204 of the 217 deputies
present in the Majlis, or parliament, voted for Musavi. Eight voted
against him, five abstained and the remainder did not attend.
   In a speech before today's vote, Musavi declared that a
``massive mobilization by Iran's enemies is a warning that we must
prepare for an ... all-out struggle against them.''
   He stressed: ``We are faced with an historic confrontation, the
most important manifestation of which has emerged in the
warfronts'' with Iraq.
   He did not elaborate, but he was clearly referring to a string
of Iraqi victories since mid-April.
</TEXT>
