<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NEA-Dukakis     06-30 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NEA-Dukakis,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Arm of Nation's Largest Teacher Union Backs Dukakis
^With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential hopeful Michael Dukakis
won the backing Thursday of the political arm of the National
Education Association, the nation's largest teacher union.
   The decision came during a closed-door meeting of NEA's
political action committee in New Orleans where the teacher group
will hold its annual convention next week. The union's endorsement
won't be official until Friday, when the NEA board of directors is
scheduled to meet and almost certainly concur with NEA-PAC's choice.
   NEA officials said the endorsement applies only to the
Democratic nomination. The 1.9 million-member union won't make a
final presidential endorsement until Sept. 8, after both parties
have held their conventions.
   Dukakis ``believes in and supports a view and a vision of
education policy consistent with our efforts to assure every child
a quality education,'' said NEA president Mary Hatwood Futrell.
   On Wednesday, Dukakis picked up his first formal labor
endorsement from the 59,000-member National Treasury Employees
Union, a group that represents mostly federal Internal Revenue
Service and Customs Service workers.
   The labor movement, stung by charges that it contributed to the
landslide defeat of Walter Mondale in the 1984 presidential
campaign with its strategy of early endorsements, has mostly held
off endorsements so far in 1988.
   It is unlikely that George Bush, who has clinched the Republican
nomination, will gain the teachers' blessing because he has refused
to respond to the union's questionnaires on education issues or to
meet with union officials, said Futrell in a recent interview.
   The NEA has frequently locked horns with the Reagan
administration on a variety of subjects, especially federal aid to
school programs.
   The American Federation of Teachers, the rival teacher union
with 680,000 members, won't endorse a candidate until after the
political conventions. But the AFT's president, Albert Shanker, and
political director, Rachelle Horowitz, will both be Dukakis
delegates in Atlanta.
   Futrell said she had met with Democratic candidates Jesse
Jackson and Dukakis. But she said she was rebuffed by the Bush camp.
   ``My indication is that they think it wouldn't be desirable. He
has eliminated himself from the process,'' she said.
   In her discussion with Jackson, she said she ``indicated our
concern that we should come out of the convention united. We
stressed the unity issue.''
   Futrell, a Mondale delegate in 1984 and a political activist in
her home state of Virginia, will not be a delegate this year. But
Kenneth Melley, the NEA's director of government relations, said
the union will have 280 delegates and 77 alternates in Atlanta,
with a large majority for Dukakis. The NEA will send 28 members as
delegates to the Republican National Convention.
   The NEA fielded 279 delegates and 84 alternates in 1984 at the
Democratic Convention.
   In NEA questionnaires submitted to presidential hopefuls of both
parties last year, Dukakis backed nearly every item on the union's
legislative agenda including opposition to any English-only
constitutional amendments or public funding of private schools
through vouchers.
   But he parted company with the union with his opposition to
federal tax deductions for union dues.
</TEXT>
