<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-30 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stuck on the bottom of the world since August,
Debbie Enzenbacher had a craving for candy.
   There's no grocery store at the corner glacier, of course, so a
Chicago company made an air drop of sweet stuff over the South Pole
to boost the spirits of researchers who lack the comforts of home.
   ``When they told us it was a plea from the South Pole for a
supply of Tootsie Pops, we didn't know if it was a joke or a
serious request,'' said Ellen Gordon, president of Tootsie Roll
Industries Inc.
   It was no joke.
   Mrs. Gordon said she received a letter from Miss Enzenbacher
last December. The first drop was made in February and another drop
was scheduled this week.
   Miss Enzenbacher, 28, of Calumet Park, employed by Antarctic
Services Inc. of Paramus, N.J., is in charge of materials for a
19-member team doing research, according to her mother, Jean
Enzenbacher.
   ``I find that one of the things I truly miss here that is not
available on the continent, since there are no stores, is your
Tootsie Roll Pops,'' Miss Enzenbacher said in her letter.
   ``Is there any way you could possibly send us some?'' she asked.
``It would make the long six months' winter night ... that much
more bearable.''
   Mrs. Gordon said the company reponded in February by
air-dropping 1,280 Tootsie Rolls, the chewy chocolate candies, and
400 Tootsie Roll Pops.
   In a thank-you letter to the company in March, Miss Enzenbacher
said it had been ``consistently colder than minus 100 degrees since
February, what with the wind chill here and all. But still, it is
starkly beautiful.''
   Mrs. Enzenbacher said her daughter studied anthropology in
college and did a thesis on Antarctica while getting a master's
degree in international relations.
   ``She has a love of this strange climate,'' her mother said.
   Besides her affection for science, ``She has a sweet tooth,''
Mrs. Enzenbacher confided.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outer clothing isn't the only thing people tend
to shed at the beach. Try rings, rare coins and pocket knives.
   The Midwest Historical Research Society has nearly 120 members,
all carrying metal detectors in search of treasure.
   ``Wedding rings seem to predominate in the jewelry we find,''
said Sara Seibs, a Chicago realtor who plies the beaches, parks and
forest preserves with her metal detector in her spare time.
   ``At the beaches we tend to find many more men's wedding rings
than women's, although I'm not quite sure why,'' Ms. Seibs said in
a recent interview. ``Maybe men wear looser rings and their fingers
shrink in the cold water.''
   Ms. Seibs, president of the group of metal detector hobbyists,
says rings of all sorts turn up.
   ``Aluminum pull tabs from beer cans drive everybody crazy,'' Ms.
Seibs said. ``You find about 100 of them for every coin or useful
item you detect _ especially on beaches.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Also moving on some sports circuits</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Sophie Masloff called New York Mayor Ed
Koch ``the big apple sauce'' after he pretended he didn't know
where Pittsburgh was during an exchange spurred by ads run before a
Pirates-Mets three-game series.
   The Pirates, in second place behind the Mets in the National
League East, referred in radio ads to the Mets as ``just one more
thing to hate about New York.''
   In an interview Wednesday with WWOR-TV of Secaucus, N.J., Koch
was asked what he would say to the mayor of Pittsburgh or its
residents about the ads. ``Grow up,'' he responded.
   When asked what he thought of Pittsburgh and whether he has ever
been there, Koch said with a straight face, ``Where is it?'' and
``What country?''
   Masloff responded on KDKA-TV later in the day.
   ``The nerve of him,'' she said. ``He's not the big apple. He's
the big apple sauce.''
   New York won two of the three games.
