<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-AirCrashes     06-30 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Air Crashes,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>F-16 Crashes Rekindle Controversy Over Military Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
coalition government on Thursday called for the immediate grounding
of F-16 fighter jets stationed in West Germany.
   Three U.S. Air Force F-16s crashed Wednesday in two incidents in
West Germany. The crashes, which occurred 90 miles apart, rekindled
controversy over low-level military training flights.
   ``If the F-16, which has recently piled up a number of crashes,
has a technical fault, it must be temporarily grounded,'' said
Werner Hoyer, a military expert and member of the Free Democratic
Party.
   The party is the junior partner in Kohl's coaliton goverment.
   Five F-16 fighter jets have crashed in West Germany in the last
three months.
   U.S. Air Force officials declined comment on the possible
grounding of the F-16s or on a published report that said cracked
blades might have caused one of the accidents.
   A U.S. Air Force pilot was killed Wednesday when his plane
collided with another F-16 on a training flight near Bodenheim,
about 35 miles west of Frankfurt. The other pilot ejected safely.
   Later Wednesday, another U.S. Air Force pilot ejected to safety
when his F-16 crashed in the Black Forest.
   Military air crashes in March and April triggered a storm of
public controversy after fighter jets went down near a nuclear
power plant and an ammunition dump. An F-16 also crashed into a
small village, killing the pilot and a resident on the ground.
   West German Defense Minister Rupert Scholz, in an interview with
Suedwestfunk radio, said Thursday that he had asked U.S. officials
to work with the West Germans ``to do an exact analysis of a number
of potential causes,'' of the crashes and ``to do all possible to
prevent such accidents from being repeated.''
   But Scholz added that it was premature to ground the aircraft.
The U.S. Air Force European commander, Gen. William L. Kirk, also
has said the cause of the crashes must first be determined before
making any move.
   Florian Gerster, a member of the main opposition Social
Democratic Party, told reporters in Bonn that military flights over
densely populated West Germany had reached the stage ``where it is
as if we must protect ourselves against attacks from our own air
defenses.''
   Gerster charged that West German and U.S. air forces try to
outdo each other in practicing low-level and other flight training
exercises.
   The military's unofficial Stars and Stripes newspaper said
Thursday that the U.S. Air Force recently has replaced the engines
of 31 F-16 jets ``because of potential cracks in high-speed engine
blades.''
   It said blade cracks found in some General Electric F110 engines
that are used in some F-16s were ``the likely cause'' of an April
18 crash near Erzberg, West Germany.
   Most F-16s are powered by a Pratt-Whitney engine, but the Air
Force ordered the GE F110 engines in 1984 as part of an effort to
increase competition among engine manufacturers, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
