<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0695 06-30 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0695,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Forget Polls, Expect Close Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Jackson meeting scheduled, inserting new grafs
3-4</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis dismissed as meaningless Thursday
new polls showing his lead over George Bush had shrunk dramatically
and said he always had anticipated ``a very tough and very
competitive race'' for the presidency.
   He refused to speculate publicly about his next big campaign
decision, the choice of a Democratic running mate. ``I'll make a
decision when I'm ready to make a decision,'' he told reporters.
   Jesse Jackson, who has pressed for an offer of the No. 2
position, will meet Monday night with Dukakis, said Dayton Duncan,
Dukakis' campaign press secretary. Duncan said Jackson and his wife
would have dinner with Dukakis and his wife at the Massachusetts
governor's Brookline home and then accompany them to the July
Fourth fireworks and Boston Pops concert alongside Boston's Charles
River.
   The aide gave no indication what Dukakis and Jackson might
discuss.
   Dukakis, in Illinois on the second day of a campaign swing
through the Midwest, told workers at a Reynolds Aluminum Co. plant
that Reagan administration talk of economic prosperity is
misleading.
   ``Too many of our families are struggling to hold on,'' he said.
   The Massachusetts governor spent most of Wednesday in Washington
talking to members of Congress including four senators often
mentioned as potential running mates.
   He planned a return trip to the Capitol on July 13, less than a
week before the Democratic National Convention.
   Aides have speculated that he might not wait until the
convention to announce his choice. But he responded that ``I
haven't made any judgment about timing'' when asked if the July 13
trip could be taken as assurance that no decision would be
announced before that date.
   ``I have the luxury of having the time and of being able to do
this thoughtfully and deliberately,'' he said. ``I'd rather spend
more time than less and make the right decision. I'm not going to
hurry it.''
   One of the senators Dukakis met with on Wednesday _ Sam Nunn of
Georgia _ took himself out of the running for a spot on the
Democratic ticket. Others with whom Dukakis met individually were
Sens. John Glenn of Ohio, Bob Graham of Florida and Lloyd Bentsen
of Texas _ all from states considered critical to a Democratic
victory in the presidential election.
   During the past two months, national polls have said Dukakis
holds leads of from seven to 17 points over the Republican vice
president, but two surveys made public this week showed a much
smaller margin.
   One, by the Gallup Organization, said voters favored Dukakis
over Bush by a margin of 46 percent to 41 percent, slightly more
than the three-point margin of potential sampling error. The other,
by ABC News and Money Magazine, had 45 percent for Dukakis to 42
percent for Bush, less than the four-point margin of error.
   Asked about the new surveys, Dukakis replied, ``I can only say
what I've been saying for 16 months: Early polls are meaningless.''
   He added, ``This is a wide open race; it always has been and
this is going to be a very tough and very competitive race just as
the primary was.''
   In the past week, Dukakis has approved a new cigarette tax to
help balance his state budget and also has had questions raised
about a possible scandal involving acquisition of land for a new
state prison.
   In addition, both Bush and President Reagan have hit hard at the
Massachusetts governor, particularly on the tax issue.
   In his speech to workers at the aluminum plant, Dukakis
questioned the the Republican administration's claim to have
created millions of new jobs.
   ``Today there are more Americans working than at any time in our
history,'' he said. ``But average family income in America is right
where it was 20 years ago.'' He said new jobs opening up between
1979 and 1985 paid far less than jobs lost during that period.
</TEXT>
