<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Politics     06-30 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Politics,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yakovlev Head of Ideology, Party Man Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politburo member Alexander N. Yakovlev, a close
adviser to Mikhail S. Gorbachev, is now the overseer of ideology in
the Communist Party, a senior party official said Thursday.
   Byelorussian party head Yefrem Sokolov was asked at a news
conference to outline the individual responsibilities of the 13
members of the ruling Politburo following a complaint by a delegate
to the Communist Party's national conference that he did not know
which leader does what.
   ``I may make some mistakes,'' Sokolov said. ``You know very well
that Yakovlev is responsible for ideology.''
   He said Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev, who was once thought
to have the key task of overseeing ideology, ``is responsible for
organizational work in the Politburo.''
   Central Committee official Georgy Kryuchkov said Ligachev chairs
the sessions of the policy-making body's secretariat, which is
responsible for day-to-day handling of party affairs. That is a job
that customarily falls to the No. 2 member of the ruling Politburo.
   There were unconfirmed reports last spring that Ligachev had
lost the ideology portfolio after engineering a public attack on
Gorbachev's harsh criticism of the nation's Stalinist past.
   Neither Sokolov nor Kryuchkov would confirm or deny when pressed
by reporters that Ligachev has specifically lost the ideology
portfolio.
   ``He was dealing with, and is dealing with, these questions,''
said Kryuchkov. ``He has never relinquished these duties.''
   Sokolov made it clear, however, that he considered that all
Politburo members deal with ideology, leaving unclear whether
Ligachev has any special responsiblities in that field.
   Rumors that Ligachev had lost the key ideology portfolio
surfaced after the publication of a letter March 13 from Leningrad
teacher Nina Andreyeva.
   Mrs. Andreyeva attacked the reforms and the criticism of Josef
Stalin that has grown in the Soviet media. The publication of her
letter in the daily Sovietskaya Rossiya triggered protest from
intellectuals and led to a public outcry and rebuke from the party
newspaper Pravda in April.
   Pravda editor Viktor G. Afanasyev confirmed Monday Mrs.
Andreyeva had written a reply to that article, but he declined to
give details.
   Kryuchkov said Thursday Mrs. Andreyeva had written a letter to
the conference presidium. He said it was similar to her other
letter but declined to elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
