<DOCNO> AP880630-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance 2ndLd-Writethru a0731 06-30 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0731,570</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to correct day to Thursday, sted Wednesday</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
announced Thursday by the Supreme Court.
   
   YOUNG KILLERS
   
   The court agreed to consider banning the death penalty for all
juvenile murderers, a day after issuing a decision that could end
capital punishment for killers not yet 16 when they committed their
crimes.
   The justices said they will decide sometime next year whether
use of the death penalty for anyone under 18 when the crime was
committed violates the Constitution's ban on ``cruel and unusual
punishment.''
   The cases are High vs. Zant, 87-5666, and Wilkins vs. Missouri,
87-6026.
   
   AGENT ORANGE
   
   The court apparently removed the last legal obstacle to a $180
million settlement between Vietnam veterans and manufacturers of
the herbicide Agent Orange.
   The justices, without comment, let stand rulings that dismissed
lawsuits by about 300 veterans who challenged the settlement, in
which some 120,000 others are expected to participate.
   The cases are Lombardi vs. Dow Chemical, 87-436, and Krupkin vs.
Dow Chemical, 87-620.
   
   BIAS
   
   The court agreed to study alleged race discrimination in Alaskan
salmon canneries, setting the stage for an important sequel to a
one-day-old ruling that makes it easier for workers to prove their
bosses are guilty of illegal bias.
   The justices said they will hear an appeal by two companies
based in Washington state and Oregon that operate canneries in
Alaska.
   The case is Wards Cove vs. Antonio, 87-1387.
   
   DEATH PENALTY
   
   The court agreed to hear the appeal of a Texas man sentenced to
death who, the justices were told, has the reasoning capacity of a
7-year-old.
   The justices said they will study arguments that executing
Johnny Paul Penry for the Oct. 25, 1979, killing of Pamela
Carpenter would be ``cruel and unusual punishment'' banned by the
Constitution's Eighth Amendment.
   The case is Penry vs. McCotter, 87-6177.
   
   DEFENSE CONTRACTOR
   
   The court let stand a ruling that forced a defense contractor to
pay damages for an on-duty accident involving a Navy pilot.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Grumman
Aerospace Corp., ordered to pay $840,556 to the family of the pilot
who died when his plane crashed off the California coast in 1979.
   The case is Grumman vs. Shaw, 85-1529.
   
   LAWYERS ADS
   
   The court agreed to decide whether states may ban virtually all
lawyer advertisements featuring testimonials or client endorsements.
   The justices said they will review a California rule that
presumes such ads are false or misleading.
   The case is Oring vs. California, 87-1224.
   
   AIRBAGS
   
   The court rejected the appeal of a Minnesota woman severely
injured in a 1983 car crash, turning away arguments that her car's
manufacturer negligently failed to install airbags.
   The justices, without comment, let stand rulings dismissing that
portion of Jan Marie Wickstrom's product-liability lawsuit against
Toyota Motor Corp. and its U.S. subsidiaries.
   The case is Wickstrom vs. Maplewood Toyota, 87-1881.
   
   CONGRESSMAN
   
   The court refused to kill a libel lawsuit against a Tennessee
congressman who criticized a legal services lawyer.
   The court, by a 6-3 vote, let stand a ruling that Rep. Don
Sundquist, R-Tenn., may be sued for statements he made in a letter
to the U.S. attorney general. The lawsuit also alleges he repeated
the libelous statements in a news release.
   The case is Sundquist vs. Chastain, 87-1756.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
