<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GayMass Bjt   06-30 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Mass, Bjt,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seattle Archdiocese Creates Ministry To Homosexuals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seattle Archdiocese will assume sponsorship
of Mass for homosexuals, the archbishop announced Thursday, but the
group that had run the ministry is divided over whether to accept
the change or move elsewhere.
   While accepting homosexuals within the church, Archbishop
Raymond G. Hunthausen made clear that ``church teaching rejects
homosexual acts.''
   The Seattle chapter of Dignity, a group for homosexual
Catholics, was evenly split Sunday in a vote on whether to endorse
Hunthausen's decision or to move the Mass elsewhere. Calls to the
organization's office Thursday were answered by a recording.
   ``Hunthausen is the best bishop we have in the country,'' an
unidentified Dignity spokesman told The Seattle Times after
Sunday's vote.
   The spokesman said the group was convinced Dignity would never
have been pushed out except for Vatican pressure on Hunthausen, who
was relieved of some duties in 1986 because of his tolerance of the
group.
   Hunthausen said the decision was ``in response to the challenge
offered'' in a Sept. 30, 1985, letter from Rome in which he was
strongly criticized for allowing Dignity to celebrate weekly Mass
in St. Joseph's Church in Seattle.
   ``For 16 years, Dignity has assumed a ministry to Catholic gay
and lesbian persons which has included a celebration of weekly
liturgy,'' Hunthausen said. ``However, because Dignity has taken
public positions that are contrary to the teaching of the church,
Dignity will no longer retain the sponsorship of the celebration of
the Eucharist that has taken place at St. Joseph's Church.''
   Hunthausen said he was appointing the Rev. Gerald Stanley,
pastor of St. Edward's Church here, to coordinate the ministry
along with other priests.
   The ministry ``must be based on Catholic moral teaching,''
Hunthausen said. ``Such teaching must ensure that the church's
position on human sexuality is presented clearly and without
ambiguity.
   ``Church teaching rejects homosexual acts, but not homosexual
people.''
   The 1985 letter critical of Hunthausen followed a 1983
``apostolic visitation'' in which a delegation examined whether the
bishop was lax in certain areas of his ministry.
   In September 1986, the Vatican appointed an auxiliary bishop to
relieve Hunthausen of certain duties, including authority over
ministering to homosexuals.
   That unprecedented move upset many U.S. bishops, and the Vatican
last year restored Hunthausen's powers, appointed Coadjutor
Archbishop Thomas J. Murphy to assist him and named a three-bishop
commission to review Hunthausen's administration.
   In 1983, Hunthausen delivered, on videotape, the welcoming
address at Dignity's national convention in Seattle and permitted
the group to celebrate Mass at St. James Cathedral. He was
upbraided for that in the 1985 letter by Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger,
prefect for the Congregation of the Doctrine of the Faith, who
wrote that the archdiocese should not support a group that doesn't
accept church teaching ``concerning the intrinsic evil of
homosexual activity.''
   Dignity, with more than 100 chapters, has sponsored Mass,
sacraments, programs, and worked for homosexual Catholics for more
than 20 years. The organization maintains homosexuals can express
their sexuality in a morally responsible way.
   But the group has been forced out of churches in several cities,
including New York and San Diego, since a 1986 Vatican letter
labeled all homosexual activity a sin and said even a tendency
toward homosexuality is an ``objective disorder.''
   The directive warned bishops not to support any group that
condones homosexual activity.
   Hunthausen's decision follows the lead of Cardinal Joseph
Bernardin, a member of the commission overseeing Hunthausen. In
May, Bernardin said his Chicago Archdiocese would take over the
Mass and ministry to Catholic homosexuals.
   Bernardin's decision was initially hailed by gay activists as an
acceptable alternative to a ban of the group from church property,
but the issue has since split Chicago's homosexual Catholic
community.
   Dissidents have begun celebrating Mass in a Lutheran church in
defiance of Bernardin's decision.
   In San Francisco, Archbishop John Quinn, another commission
member, permits the Dignity chapter to meet in a Catholic church.
   ``The ground rules for this thing are that so long as they don't
take a public position in opposition to church teaching, they're as
welcome as anybody else,'' said archdiocesan spokesman Norman
Phillips.
</TEXT>
