<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Scotus-AgentOrange     06-30 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Agent Orange,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Clears Way for Agent Orange Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Thursday cleared away the
last legal obstacle to a multimillion-dollar settlement between
Vietnam veterans and manufacturers of the herbicide Agent Orange.
   The justices, without comment, let stand rulings that dismissed
lawsuits by about 300 veterans who had challenged the 1984
settlement.
   ``We've been waiting for four years for this appeals process to
end,'' said Frank McCarthy, president of the Vietnam Veterans Agent
Orange Victims Inc.
   ``The money will be put to good use _ most of all, a lot of
children who aren't getting help will begin to receive that help
now for their birth defects,'' McCarthy said.
   Agent Orange, which was sprayed over Southeast Asia during the
1960s by the U.S. military as a defoliant, contains highly toxic
dioxin. Veterans contend that exposure to it causes cancer and
other illnesses. They say Agent Orange exposure caused miscarriages
by wives of servicemen and birth defects in their children.
   The $180 million settlement has grown and, with interest, now
totals about $240 million.
   Estimates on how many people will receive some payment from the
settlement fund range as high as 250,000.
   The chemical companies sued over their making Agent Orange were
Monsanto, Dow, Uniroyal, Hercules, T.H. Agriculture and Nutrition,
Diamond Shamrock and Thompson.
   ``We are pleased,'' Dow spokeswoman Pat Brink said after the
high court's action Thursday. `What pleases us the most is that the
veterans will now get the money they've been waiting for.''
   She noted, however, that Dow has never conceded that Agent
Orange was responsible for any health problems.
   The lawsuit acted on Thursday was filed by veterans who opted
out of the huge class action lawsuit that ended in a settlement.
   The smaller suit was dismissed when a federal judge ruled that
the Agent Orange manufacturers were immune from being sued over the
alleged health effects of the herbicide.
   The ensuing appeals from that ruling had been pending before the
nation's highest court for months, held until a key decision about
government contractors' legal liability.
   Three days ago, the court ruled that government contractors
cannot be sued over government-approved design defects unless the
contractors failed to notify the government about hazards they knew
about.
   U.S. District Judge Jack Weinstein threw out the suits filed by
the 300 veterans, relying on three findings:
   _That no plaintiff could prove a particular illness was caused
by Agent Orange.
   _That no plaintiff could prove which defendant manufactured the
Agent Orange that allegedly caused his or her injury.
   _And that all the claims were barred by the military contractor
defense.
   His dismissal was upheld by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1706EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ContinentalPleas     06-30 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental Pleas,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Bank Officers Enter Guilty Pleas In Continental Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A longer version ran on financial wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Continental Illinois National Bank &
Trust Co. officer and an ex-banker from Oklahoma accused of
contributing to Continental's near collapse pleaded guilty Thursday
to criminal charges.
   John R. Lytle pleaded guilty to misapplication of bank funds and
William G. Patterson pleaded guilty to aiding and abetting Lytle
before U.S. District Judge Milton I. Shadur.
   Shadur had been scheduled to preside over a retrial of the men
on charges of wire fraud and misapplication of bank funds, after
the defendants' initial trial ended with a deadlocked jury two
months ago.
   Lytle, 53, a former Continental vice president, was accused of
taking on millions of dollars in risky loans from customers of Penn
Square Bank of Oklahoma City in return for alleged kickbacks.
   Patterson, 38, former head of energy lending at Penn Square, was
accused of arranging the kickbacks, in the form of $585,000 worth
of unsecured personal loans to Lytle between 1980 and 1982.
   Each man faces up to five years' imprisonment and a $5,000 fine,
said Shadur, who set sentencing for Aug. 30.
   The plea agreement reached by prosecutors and defense attorneys
will avert the need for another long trial like the 6{-week
proceeding that ended May 3 when a jury said it was deadlocked
after deliberating five days.
   The panel, however, cleared a third defendant, Oklahoma drilling
contractor Jere Sturgis, of wire fraud charges for allegedly
participating in a purported scheme to defraud Continental.
   ``As far as we're concerned, this is it. This puts to rest the
Continental Bank chapter, book, encyclopedia, whatever you want to
call it,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Joesph Duffy said after Shadur
accepted the plea agreement. ``The object was justice, and we think
there's justice in the guilty plea.''
   Shadur last month approved a retrial of Lytle and Patterson at
the request of prosecutors, who cited the fact that 11 jurors had
voted to convict the pair and one had held out for acquittal.
   Penn Square failed in 1982, and Continental came close to
collapse two years later after the largest run on deposits in
banking history. The government kept Continental's doors open with
a $4.5 billion bailout.
   Prosecutors charged that Patterson manipulated Lytle and Sturgis
in schemes to save his own failing bank.
   The government accused Lytle, caught in spiraling personal debt
to finance a luxurious lifestyle, of accepting kickbacks from
Patterson in exchange for buying risky energy loans from Penn
Square for Continental.
   Attorneys for Lytle and Patterson contended Continental was
saddled with the troublesome energy loans because of an aggressive
lending policy, not because of a fraud scheme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
