<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1941EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviet-Inspections     06-30 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet-Inspections,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Inspection Team Heads For Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. inspection team was headed to Moscow to
carry out the first ``baseline inspection'' under the treaty signed
last December to eliminate superpower medium-range nuclear
missiles, officials said Thursday.
   A Soviet team also was expected to announce a visit to the
United States starting on Friday, the beginning of a 60-day period
during which the two sides may inspect scores of sites associated
with the missiles to be eliminated.
   The ``baseline inspections'' are to verify the exact number of
missiles and related components to be destroyed under the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty signed at the Washington
summit last Dec. 9.
   At 12:30 EDT on Thursday, the United States notified the Soviet
Union through a new Risk Reduction Center located in the State
Department that a team headed by Brig. Gen. Roland Lajoie, chief of
the On-Site Inspection Agency, would arrive in Moscow at about 3:30
p.m. (Moscow time).
   ``They will travel to the Soviet Union on a U.S. Air Force C-141
from Rhein-Main Air Force Base'' near Frankfurt, West Germany, the
Pentagon said in a statement.
   Under the terms of the treaty, the two sides must give each
other 16 hours' notice of their intent to make an inspection. The
U.S. team had not given notice of the exact sites to be inspected,
preferring to wait as late as possible, said Kendell Pease, a
spokesman for the American agency.
   In addition to the short-notice spot inspections, the INF treaty
allows the Soviets to station up to 30 inspectors for the next 13
years in Magna, Utah, site of Hercules Plant No. 1, where
medium-range American missiles were produced.
   The U.S. government, in turn, has the right to station
inspectors near a Soviet missile-producing site, the Votkinsk
Machine Building Plant.
   The treaty, the first to allow such on-site inspection, is
viewed as a trial for the proposed Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty,
which would slash arsenals of long-range superpower nuclear weapons
by 30-50 percent, and involve much more complicated verification
procedures.
</TEXT>
