<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolRestructuring     06-30 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Restructuring,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AFT Prexy Says U.S. Needs Another Revolution _ In Public Schooling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Federation of Teachers
announced Thursday it is launching a program to reform the most
basic teaching methods in U.S. public schools.
   Albert Shanker, president of the AFT, made the announcement at a
news conference kicking off the convention for the 500,000-member
federation.
   He said the ``AFT Center for Restructuring'' could lead the way
in bringing about a revolution in teaching.
   ``The center will critically examine the assumptions on which
traditional schooling have been based,'' he said, with the center
in the AFT's Washington headquarters acting as a kind of clearing
house for innovative ideas passed up from the teachers ``working as
a team.''
   ``We think this is the first time in the history of the country
that there has been (an effort) sponsored by teachers, devoted to
the notion that the best kind of change comes through a process of
continuous experimentation,'' Shanker said.
   The biggest problem for 40 million students in American
elementary and secondary schools right now ``is that the schools
have been the same for the last 200 years,'' the union leader
declared.
   The center will supply general outlines and suggestions on
methods of interesting district boards and parents to try new ways
to teach, he said, adding that ``many of these things do not
involve additional money.''
   ``My guess is that if teachers and principals, at school level,
begin to do exciting things the public will later on say `you're
doing such terrific things that we are now more willing to invest
money.'''
   The center will encourage the formulation of ``new ways of
testing and assessing what students do, with the idea of drawing a
more accurate picture of students'' in given schools, he said.
   Shanker took aim at the basic granite of American public
education, starting with organizational and academic orders issued
from district boards and superintendents to the principals and
teachers.
   He spanked the school bell, class periods, daily teacher-changes
and, finally, multiple-choice tests, which sourly described as a
tool principals and superintendents hope will make them ``look
good.''
   Shanker said the AFT does not have all the answers, but added,
``If we keep doing the same things (as in the past), we are going
to have the same results ... we don't like the results.''
   Shanker criticized education reform efforts over the past few
years which are aimed at tightening teaching standards and moving
back to a classic curriculum.
   ``We welcome these moves,'' he said. ``However, we do not
believe the implementation of these forms will bring about
substantial improvement in student achievement in most areas.''
</TEXT>
