<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Angola     06-30 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Angola,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Proposes Southern Africa Peace Plan to Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi on Thursday
presented President Reagan with a plan calling on the United States
to sponsor a peace settlement for southern Africa.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said that ``generally
speaking'' Reagan supports the plan, which calls on the United
States to continue providing arms to Savimbi's UNITA forces as long
as the Soviet Union and Cuba back the Angolan government.
   In a speech to the National Press Club, Savimbi said the plan
urges the United States to pursue negotiations with Cuba, the
Soviet Union and South Africa for the withdrawal of all foreign
troops from Angola as soon as possible.
   It also calls on the United States and ``key African states'' to
promote a dialogue between UNITA and the Angolan government that
would lead to an interim government and free elections.
   The U.S. government is sponsoring talks among South Africa,
Angola and Cuba to seek the withdrawal of South African and Cuban
troops from Angola and independence for neighboring South-West
Africa, or Namibia, which is controlled by South Africa.
   According to U.S. officials, Cuba has about 45,000 Cuban troops
in Angola doing much of the fighting with UNITA. Savimbi said Cuba
sent in an additional 12,000 troops in March and April and now has
57,000 troops there. In addition, he said, there are 2,500 Soviets,
3,000 North Koreans and 600 East Germans.
   The Soviets have helped the Angolan forces with military
planning and provided them with MiG-23 jet fighters, helicopter
gunships, missiles and radar sights, he said.
   Savimbi declined to say how much aid he received from the United
States and South Africa, but it is estimated he gets about $16
million a year in U.S. aid, including shoulder-fired Stinger
anti-aircraft missiles.
   He credited the missiles, which he declined to name since the
United States doesn't officially acknowledged that it is providing
them, with stopping air strikes against his forces enough so UNITAs
hospitals, schools and factories can operate.
   He claims to control one-third to one-half the territory of
Angola, a country nearly twice the size of Texas.
   Vice President George Bush, who also met with Savimbi, issued a
statement calling the guerrilla leader ``a true patriot.'' Bush
said he used the meeting to ``reaffirm my strong support for his
struggle and the struggle of UNITA to rid Angola of communism.''
   Bush, the Republican presidential nominee-to-be, added that ``a
cut-off of support of Dr. Savimbi, as suggested by the Democrats,
would be an immoral sell-out of a loyal friend and a foreign policy
disaster.''
   Democratic presidential candidates Michael Dukakis and Jesse
Jackson have called for an end to aid for UNITA. Savimbi said he
had sent letters to the two candidates seeking to explain his
position and had met with aides to Jackson.
   ``We think something will come out,'' he said.
   ``Governor Dukakis did not get yet the correct information about
what we are doing,'' said Savimbi. ``We believe that he is a very
good American. The day he knows we are working for peace and
democracy and stability in the whole of southern Africa I think he
will have a different approach.''
   Savimbi noted that the Angolan government had sent a rival
delegation to Washington to lobby against him during his visit and
said he had tried to meet with the officials, but they had not
responded to his request.
   About 25 protesters chanting anti-Savimbi slogans demonstrated
outside the National Press Building during his luncheon speech, and
a man interrupted his speech from the open door of the dining room
to shout three times, ``Savimbi is a murderer.''
   ``I think that's democracy,'' said Savimbi. ``It's good.''
</TEXT>
