<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1735EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseProbe-Overhaul     06-30 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Overhaul,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Sparks First Overhaul Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon's complicated purchasing system
would be overhauled and centralized under a bill introduced
Thursday as one of the first pieces of legislation resulting from
the Pentagon bribery and fraud investigation.
   ``The current bribery probe at the Pentagon is not surprising,''
said Rep. Tom Ridge, R-Pa., one of the 55 House co-sponsors and
also a co-chairman of the congressional Military Reform Caucus.
   ``It has happened before and it will happen again unless we
change the fundamental way we do business,'' said Ridge.
   The bill would create a single buying office, known as the
Defense Acquisition Agency, to replace the current mix of
purchasing agencies scattered throughout the Defense Department.
   For example, each of the four services buys weapons separately
for the nation's 2.1 million uniformed personnel. In addition,
there are separate purchasing agencies for the 1 million Defense
Department civilians.
   The current investigation focuses on allegations that defense
contractors and consultants, many of whom are former military men,
bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details that could be
vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars.
   The bill is the first piece of legislation resulting from the
2-year-old probe, which became public only two weeks ago. More
legislation is expected later, according to Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis.,
chairman of the House Armed Services Committee.
   The bill provides that the Defense Acquisition Agency would only
have civilian employees. They would be trained at a Defense
Acquisition University that would also be created by the
legislation.
   Rep. Dennis Hertel, D-Mich., another co-sponsor, said, ``The
Pentagon needs a change in its mindset. The American people will
not tolerate these annual procurement scandals while nothing
fundamentally changes at the Department of Defense.''
   Hours later, Rep. Charles Bennett, D-Fla., introduced a bill he
said would close the ``revolving door'' between defense contractors
and the Pentagon. It would require Pentagon officials to wait two
years after they quit before working for a defense contractor.
   ``Our whole procurement system will continue to be suspect if,
on a Friday, someone can sit on the government side of the table
with responsibility for millions of taxpayer dollars and then on
Monday be sitting on the contractor's side of the table,'' Bennett
said.
</TEXT>
