<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 2039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmersHome     06-30 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers Home,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rep. English Assails FmHA Management</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political appointees may be attempting to
sabotage the Farmers Home Administration, the lender of last resort
to the nation's farmers, Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., charged
Thursday.
   A House committee report last week declared management of the
agency inadequate and unable to properly oversee the operations of
1,900 county offices. English said may be a sign political
appointees ``don't like the program and they don't think the
government should have this program.''
   ``If you look at it in a sinister way, you could draw the
conclusion that they're doing their best to make sure the program
does not work _ you could say they were sabotaging the program,''
said English.
   FmHA Administrator Vance Clark, appointed by President Reagan in
March 1986, said he did not know what English meant when he
referred to sabotage.
   ``It's a nice rhetorical flourish which is consistent with the
intemperate tone of the report as well as the season of the year,''
Clark said. ``But this level of discourse lends little in the way
of credit or credibility to the report or its chief author.''
   English, chairman of the Government Information, Justice and
Agriculture subcommittee, said the FmHA's ``inability to supervise
its own affairs has meant that farmers have not had access to
valuable programs the law intended for them.''
   English based his findings on a hearing he conducted last
November to determine the FmHA's effectiveness in administering
farm programs in its jurisdition. The House Government Operations
Committee, chaired by Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, released a report
on that hearing last week.
   In summary, the report found that ``in many instances, the
national office does not know what is going on in the county
offices and does not have any way of finding out.
   ``All of the problems at FmHA identified by the committee could
have been alleviated or avoided altogether by competent,
professional, effective management,'' the report said.
   The committee in its report recommended that the secretary of
agriculture ``require FmHA to institute effective management
procedures so that the department, the Congress and the public may
be assured that the agency is meeting its mission.''
   Witnesses complained of racial discrimination, farmer
intimidation by FmHA county supervisors, disregard of regulations
by local FmHA workers, and loans that sometimes were made too late
for farmers to produce their crops.
   The report said that despite strict prohibitions against selling
farmland from inventory if it would depress price levels, 14 FmHA
state directors sold land without conducting the analysis required
by the national office.
</TEXT>
