<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FERCNomination     06-30 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FERC Nomination,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Staffer To Be Nominated To FERC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan intends to nominate Elizabeth
Moler, a member of the staff of the Senate Energy and Natural
Resources Committee, to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission,
the White House announced Thursday.
   Ms. Moler, 39, would succeed Charles Stalon in one of the two
Democratic seats on the five-member commission if her nomination is
confirmed by the Senate. Stalon's appointment expired last Oct. 20,
but commissioners may remain in office for a year if no successor
has been sworn in.
   Her term would expire Oct. 20, 1991.
   Ms. Moler, a 1970 graduate of American University in Washington
and the George Washington University Law School, has been on the
committee staff since 1976 and also has worked on House staffs.
   Martha Hesse, commission chairman, said in a statement of
welcome that Ms. Moler was respected ``for her professional
non-partisan approach'' to the issues the commission deals with _
regulation of natural gas production and pipeline transportation,
wholesale electricity sales, hydroelectric dams and oil pipelines.
   The nomination still would leave the commission's membership
unsettled. The panel has one vacancy created by the resignation of
Michael Naeve in March and will have another next month with the
departure by resignation of Anthony Sousa. Ms. Hesse has not been
confirmed as chairman and the term of the fifth member, Charles
Trabandt, expires in October.
