<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1943EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PriorCensorship     06-30 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prior Censorship,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voice of America Writer Sues To Publish Article Without Agency
Review</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Voice of America writer filed suit Thursday
challenging a requirement that she obtain government permission to
publish an article accusing the Reagan administration of
politicizing agency broadcasts.
   The suit by Carolyn Weaver is the first court challenge to
regulations that require Voice of America employees to obtain prior
approval before publishing articles or making speeches about U.S.
foreign policy or the operation of the agency, according to her
attorney, Stephen M. Kohn.
   All books or manuscripts ``of official concern'' must be
submitted for clearance by the U.S. Information Agency, which
operates the Voice of America. The regulation also covers employees
of the State Department and the Agency for International
Development.
   The government has the right to delete passages or stop
publication of publication of material it considers ``inaccurate,
inconsistent with current foreign policy, or can reasonably be
expected to affect adversely U.S. foreign relations,'' according to
the regulations.
   Weaver, a part-time writer and editor, is preparing an article
that accuses the VOA of failing to observe requirements of its
charter that it be an ``accurate, objective and comprehensive''
source of news for foreign listeners.
   Her lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court, charges that the
clearance requirement is a form of prior restraint prohibited by
the First Amendment.
   The suit seeks an injunction barring USIA from requiring her to
submit the article for its review before it is sent to the Columbia
Journalism Review.
   The magazine must have the manuscript by July 14 in order to
publish the piece in its September-October issue, according to the
lawsuit.
   In a series of cases, federal courts have upheld prepublication
review of manuscripts by former CIA employees to prevent
unauthorized disclosure of classified information.
   But Weaver, who has no access to classified information,
contends that in at least one decision, a court has explicitly
prohibited restrictions on the publication of unclassified material.
   In 1972, the Supreme Court declined to review a federal appeals
court finding that ``the First Amendment limits the extent to which
the United States, contractually or otherwise, may impose secrecy
requirements upon its employees and enforce them with a system of
prior censorship.''
   In that case, former CIA agent Victor Marchetti was barred from
publishing confidential information, but the appeals court said he
kept ``the right to speak and write about the CIA and its
operations, and to criticize it as any other citizen may.''
   Kohn said the regulation ``denies the American public access to
critical views of United States foreign policy.
   ``Even if an employee is given permission to criticize U.S.
foreign policy, it is approved criticism _ approved criticism is
not real criticism,'' he said.
   Lois Herman, a USIA spokeswoman, said the agency did not have a
comment on the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1943EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EnvironmentConference     06-30 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Environment Conference,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Call For Reduction in Carbon Dioxide Emissions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AM-Ozone in digest.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists called Thursday for a 20 percent
reduction in carbon dioxide emissions by the year 2005 to combat
the so-called ``greenhouse effect'' that is trapping heat like a
blanket around the Earth.
   ``Every day we wait for a reduction in greenhouse gases will
bring us closer to disaster,'' Dutch Environment Minister Eduardus
Nijpels told the closing session of a four-day conference on the
changing climate hosted by the Canadian government.
   Scientists use the term ``greenhouse effect'' to refer to
manmade pollution trapped in the atmosphere that is warming up the
Earth's surface.
   Carbon dioxide, one of the pollutants, is naturally emitted by
animal and plant life. An excessive buildup of that and other gases
results from the burning of fossil fuel in power plants, factories,
homes and cars, as well as agricultural and industrial pollution.
   More than 300 scientists and government officials from 40
countries and agencies warned in a closing statement that the
increase in greenhouse gases will raise temperatures by 3 to 8
degrees before the middle of the next century unless something is
done.
   ``Many scientists believe that warming due to greenhouse gases
has begun,'' the statement said. It said that unless the global
warming is halted, ``the expected rates and magnitude of climate
change will greatly exceed those experienced since civilization
began.''
   The scientists said that merely to stabilize carbon dioxide
concentrations, emissions would have to be reduced 50 percent.
   But after European countries pointed out they have already taken
many clean air measures, the conference recommended an initial goal
of reducing carbon dioxide emissions ``approximately 20 percent of
1988 levels by the year 2005.''
   About half of the recommended reduction can come from more
efficient use of existing energy supplies, the statement said,
noting some countries have shown they are energy savings of 2
percent annually.
   In an opening day speech Monday, Sen. Timothy E. Wirth, D-Colo.,
said the United States could save more than $200 billion a year in
energy costs through improved efficiency in transportation,
construction and government.
   He cited photovoltaic solar energy as a promising alternative to
fossil fuel and said it was time to reexamine nuclear power.
``Those nations that have halted the nuclear option are going to
have to reconsider,'' he said.
   The scientists called on all nations to ratify the 1987 Montreal
Protocol on halting the depletion of the earth's ozone layer by
reducing the use of chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs. On Thursday,
Canada became the fourth country to do so.
   CFCs are used in aerosol sprays, refrigerator coolant,
insulation and industrial cleaning. Once released, the CFCs break
down the ozone layer, allowing the sun's harmful ultraviolet rays
to reach the surface of the earth and thus increasing the incidence
of skin cancer.
   The scientists also said global warming from carbon dioxide,
methane, nitrous ozide, CFCs and the depletion of the ozone layer
could raise sea levels by up to five feet by the year 2050,
inundating coastal areas.
   In opening the conference, host Prime Minister Brian Mulroney
said Canada would like to see an International Law of the Air to
protect the atmosphere as the existing Law of the Sea defends the
oceans.
   But the conference endorsed a suggestion from keynote speaker
Gro Harlem Brundtland, prime minister of Norway, for work towards
an international convention on atmospheric protection.
   The conference also urged the establishment of a ``world
atmosphere fund'' financed by a tax on oil, gas and coal in
industrialized countries to pay for global protection efforts.
   The conference had few representatives from the Soviet bloc and
no representative from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency.
   U.S. Rep. George E. Brown, Jr., (D-Calif., sent a message
complaining that Washington will drag its feet on environmental
issues ``until an enlightened leader occupies the White House.''
   Meetings are planned in Ottawa next year and in Geneva in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
