<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1808EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Preppies-Murder     06-30 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Preppies-Murder,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Preppie Death: Good Kids, Good School, Bad Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They were good kids from good families, June
graduates of a prestigious Jesuit prep school.
   So why did a simple problem _ as simple as a classic premise for
a situation comedy _ begin a series of events that left one dead
and four others in disgrace?
   ``You just sit back and say, `How the hell could this happen?'''
Fordham Preparatory School headmaster Cornelius McCarthy said
Thursday. ``I think it was immediate gratification. They perceived
the need to solve this problem immediately.''
   James Patrick Cooney, 18, was shot to death by an off-duty
policeman during a Bronx robbery spree designed to raise $1,000 for
car repairs, police said. Cooney and his friends allegedly tried to
rob the officer minutes after they held up a grocery store at
gunpoint early Sunday.
   After Cooney was shot, the other 18-year-olds who were in the
car with him dumped his body in a park, wiped blood from the car
and burned some bloody clothing, police said.
   The body was found Wednesday after one youth, Barry Bootan,
bragged of the incident to a girlfriend, who told police,
authorities said.
   It all began with the kind of problem that has formed the basis
for teen-age sitcoms like ``Happy Days'' or movies like ``Risky
Business'' _ A teen-ager loans his father's station wagon to a
friend for a date. When the car is damaged in an accident, the kids
plot how to raise the money to get it fixed before Dad comes home.
   In this case, Cooney borrowed a station wagon Friday belonging
to the father of his classmate, Bootan. But Cooney drove the car
into a utility pole, scraping and denting the vehicle. Bootan was
frantic because his father was returning from a fishing trip Sunday
and he could find no one to loan him $1,000.
   To get the money, they allegedly enlisted the aid of another
Fordham student, Jason Katanic, who provided a car and a
.22-caliber rifle. Two other students accompanied them.
   The solution the youths allegedly devised _ armed robbery _
seemed inexplicable in light of their seemingly solid pasts and
promising futures.
   Cooney's stepfather is a 19-year veteran of the Police
Department who insisted that his stepson attend Fordham Prep even
though the family could barely afford the $3,700-a-year tuition.
   Bootan and Katanic, who face charges of attempted murder,
robbery and attempted robbery, were honor students at Fordham Prep.
   Two other students alleged to have been riding in the car but
not charged in the case also came from privileged backgrounds:
Brendan Moynihan, who lives in the expensive Westchester County
town of Pelham, is the son of a former Manhattan prosecutor; Daniel
Florio, who comes from Queens, reportedly is related to a judge.
   Speculation, however, centered on Cooney, ``J.P.'' to his
friends, who lived with his mother, stepfather and older sister in
a three-story redbrick house on a quiet Bronx street.
   A next-door neighbor described Cooney as polite and helpful. The
youth shoveled snow from his walk, tended his flower bed and
carried neighbors' groceries, the neighbor said.
   In school, he was a member of the wrestling team and, like all
graduating seniors, he performed 60 hours of community service. He
reportedly had been admitted for the fall semester at St. John's
University in Queens.
   Fordham Prep is a 147-year-old school with a reputation for
rigid academic standards and strict discipline. Virtually all 209
students who graduated June 3 planned to attend college.
   ``This is so out of character,'' said McCarthy. ``None of them
had any major disciplinary problems. He (Cooney) satisfied his
academic requirements. He seemed like the kind of kid who enjoyed
life.''
   But some of those who knew Cooney said he showed another side.
One classmate said he had begun to hang around with a rough crowd,
many of whose members were not Fordham Prep students, and had begun
to neglect his studies.
   Cooney left the school when he was a sophomore because of low
marks and never seemed entirely happy there when he returned. In
this year's yearbook, the space beneath Cooney's photo, reserved
for student activities and achievements, is blank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
