<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia     06-30 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenians Propose Solutions, Azerbaijan Rejects Them</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenian delegates to the Communist Party
conference on Thursday offered several solutions to their regional
dispute with the republic of Azerbaijan, but the Azerbaijanis
rejected all of them.
   Eduard M. Dzhrbashyan, director of the Institute of Literature
of Armenia's Academy of Sciences, said one of the proposed
compromises was turning the disputed region of Nagorno-Karabakh
over to the home area of Mikhail S. Gorbachev in southern Russia.
   Nagorno-Karabakh, a Caucasus Mountains enclave, is part of the
predominantly Moslem Azerbaijan republic but is dominated by mostly
Christian ethnic Armenians. Residents have been agitating for
annexation by Armenia since February.
   Armenia's parliament has endorsed the demand but Azerbaijan has
rejected it, leaving the issue deadlocked.
   Azerbaijan President Suleiman Tatliev told a news conference the
solution to the dispute lies in fostering friendship between
Azerbaijanis and Armenians, restoring a calm atmosphere in the
region and ``normalizing the situation.''
   Afrand Dashdamirov, deputy head of the propaganda department of
Azerbaijan's Communist Party Central Committee, told reporters the
compromises mentioned by the Armenian delegates ``would lead to the
disintegration of Azerbaijan.''
   Nagorno-Karabakh's legislature proposed on June 21 that the area
be turned over temporarily to the central government in Moscow in
an effort to calm tensions that have led to violent strikes,
demonstrations and riots.
   Dzhrbashyan told reporters that Nagorno-Karabakh, now classified
as an autonomous region of Azerbaijan, should be put under the
control of the Russian republic, specifically of the Stavropol
region north of the Caucasus Mountains.
   Dzhrbashyan did not make clear who was considering the
compromise, but his mention of it as a conference delegate
indicated it had some official support. He did not mention it was
Gorbachev's home area.
   Gorbachev was born in a farming village in the Stavropol region
in 1931, and worked there for 23 years in Communist Party jobs.
   Dzhrbashyan said the Stavropol region should be considered
because it was the closest part of Russia to Nagorno-Karabakh. He
said the idea of alliance between the two areas dates back to the
17th century.
   The current Communist Party conference is scheduled to adopt a
resolution outlining policy toward the country's more than 100
ethnic groups.
   Grant M. Voskanyan, Armenia's president, said a commission
drafting a resolution on ethnic relations had come up with no
specific proposals for resolving the dispute. But he said the party
Central Committee recommended the conference consider ``perfecting
federation'' of the Soviet Union and expanding the rights of
republics.
</TEXT>
