<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-WaterBank     06-30 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Water Bank,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Wewtrland Areas to be Opened for Emergency Hay Cutting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Certain wetland areas protected under the
Water Bank Program will be opened up for emergency hay cutting to
provide forage for drought-stressed livestock, the government
announced Thursday.
   The approval will be effective Friday in some counties and
within 15 days in others. The Water Bank Program, or WBP, is
jointly administered by the Agriculture and Interior departments.
   About 524,000 acres in 222 counties of 12 states are in the
conservation program. An estimated 350,000 of these could be used
for haying if declared eligible.
   Under the program, participants agree, unless otherwise
authorized, not to harvest hay or otherwise use the land for crops
for 10 years. In return, they receive annual rental payments from
the government.
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel said the later authorization for
some counties will protect waterfowl still nesting in wetland areas.
   ``Early next week, we will review the status of nesting in those
areas and determine if some can be opened for haying at that
time,'' he said.
   Conditions for haying the WBP land include:
   _Ten percent of the land nearest the wetland will not be hayed.
   _Haying will begin on the land farthest from the wetland and
progress inward.
   _Participants haying on these lands will have their next federal
rental payment reduced by 25 percent for each acre hayed.
   USDA officials said counties already approved for haying and
grazing of land taken from production under annual commodity
programs, along with Conservation Reserve Program land approved for
haying in Arkansas, California, Louisiana, Michigan, Mississippi,
Nebraska and Wisconsin, will be eligible for immediate WBP haying.
   The following Minnesota counties also will be eligible for
immediate WBP haying: Blue Earth, Brown, Carver, Cottonwood,
Freeborn, Jackson, Le Sueur, Lincoln, Lyon, Murray, Nicollet,
Renville, Rice, Scott, Sibley, Steele, Todd and Waseca.
   All counties approved for haying and grazing under the crop
programs and the Conservation Reserve Program in Montana, North
Dakota and South Dakota will be approved for WBP haying not later
than July 10, officials said.
   In Minnesota, the following counties will be approved not later
than July 15: Becker, Big Stone, Chippewa, Clay, Douglas, East
Ottertail, East Polk, Grant, Kandiyohi, Lac Qui Parle, McLeod,
Mahnomen, Meeker, Pope, Stearns, Stevens, Swift, Traverse, West
Ottertail, Wright and Yellow Medicine.
</TEXT>
