<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0737 06-30 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0737,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary of State Visits El Salvador and Honduras</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with Honduran
developments. Removes embargo. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
on Thursday called on the leaders of El Salvador and Honduras to
protect their fragile democracies and warned of the dangers of
communist rule.
   Shultz came to Tegucigalpa after a four-hour visit to El
Salvador, during which he urged the government to keep fighting the
leftist guerrillas, but also expressed concern about an upsurge in
politically motivated killings of civilians.
   At an airport arrival ceremony in this capital city, Shultz said
Honduras has advanced economically and socially under its
6-year-old democracy, while in Nicaragua per capita income has
dropped by 50 percent in the past 10 years.
   Shultz's message has been essentially the same since he began
his Central American trip in Guatemala on Wednesday: despite
difficult problems, the region's four democracies are performing
far better than Nicaragua, ``the odd man out'' in the area.
   ``The Sandinistas seek to build totalitarian society on the back
of a massive military machine,'' he said.
   In a show of American support, Shultz signed aid agreements
worth more than $180 million combined for El Salvador and Honduras.
He gave a pep talk to about 250 U.S. servicemen at the air base at
Palmerola, his first stop in Honduras.
   These forces are part of an estimated 1,200 U.S. troops who
stationed in Honduras partly as a deterrent to any potential
military move by Nicaragua, which borders on the south.
   Shultz's three-day trip to the region ends Friday in Costa Rica
and is his longest visit to Central America in four years.
   While criticizing Nicaragua, Shultz has said little about future
steps now that peace talks have broken down between the Sandinistas
and the U.S.-supported rebels, known as Contras.
   He has spoken only in vague terms about the failed negotiations,
telling his listeners that pressure on the Sandinistas must be
maintained if the goal of peace and democracy is to be achieved in
Nicaragua.
   But he has offered no specific suggestions and has made only
scant reference to the Contras.
   Shultz scheduled a meeting with Contra leaders Thursday night
during a return trip to Guatemala.
   In El Salvador, Shultz met with acting President Rodolfo
Castillo Claramount and with military leaders.
   About 2,000 university students who marched through downtown San
Salvador to demand greater government spending on education also
protested Shultz's visit.
   ``We repudiate the visit of Shultz!'' shouted the march leader
through a megaphone.
   ``We repudiate!'' the students responded.
   Before meeting the officers, Shultz said: ``I will say to them
that we must see a strong effort, as we have seen, to combat the
terrorist guerrillas, and that's going well.
   ``And of course there must always be vigilance on the question
of human rights, and I will emphasize that as well,'' he told
reporters after meeting with Castillo Claramount.
   U.S. officials said Shultz expressed concern about a rise in
politically motivated killings of civilians in El Salvador to an
average of 34 a month, an increase from a monthly average of 27
last year.
   The administration is worried that a major setback in human
rights performance could jeopardize congressional support for U.S.
aid to El Salvador, which is receiving $400 million in aid this
year.
   Castillo Claramount is acting in place of President Jose
Napoleon Duarte, who is being treated for terminal cancer in
Washington.
   In Honduras, a key ally of the United States in its bid to oust
Nicaragua's government, Shultz said the drive for democracy
contrasts with the situation in Nicaragua. Honduras has for years
provided a safe haven to the Contras.
   During his five-hour stay in Honduras, Shultz had lunch with
Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras and met with President Jose
Azcona Hoyo.
</TEXT>
