<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Bombing     06-30 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Bombing,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Counter-Terrorism Experts To Help With Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.S. counter-terrorism experts
is in Greece to help police investigate a car-bomb explosion that
killed a U.S. defense attache, a senior police officer said
Thursday.
   The officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
10-member U.S. team would offer ``specialized assistance'' to Greek
police supervising the investigation. He did not elaborate.
   U.S. Embassy officials declined to comment on the team's
presence in Greece.
   A bunch of pink and white roses lay scattered Thursday over the
twisted metal fence where the explosion on Tuesday lodged the car
of U.S. Navy Capt. William Nordeen.
   Nordeen, 51, died when a car-bomb exploded next to his
armor-plated automobile just 100 yards from his house in Kifissia,
a northern Athens suburb.
   The former Navy pilot's body, now at the U.S. Air Force base at
Athens Airport, will be flown home next Tuesday for burial at
Washington's Arlington cemetery. A memorial service will be held in
Athens over the weekend, diplomats said.
   U.S. Embassy officials said the State Department would offer a
$500,000 reward for information leading to the arrest and
conviction of Nordeen's killers.
   The Greek terrorist organization November 17 claimed
responsibility for the bomb. The group vowed Wednesday to keep
attacking American targets ``until the last American soldier leaves
Greece.'' The statement appeared in the left-wing daily Ethnos.
   There are 3,500 American military personnel currently stationed
at four U.S. bases in Greece.
   Greek government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos denied foreign
press reports that Greece was unable to take effective measures
against terrorism.
   ``Foreign press reports about the lack of eagerness and
incompetence of the Greek security services are completely
groundless and innaccurate,'' Kostopoulos told reporters.
   The senior police officer said the investigation had made no
headway so far.
   November 17 has claimed 12 political assassinations in 13 years,
including those of three American diplomats. None of its members
has ever been arrested.
   The group is named for the date in 1973 when troops crushed a
student uprising against the 1967-74 military dictatorship.
   According to police, group members placed up to 88 pounds of TNT
inside a stolen car, which they detonated with a remote control
device as Nordeen was driving by. They had stacked bags of cement
on one side of the car to direct the explosion towards Nordeen's
car.
   ``The device is the same as the one they tried to use in their
last attack. They are using them to get around the armor-plating,''
the police official said.
   In January, police acting on a tip found a powerful bomb in a
trash can outside the home of George Carros, an Athens-based
official of the U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency.
   November 17 later claimed in a statement it had called off a
planned attack against Carros.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
