<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseProbe-Pentagon 1stLd-Writethru a0Ai- 06-30 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Pentagon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Rejects Congressional Calls for Contract Freeze</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new 7th graf ``But Aspin'' to update with further
Aspin comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense contract freeze proposed by
congressmen irate over alleged procurement fraud could raise the
cost of weapons, force plant layoffs and lower the readiness of the
armed forces, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   ``We would be glad to discuss with the Congress the question of
freezing awards of new contracts while the Justice Department is
investigating allegations of procurement fraud,'' said spokesman
Fred S. Hoffman. ``But at this point we feel it would be imprudent
to apply such a freeze or moratorium.''
   The chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, Rep. Les
Aspin, D-Wis., said Wednesday that Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci should order ``absolutely no contracts signed for 60 days
(or) six weeks'' with companies implicated in the criminal
investigation.
   If the Pentagon froze new contracts, ``the innocent would suffer
as well as the guilty ... You may be sure that we will take
precautions in any awards,'' Hoffman told reporters in response.
   ``Our contracts have adequate clauses which can be brought into
play to reopen them and take other action to protect the public
interest,'' he said.
   ``However, we wonder whether the members of Congress calling for
a freeze or a moratorium have thought through the possible
consequences, such as higher program costs, production line
shutdowns, widespread plant layoffs and damage to the readiness of
our forces,'' he said.
   But Aspin said late Thursday he had talked to Carlucci and ``I
don't think we're that far apart in what we're thinking. My goal is
to make sure the contracts that are being let now, not the ones
involved in the investigation, are free of any taint. That's his
goal, too.''
   Hoffman said Defense Department officials were looking into
allegations by the coordinating prosecutor in the case, U.S.
Attorney Henry Hudson of Alexandria, Va., that some suspects had
destroyed documents since warrants in the case became public on
June 14.
   The investigation centers on allegations that defense
contractors and consultants, many of them former military men,
bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details vital in winning
contracts worth billions of dollars.
   Hudson said in court papers that ``the government has already
become aware of several incidents of destruction of documents
related to this case.'' He did not say where.
   Hoffman said he had ``heard of none'' destroyed in the Defense
Department, but ``we are looking into it ... Our people are taking
what we believe to be adequate measures'' to protect critical
documents. He said he could not to specify what measures Pentagon
officials were taking.
   The spokesman also rejected Aspin's assertion the Navy should
have postponed a $960 million contract, announced June 23, to buy
F-A-18 fighter planes from the McDonnell-Douglas Corp, one of the
companies involved in the investigation.
   ``I am informed by Navy officials ... that there is no
suggestion of any taint in conncetion with that contract,'' Hoffman
said.
   Because of the Justice Department action, Pentagon Inspector
General June Gibbs Brown was reopening one contract investigation,
previously closed, and reviewing five other cases to determine
whether any were tainted, he said.
   ``Overall, there were some six matters that are being
examined,'' Hoffman said.
   The office of the Pentagon inspector general, which does not
have the power to prosecute, ``has a longstanding modus operandi
that as investigative matters are developed or made public, its
procedure is to review related cases to see if there are any
potential problems or parallel issues,'' Hoffman said.
   Pentagon officials declined to discuss specifics of the cases
under review. At least one of them is known, however, because of
interest expressed by Rep. John D. Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of
the House Energy and Commerce Committee.
   That case involved a tip to a telephone hotline received last
August, alleging that former Assistant Navy Secretary Melvyn R.
Paisley and two defense contractors had conspired to limit
competition on contracts for a $1 billion radar-warning system used
on Navy aircraft.
   Paisley, who left the Navy job in April 1987 to open a
consulting business, is thought to be one of the central figures in
the current probe. His home and offices were searched two weeks ago.
   After receiving word of the hotline tip, the inspector general's
staff opened what turned out to be a seven-month investigation. The
case was closed on March 14 for lack of evidence to substantiate
the charges.
   It was reopened at Ms. Brown's direction on June 16, two days
after the FBI investigation was publicly disclosed.
</TEXT>
