<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MX-Hearings     06-30 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MX-Hearings,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force To Hold Hearings in 11 Western States on Rail-Based MX</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Department officials will conduct
hearings in July and August near 11 Western sites that have been
designated as possible bases for the rail-mobile MX missile, the
Air Force said Thursday.
   The Air Force filed a draft environmental impact statement on
the plan, which has been all but sidetracked in Congress and which
is opposed by ecology activists in states where the missile might
be stationed.
   Pentagon spokesman Fred Hoffman said the Air Force filing
initiates a 60-day public comment period on environmental aspects
of the basing plan.
   ``The Air Force will hold public meetings at each of the
communities which could be affected by the proposal,'' Hoffman said.
   Despite opposition, Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci on May
18 approved $328.7 million in contracts for the rail-mobile MX, a
missile he says is necessary to counter two mobile missiles already
deployed by the Soviets: the 10-warhead SS-24, based on rails, and
the single-warhead SS-25 on trucks.
   The MX can carry 10 warheads, and Air Force officials call in
the most accurate strategic missile in the U.S. arsenal.
   ``We are not terminating the program,'' Hoffman told reporters
at a briefing. ``We are moving ahead on a plan that we have laid
out.
   ``We live in hope that if not this year, then next year the
Congress will see the wisdom of the approach that we have been
recommending,'' he said.
   The United States never has succeeded in deploying a mobile
intercontinental ballistic missile, in large part because of
community opposition, and had demanded that such weapons be banned
under a proposed Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty now under
negotiation with the Kremlin.
   But at last month's Moscow summit diplomats offered a proposal
to allow a set number of mobile missiles within tightly defined
geographical areas that could be inspected by satellites or teams
from each country. That proposal will be debated when negotiations
resume in Geneva next month.
   The Air Force wants to deploy 25 MX trains, each carrying two of
the ``Peacekeeper'' missiles.
   They would be kept at F.E. Warren Air Force Base in Cheyenne,
Wyo., in peacetime, then scatter along the civilian rail system in
times of East-West tension or war, making them difficult targets
and a deterrence against a surprise Soviet nuclear attack.
   Up to four more trains might be deployed later at as many as 10
other Air Force bases.
   So far, Congress has approved deployment of 50 MXs, to be based
in existing Minuteman silos, but has been cool to putting MXs on
trains.
   The Air Force filed the draft environmental impact statements
after the 8th Circuit Court of Appeals in St. Louis ruled on May 18
that a judge must consider environmental claims against the basing
plan, but could not rule on the relative merits of deploying the
missiles on rails or in silos.
   Besides Warren, the other Air Force Bases at which MX trains
might be deployed are: Barksdale, La.; Dyess, Texas; Eaker, Ark.;
Fairchild, Wash.; Grand Forks, N.D.; Little Rock, Ark.; Malmstrom,
Mont.; Minot, N.D.; Whiteman, Mo.; and Wurtsmith, Mich.
   The Pentagon said copies of the draft environmental impact
statment could be obtained by writing to: AFRCE-BMS@DEV, Norton Air
Force Base, Calif., 92409-6448. And more information about the
program can be obtained by calling the Peacekeeper Rail Garrison
Program, Ballistic Missile Office, at (714) 382-6631.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
