<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 2020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     06-30 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Leader Appeals to Romania on Ethnic Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz
appealed on Thursday for dialogue with Romania in the steadily
worsening dispute over how the neighboring Soviet bloc ally treats
its ethnic Hungarian minority.
   Istvan Oeszi, deputy foreign minister, summoned the acting
Romanian charge d'affaires and told him that expelling diplomats is
``diametrically opposed to the agreements valid between the two
countries and the norms of European cooperation.''
   It was the first official Hungarian comment on Romania's
decision, announced Tuesday, to close the Hungarian consulate at
Cluj in Transylvania and expel its staff members.
   Grosz, who also is premier, told Western journalists in an
impromptu meeting that he will go ahead with a planned visit to
Romania, because ``if we don't talk to each other we cannot
understand each other.''
   No date has been announced for the trip, but it is believed
Grosz will go to Bucharest after visits in July to Moscow, Warsaw
and Washington.
   The issue of Romania's 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians always has
been delicate, but in recent months Hungarians have become
increasingly vocal about it.
   Romania's announcement came one day after 50,000 people
demonstrated in Budapest against a Romanian plan to level 7,000
villages and replace them with agricultural-industrial centers.
Hungarians claim the project will disperse the ethnic Hungarians,
largely concentrated in Transylvania, destroying their culture and
tradition.
   Hungary claims the minority is discriminated against and Romania
accuses the Hungary of interfering in its domestic affairs.
   Both Grosz and Oeszi, as quoted in a Foreign Ministry
communique, said Monday's protest was not directed against Romania
or its leadership.
   Nicolae Ceausescu, the Romanian leader, issued a denunciation
Tuesday of ``new actions of a chauvinistic, nationalistic,
anti-Romanian, anti-Socialist nature'' by Hungarians.
   Romania also ordered the closure of a dormant Hungarian cultural
institute in Bucharest.
   Grosz said he does not intend to raise the issue with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev when he visits Moscow next week because
``it is a bilateral issue and not an affair of the Soviet Union.''
   He will be the first East bloc leader to meet with Gorbachev
after this week's Moscow party conference, at which the Kremlin
leader has called for more reforms in his program of
``perestroika,'' or restructuring. Grosz became Hungarian party
chief in May, replacing Janos Kadar.
</TEXT>
