<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BlackBoxes-Commuters     06-30 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Boxes-Commuters,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Requires `Black Box' Recorders in Most Commuter Aircraft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commuter airlines must have so-called ``black
box'' recorders in most of their aircraft within three years to
help accident investigators determine the cause of a crash or
safety incident, the Federal Aviation Administration ruled Thursday.
   Large jetliners already are required to have the recorders,
which provide information about an aircraft's performance and
provide a 30-minute loop tape of conversation in the cockpit.
   The devices have been crucial in revealing the causes of many
airliner crashes over the years.
   But commuter planes of fewer than 30 seats have not been
required to have the devices.
   Under a final FAA rule announced Thursday, multi-engine,
turbine-powered commuter planes carrying more than six passengers
and flown by two pilots will be required to have a cockpit voice
recorder.
   Slightly larger commuter planes carrying 20 or more passengers
will also have to be equipped with a digital flight data recorder
that stores such information as air speed, altitude, aircraft pitch
and heading.
   No commuter planes are now required to have such equipment.
Under the rule, commuter airlines must have the black box recorders
within three years of the effective date of the rule, which is
expected to be in 90 days.
   The cockpit voice recorder must be included in new aircraft and
retrofitted into planes already in service. The flight data
recorder must be in both new and in-service aircraft when a plane
has 20 or more seats. There is no retrofit requirement on the
flight data recorder in the smaller commuter planes that have fewer
than 20 seats.
   ``Although the FDR and CVR do not enhance safety by themselves,
they have proven to be invaluable accident investigation tools and
have led to numerous improvements in aviation safety,'' said FAA
Administrator Allan McArtor.
   Last year, Congress directed the FAA to expand its requirements
for the ``black box'' recorders to include the commuter airlines
which last year carried about 32 million passengers.
   The National Transportation Safety Board for years has called on
the FAA to require the recorders in commuter aircraft. Earlier this
year, the NTSB cited a number of accident investigations which
would have been much easier had information from such recorders
been available.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
