<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Truce     06-30 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Truce,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Extends Truce, Proposes New Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cuba-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega extended a
unilateral cease-fire until July 31 and proposed new talks with
rebel leaders.
   Speaking to 1,200 military officers Thursday soon after
returning from a trip to Cuba, Ortega called the moves a
``demonstration of common sense and responsibility because we don't
want to give up the possibility of a negotiated solution.''
   He added, however: ``This does not mean that we are going to let
down our guard ... because we know that they are not going to keep
their word and are infiltrating forces from Honduras.''
   Ortega proposed holding the talks July 27-29 in Managua. There
was no immediate response from the U.S.-backed rebels, known as
Contras, who began fighting the leftist Sandinista government nerly
seven years ago.
   Earlier talks broke down June 9.
   The current cease-fire, announced by the government at the end
of May when a temporary truce declared by both sides expired, ended
at midnight Thursday.
   A March 1 agreement between the Sandinistas and Contras included
a 60-day cease-fire to allow for negotiations on a permanent truce
and democratic reforms demanded by the rebels.
   The government's extension of the truce came during a visit by
Secretary of State George P. Shultz to U.S. allies in Central
America. His three-day visit includes Guatemala, El Salvador,
Honduras and Costa Rica.
   Ortega said Shultz was bringing the region ``a message loaded
with hate for the people of Nicaragua, directed at seeking how to
isolate it and seek more resources in Congress to continue the war
against Nicaragua.''
   Shultz has criticized Nicaragua during his trip, calling it a
totalitarian society.
   In Cuba, Ortega signed a $150 million assistance agreement under
which Havana will pardon a $50 million Nicaraguan debt.
   Cuba also will provide 270,000 tons of oil in the next three
years, food and technical assistance for sugar refineries and
construction of an industrial plant on the Caribbean coast.
   Ortega said the agreement showed ``the willingness of the Cuban
people and government to contribute with the people and government
of Nicaragua to better face the critical situation that North
American aggression is imposing on us.''
</TEXT>
