<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YoungKillers     06-30 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Young Killers,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cooper's Defense Attorney, Prosecutor Want High Court Decision</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRAN RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who prosecuted a teen-ager for
murder and the attorney trying to keep her out of the electric
chair applauded the U.S. Supreme Court's decision Thursday to
consider the constitutionality of executing juveniles.
   At the same time, Lake County Prosecutor Jack Crawford and
William L. Touchette, the attorney for inmate Paula Cooper, agreed
that just because the justices will consider the issue next year
doesn't mean they will resolve it.
   Touchette pointed out the court has heard two Oklahoma cases
involving teen-age killers _ one in 1981 and the other on Wednesday
_ ``and neither case has definitively settled anything regarding
the execution of juveniles.''
   He said both cases were decided on narrow grounds, meaning they
affect cases with similar factual situations and state statutes
without addressing the more sweeping Eighth Amendment issue of
cruel and unusual punishment.
   ``If they keep hearing the cases, eventually they won't have
narrow state law to decide it on. It will be the general
constitutional issue,'' he said.
   On Wednesday, the high court overturned an Oklahoma youth's
death sentence but failed to reach the majority needed to resolve
the juvenile death penalty issue.
   Just 24 hours later, the justices announced they will accept
cases from Georgia and Missouri to reconsider the fate of young
killers.
   Court watchers cautioned against reading too much into the
court's willingness to restudy the issue so promptly.
   ``It's foolish to try and predict what the court will do,'' said
Henry Schwarzschild of the American Civil Liberties Union in
Washington.
   Crawford agreed. ``I think it's very premature to assume ...
they're going to strike down the death penalty for all juveniles,''
he said. ``It is significant they're going to hear it, but it
doesn't dispose of the issue.''
   ``We need an answer. It can end a lot of litigation one way or
another,'' Touchette said.
   Cooper, 18, was 15 when she stabbed a 78-year-old Bible studies
teacher 33 times during a 1985 robbery in Gary that netted her
about $10 and a car. She pleaded guilty.
   Three other teen-age girls were convicted or pleaded guilty, but
Cooper was the only one to receive the death penalty.
   ``We'll continue to press for the death sentence for Cooper in
light of the seriousness of the crime and the maturity of the
defendant in the case,'' said Crawford, who described Cooper as a
``vicious killer.''
   ``In my opinion, you can't assess penalties on the basis of age
because of the wide disparity of maturity,'' he said. ``Any time
you consider a factor that is not a part of the crime, you have a
lot of unfairness.''
   An international outcry about Cooper's sentence prompted the
1987 Legislature from 10 to 16 the minimum age at which a person
can receive the death penalty. Cooper was not affected because the
law was not retroactive.
</TEXT>
