<HEAD>Fallen Gorbachev Protege Wants to Speak at Party Forum</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris N. Yeltsin, the former Moscow party boss,
has asked permission to address the Communist Party's national
conference, an official said Thursday.
   Earlier in the day, a conference delegate said the meeting
should hear Yeltsin to be able to decide whether he supports
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform drive, or if his ideas are ``leftist
eccentricity.''
   Gorbachev accused his tough-talking former protege of excessive
ambition and presided over his removal in November. The previous
month, at a closed-door meeting of the party's policy-making
Central Committee, the 57-year-old Yeltsin had criticized the pace
of Gorbachev's program for change.
   A week after his ouster, Yeltsin was named to a job with the
rank of minister in the State Construction Committee. He is
attending the conference as a delegate from the region of Karelia,
near the Finnish border.
   Yuri A. Sklyarov, head of the Central Committee's Propaganda
Department, told a news conference Yeltsin was among the 261
delegates at the 5,000-member meeting who had asked to speak, but
gave no indication when he might be given the floor.
   During the Moscow summit between Gorbachev and President Reagan,
Yeltsin gave an interview to Western broadcast journalists in which
he called for the resignation of No. 2 Kremlin leader Yegor K.
Ligachev, who is reputedly more conservative than Gorbachev.
   Speaking at the conference, German Zagainov, an administrator in
a scientific institute, turned to Gorbachev and said: ``In the
interview with foreign journalists during the summit with President
Reagan, you ... said it would be interesting for you to know what
Comrade Yeltsin said to foreign journalists. For us, ordinary
members of the party, it would also be interesting.''
   In his televised remarks, Zagainov called Yeltsin a well-known
supporter of Gorbachev's reforms, and asked: ``Why didn't he give
an interview to our press? We would like to know his explanation at
the conference. If it is leftist eccentricity, it will get the
appropriate evaluation. If there is something healthy, we'll
consider it.''
   At the 27th Party Congress in 1986, Yeltsin gave one of the most
talked about addresses, in which he condemned excess privilege for
the Soviet elite.
</TEXT>
