<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Women,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top British Court Upholds Women's Claim for Equal Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Lords, the nation's highest court, on
Thursday upheld an equal pay claim by five women who complained
that male co-workers were earning more for doing the same job.
   The five Law Lords dismissed an appeal by Freemans mail-order
company of Peterborough, northern England, which argued that at
least one of its male employees is paid the same as the women as
warehouse operatives.
   The women had argued that male workers earned an extra $7.20 a
week to do ``work of equal value.'' The women earn $131 a week.
   It is the third House of Lords victory in three months for
British women fighting sexual discrimination at work.
   In April, Maria Brown, 35, won a ruling that she had been
unfairly chosen to be laid off from her job with Stockton-on-Tees
borough council in northeast England because she was pregnant.
   In May, a 28-year-old cafeteria cook, Julie Hayward, won her
pioneering fight for equal basic pay _ regardless of fringe
benefits _ with male colleagues at Cammell Laird shipyard in
Birkenhead, northwest England.
</TEXT>
