<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 2036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-30 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0618</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Some Parts of Midwest Go From Drought to Flooding; Cooler Air
Prevails
^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Parts of the Midwest went from drought to flood conditions
Thursday, while the Northeast saw temperatures plummet to record
lows.
   Parts of Kansas and Nebraska were hit by downpours Wednesday
night and Thursday that flooded roads, filled ponds and sent rivers
rushing.
   Worden, Kan., received 12 inches of rain Wednesday night, and
several other locations about 20 miles south of Lawrence and
Topeka, Kan., received more than eight inches.
   The rain swelled the Wakarusa River at Lawrence to six feet
above flood stage. In Nebraska, up to 10 inches fell 10 miles
southwest of Callaway, and more than five inches were measured six
miles west of Broken Bow.
   On Wednesday, Gerald Martian of rural Trail City, S.D., had
never seen it so dry. On Thursday, he had never seen it so wet
after an estimated 11 inches of rain drenched his farm.
   ``It's too much for one time,'' said Martian, who has been
farming for nearly 30 years.
   Cool weather prevailed in the Northeast as afternoon
temperatures were in the 50s and 60s from New England across New
York and northern Pennsylvania to the northern Great Lakes.
   Readings were in the upper 60s and 70s from the mid-Atlantic
states to South Carolina.
   The Missouri Valley also cooled off, and temperatures were in
the 50s and 60s from western parts of the Dakotas across Nebraska
to northern Missouri.
   Record low temperatures for the date included 48 degrees at
Allentown, Pa.; 50 at Atlantic City, N.J.; 52 at Baltimore; 48 at
Binghamton, N.Y.; 38 at Boise, Idaho; 48 at Cleveland; 38 at
Concord, N.H.; 36 at Duluth, Minn.; 37 at Elkins, W.Va.; 49 at
Harrisburg, Pa.; 44 at Hartford, Conn.; 43 at Madison, Wisc.; 46 at
Mansfield, Ohio; 46 at Pittsburgh; 48 at Syracuse, N.Y., and 44 at
Youngstown, Ohio.
   Thunderstorms extended across parts of the Carolinas and Georgia
and from Alabama and Georgia to Florida.
   Strong winds accompanying thunderstorms toppled trees onto power
lines north of Dothan, Ala., and in northeast Georgia. Winds turned
over a small pumphouse and blew a tree onto a road south of Dothan.
   Severe thunderstorm watches were in effect Thursday night for
parts of South Carolina, Georgia, Alabama, Florida, Arkansas,
Missouri, Kansas and Oklahoma.
   Showers extended across parts of New York and northern New
England. Rain extended across eastern North Carolina, and from
central South Dakota to western Nebraska. Thunderstorms developed
in southeast Colorado.
   Temperatures reached the 90s in much of Florida, parts of the
Gulf coastal states, the southern Plains and the desert southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 50
degrees at Ithaca, N.Y., and Utica, N.Y., to 106 degrees at Palm
Springs, Calif.
   The low for the nation Thursday morning was 29 degrees at
Yellowstone, Wyo., and West Yellowstone, Mont.
   The forecast for Friday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms extending from the southern Atlantic Coast across
Florida, the Gulf Coast region, the central and southern Plains,
and the southern Rockies to northern Arizona.
   Showers and thunderstorms also are expected in northern Florida
and parts of western Missouri and eastern Kansas. Showers also were
forecast in New York, northern New Jersey and New England.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s or 80s in most of the
nation. Highs will be in the 90s from Florida across the lower
Mississippi Valley and Texas to much of Arizona, Utah, Nevada and
California. Temperatures will hold in the upper 50s and 60s in New
York and New England.
</TEXT>
