<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jane's-USBombers     06-30 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jane's-US Bombers,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jane's Says U.S. F-111s With Cruise Missiles To Be Based In
Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jane's Defense Weekly says the United States will
deploy 51 F-111 bombers in Britain armed with cruise nuclear
missiles, but the Pentagon on Thursday denied any such plans.
   The British weekly, viewed as being authoritative on defense
matters, said in its issue published Thursday that the jets armed
with cruise missiles would replace land-based missiles banned under
the superpower arms control agreement.
   Pentagon spokesman Fred Hoffman said in Washington on Thursday,
when asked about the report: ``There are no plans to equip F-111
aircraft with any type of cruise missile in the future.''
   ``Replacement of the aging F-111 force is one of several force
modernization plans that are currently under consideration,''
Hoffman added.
   ``The recently upgraded F-B-111-A will be transferred to the
Tactical Air Forces in the early 1990s and will be redesignated the
F-111-G. The final determination of basing will be fully
coordinated with all relevant parties, including foreign
governments.''
   On Wednesday, the British Defense Ministry acknowledged in a
statement that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization was
considering transferring U.S.-based, long-range aircraft to Western
Europe. It did not elaborate.
   However, the ministry said deploying air-launched cruise
missiles in Western Europe ``is not under consideration.''
   A spokesman at U.S. Air Force European headquarters at Ramstein,
West Germany, Lt. Col. Ed Neunherz, said plans have been under
consideration for years to adapt F-111s to carry cruise missiles,
but no NATO go-ahead was given.
   Jane's said Gen. William Kirk, commander-in-chief of the U.S.
Air Force in Europe, said the 51 F-111s ``would augment the
capability of striking targets deep in the Soviet Union from their
new bases in the U.K. (United Kingdom) when armed with nuclear
cruise missiles.''
   The Intermediate Nuclear Forces treaty between the United States
and the Soviet Union, signed in December and ratified last month,
provides for elimination of 1,800 Soviet and 800 Allied
medium-range missiles over three years.
   Jane's said F-111s will be transferred from Strategic Air
Command bases in New York and New Hampshire late next year or early
in 1990 to ``bolster NATO's flexible response strategy.''
   The INF treaty covers only land-based missiles with a range from
300 miles to about 3,100 miles.
   The U.S. Air Force said Wednesday that Kirk confirmed in a June
2 interview with the Omaha, Neb., World-Herald that the 51 F-111s
will be transferred on the basis of a one-for-one swap with F-111s
already in Britain.
</TEXT>
