<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dukakis-Budget     06-30 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Budget,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government's Fiscal Year Ends with No Budget in Sight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Gov. Michael Dukakis out of state campaigning
for president, Massachusetts ended the fiscal year with a nearly
$400 million deficit Thursday and headed into the new fiscal year
without a budget.
   Dukakis awaited final action by the Legislature on his plan to
close the books on fiscal year 1988 and on a compromise spending
plan for 1989.
   At the same time, a series of tax bills and fee-raising measures
to help the state pay for expanded spending in fiscal 1989 neared
enactment.
   The Revenue Department, meanwhile, was busy opening envelopes in
a drive to collect every possible tax dollar that can be attributed
to fiscal 1988.
   The agency will not close its books before next week, but one
administration official said Thursday that there was ``no good
news'' in the final month of the fiscal year.
   The Dukakis administration has acknowledged that state
government is technically $397 million short for 1988.
   To deal with that shortfall, the governor has filed the final
supplemental budget of the year, a proposal that includes a plan to
tap cash reserves and make bookkeeping adjustments to close the
gap. State law requires a balanced budget.
   In recent years, Massachusetts has often gone several days or
even weeks into a new fiscal year without a budget.
   House Minority Leader Steven Pierce charged Thursday that it was
``inconceivable'' that the governor would be out of state
campaigning with the budget crisis unresolved.
   Dukakis spokesman Steve Crawford said the government would be in
his office Friday, Saturday and possibly Monday.
   ``He is in constant contact with his office. His chief of staff
and his secretary of administration and finance are regularly
discussing the budget process with legislative leaders,'' Crawford
said.
</TEXT>
