<DOCNO> AP880630-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 2121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-IndustrialAccident     06-30 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Industrial Accident,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Inspector Says Training in Chemicals Essential to Safety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fifth worker died Thursday from cyanide
fumes released when a cleanup job at a metals-plating company went
awry.
   The worker, Craig Fogle, 19, had collapsed in Tuesday's accident
while trying to rescue co-workers, authorities said. He died at
Parkview Memorial Hospital in Fort Wayne, said Westley Falcaro, a
hospital spokeswoman.
   The four other deaths occurred when a worker collapsed while
cleaning the inside of a plating tank at Bastian Plating Co. and
three co-workers either entered or fell into the tank in a rescue
effort, investigators said.
   Hydrochloric acid used in the cleaning mixed with sludge in the
tank to release the cyanide gas, investigators said.
   In addition to the five dead, 24 people, mostly employees and
rescue workers, were injured. One remained hospitalized, a police
officer listed in satisfactory condition at DeKalb Memorial
Hospital, a spokeswoman said.
   The accident raised questions about the training workers receive
in handling chemicals.
   Chemical training ``is extremely important for all employees,
because if something like this happened, they would have the
information so they could react,'' said Sonny Painter, an inspector
for the Indiana Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
   Kirk Carpenter, an attorney for Bastian Plating, said he
believes the company met government safety standards.
   Lance Baughman, who has worked at the plant five years, said he
was required to pass a written test before he began. He said the
test dealt with proper clothing to wear around chemicals and a
coding system for identifying the degree of hazard presented by
particular chemicals.
   But he said test ``basically doesn't tell you anything about the
chemicals themselves. I've been there for five years, and I
basically have had to learn everything on my own, just trial and
error.''
</TEXT>
