<DOCNO> AP880630-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 2243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Protest     06-30 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Protest,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Acknowledges Peasant Protest, Denies Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first official report to acknowledge that a
peasant protest took place last week in a village near Beijing said
Friday that police who broke it up were unarmed and denied that
anyone was killed.
   The Xinhua News Agency did not comment on statements by Chinese
witnesses that 60 to 70 protesters were seriously hurt by police
using electric cattle prods and clubs and that at least 10 people
remain under arrest.
   Peasants in Guce, 37 miles southwest of Beijing, told The
Associated Press on Thursday that more than 1,500 villagers clashed
with thousands of armed police before dawn June 21.
   Some villagers told Western reporters that three people were
killed, but those who spoke to the AP said they could not confirm
this.
   The peasants were trying to stop a local petrochemical plant
from releasing contaminated water from a reservoir into a stream,
poisoning their wells.
   The peasants gathered at the reservoir to try to halt the
release of water, but police beat them and used cattle prods
indiscriminately, witnesses said.
   Xinhua gave the number of villagers involved as ``hundreds,''
and said most left when officials explained that the water level
was dangerously high and the dam might collapse, causing a flood.
   ``The rest who refused to leave were led away by unarmed
police'' and the water was released, the report said. It gave no
number nor did it say what happened to those led away.
   ``Nobody was killed,'' Xinhua quoted local party secretary Wang
Zuosheng as saying. He made no comment on injuries.
   Peasants told the AP that about 150 people were arrested, but
that all but 10 were released within 48 hours.
   On Thursday, workers were digging trenches down the main village
road to install water pipes to hook up alternate water sources. The
villagers said their well water was made undrinkable by the release
of contaminated water and claimed some people had been sickened by
it.
   Officials have refused to say what chemicals were dumped in the
reservoir, and the Xinhua report did not say. It confirmed that
work was under way to provide drinking water and said 110 tons of
flour were distributed as compensation to about 4,000 affected
farmers.
   The report quoted an official of the Yanshan Petrochemical
Corp., which released the contaminants, as acknowledging the water
contained ``more pollutants than the amount permitted by state
regulations.'' He said the company was installing new equipment to
process waste water in the future.
</TEXT>
