<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Cambodia-Vietnam 2ndLd-Writethru   06-30 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia-Vietnam, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0824,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Calls Back Its Generals From Cambodia After Decade Of War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 13th graf pvs ``We do not...'' with 1 graf to CORRECT
name to Gaston Sigur, sted of Sigur Gaston. PICKS up 14th graf pvs
bgng, As part of...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cheering Cambodians lined an airport
road Thursday as Vietnam pulled its military leaders out of
Cambodia, loosening its grip on this long-suffering country after
nearly a decade of combat.
   Vietnam disclosed its casualties in the war for the first time.
It said 55,000 of its troops had been killed since 1977, when
Vietnam began clashing with the China-backed Khmer Rouge regime
which then ruled Cambodia.
   On Thursday, Vietnam officially turned over control of its war
against anti-Vietnamese insurgents to Cambodian commanders.
   ``We think the Cambodian armed forces can shoulder their
responsibilities themselves,'' said Lt. Gen. Le Kha Phieu, a former
deputy commander of Vietnamese forces in Cambodia.
   Gen. Le Ngoc Hien, the Vietnamese commander in Cambodia, and
about 300 of his officers were greeted by thousands of Vietnamese
after flying from Phnom Penh to Ho Chi Minh City, once known as
Saigon.
   Earlier in Phnom Penh, an estimated 50,000 Cambodians lined the
city's broad boulevards and the road to the airport as the
Vietnamese officers departed aboard Soviet-made aircraft for the
short flight to Vietnam.
   Robed Buddhist monks offered blessings for a safe journey.
Onlookers waved both Cambodian and Vietnamese flags.
   The military commanders are among 50,000 Vietnamese troops that
Hanoi says will head home by the end of the year in the largest of
seven annual pullouts from Cambodia.
   Officials said 3,000 soldiers also returned to Vietnam Thursday
by buses and trucks.
   The Vietnamese have been fighting a coalition of guerrilla
forces in Cambodia that includes the communist Khmer Rouge, the
non-communist Khmer People's Party and followers of former leader
Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   Cambodian Premier Hun Sen played down fears that a total
Vietnamese withdrawal _ promised by 1990 _ would lead to a return
to power of the Khmer Rouge.
   In Washington, the State Department's top official for Asia said
the world would not accept a Khmer Rouge resurgence.
   ``We do not believe that that can happen ... and we are fully
confident that the international community will never accept
that,'' said Gaston Sigur, assistant secretary of state for East
Asia and Pacific affairs.
   As part of recently intensified efforts to find a political
solution to the Cambodian conflict, U.N. Special Envoy Rafeeuddin
Ahmed was coming to Phnom Penh for talks with Hun Sen. It would be
the first time a U.N. envoy would hold formal talks with the
Cambodian government, which the United Nations does not recognize.
   Knowledgeable Thai sources said the envoy last weekend traveled
to the Thai-Cambodian border to meet Prince Norodom Sihanouk,
leader of the three-party, anti-Vietnamese coalition that is
recognized by the U.N.
   Phieu disclosed that 30,000 Vietnamese died in border clashes in
1977-78 with the Khmer Rouge, who killed more than a million
Cambodians between 1975 and 1978. Phieu said an additional 25,000
Vietnamese troops were killed in Cambodia since Vietnam invaded in
1978.
   He said Hanoi's troops have been sustaining fewer casualties in
recent years, indicating that the guerrilla forces were becoming
weaker. The three-party coalition, backed and supplied by China, is
said by Western analysts to field about 50,000 fighters.
   The Khmer Rouge ``remain a force in Cambodia but are in decline
because they receive no support from the Kampuchean (Cambodian)
people,'' Phieu said.
   He said 13,000 troops have returned home so far this year,
leaving less than 100,000 in the country. All military advisers and
experts had also been pulled out, he said.
   Analysts attribute the withdrawal to crushing domestic economic
problems and pressure from Moscow, Hanoi's chief backer.
   At a departure ceremony, Cambodian Defense Minister Koy Buntha
pledged to strengthen his forces _ said to number about 35,000 _ to
replace the Vietnamese, whom he thanked at the airport for ``your
blood and sacrifice.''
   Hien and his party were presented with garlands by Cambodian
girls dressed in ancient dress as they boarded the aircraft at
Pochentong airport.
   More than 70 foreign journalists followed the departing command
on a separate airplane.
   On arrival in Vietnam, a band played while Hien, sweat rolling
down his face under a scorching sun, shook hands and accepted
flowers from youths dressed in white uniforms and red kerchiefs.
   Deputy Defense Minister Tran Van Quang saluted and embraced the
officers.
</TEXT>
