<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Teachers     06-30 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Teachers,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High School Educators End Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece's 45,000 high school teachers
returned to the classrooms Thursday, ending a five-week strike over
pay and working conditions and allowing senior students to begin
yearend examinations.
   The walkout ended after Education Minister George Papandreou
pledged a special wage supplement of $200 every three months for
work on extracurricular activities. He also promised the teachers
they will get a $112 book allowance.
   Fiercely competitive examinations for entrance to Greece's 17
state-run universities will start July 14, one month later than
scheduled.
   Papandreou, son of Socialist Premier Andreas Papandreou, managed
to end the strike after just seven days in office.
   ``I feel tremendously relieved, but a lot still has to be sorted
out,'' the 36-year-old sociologist told The Associated Press.
   Educators have staged intermittent work stoppages throughout the
school year.
   According to European Community statistics, Greek public school
educators are the lowest paid in Western Europe.
   A department head with over 30 years' teaching experience earns
each month the same amount as an Athens taxi driver takes home,
just over $600.
</TEXT>
