<HEAD>Jackson Says He Will Respond To Dukakis Veep Questionaire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Thursday he intends to respond
to a request from the campaign of Michael Dukakis for detailed
background information being sought from prospective running mates.
   Jackson, talking to reporters on the front lawn of his home
here, also said he and his wife, Jackie, accepted an invitation
from Dukakis and his wife, Kitty, to dine with the Democratic
nominee-to-be on Monday and attend at Fourth of July concert in
Boston.
   But Jackson refused to comment on whether he would use the visit
to disclose whether he wants to pursue the second spot on the
ticket.
   ``We are quite serious in our quest for consideration and our
request for information as to what are the standards ... the
guidelines,'' Jackson said.
   ``At this point, I will simply pursue the process and convey my
private conclusions to Gov. Dukakis'' later, he said.
   Ron Brown, a top Jackson campaign official in Washington, has
been holding talks with Paul Brountas, Dukakis' campaing chairman
who is coordinating the screening process for the Massachusetts
governor, Jackson said.
   ``There's no reason at this point not to substantially respond''
in person or in writing to requests for information, he said.
   ``It's not very difficult for us,'' Jackson said. ``I'm the only
one under consideration who has passed the same tests as Mike
Dukakis has passed.''
   Jackson said he had already been put under scrutiny by the
Federal Election Commission, the news media and the millions of
people who voted for him during the primary season.
   ``My basic request of Mr. Dukakis ... is to let me know what the
rules are,'' Jackson said. ``I know that tradition leaves out most
American people. Therefore, there must be a new tradition for fair
consideration.''
   Jackson also said he had meetings Thursday to discuss financing
for Keep Hope Alive, a political action committee he plans to
organize.
   He said the committee would ``continue to build a progressive
movement in our country'' by financing voter registration drives
and campaigns in key districts.
