<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica 1stld-writethru   06-30 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, 1st ld-writethru,a0793,0815</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Defy Regulations; Bomb Wounds 14</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-2 UPDATE with police finding body of man believed
bomber. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, The government ...; INSERTS 3 grafs
after 11th graf, Hospital officials ... giving details. Picks up
12th graf pvs, The New ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church leaders deliberately
violated the law Thursday, and a banned newspaper resumed
publication with a fierce attack on government policies. A bombing
in Johannesburg meanwhile wounded 14 people.
   The bomb exploded in a shopping arcade just after 1 p.m. Shortly
before midnight Thursday, police said they found the mutilated body
of a man believed to have been killed in a second explosion while
trying to set a bomb.
   The government published three bills Friday that would make
possible the first legal multiracial residential areas in South
Africa but also would tighten segregation elsewhere and increase
penalties for violating it. The bills will be debated in August.
   The Rev. Frank Chikane, secretary-general of the South African
Council of Churches said leaders of the 26 affiliated churches
``feel we are not obliged to obey apartheid laws _ unjust laws.''
   He and other leaders issued a statement urging Christians to
boycott the Oct. 26 municipal elections on grounds that
participation in structures that perpetuate apartheid is a sin. The
elections are segregated by race.
   Apartheid is the policy of race segregation that preserves power
and privilege for South Africa's 5 million whites and denies rights
and a voice in national affairs to the 26 million blacks.
   New regulations President P.W. Botha imposed June 10, in
extending the state of emergency for a third year, prohibit both
calls for election boycotts and publication of such ``subversive''
statements. About 20 local and foreign journalists covered the news
conference and many reported the statements.
   Violating the regulations carries a maximum penalty of 10 years
in prison or a fine of $8,600.
   ``Each one of the church leaders took into account the possible
implications of their action,'' said the Rev. Beyers Naude, a white
clergyman who is honorary vice president of the council of
churches. ``We felt very strongly we have no option but to be
obedient to the law of God.''
   At least 14 people _ 13 whites and one black _ were hurt by a
bomb that exploded outside a fast food restaurant in the arcade of
the Poyntons Building, which houses the air force and prison
service headquarters on upper floors.
   Hospital officials said none was hurt seriously. Two of the
injured whites were children.
   The sound of a second explosion at about 9:45 p.m. in the city's
Joubert Park area drew police, soldiers and ambulances, but no
damage was found.
   About two hours later, police said they found the mutilated body
of a man near the park's Johannesburg Art Gallery. They said they
believed he was killed by a bomb he was trying to set.
   No further information was immediately available.
   The New Nation newspaper, which Home Minister Stoffel Botha had
banned for three months as a threat to public safety, published a
front-page editorial Thursday saying: ``We are back. Back to
continue writing about the aspirations and desires of the voteless
majority.''
   New Nation, a 2-year-old paper published by the Southern African
Catholic Bishops Conference, has a circulation of 50,000 and is
aimed at the black community.
   It was suspended March 22 under the minister's nearly unlimited
emergency power to close newspapers or restrict their content, and
he is free to reimpose the ban.
   Signers of the statement opposing the elections included
Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu; leaders of Presbyterian,
Methodist, Baptist and Evangelical churches, and the Rev. Allan
Boesak, president of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches.
   ``We cannot participate in the elections and we call on all
Christians not to participate in the implementation of their own
oppression or the oppression of others'' by voting or by seeking
office, it said.
   ``These elections cannot be free and fair. ... Many of the
leaders of the people ... are in detention and the people's
organizations are banned.''
   It was the clearest act of civil disobedience by church leaders
since February, when several were arrested trying to march on
Parliament with a petition protesting the banning of 17 major
anti-apartheid groups.
   Clergymen said at the time they would try to fill the gap
created by the banning orders and subsequently have pledged direct,
non-violent action against apartheid laws and emergency regulations.
   The council of churches, which is holding a five-day national
conference this week at St. Barnabas College in Johannesburg,
represents all major Protestant denominations in South Africa
except the white branch of the Dutch Reformed Church, to which most
of the governing Afrikaners belong.
</TEXT>
