<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military prosecutor charged three
Slovenian journalists and an army officer with revealing military
secrets, it was reported Thursday.
   Janez Jansa and David Tasic, both columnists of the liberal
Mladina youth weekly, and Sgt. Maj. Ivan Borstner, were indicted
``for possessing and revealing a military secret,'' the official
Tanjug news agency said.
   All three have been in military custody since the end of May,
when a police search of their homes and offices uncovered photostat
copies of a classified military document allegedly dealing with the
Yugoslav army's command structure and the combat readiness of some
units.
   The same charges were filed against Mladina's outspoken chief
editor, Franci Zavrl, the agency said, but he has not been
detained. Tanjug cited a statement released by military prosecutor
Col. Zivko Mazic.
   Supporters of Jansa said Thursday he had started a hunger strike.
   ``Jansa started a hunger strike Wednesday that he said will last
until he is set free,'' Bojan Korsika, spokesman for an unofficial
human rights committee, told The Associated Press by telephone from
the city of Ljubljana.
   The arrests have sparked an unprecedented wave of public protest
in Slovenia, where at least 60,000 people have signed a petition
demanding the release of the three.
   About 400 church groups, unofficial forums, trade union
chapters, companies and Communist Party cells have donated money to
a special defense fund.
   Some 30,000 people recently attended a cultural gathering in
Ljubljana which featured a rock concert and speeches by prominent
Slovenian public figures.
   All three journalists have in the past sharply criticized the
Yugoslav army and former Defense Minister Branko Mamula, accusing
him of misappropriating public funds.
   Borstner was accused of having leaked the top-secret military
document to the journalists. The Tanjug statement said he cut off
the top part of the document, which contained the ``classified''
stamp before handing over the paper.
   Jansa and Tasic were arrested soon after Mladina published what
it said was proof the army was plotting to stage a coup in Slovenia
on behalf of conservatives in Yugoslavia's southern republics in
order to quell growing dissent.
   Although Slovenia's leadership has refuted the allegations, it
has demanded that the group be tried by civilian courts.
   Slovenia is the country's economically most developed region.
Its liberal, market-oriented communist leadership has been the
target for frequent attacks from party hardliners in the country's
southern republics, for allegedly not cracking down on
non-conformist tendencies.
   The date of the trial was not disclosed.
</TEXT>
