<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaf Caption Prank,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caption Prank Angers Deaf, Beauty Pageant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A TV station broadcast a closed-captioned
message promising deaf viewers, in vulgar terms, a glimpse of
breasts and buttocks at the Miss Wisconsin beauty pageant.
   WISC news director Tom Bier said the caption was mistakenly
aired after it was filed on the department's computer. The female
employee responsible was suspended for five days, said station
manager David Banks.
   ``There was no intention for this to get on the air. It
shouldn't have happened, but it did,'' Bier said. ``We do apologize
for it.''
   The offending phrase was broadcast Saturday. Deaf viewers, who
use decoders to receive captions on the screen, were told to expect
scenes from that day's pageant on the 10 p.m. news.
   ``To my knowledge we've only had one call about it today,'' Bier
said Thursday.
   Sue Captain, co-director of the Miss Wisconsin pageant, called
the message ``completely demeaning _ not only to the pageant, but
to the deaf community as well.''
   Bette Mentz-Powell, coordinator of interpreter services for the
state Office of the Hearing Impaired, said she was unaware of any
complaints.
   ``If I'd have been tuned in, I would have screamed. It is
offensive to all women,'' she said. ``It doesn't matter whether it
was broadcast'' over the closed-caption system or read aloud.
</TEXT>
