<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Agriculture     06-30 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Agriculture,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought May Cause Cut in Federal Programs that Discourage Farm
Production</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal programs that encourage farmers to
produce less and export more could be cut back because of the
drought gripping the Farm Belt, U.S. Agriculture Secretary Richard
E. Lyng said Thursday.
   ``I think we will continue to export crops,'' Lyng said. ``But
we may not be as aggressive as we have in the past because it looks
like we will have a reduction in surplus stocks.''
   Lyng told a meeting of producers, processors and retailers that
the Agriculture Department is working with Congress to devise a
drought-relief plan, adding that it was too early to tell how
damaging the drought will be.
   ``During July we'll look at the status of each crop to see if we
need to make changes in any government programs,'' Lyng said.
   Lyng said the department had begun several emergency programs to
help farmers and ranchers locate hay and forage for livestock.
   Several officials at the meeting predicted consumers would soon
be paying less at the meat counter because the drought, by drying
up pastures and driving up feed prices, has forced producers to
sell off cattle early and at reduced prices.
   ``Beef prices should be going down right now,'' said Dean
Kleckner, president of the American Farm Bureau. ``If the consumers
don't see lower prices in the supermarket within the next few
weeks, it's time to ask the store manager why not.''
</TEXT>
