<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 2343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bolivia-Drugs     06-30 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia-Drugs,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Strike To Protest Killing Of Six Coca Leaf Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 48-hour general strike called to
protest the killing of six coca leaf farmers shut down many
factories, mines, trains and domestic airline flights on Thursday.
   But in this capital city and other major towns, banks,
businesses, government offices and city transportion operated
normally.
   The strike began Thursday and was organized by the Workers
Central, which represents most of Bolivia's labor force.
   The labor federation also called on farmers to block roads and
suspend providing food supplies to the cities, but there were no
reports of roadblocks in the vicinity of La Paz or other major
cities.
   Workers Central said in a statement that it organized the strike
because ``we can no longer support the abuses, crimes and social
injustice committed by the government.''
   The statement criticized police for the deaths and demanded the
removal of U.S. military and Drug Enforcement Administration agents
operating in the Chapare, a tropical region to the east of La Paz
where Monday's confrontation took place.
   The six men were killed by Bolivian police gunfire Monday when
thousands of coca leaf farmers surged toward a police and DEA camp
trying to take it over. They were protesting U.S.-backed bills in
the Bolivian legislature that would outlaw most of the Chapare coca
plantations.
   At least 300,000 Bolivian farmers depend on coca leaf farming
and cocaine processing for their livelihood. Coca leaf is the raw
material for cocaine.
   The country's conservative government attributed the violence to
``cocaine traffickers and politicians who are trying to prevent the
approval of the law.'' The U.S. government is conditioning part of
its economic aid to passage of the measure, which would also impose
stiff penalities on traffickers.
   A joint session of Congress that was meeting this week to pass
the bill postponed consideration of the measure after Monday's
violence until a new session of congress convenes Aug. 6.
   Bolivia, an impoverished country of 6.7 million in the heart of
South America, produces an estimated one third of the cocaine that
reaches U.S. and European markets, the DEA says.
</TEXT>
