<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 2304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-StarWars-Test     06-30 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Star Wars-Test,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tiny `Star Wars' Rocket Tested Successfully</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a rare public demonstration of Star Wars
technology, Rocketdyne on Thursday tested what it calls the free
world's most efficient rocket engine, a 2-ounce thruster designed
for use on a missile-killer.
   The engine tested at a company laboratory in the hills above
suburban Simi Valley was designed for use as a ``divert thruster''
for a space-based interceptor in the proposed Strategic Defense
Initiative, Rocketdyne said.
   It would guide the interceptor, also known as a kinetic kill
vehicle, from its base on a satellite toward an incoming nuclear
missile, the company said in a statement. The KKV would then
destroy the incoming missile, Rocketdyne said.
   A KKV would destroy targets through force of impact and is
conceived as a non-nuclear device, the company said.
   Officials from the Air Force Space Division, Rocketdyne and its
parent company, Rockwell International, deemed the test successful.
   With a weight-to-thrust ratio of 1-to-1,200, the thruster is the
most efficient ``in the free world,'' Rocketdyne said.
   ``The engines we were running with around five years ago were
1-to-20,'' said Ernie Bunch, a Rocketdyne engineer in the
space-based interceptor, or SABIR, program.
   Officers from the Air Force Space division in El Segundo and
managers from Rockwell International watched the demonstration.
   Rocketdyne officials did not put a price on each engine but said
the company's contract to develop it was worth about $30 million.
   The engine was fired, or pulsed, for five milliseconds while
fixed on a stand and then was shut off for a tenth of a second.
This cycle was repeated dozens of times. The result sounded like
machine gun fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
