<2ND_LINE>AM-Professor Defector,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Professor Defects With Unwitting Help Of Nobel Prize Winner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban professor said Thursday he defected to the
United States on the pretext of visiting Nobel Prize-winning author
Gabriel Garcia Marquez.
   Antonio Ricardo Valle, a 32-year-old professor of
Marxist-Leninist studies at the University of Havana, revealed his
defection at a news conference here.
   He defected June 10 in the U.S. Embassy in Bogota, Colombia, and
was given permission from the State Department to fly to Miami last
weekend, he said.
   ``He didn't know, essentially, my political views,'' Valle said
of Garcia Marquez, who helped him obtain travel papers to Colombia.
``He didn't know I didn't conform to Castro's system.''
   Valle, who met Garcia Marquez at the home of a mutual friend in
Havana, said the 1982 Nobel laureate is a ``very close friend of
Castro's.''
   Garcia Marquez called two or three times a week to speak with
the leader of the communist nation and visited Valle on trips to
Cuba, the defector said.
   ``He encouraged me not to fear being critical,'' Valle said.
``But I would explain to him I had hundreds of pages hidden in my
home I knew would never be published because of political
censorship.''
