<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States' foreign debt burden climbed
to $368.2 billion in 1987, a sharp 36.8 percent rise over the
previous year, as the country lengthened its lead as the world's
largest debtor nation.
   The Commerce Department said the new debt total was $99 billion
higher than the $269.2 billion in debt to foreigners that the
United States owed at the end of 1986.
   The debt means that foreigners now own more in U.S. assets than
Americans own abroad. For 1987, the government reported that
foreign holdings in the United States increased to $1.54 trillion
from $1.34 trillion at the end of 1986. American investments
overseas totaled $1.17 trillion at the close of 1987, up from $1.07
trillion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
