<TEXT>
   A new age in environmental monitoring begins
Friday.
   It's the deadline under a 1986 law for 30,000 industrial
installations to file with federal and state authorities an
estimated 1.5 million pages reporting all their releases of 328
hazardous chemicals to the environment in 1987.
   The Environmental Protection Agency is supposed to put the
information into a data base that anyone with a personal computer
and a telephone modem can query. That system won't be up and
running until sometime next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a dramatic epilogue to
its just-concluded term, announced Thursday it will consider
banning capital punishment for all juvenile murderers after it
returns to the bench next fall.
   In formally wrapping up its 1987-88 term Wednesday, the court
came close to banning the death penalty for anyone who commits a
murder before they are 16.
   Just 24 hours later and without reconvening, the justices issued
written orders saying they will use cases from Georgia and Missouri
to reconsider the fate of young killers. The court said it will
decide sometime in 1989 whether use of the death penalty for anyone
under 18 when the crime was committed violates the Constitution's
ban on ``cruel and unusual punishment.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experimental radiation treatment nearly
stopped the progression of multiple sclerosis in some patients for
up to four years, longer than any other therapy yet tried, a study
says.
   While radiation is probably not the ultimate answer to multiple
sclerosis, researcher Stuart Cook said, ``right now, if I had
chronic progressive MS, I would be very interested in taking part
in a trial that was using this.''
   The study is described in the July issue of the journal
Neurology by Cook, chairman of the neuroscience department at the
University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey-New Jersey
Medical School, Raymond Troiano of the medical school, Corinne
Devereux of the Clara Maass Medical Center in Belleville, N.J., and
colleagues.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have determined the atomic
structure of Earth's most common protein, a feat experts say
eventually may help them increase food production and design new
drugs.
   Biochemist David Eisenberg spent 18 years determining the
three-dimensional arrangement of the 37,792 atoms in RuBisCO, a
protein that ultimately sustains life by making every plant grow.
   ``This is a very notable achievement,'' said Fred Hartman,
acting director of biology at Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A courtroom decision made by flipping a coin
often can be more accurate than one based on the judgment of
psychologists and psychiatrists, according to a study.
   David Faust, an associate professor of pscyhology at Brown
University, and Jay Ziskin, a California lawyer and psychologist,
said in a Science article for publication Friday that jurors or
other citizens can make psychological judgments as accurately as
the professionals, ``thus raising substantial doubt that
psychologists or psychiatrists meet legal standards for expertise.''
   Psychological experts often are used in criminal trials to
assess the mental health and the potential for violence of
defendants. In many states, the punishment phase of capital murder
trials takes into consideration a prediction of the continued
violent behavior of the defendant. Often the state calls on
psychologists or psychiatrists for opinions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A throng of cheering Cambodians
lined an airport road Thursday as Vietnam pulled its military
leaders out of Cambodia, loosening its grip on this long-suffering
country after nearly a decade of combat.
   Vietnam admitted for the first time that about 25,000 of its
troops have died since it invaded Cambodia in 1978 and toppled the
China-backed Khmer Rouge regime.
   On Thursday, it officially turned over control of its war
against anti-Vietnamese insurgents to Cambodian commanders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The withdrawal of Vietnamese forces
from Cambodia has conjured fears of a comeback by the dreaded Khmer
Rouge, one of the most brutal regimes of modern times.
   Although it has been nearly a decade since the Khmer Rouge were
toppled by the Vietnamese invasion, there is a fear in southeast
Asia of a reprise of their 1975-78 reign of terror in Cambodia.
According to some estimates, up to 3 million people died.
   ``One has to be either naive or an idiot to believe that the
Khmer Rouge in the '80s can be different from the Khmer Rouge of
the '70s,'' Prince Norodom Sihanouk, Cambodia's former leader, said
recently.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted sex offenders in Georgia and Washington will be
required to submit to AIDS tests under laws effective Friday, while
Colorado apparently is the first state to require such a test for
those charged but not yet convicted of sex offenses.
   Of dozens of new state laws taking effect July 1, many are
efforts to deal with acquired immune deficiency syndrome, a deadly
disease for which there is no cure and which is spread mainly
through sexual contact and the sharing of needles by drug abusers.
   Colorado's law would make test results available ``to any victim
of the sexual offense who requests such disclosure,'' but those
victims would face fines or jail terms if they disclosed the
information to unauthorized people.
