<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-PolishTVStar Adv01   06-30 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Polish TV Star, Adv 01,0776</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, July 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>CNN Anchor Surprised to Find Herself a Polish Star</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every night about midway through
``Panorama of the Day,'' one of Poland's most popular news
programs, a pert, blond American pops up on the screen and says, in
English, ``This is Headline News, I'm Bobbie Battista.''
   That one line has been enough to make the CNN anchor the
best-known American television personality in Poland, as she
learned as the official guest of Polish television recently.
   In Krakow, children clamored to find out the name of her
favorite rock star. In Czestochowa, monks lined up for her
autograph. And everywhere, her Polish fans wanted to know much
money an American anchor makes.
   Her celebrity status has both pleased and baffled the seven-year
CNN veteran. ``The viewers don't even see me that much every night
_ like for two minutes and I barely say anything,'' Battista said.
   Rarely, it seems, has the global network gotten so much for so
little.
   ``We're on in 60 countries at this point and we get letters from
all over the place, but nowhere has the impact been greater than in
Poland. ... I think it just goes with their fascination with
anything Western,'' she said.
   This April, CNN signed a deal with Poland under which its
broadcasts will be carried regularly on state-run television. Poles
privileged enough to own satellite dishes have been able to pick up
CNN in English for several years.
   Under the agreement, Polish television can use CNN's
international feed for domestic broadcast. The six-hour time
difference makes Battista's midday anchor shift in Atlanta an ideal
pickup for Panorama, which airs nightly at 9:30 p.m. in Warsaw.
   Each day, ``Panorama'' uses one CNN Headline News report, which
it intersperses with a similar report from the Soviet evening news
program, ``Vremya,'' in addition to clips from Polish TV.
   ``Above all, `Panorama' is able to present different points of
view of what is going on in the world. Even if the subjects are the
same, there is a different point of view,'' said Jozef Wegrzy, the
director of Polish television's second channel, which produces
``Panorama.''
   The international angle and the program's fast-paced formula
have earned it an average of 12 million viewers a night since it
went on the air just over a year ago.
   Polish TV tapes and translates the CNN report daily and has the
right to edit it. While still in Atlanta, Battista received a
couple of tapes of the program which the Poles had retranslated in
English and sent back to her.
   ``I was suprised a couple of times because I kind of looked at
the screen and thought, `That's not what I said.' So that's of some
concern. But for the most part, they're being pretty
straightforward with it,'' she said.
   On a recent visit, Battista the journalist became Battista the
CNN diplomat. She taped a talk show with Daniel Passent, editor of
the weekly Polityka and the show ``Closer to Your World,'' a
round-table discussion program that includes foreign journalists.
   It was a new role for a woman used to asking the questions, and
one that precluded her from making a pilgrimage to Gdansk to
interview Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, one person most first-time
journalists to Poland try to see.
   Despite her success as a television personality, Battista
appeared eager to get back on the other side of the camera.
   No doubt her Polish fans were eager as well. While she has been
visiting, ``Panorama'' was obliged to air its CNN segments without
her.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   FINALLY! MUGS GO NATIONWIDE _ NBC, which operates a popular and
lucrative souvenir store in Rockefeller Center in New York, is
planning to retail such memorabilia as ``Late Night'' T-shirts and
``Today'' show coffee mugs nationwide through its newly established
marketing branch, Peacock Enterprises. NBC began testing the idea
in April with an NBC store at Union Station in Indianapolis. NBC
also plans to make movable kiosks available to affiliates for
promotional use in places like shopping malls. ...
   NBC NEWS NUGGETS _ NBC is launching a service for daytime
viewers _ 30-second on-the-hour headlines from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m.
EDT. NBC News President Lawrence K. Grossman promised affiliates
meeting in Hawaii that the news nuggets, to begin in August, will
``serve to promote your own news image as the round-the-clock
source of news in your communities.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, July 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv01   06-30 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 01 ,0621</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday July 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Worriers: Remember This</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the economic news scares you, accompanied as
it usually is with ominous commentary from the ``experts,'' you
might consider the undistinquished record of worry over recent
months.
   You can pick your time period, but this one begins last October,
when those who claim to know told you the stock market crash would
scare business and consumers into retrenchment.
   Neither retrenched, they barely flinched. Business actually
added more to its spending plans for better production facilities.
Consumer spending slowed, but not by much. Whatever, it was
destined to slow anyway.
   Meanwhile, the stock market has recovered about $400 million of
the trillion dollars lost in the crash.
   The anticipated recession didn't come. Those who claim to know
still say it is coming. Someday they'll be correct, of course,
because recessions eventually come. But the ``imminent''
descriptive is out. Wait 'til next year.
   The market crash, the recession to come and inflation and the
big budget and trade deficits and all those other bad things would
cause the dollar to free-fall and cause foreign investors to flee,
the experts warned. It didn't happen.
   Neither did the budget deficit continue to grow to the heavens.
It slowed, and now it appears the deficit next year might decline
to 2.9 percent of gross national product, down from 3.3 percent
this year.
   The trade balance didn't continue to worsen; it improved. The
savings rate didn't continue to decline; it has risen since last
fall. The consumer debt position hasn't continued to rise in a
straight line; the rate of growth has turned down.
   You may recall that the level of factory utilization was rising
into very dangerous territory, according to some warnings, because
with little idle capacity available there would be production
snafus and higher prices. ``Dangerous territory'' became a summer
meadow.
   Rising employment would mean fewer workers available to operate
the nation's factories. That, said the people who know, would mean
upward pressure on wages. But recent wage agreements have been
below the inflation rate.
   Lots of the old problems are still there, and most likely they
will remain a threat for a long time to come. And there is a big
new one _ the drought, which is likely to force up prices of some
commodities.
   But now the popular economic analysis is one that shows
differences instead of similarities between the crash of 1987 and
the stock market debacle of 1929 that ushered in the Great
Depression of the 1930s.
   A typical one: Commodity prices plunged after the 1929 crash but
rose after the 1987 crash. Industrial production fell steeply in
1929 but rose in 1987. Employment fell in 1929 but rose in 1987.
Business spending fell in 1929 but rose in 1987. Federal Reserve
policy tightened in 1929 but became looser in 1987.
   The people who claim to know are quieter now. They are less
inclined to extrapolate into infinity the latest negative change in
prices or interest rates. Besides, they have fewer listeners.
   Given time, there will be new things to worry about because that
is the way it has always been. Oddly, a period of good economic
news is a fertile field for the growing of fears.
   But now we know that some of the fears are fiction, and that _
given the great volume of them that are presented to us by the
folks who claim to know _ relatively few of them come to pass.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Fri July 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
