<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0611EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-LifeAbroad-Argentina Adv07   06-30 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Life Abroad-Argentina, Adv 07,0837</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, July 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: Argentina _ Everybody Loves Alfajors</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTof a series of periodic reports by
Associated Press correspondents on people, places and things in
other countries. The spelling of Havanna inE _ This is one  the 9th graf
and later
is CORRECT.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAR DEL PLATA, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The French have croissants, the
English their kidney pie and Italians their ice cream. Argentines
have their alfajors.
   Alfajors simply are cookie sandwiches, usally filled with a
caramel-like spread called dulce de leche and covered with white or
dark chocolate.
   They're equally popular with grownups and children.
   ``Delicious, veI never get tired of
them,'' Trassens said, fingering an inch-thick alfajor.
   Alfajors remain almost exclusively Argentine because of the
popularity of dulce de leche, a widely used substance that is made
by boiling down milk and adding sugar. Dulce de leche is used on
everything from ice cream to pancakes, toast, cakes and pies.
   ``Nobody in the world consumes dulce de leche like the
Argentines,'' said Abel Ayala, deputy director of the business,
industry and production union.
   Trassens first began making his alfajors by using his
great-grandfather's cookie recipe and dulce de leche in 1946 at his
cafe in Azul, a farm community not far from Mar del Plata. Two
years later, he moved to Mar del Plata.
   Now the nation's sixth largest city with 475,000 residents, Mar
del Plata makes alfajors for everyone, except for those who buy
them from a small factory in nearby Uruguay. Much of Mar del
Plata's alfajors are bought by the 2 million or so vacationers who
come every year for the beaches and casinos.
   Trassens said investors from the United States and Brazil have
tried to woo him to begin production in their countries of his
brand of alfajors, which sell for about 20 cents each _ less by the
dozen.
   Trassens said he is considering expansion, noting in particular
the rising numbers of Hispanics in the United States who might have
heard of the alfajor. But he added special problems might arise
with the dulce de leche, which goes dry in about three weeks.
   Virtually all alfajors are eaten within two weeks or so in
Argentina and they contain no preservatives, which Trassens said
would be required to manufacture them in the United States.
   Packaging _ most are sold in aluminum wrappers _ would have to
change too, he said.
   In Argentina, industry statistics indicate that about 300
businesses make alfajors, from round-the-corner sweetshops to
Havanna, which began four decades ago when a Greek cafe owner _
``who probably couldn't spell Cuba's capital,'' Morales said in
reference to the company's name _ offered them to customers.
   Outside Mar del Plata, Terrabusi and Bagley of Buenos Aires are
major sellers of alfajors, while smaller, drier-style fruit
alfajors are made in large quantities in the interior cities of
Cordoba and Santa Fe.
   Others use variations that contain mint, marmalade, coconut, rum
or nuts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, July 7</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
