<DOCNO> AP880630-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0613EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv01   06-30 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 01,0606</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, July 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commission of the Seventh-day Adventist
Church wants more time to study whether to allow ordination of
women as full ``ministers of the Gospel.''
   Neal Wilson, denominational president, told the 80-member
commission that ``fairness requires that this issue be given
priority treatment, and it must not go on forever.''
   The denonations's annual council is to consider the issue in
late 1989, with recommendations about it to go to a 1990 general
conference.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calling abortion the ``No. 1 social and moral
issue of our day,'' the Southern Baptist Home Missions Board is
encouraging churches to start crisis pregnancy centers, says board
President Larry Lewis.
   The board has named Sylvia Boothe, a former foreign missionary,
as the agency's first coordinator for abortion alternatives. She
has directed a crisis pregnancy center in Oklahoma City for the
past two years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TUPELO, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Family Association says CBS
should apologize to the public and fire those responsible for
showing Mighty Mouse sniffing what appeared to be cocaine on a
Saturday morning cartoon.
   The Rev. Donald E. Wildmon, AFA executive director, said that in
the episode, Mighty Mouse feels dejected until he draws a handful
of powder from under his cloak, inhaling it, and afterward is back
to normal.
   Wildmon says the intent seemed to be to ``show that cocaine
helps one overcome feeling `down'.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proliferating Holocaust memorials about the Nazi
decimation of Jews tend to ``distort or erase the past under the
guise of memorializing it,'' says Dennis B. Klein.
   Klein, director of the International Center for Holocaust
Studies of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, says ``any
reconstruction of the past mediates if not erases history'' because
``memory is selective.''
   The Holocaust particuarly ``lends itself to historical
revision'' because it is so repellent, he says. He says all the
memorials being constructed to it ``often serve as evasions of the
real issues.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Federation of Priests'
Councils says priestly celibacy should be optional and restoration
to the priesthood should be sought for resigned, married priests.
   At its annual convention here, the federation also said the
permanent diaconate, a step just short of priesthood, should be
open to women.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Disney can build fantasy parks
glorifying a make-believe mouse, Melvin Wilcox says Christians
should be able to re-create Jerusalem in West Texas to tell the
good news of Jesus Christ.
   Wilcox of West Palm Beach, Fla., has formed ``Jerusalem 30 A.D.
International Ministries,'' and wants to raise $2.5 billion to
build the project on 25,000 acres of arid land 60 miles south of
Midland.
   He says the Texas ``holy city'' will be a place of reflection
and learning, will employ 10,000 people, allow no cars and that
employes and visitors will wear biblical-era garb.
   He says it will feature a seminary, museums, art galleries, a
Roman theater, a sports arena with chariot racing, marketplaces,
palaces and medical facilities.
   Midland Mayor Carroll Thomas has some doubts about the plan,
saying, ``I don't think it's economically viable at all or
realistic. It's got some romance to it and I think people are
latching on to that.''
   Wilcox says skeptics will prove wrong. ``As for doubting
Thomases, they laughed at Walt Disney when he came up with Snow
White and the Seven Dwarfs.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, July 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0614EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a p AM-AmbassadorBush Adv05   06-30 0997</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ambassador Bush, Adv 05,1021</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, July 5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Snapshot '88</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush's Ambassadorship to China, United Nations Provided Resume
Rarity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One in a series of occasional mini-profiles of the White
House hopefuls.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henry Kissinger was shocked. George Bush had
been a loyal soldier as chairman of the Republican National
Committee in the aftermath of Watergate, and now in late 1974
President Ford was offering a choice of glittering rewards: London
or Paris.
   No thanks, Bush said. How about the ambassadorship to China?
   ``When Henry heard I'd turned down the ambassador's posts in
London and Paris in order to go to Beijing, he was baffled,'' Bush
wrote in his memoirs. ``There'll be some substantive work from time
to time,'' Bush remembered Kissinger as saying, ``but for the most
part you'll be bored beyond belief.''
   Kissinger may have been right. According to Bush and several
people who worked with him those 13 months, the U.S. Liaison
Mission in Beijing was set up in the early 1970s to exist, not to
do anything in particular.
   Kissinger himself handled the tricky diplomacy. There were few
bilateral cultural, military or economic ties and there wasn't much
of a social whirl _ not at a time when Chinese leaders were still
wary of the West. Bush's predecessor, David Bruce, rarely left the
U.S. compound.
   Boring or not, the time Bush spent in Beijing and as U.S.
representative to the United Nations from 1971 to 1973 gave him
something rare on a presidential resume: service as an ambassador.
Only former President William Howard Taft came close with service
as governor general of the Philippines.
   Bush, now set to become the Republican presidential nominee,
became a member of the diplomatic set in 1970 after he lost a
Senate race in Texas to Democrat Lloyd Bentsen. The consolation
prize was an appointment to the United Nations by President Nixon,
who took a lot of heat for putting a diplomatic rookie like Bush in
the prestigious post.
   The major controversy during Bush's tenure was the fight over
Chinese membership in the world body.
   Kissinger and Nixon, eager to foster good relations with China
without appearing to abandon longstanding allies in Taiwan, favored
``dual representation'' that would permit both Chinas to stay.
   Bush lobbied for dual representation, but on Oct. 25, 1971, the
proposal was defeated by the U.N. General Assembly and Taiwan was
expelled.
   Bush said later that when he left the United Nations in January
1973 to head the Republican National Committee he was more critical
of the world body than he had been before, having seen its ``flaws
and limitations first hand.''
   In September 1974, Bush, his wife Barbara, and their newly
acquired cocker spaniel, C. Fred Bush, headed for Beijing where
they spent the next year and a month living in a walled compound
guarded by green-uniformed soldiers of the People's Liberation Army.
   ``The PLA guards were really there to keep an eye on us and to
make sure no Chinese people could get in to talk to us,'' a member
of Bush's Beijing staff said in a recent interview. The diplomat,
who still works in the U.S. government, spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   ``I remember one time a U.S. ambassador to another country came
to visit and the guards wouldn't let the ambassador's wife into the
compound because she was Asian _ they wouldn't believe she wasn't a
Chinese citizen,'' the diplomat said.
   ``Bush found out about it and went crazy. He called up the
foreign ministry and demanded an apology. I think if he had an
AK-47 he would have gone down there and shot up the ministry. It
was the only time I saw him lose his temper.''
   According to the diplomat and others who worked on Bush's staff,
including John Holdridge, the deputy chief of mission, there was
little contact between American diplomats in Beijng and the Chinese
government.
   For one thing, it was not until the Carter administration that
full diplomatic relations were exchanged. And in the waning days of
Mao Tse-tung, Chinese officials cautious about the succession were
not eager to stick their necks out and become friendly with any
Western diplomats, much less Americans.
   ``We were very much isolated,'' said Holdridge, who later became
ambassador to Indonesia. ``We tried to keep busy, to make contacts
and to carry on diplomacy, but there was very little interraction
with the Chinese.''
   ``It was tough duty,'' said Peter Bergin, a member of the
mission staff. ``There really wasn't very much to do.''
   By all accounts, Bush spent much of the time improving his
already-good tennis skills. He played on courts at Beijing's
International Club with other diplomats and a ``club pro'' provided
by the Chinese government.
   The envoy and his wife also spent hours cycling through the
dusty and windy streets of Beijing, drawing stares from Chinese
citizens unaccustomed to Westerners. The sight of Bush's dog was
also a novelty in a country where canine was as common on a menu as
on a leash.
   ``Bush used the time very wisely, in a political sense.'' the
diplomat who spoke privately said. ``In those days, it was nearly
impossible to get a visa to visit China, but you could get around
it by getting an invitation from the head of the liaison office.
   ``Bush used it like a political plum and there was a steady
stream of important visitors from the States. It was his way of
keeping his hand in U.S. politics.''
   Bush wrote that one of the highlights of his tour was a meeting
with Mao, who lived in seclusion and died the next year.
   ``I am going to heaven soon,'' Bush quoted Mao as saying. ``I
have already received an invitation from God.''
   Bush soon got an invitation too. Ford asked him to run the
Central Intelligence Agency and his diplomatic career was over.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, July 5</NOTE>
