<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 2356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:RomeroMovie Adv07   06-30 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Romero Movie, Adv 07,0792</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, July 7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Life of Slain Salvadoran Archbishop Being Filmed in Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CUERNAVACA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Ellwood E. Kieser, producer
of the movie ``Romero,'' believes he is telling the tale of a 20th
century hero.
   ``I'm not doing a political tract; I'm not preaching a sermon,''
Kieser said in a recent interview on the set.
   But he clearly sees the story of assassinated Archbishop Oscar
Arnulfo Romero of El Salvador as an audience-grabber with
impressive moral overtones.
   ``I feel he is for the latter part of the 20th century what
Mahatma Gandhi was for the first part,'' Kieser said.
   The movie, starring Raul Julia in the title role and an almost
completely Hispanic cast, may well be the first commercial feature
by a Roman Catholic order. Its budget is in the $2 million range.
   Kieser's company, Paulist Pictures, is associated with the
Paulist Fathers. He produced their television program, ``Insight,''
for 23 years until it was discontinued in 1983.
   Last year, he produced the television movie, ``We Are the
Children,'' starring Ted Danson and Ally Sheedy, about the famine
in Africa.
   ``Our whole thing is to combine entertainment with audience
enrichment,'' he said.
   Although he prefers to be called Bud, greetings of ``Hello,
Father,'' can be heard as he moves about the set. He also has
learned enough Spanish to be able to say Mass for anyone involved
in the production who wants to attend.
   To Kieser, Romero was a mouse transformed into a tiger, a
withdrawn intellectual who gathered courage in response to the
horrors around him until he was silenced by an assassin.
   ``I have the chance to tell the story of Oscar Romero to a
couple of hundred million people,'' the producer said.
   Julia, however, believes the archbishop's courage always was
there.
   ``His change came about as he realized the circumstances _
outside of his world of editing, writing and studying,'' the actor
said in an interview in his trailer.
   Julia groped for the right words to explain Romero's emergence
as a vocal human rights advocate as the situation deteriorated in
El Salvador and emerged in a full-scale war that still persists
between leftist rebels and the U.S.-supported government.
   ``He started seeing that other reality,'' Julia said, costumed
in priestly garb. ``But I think he always was a committed man, a
religious man, an honest man.''
   Julia also insisted that the movie is not a political one but
rather ``a movie about people.''
   Yet the film's script quotes extensively from Romero's homilies
as the violence escalates before the outset of the war in late 1979
and as the rightist death squads that claimed thousands of victims
take their toll.
   Salvadorans jammed the unfinished metropolitan cathedral to hear
Romero conclude his homily each Sunday with his report on the
week's grim events. Loudspeakers were set up outside so the
overflow crowd could hear and, as the movie dramatizes, the sermons
also were broadcast nationally.
   ``When you hear the words of a man telling you to kill, remember
instead the words of God,'' Romero said the day before his
assassination. ``No soldier is obliged to obey an order contrary to
the law of God.
   ``I beseech you, I beg you _ I order you: Stop the repression.''
   A lone gunman killed the archbishop as he said Mass at the
Divine Providence Chapel in San Salvador on March 24, 1980.
Although no one has ever been arrested, it is widely believed to
have been ordered by the death squads.
   ``He was an ordinary person who brought forth his courage,''
said Julia, who has listened to many of the archbishop's sermons
and even his tape-recorded musings.
   John Duigan, making his first movie outside his native
Australia, is directing. The script is by John Sacret Young, who is
involved in the critically praised TV series, ``China Beach.''
   Unlike previous movies about Central America such as ``Under
Fire'' and Oliver Stone's ``Salvador,'' ``Romero'' does not dwell
on an American venturing into the region but instead concentrates
on the native situation.
   ``The story just didn't call for an American,'' Sacret Young
said. ``None of them were major enough. Our choice was, not to
leave them out, but to tell it the way Romero might have thought
about it.''
   He also describes the archbishop in heroic terms.
   ``If you told it as fiction, it would be unbelievable,'' the
writer said. ``Eventually, in that crucible, he changed, so he was
not following events, he was leading events.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, July 7</NOTE>
