<1ST_LINE>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv09-10   06-30 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 09-10,0727</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<HEAD>Advance for Weekend Editions, July 9-10, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cavalier Goes Through Major Changes</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   My, how things have changed. The Chevrolet
Cavalier _ a hum-drum compact first introduced in the 1982 model
year as an import fighter _ has been transformed into a latter-day
muscle car in a new-for-1988 model, the Cavalier Z24.
   Listen to the rumble of the 2.8-liter, fuel-injected V6. Feel
the power as the Goodyear Eagle GT + 4 tires grab the road. Hear
them squeal as the car races ahead.
   Hunker into the comfortable, somewhat sporty seats. And get
ready for a fine ride in a reasonably priced car _ $13,209 out the
door for the test car.
   Chevrolet first tried out the sporty Z24 concept on the Cavalier
two years ago. But it's only in the 1988 model year that the
General Motors Corp. division has started to hit the mark.
   The 1988 Cavalier Z24 Coupe is a nice mix of sport styling _
including air dam on the front and rocker extensions _ and old-time
American car performance. The V6, coupled with a five-speed manual
transmission in the test car, was responsive.
   However, the transmission could feel a bit notchy. It was easy
to drive the car hard, feel the responsiveness, but those quick
starts took a toll on fuel economy.
   The suspension _ firm but still offering a nice ride _ was
commendable.
   Exterior and interior fit and finish was excellent. Seats were
comfortable, though not fitted with all the gadgets, such as
adjustable lumbar support, that are found in some other sporty cars.
   The dashboard was easy to read with traditional gauges, though
an electronic instrument cluster is available. A light came on to
tell the driver when to shift _ slightly annoying until you get
used to it.
   Interior leg room was fine in the front but could be miniscule
in the rear if the front seats were moved all the way back.
   The rear deck lid was a bit heavy, but was designed so that
anyone hoisting items into the trunk would not have to lift them
over the car body _ just ease them over the bumper. Inside, the
trunk was flat and spacious.
   Chevrolet reports that sales of the Z24 have been going well.
The division had a 50-day supply in early May compared with a
70-day supply a year earlier, and a second shift at one of the Z24
plants has been requested in anticipation of additional demand.
   Chevrolet said competitors include the Ford Mustang, which has a
GT versions with eight-cylinder engine and base price of around
$13,000, and the Toyota Celica ST, which starts around $12,000.
   Besides the base-priced $10,725 Cavalier Z24 _ also offered in a
$15,990 convertible _ the Cavalier line includes a two-door value
leader with a base price of $6,995, a sedan at $8,195, a four-door
station wagon at $8,490, and a four-door RS sedan with a base price
of $9,385.
   Typical Cavalier buyers are 25 to 34 years of age with
elementary school-aged children, Chevrolet said, adding that a
growing number of buyers are young couples and singles under 30.
   Most buyers have high school educations, and occupations are
typically blue collar. Household income is in the $25,000 to
$50,000 range, with a high concentration around $35,000, the
division said.
   Top sales for the Cavalier line came in the 1986 model year,
with 388,722 sold. In 1987, sales dipped to 295,316, but the new
Z24 should help the 1988 model year tally.
   Consumer Reports said the 1985 and 1986 Cavalier V6 cars ranked
worse than average and much worse than average, respectively, in
their report from owners about trouble spots.
   Both models suffered from suspension problems, but the 1988 Z24
has a new suspension system. The 1986 Cavalier V6 also was faulted
for engine problems, but the V6 in the Z24 has been redesigned,
Chevrolet spokesman Ed Lechtzin said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, July 09-10</NOTE>
