<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Guyana-Socialism Adv10-2Takes   06-30 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Guyana-Socialism, Adv 10-2 Takes,0769</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Socialist Guyana Courts Private Investors to Spur Development</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An accompanying item is BC-Guyana-Glance, b0700.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERNAN TURNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Socialist Guyana has changed course
dramatically and declared a moratorium on nationalizations while
opening doors to private business and foreign investment.
   ``It's a matter of life or death, a very obvious move that
should have been made years ago,'' Anglican Bishop Randolph George,
an outspoken critic of the government, said in an interview at his
wooden, Victorian residence.
   ``We've come full circle,'' agreed George C. Fung-On, executive
secretary of the Georgetown Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
   President Desmond Hoyte wants the world's investors to know that
Guyana, on South America's northeastern bulge, recognizes it needs
private capital to stimulate what his planners call a ``quantum
leap'' in economic growth.
   Hoyte, victor in government-controlled elections in December,
1985, has dropped much of the nationalist and socialist rhetoric of
President Forbes Burnham, the leader of the People's National
Congress government from 1964 until his death on Aug. 6, 1985.
   Hoyte told Canadian businessmen last year Guyana's
nationalization of private enterprise was ``a chapter in our
history which we now consider closed.'' After that, he told
potential investors in Miami, Fla., ``There is business to be done
in Guyana now and Guyana is willing to do business.''
   He carried the appeal to London this past May.
   Hotels are jammed with Canadian and U.S. miners, Brazilian and
Texas oilmen, Japanese traders and assorted entrepreneurs checking
out the investment opening.
   Already, Canadian gold mining companies and U.S. oil companies
have signed exploration agreements.
   ``There are some indicators of a great deal of foreign
interest,'' said Raymond Ackloo, manager of the National Bank of
Industry and Commerce, which was the Royal Bank of Canada before it
was nationalized.
   But Ackloo, in an interview, predicted ``a considerable lag time
before one sees any real impact'' on the economy.
   Hoyte's speeches acknowledge that Guyana must overcome its
reputation under Burnham as ``a bad investment risk.''
   Guyana is South America's only English-speaking country and as a
former British colony has close ties to the nearby Caribbean
island-nations. Its 780,000 people occupy an 83,000-square-mile
area, about the size of Idaho.
   Hoyte is negotiating an agreement with the United
Nations-affliated International Monetary Fund (IMF) in Washington
to help Guyana resume payments on its crushing foreign debt and to
free foreign aid suspended because of the arrears.
   The foreign debt exceeds $1.3 billion, or some $2,000 for each
man, woman and child in a country where the minimum wage is the
equivalent of $2.50 a day.
   The IMF suspended aid in 1985, the World Bank in 1986. Others
dropping direct aid include the United States, Britain and the
Caribbean Development Bank. The United States donated $4.4 million
worth of wheat and $3.2 million in soybeans and dairy products in
1987.
   In an interview, Prime Minister Hamilton Green rejected the
notion that Guyana is replacing socialism with private enterprise.
   The 1980 Constitution, which establishes a cooperative republic
``in transition from capitalism to socialism,'' recognizes a
tri-sector economy: public, private and cooperative.
   ``It is our view that at this stage the private sector can play
a more dynamic role,'' Green said.
   He said nationalization had strengthened the public sector.
   ``We have passed that stage. We're marching on, and we make no
apologies for what we did in the past,'' he said.
   The country's foreign exchange reserve is practically depleted,
probably the equivalent of less than $10 million.
   Economic growth is stagnant, although sugar and bauxite, which
bring in more than 80 percent of foreign exchange, are expected to
earn a small profit this year. Bauxite is the source for aluminum.
   Inflation estimates range from 37 to 50 percent. Unemployment
and underemployment are 25 to 35 percent.
   Workers earning the minimum wage 25 Guyana dollars a day ($2.50
at the official exchange rate but only 83 U.S. cents on the black
market), face prices of 10 Guyana dollars a day for transportation,
25 for a pound of chicken, 17.50 for beef, 1.70 for a single egg,
2.50 for a pint of milk, 10 dollars for the gallon measurement of
rice used here and 3.50 for a pound of wheat.
   Fuel supplies are sporadic _ bauxite is traded for petroleum
from neighboring Venezuela _ and housewives wait in line all day
for a can of cookstove kerosene.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Guyana-Socialism Adv10-1stadd   06-30 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Guyana-Socialism, Adv 10-1st add,0559</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 10 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>GEORGETOWN: cookstove kerosene.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The country is rich in potential exports such as lumber and wood
products, shrimp and precious metals. Diamonds, gold, and even
prawns are smuggled abroad and sold for U.S. dollars that then feed
a thirsty black market.
   Economists believe the black market is what keeps Guyana alive,
accounting for 80 percent of the country's business activity, a
parallel market not reflected by official statistics and a safety
valve that makes consumer goods available to the people.
   One U.S. dollar buys 30 Guyanese dollars on the street.
   Stores and sidewalks are jammed with contraband, everything from
toothpaste to 15-speed, off-road bicycles. This is in sharp
contrast to life under Burnham, whose insistence on self
sufficiency went to the extremes of banning the sale of wheat flour
and bread, to encourage the use of flour made from rice, which is
locally grown.
   The government now looks the other way, even allowing government
stores and the Defense Department to buy smuggled goods.
   The investment opening has not been accompanied by political
reform.
   Bishop George and other government critics say that if free and
open Parliament elections were held today, the now-governing
People's National Congress party would be forced to share power
with a coalition.
   ``There is no democratic opening; there is an opening to
investment ... especially to foreign investment,'' said Eusi
Kwayana, a member of Parliament and founder of the mixed-race,
left-of-center Working People's Alliance.
   Kwayana said the Patriotic Coalition for Democracy, formed after
the 1985 elections by five opposition parties, has unsuccessfully
demanded that the government ``democraticize'' the country. The
coalition declared the 1985 national elections fraudulent and
boycotted municipal elections in 1986.
   Cheddi Jagan, a former prime minister and now minority leader in
Parliament of the Marxist People's Progressive Party, a coalition
member, said in an interview Hoyte's program is making living
conditions worse for the people. He maintained that public protests
would bring repression and ``the death of democracy.''
   ``Burnham died and Hoyte is now moving backwards, back to the
position where he and Burnham put us in 1978, back with the IMF,''
Jagan added in an interview.
   Race plays an important role in determining political party
affiliation. Hoyte's party is supported by urban Afro-Guyanese, 43
percent of the population. Jagan's party base is among the the
mostly rural East Indians, 51 percent of the population.
Indo-Guyanese merchants dominate the country's commercial life.
   Michael McCormack, executive secretary of the Guyana Human
Rights Association, said in an interview Burnham-style political
violence and surveillance of opponents have disappeared.
   ``I can't think in the last couple years of any act of political
violence,'' McCormack said. ``That's a plus under Hoyte.''
   The association advocates free and fair elections.
   The government has tolerated the establishment of a privately
owned, secular newspaper, the Stabroek News, often critical of
Hoyte's administration.
   Prime Minister Green described relations with the United States
as ``good,'' and a recent U.S. embassy report on Guyana reflects
U.S. pleasure with economic developments, but added that ``while
the business climate has been buoyed by the government declarations
... investors are still wary and want others to test the waters
before they jump in themselves.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
