<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Poland-Aftermath Adv10-2Takes   06-30 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Poland-Aftermath, Adv 10-2 Takes,0765</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>In Aftermath of Strikes, Polish Government Seeks to Set Things
Right</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Gorbachev scheduled to visit sometime between July 10-20, 3rd
graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the aftermath of labor unrest this past
spring, the government is moving to hasten economic reform,
increase supplies of consumer goods and legalize some independent
groups in hopes of heading off more outbursts.
   But some opposition quarters doubt the government will succeed
and that more strikes are inevitable.
   An unknown factor, however, is Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the
reformist Soviet leader who is scheduled to visit Poland sometime
soon.
   Five strikes in Poland from April 25 to May 10, and brief
stoppages or strike threats in 25 more workplaces, constituted the
worst labor unrest in the country since the 1981 martial-law
crackdown on the Solidarity independent trade union.
   The spring strikers demanded the legalization of Solidarity and
wage increases to counter price increases of 45 percent so far this
year.
   The rising prices are part of the government's multifaceted
program to reform the moribund economy.
   The program calls for introducing market equilibrium through
higher prices, encouraging private and managerial enterprise and
reducing central economic controls _ all similar to what Gorbachev
is attempting in the Soviet Union.
   ``The recent events produced an impulse to think deeper and move
faster,'' said one senior Communist Party activist, speaking only
on condition of anonymity. ``There is no way back. The only way is
forward and forward with much bigger steps.''
   The Polish leader, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, emphasized the need
for quick improvements in production in an unusual, eight-hour
meeting June 5 with the directors of the country's 41 largest
enterprises.
   Jerzy Malkowski, spokesman for the economic reform program, said
the government plans to introduce some steps ahead of schedule.
Long-awaited laws on setting up private businesses and easing
limits on foreign investment were approved by the government
shortly after the strikes and are expected to be enacted by the
Sejm (parliament).
   In one of the first uses of new special economic powers, the
government cut off tax benefits for companies that increase exports
at the expense of supplies for the domestic market, Malkowski said.
   On the political front, the government has signaled that it will
grant legal status to several independent groups, including the
Economic Society whose aim is to promote and aid private
businesses, a Warsaw political discussion club and the dormant
Polish chapter of the PEN writers' club.
   But authorities remain firmly opposed to legalizing Solidarity,
an issue that many in the opposition regard as the litmus test of
officials' sincerity in reaching an accord.
   The Communist Party activist said legalizing Solidarity would
lead to an escalation of pay demands in the factories, which he
maintained Poland cannot afford in its current economic condition.
When the economy improves, he argued, authorities can then think of
allowing union pluralism.
   The answer does not satisfy Solidarity activists.
   ``The basic question at the moment is whether, on the part of
the authorities, there is political willingness for deep changes in
the system,'' said Bronislaw Geremek, a historian and leading
adviser to Solidarity. ``Poland at the moment needs a spectacular
change so that it could create a psychological shock.''
   Otherwise, he added, ``there is no possibility of launching
political and economic changes.''
   Legalizing groups like PEN would have been signs ``of
extraordinary political significance'' a year ago, before the
strikes, said Geremek. But now they are ``too little, too late''
because they are addressed to a limited circle of intellectuals and
do not try to answer worker frustrations, he said.
   Malkowski acknowledges that the average Pole has seen very few
benefits of the economic reform program so far and contends that is
hindering public support.
   ``Obviously one does not convince people by rhetoric and words,
but by facts. This is why I say this year the problem is that we
have too few facts.''
   The situation should be better next year when, he said, people
will see the effects of a freer marketplace and greater competition
and supplies.
   ``Now we have the paradoxical situation in which an item is more
expensive and not available,'' he added. ``I think this is one of
the more significant factors arousing social frustration. As long
as the warehouses and stores do not get filled with goods, society
will question the sense of price increases.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880630-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Poland-Aftermath Adv10-1stadd   06-30 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Poland-Aftermath, Adv 10-1st add,0589</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WARSAW: price increases.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   But Halina Bortnowska, a Roman Catholic intellectual and
journalist, expressed deep skepticism about economic reforms in the
absence of any popular control of the program.
   ``There is something in the system that does not tolerate real
public control, and without this control, how can we change the
economy?'' she said. ``We are expected to pay (in higher prices and
austerity), and where are the guarantees that this will not be
wasted again?''
   Malkowski argued the system contains checks against economic
abuses by authorities. He mentioned the Constitutional Tribunal, to
which citizens can appeal, and a much freer and critical press
compared to previous decades.
   ``I can accept the criticism that it is not all that you or I
could imagine in central Europe, but it is due to the reform to a
large extent.''
   He added that authorities planned to move further ``in the
direction of democratic changes.''
   Geremek said he is convinced ``that if an essential change in
the way of exercising power by the Communists does not take place,
the situation will become more and more inflamed, less and less
stable.''
   ``Any kind of normalization of Poland's place in Europe without
such a change is impossible. I think this a problem for the Poles,
it is a problem for Gorbachev and a problem for Europe.''
   Geremek said he sees Gorbachev's visit as a key to Poland's
future.
   ``The April-May events in Poland have apparently created a
certain curve in Poland's evolution,'' he said. ``In the next few
weeks it should be determined what the direction of Poland's policy
will be. ...
   ``One may assume that (during Gorbachev's visit) certain key
decisions for future evolution will be made,'' Geremek said. ``It
will either be a new policy or a new team.''
   A Catholic journalist also closely linked to Solidarity said he
too sensed a new mood since the strikes.
   ``There has been a political change once again,'' said Krzysztof
Sliwinski. ``The mood of martial law is finished right now.
Something new is going on.''
   But he added that he doubted the country's leaders were ready to
take the big step of offering power to its opponents.
   ``They are deadly anxious about sharing power because they don't
believe in it. ... They think that if they share power, they will
lose it.''
   He maintained Polish society is demanding a greater say in its
affairs, comparing it to the American Revolution slogan: ``No
taxation without representation.''
   Another thing that has changed is the people's attitude toward
the Soviets, he said.
   ``Active people in Poland have abandoned totally their
anti-Soviet mood. Rather they are in a mood not to make too much of
a problem for Gorbachev.''
   Several statements from officials have indicated the government
is interested in increasing dialogue, perhaps along the lines of an
``anti-crisis pact'' in which both sides would unite behind a
program for the economy.
   The government spokesman, Jerzy Urban, has spoken of creating
new ``institutional'' forums for dialogue.
   He has proposed a price-wage commission on which consumers and
workers would be represented, and a ``round table'' of
representatives of associations, including groups not yet
officially registered.
   But young workers interviewed at the Ursus tractor factory
outside Warsaw say they put little stock in the government moves
and are expecting another round of strikes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
