<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's chief economic forecasting
gauge dipped slightly in May, the first setback since January, but
analysts shrugged off the tiny downturn as no threat to prospects
for the rest of the year.
   The Commerce Department reported a 0.1 percent decline last
month in the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, primarily
reflecting weakness in the stock market, manufacturing orders and
the labor market. At the same time, the department on Wednesday
revised upward, from 0.2 percent to 0.5 percent, the gain it had
initially reported for April.
   Economists dismissed the decline, saying growth would continue
at least through the remainder of 1988 with no danger of recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has
asked the Swiss government for help in investigating an alleged $19
million insider trading scheme.
   SEC Chairman David S. Ruder told the Senate Banking Committee's
securities subcommittee Wednesday that his investigators have
learned that Hong Kong businessman Fred C. Lee traded some U.S.
securities from Switzerland.
   Ruder said the SEC is seeking information from Swiss
authorities, and trying to get a freeze on assets held there by
Lee, who allegedly used insider information garnered by a junior
analyst at Morgan Stanley & Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Labor Committee has approved
compromise legislation to raise the federal minimum wage to $4.55
per hour over the next three years.
   Floor action on the bill is not expected until after the
Democratic National Convention, which occurs the week of July 18.
   Republicans are expected to offer amendments that would cap the
increase at $4 an hour, provide a training wage and exempt all
small firms from the wage requirement. The current minimum wage is
$3.35.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has ruled that non-union
workers may withhold financial support from unions representing
them in collective bargaining if some of that money is used for
activities not directly related to the negotiations.
   The high court also issued a key civil rights ruling allowing
employees to use statistical evidence to prove their bosses are
guilty of illegal discrimination.
   The union ruling could deprive many unions of significant
portions of their revenue, while the civil rights decision will
impact numerous lawsuits filed by women and members of racial
minorities who say they have been treated unfairly.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency has
unveiled massive new draft regulations aimed at upgrading
protection of 2.5 million farm workers from pesticides.
   The agency said Wednesday it was unable to estimate how many
worker poisonings would be avoided as a result, because no one
knows how many are occuring now.
   Farmers using hired labor, chemical manufacturers and others
will have to spend an estimated $170 million to comply in the first
year the regulations are effective, and smaller sums after that,
said Louis True, head of program management and support in EPA's
pesticide program.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co. has threatened to abandon
its hostile $1.4 billion bid for Irving Bank Corp. unless it
receives a favorable court ruling within two days or reaches an
amicable settlement with Irving.
   Bank of New York stated Wednesday that it submitted a written
request to the New York State Supreme Court for a ruling by Friday
on the validity of Irving's anti-takeover ``poison pill'' and
numerous other pending legal issues.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady denied the bank was
issuing an ultimatum. Bank of New York's deadline for conditional
merger approval from the Federal Reserve Board expires on July 9.
</TEXT>
