<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-30 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unleaded Gas Rises, Rest Of Market Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracts for unleaded gasoline are continuing
to rise, over speculation that demand will grow as many motorists
prepare to spend part of the long Fourth of July weekend on the
road.
   Other futures contracts posted losses in active trading
Wednesday on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   On the New York Merc, the July contract for unleaded gasoline
rose 1.09 cents to 52.62 cents a gallon. Some longer-term contracts
were lower.
   Among other refined products traded on the exchange, the July
contract for home heating oil slipped 0.79 cent to 41.52 cents a
gallon.
   ``This is the peak season for gasoline,'' said Peter Beutel, an
oil analyst with Elders Futures Inc.
   Beutel said a recent American Petroleum Institute report showed
demand for gasoline was at its highest point in about 10 years.
   The report said an average 8.53 million barrels of gasoline were
transferred from refineries to distributors each day for the week
ending June 24. That surpassed the previous highest level of 8.48
million barrels in July 1978.
   ``Because prices have been so low lately, a lot of people are
driving more,'' Beutel said.
   The API report also showed stocks of gasoline were down 7
percent from a year ago, and that helped send gas prices higher
Wednesday, Beutel said.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude oil, fell 35 cents to $15.43 per barrel.
   ``Most people still perceive an oversupply of crude oil,''
Beutel said.
</TEXT>
