<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-IBMMoves     06-30 0825</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IBM Moves,0851</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM To Consolidate Operations In $600 Million Cost-Cutting Move</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major consolidation by International Business
Machines Corp. is expected to lead to the resignations or early
retirements of 3,000 to 4,000 employees, the giant computer maker
says.
   The $600 million consolidation by the world's biggest computer
company is intended to ``further reduce costs, provide for future
growth and speed new products to customers,'' IBM announced
Wednesday.
   ``This is a major, major restructuring,'' Terry Lautenbach, IBM
senior vice president and general manager of IBM United States,
said in an interview.
   In its last big move to cut costs, IBM offered incentives that
resulted in the early retirement of 13,000 employees in the United
States and 2,000 outside the United States in 1986 and 1987.
   IBM said it would cut 1,600 jobs in Boca Raton, Fla., the
birthplace of the original Personal Computer, by eliminating
manufacturing there, and 2,800 jobs in Tucson, Ariz., where it will
phase out manufacturing of data storage products.
   IBM also will close two plants of Rolm Systems that manufacture
telecommunications equipment, moving work from the Santa Clara,
Calif., operation to a nearby San Jose plant and from the Austin,
Texas, site to IBM's nearby main Austin site.
   Jobs will be added in other places such as IBM's Research
Triangle Park near Raleigh, N.C., which will take over the
manufacturing of Personal System-2 computers from Boca Raton.
   IBM will offer jobs to all employees displaced by plant
closings. But in an apparent effort to cut employment, it will
offer two years' salary and a $25,000 bonus to any employees in the
Boca Raton and Tucson sites who choose to resign or retire.
   Lautenbach characterized the payments as a form of assistance to
people who chose to leave, rather than as an incentive to get them
to leave.
   IBM also intends to try to cut its headquarters staff in
Westchester County, N.Y., and elsewhere by offering eligible
employees four weeks' salary for every year of service as
separation bonuses.
   The cuts will result in a charge of $600 million against pre-tax
earnings in the second quarter, IBM said. However, the impact on
first-half earnings largely will be offset by an accounting change
related to treatment of deferred income taxes.
   IBM's stock closed unchanged at $127 a share in consolidated New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   Lautenbach said improvements in manufacturing technology left
the company with more plants than it needed. He said the closings
had nothing to do with slow growth, saying, ``Our business is
growing satisfactorily.''
   IBM said the key elements of the moves, expected to be completed
by the end of 1989, were as follows:
   _Personal System-2 manufacturing in Boca Raton, Fla., will move
to IBM's Research Triangle Park plant near Raleigh, N.C., where
much Personal System-2 manufacturing already takes place. All other
operations related to the Personal System-2 in Boca Raton will
remain there.
   _Manufacturing operations at the Tucson storage products plant
will be phased out and the work moved to IBM plants in San Jose,
Charlotte, N.C.; and Poughkeepsie, N.Y. The Tucson development
laboratory will continue its operations there.
   _Rolm Systems telecommunications manufacturing in Santa Clara,
Calif., will be moved to IBM's nearby San Jose facility. Rolm
Systems manufacturing and development in Austin will be
consolidated with IBM's main Austin site.
   _IBM plants in Charlotte and Austin will take over some of the
assembly work now done in Toronto. Also, an IBM laboratory in
Toronto will get more programming development responsibility.
Manufacturing of memory cards and power systems will continue in
Toronto.
   _A plant in the New York City borough of Brooklyn will diagnose
and process electronic components, work formerly done in locations
across the country. Brooklyn's assembly operations will be
consolidated in Poughkeepsie.
   IBM plans to turn its Tucson manufacturing plant into an
industrial park that would attract high-technology companies to the
area.
   Alberta Charney, an economics and business research specialist
with the University of Arizona, said the job cuts probably would
have a ripple effect resulting in a total loss of 7,000 jobs in the
Tucson area over the long run.
   Ms. Charney estimated the payroll of the 2,800 affected
employees would be close to a $100 million income loss to Pima
County.
   In Boca Raton, IBM will remain the area's largest employer,
spokeswoman Marti Easterbrook said. She noted employment at the end
of 1989 still will be 30 percent higher than it was in 1980, before
the company tooled up for production of personal computers.
   The Boca Raton area ``cannot lose these type of jobs without
feeling it,'' said M.J. ``Mike'' Arts, executive vice president of
the Greater Boca Raton Chamber of Commerce.
   But he said, ``It will be a benefit to us since it will be a
talented labor pool in the area. I suspect many of them will stay
here and this may help us in attracting employers who need these
workers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
