<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 0847EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TeamstersSuit     06-30 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters Suit,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Behind the Feds' Lawsuit Against the Teamsters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Teamsters-related prosecutions show
that union officials made a ``devil's pact'' with the Mafia, the
government says in a 105-page memorandum in support of its lawsuit
to oust the union's leadership.
   ``Since approximately 1970,'' said the memo, ``the government
has successfully prosecuted well over 300 persons associated with
the Teamsters for Teamsters-related crimes.''
   The memo accompanied the government lawsuit filed Tuesday
seeking a court order placing restraints on the 18-member General
Executive Board of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters.
   The document is crammed with details of ``a recent series of
successful criminal and civil prosecutions'' that show the Mafia
has gained control over the Teamsters.
   The government's court papers noted that ``four of the last five
Teamsters presidents have faced federal felony charges'' and three
were convicted: David Beck for embezzlement; James ``Jimmy'' Hoffa
for obstructing justice and mail fraud and Roy Williams for trying
to bribe a U.S. senator.
   Among 26 alleged mob figures named as defendants in the lawsuit,
25 have been convicted of Teamsters-related crimes such as
extortion through threats of union problems, embezzlement of union
funds and illegal labor payoffs.
   From 1970 until now the Teamsters' executive board ``has rarely
taken disciplinary action against, or even investigated, corrupt
Teamsters officials or subordinate entities,'' the government said.
   The memorandum of law that claimed the union's leadership ``has
made a devil's pact with La Cosa Nostra.''
   Prosecutors noted that Maurice Schurr, a vice president and
member of the executive board, ``was recently convicted of
receiving illegal labor payments from Teamsters employers.''
   U.S. District Judge David Edelsten issued a temporary court
order that bars the board from making large expenditures of union
funds or destroying union records. The order also banned the 25
previously convicted mob defendants from participating in union
affairs.
   When he announced the lawsuit, U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani
quoted what the late Robert F. Kennedy and the President's
Commission on Organized Crime had to say about the Teamsters.
   The report of the President's Commission, said Giuliani,
described the Teamsters ``as the union `Most Controlled' by
organized crime.''
   Giuliani also quoted at length from ``The Enemy Within,'' Robert
Kennedy's 1960 book about a Senate probe into ``the sordid
dishonesty'' of organized crime's infiltration of the Teamsters.
   ``He was ridiculed. He was vilified. He was hated irrationally _
but he was right,'' Giuliani said of Kennedy.
   The Teamsters' executive board, which is holding its quarterly
meeting in Montreal, sharply criticized the government's lawsuit as
``a vicious antilabor attack'' and said allegations of ties to
organized crime were ``pure myth.''
   In another development Wednesday, a Canadian board member denied
any connection between the 91,500-member Canadian branch of the
Teamsters and the Mafia.
   Edward Lawson, 59, of Vancouver, a member of Canada's appointed
federal Senate, said the U.S. lawsuit ``links every honest Canadian
Teamster with a bunch of gangsters we know nothing about.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
