<1ST_LINE>u f PM-InsiderTrading 1stLd-Writethru   06-30 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insider Trading, 1st Ld-Writethru,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Expanding Probe To Switzerland in Latest Insider Trading
Inquiry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new grafs 13-14 to add info on Hong Kong firm
cooperating in case, picks up 13th graf pvs, Ruder and Lynch...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's latest major insider trading
case is just one of many it is investigating that involve
foreign-based transactions, officials of the Securities and
Exchange Commission say.
   The $19 million insider trading case that became public this
week has expanded to Switzerland, SEC Chairman David S. Ruder told
Congress on Wednesday. Ruder said authorities have learned that
Fred C. Lee, the Hong Kong trader accused in the case, traded some
U.S. securities from the European country.
   ``We're now seeking information from Swiss authorities, and
trying to get a freeze on assets he has there,'' Ruder told
reporters during a break in the hearing by the Senate Banking
Committee's securities subcommittee.
   Gary Lynch, the SEC's enforcement chief, told the lawmakers that
the Lee case is one of 40 or 50 investigations under way in which
foreign trading is involved. He said at least one of the
investigations involves ``very large dollar amounts,'' and that
others range down to as little as $40,000 to $50,000 or less.
   Ruder declined to say what the value of Lee's Swiss trades or
assets might be. But Lynch said the trades Lee made from the
European country were part of the $19 million Lee allegedly earned
by trading on inside information.
   The SEC has accused Stephen Wang Jr., 24, a securities analyst
for Morgan Stanley & Co., of providing Lee with privileged
information on at least 25 corporate takeovers that Morgan Stanley
handled. The agency says Lee made at least $19 million using the
information and gave $200,000 to Wang.
   Lee, 38, is based in Hong Kong, but also has a home in the
Washington suburb of McLean, Va. Lynch said Lee, a native of
Taiwan, has claimed Canadian citizenship with at least one
brokerage firm he used.
   The SEC is seeking $76 million from the two men, which would
cover a repayment of the money they made, plus triple damages. That
reward is surpassed by only the $100 million the SEC recovered when
insider trader Ivan F. Boesky settled with the agency in November
1986.
   Wang's attorney, Ira L. Sorkin, has declined to comment on the
accusations other than to say he is studying them.
   Lee's lawyer, Michael Perlis, said in a telephone interview
Wednesday from his San Francisco office that Lee intended to resist
the SEC's accusations but likely would remain outside this country.
   Asked about press reports quoting Perlis as indicating he might
attempt to settle the accusations for far less than the amount the
SEC is requesting from his client, Perlis said, ``That's just
speculation.''
   But he also said, ``Every case can be settled and should be
settled on terms agreeable to all parties.''
   SEC officials have said Lee did some of the allegedly illicit
trading through a Hong Kong investment management company,
Federated International Investment Management (FE) Ltd., a
subsidiary of Aetna Life and Casualty.
   In Hong Kong today, Federated's managing director, Nigel Lester,
confirmed Lee was an ex-client and the company has been cooperating
with SEC officials. He said no allegations of wrongdoing have been
raised against Federated employees, but declined to discuss details
of the SEC investigation.
   Ruder and Lynch, along with State Department legal adviser Mary
V. Mochary, appeared before the subcommittee to testify in favor of
legislation that would give the SEC more powers to conduct
securities investigations in this country at the request of foreign
countries.
   Currently, the SEC can only force the presentation of evidence
if there are indications that U.S. law has been broken. Sponsors,
including Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., chairman of the
subcommittee, hope that if that power is expanded, other nations
will cooperate when U.S. authorities need records from overseas.
   Similar legislation was introduced Wednesday in the House by
Reps. John Dingell, D-Mich., Edward Markey, D-Mass., Norman Lent,
R-N.Y., and Matthew Rinaldo, R-N.J.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
