<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Economy     06-30 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Economy,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Improves Its Economic Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community raised
its 1988 economic forecast Thursday, predicting the economies of
its 12-member nations would grow an average 2.6 percent instead of
falling into recession.
   The EEC Commission, the group's policy-making board, had
predicted negative growth following last October's collapse of
financial markets.
   Growth is expected to slow in 1989 to 2.3 percent due largely to
an anticipated slowdown in the EEC's most dynamic economies _
Spain, Italy, Portugal and Britain. Growth in the eight other
member states would likely stablize at an average 2 percent, the
EEC Commission said.
   The commission said levels of employment would continue
increasing by about 0.8 percent annually. But it said total
unemployment levels were expected to remain high throughout the
trading bloc at 11.3 percent in 1988 and 11.1 percent in 1989.
   The Commission also predicted a 1988 inflation level of ``just
over 3 percent.'' It forecast that only Greece would have a high
inflation rate of about 15 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
