<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     06-30 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0320</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices gained ground today with a boost
from declining interest rates as the markets reached the midpoint
of 1988.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 3.02 to 2,125.00 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 639 up, 289
down and 467 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 42.64 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Nearly half of that total came in a handful of high-yielding
utility stocks which were involved in trading strategies based on
their impending dividend payments.
   Otherwise, analysts said investors drew some encouragement from
a drop in bond-market interest rates.
   West German authorities raised some of their key interest rates
today, following a similar move in Britain earlier in the week.
   But investors in the U.S markets took the news in stride,
apparently concluding that the Federal Reserve would not
necessarily feel compelled to tighten credit in this country.
   Brokers were expecting the pace of activity to start slowing
today as the long July 4 holiday weekend approaches.
   National Semiconductor fell 1{ to 12~. Analysts noted
disappointment among investors over the size of the quarterly
earnings gain reported by the company after the market closed on
Wednesday.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.18 to 153.31. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .05 at 307.20.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average finished with an
8.89 loss at 2,121.98.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 577 up, 900 down and 493 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 159.59 million shares, against 152.37 million in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
