<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Germany-Rates     06-30 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Rates,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bundesbank Raises Discount Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's central bank
raised a key interest rate Thursday in a move to shore up the weak
mark and curb inflation.
   The Deutsche Bundesbank increased its discount rate _ the
interest it charges on loans to member banks _ by one-half of a
percentage point to 3 percent.
   The central bank also said it would raise its rate on securities
repurchase agreements to 3.75 percent from 3.5 percent Friday.
However, it left unchanged at 4.5 percent the less-important
Lombard rate, which is the interest charged on loans to other banks
when securities are used as collateral.
   In a statement, the Bundesbank said its 17-member governing
council decided to hike the key rates largely to support the
weakening West German mark. West German officials fear that a soft
mark will spur inflationary pressures and damage progress made in
reversing trade imbalances between the United States and its major
trading partners.
   The boost in West German rates had been widely expected by the
financial markets, mostly because of the recent surge in the
dollar. Foreign exchange dealers said the announcement had little
impact on the dollar since it already had been discounted by the
market.
   Following West Germany's move Thursday was the Austrian National
Bank, Austria's central bank, which raised its discount rate to 3.5
percent from 3 percent and also left its Lombard rate unchanged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
