<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-30 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
sharply higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reversing a
steep, two-day decline as rains ended in the Midwest and drought
fears regained the upper hand in the marketplace.
   ``It's a new day, a new beginning,'' said Joel Karlin, an
analyst with Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Wednesday's dramatic losses were pegged to unexpected showers
that brought relief to parched fields in the upper Midwest. But the
National Weather Service's 30-day outlook, issued Wednesday after
the close of trading, quashed any ideas that the drought had been
broken.
   ``They're calling for almost no rainfall from Illinois east to
Ohio and higher-than-normal temperatures in Iowa, Illinois and
Missouri, the three biggest soybean states,'' Karlin said.
   ``We really need above-normal rainfall in July,'' a critical
month for corn and soybean development, he said.
   The long Independence Day weekend is expected to be warm and
mostly dry in the Farm Belt, which added to today's bullish mood,
Karlin said.
   In early trading, wheat was 10 cents to 15 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.63{ a bushel; corn was 6} cents
to 13 cents higher with July at $3.22 a bushel; oats were 6\ cents
to 27 cents higher with July at $3.62 a bushel; soybeans were 6
cents to 34 cents higher with July at $9.65 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .47 cent lower to .85 cent higher with August
at 64.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .95 cent
lower with August at 74 cents a pound; hogs were .23 cent to .90
cent higher with July at 46.27 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .30 cent to 1.25 cents higher with July at 37.50 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mixed on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
