<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ContinentalPlea     06-30 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Plea,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Bank Officials Agree to Plead Guilty: U.S. Attorney</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former officer at Continental Illinois National
Bank and Trust Co. and a former Oklahoma banker accused of
contributing to Continental's near-collapse have agreed to plead
guilty to criminal charges, a prosecutor said today.
   A plea agreement between prosecutors and attorneys for the pair,
John Lytle and William Patterson, was to be entered at 1:30 p.m.
today in federal court, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph Duffy.
   ``I can't give any details other than what I've given already,''
Duffy said this morning, adding that the pleas were to be entered
before U.S. District Judge Milton Shadur.
   Lytle, a former vice president who once headed Continental's oil
and gas lending operation in Oklahoma, was accused of buying
millions of dollars in poor-quality loans between 1980 and 1982
from the failed Penn Square Bank of Oklahoma City in return for
alleged kickbacks.
   Patterson, former head of energy lending at Penn Square, was
accused of arranging the kickbacks, in the form of unsecured
personal loans to Lytle.
   Penn Square failed in 1982 and Continental nearly failed in 1984
before a massive federal bailout.
   Lytle and Patterson were indicted on charges of wire fraud and
misapplication of bank funds, and went to trial in March. But after
seven weeks, the proceeding ended May 3 when the jury became
deadlocked and Shadur declared a mistrial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
