<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     06-30 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower In Europe After Rate Hikes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was narrowly lower in Europe Thurdsay
despite a concerted round of interest rate hikes in several
European countries and continued intervention by the Deutsche
Bundesbank. Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said Thursday's actions appeared to have placed a
near-term cap on the dollar at about 1.8250 West German marks.
   Trading was thin, which exaggerated price movements. Dealers
said that because Thursday was the final day of the first half of
the year, many market players had already closed their books.
   The dollar attracted strong buying interest in early trading and
rose despite interest rate hikes in West Germany, Switzerland,
Austria, Belgium and the Netherlands. The increases had been
expected and were already discounted, dealers said.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7085 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7060 late
Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8170 West German marks, down from
1.8290; 1.5060 Swiss francs, down from 1.5155; 6.1250 French
francs, down from 6.1635; 2.0530 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0545;
1,350.38 Italian lire, down from 1,350.75; and 1.2126 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2173.
   In earlier Tokyo trading, the dollar fell 0.20 yen to a closing
132.20 yen. Later, in London, it rose to 133.40 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $436.40 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's late bid of $433.30. In Zurich, gold
closed at a bid $436.50, compared with $433.50 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 86 cents to close at a bid
$439.18.
   Silver bullion prices were unchanged on the London market where
the metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.66 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
