<DOCNO> AP880630-0323 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1503EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-InsiderTrading     06-30 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insider Trading,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Firm Says It Is Cooperating With Insider Trading Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local investment-management company said
Thursday it was cooperating with U.S. officials investigating an
ex-client accused of involvement in a massive insider trading
scheme in the United States.
   The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has accused
Taiwanese businessman Fred C. Lee of making $19 million by trading
on tips about impending corporate takeovers given by a junior
analyst on Wall Street.
   Nigel Lester, managing director of Hong Kong-based Federated
International Investment Management (FE) Ltd., said Lee recently
was a client and confirmed that the SEC has interviewed company
employees in the investigation.
   ``The company is cooperating'' with the SEC, said Lester, who
stressed that no allegations have been raised against Federated
International employees.
   SEC officials in Washington said Wednesday that Lee did much of
his allegedly illicit trading through a Federated account. Lester
declined to discuss details of the SEC investigation but said the
company was ``pleased with the way (the talks) are going.''
   Wall Street and SEC sources in the United States have described
Lee, 38, as a wealthy member of a Taiwanese family who had several
trading and bank accounts, interests in real estate, import-export
operations and public utilities. He has homes in Hong Kong and
McLean, Va., a Washington suburb.
   The SEC interviewed Lee in this British colony last Friday but
his whereabouts have been unclear since. ``We can't find Mr. Lee at
the moment. We have no idea where he is,'' Lester said.
   Lester declined to say when Lee became a client. He added,
however, that his company first became aware of the Taiwanese
businessman in 1985, when Lee was briefly general manager of the
newly formed Kuang Hwa Securities Investment and Trust Co. in
Taiwan.
   Federated International, a subsidiary of U.S.-based Aetna Life
and Casualty, has a 10 percent share in Kuang Hwa, said Lester.
   In Taiwan, Kuang Hwa manager Cheng Ming-yuan said Lee resigned
from the company in December 1985 and left for the United States.
Cheng said Lee had helped Kuang Hwa with licence applications and
other start-up work.
   Meanwhile, a leading official of state-run Taiwan Power Co. said
Lee holds shares in the utility worth about $1 million.
   Lee, who is identified as Lee Chuan-hong in Taiwan, is now on
the power company's board and holds about 380,000 shares, according
to a company official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Taiwan Power Co. has about 859 million shares, 94 percent of
which are owned by the government.
   Newspapers in Taiwan have reported that Lee was a major investor
in the local stock market, has high-level political contacts and is
a devout Buddhist.
   The SEC has accused Stephen Wang Jr., 24, a securities analyst
for Morgan Stanley & Co. in the United States, of providing Lee
with privileged information on at least 25 corporate takeovers that
Morgan Stanley handled. The agency says Lee made at least $19
million using the information and gave $200,000 to Wang.
   Lee's attorney, Michael Perlis, has said his client intends to
resist the accusations but has no plans to travel to the United
States. Wang's attorney, Ira L. Sorkin, has declined to comment
thus far on his client's plans.
  
</TEXT>
