<HEAD>London Shares Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed higher Thursday in slack
trading on the London Stock Exchange as the second quarter came to
an end.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 2.5
points, or 0.1 percent, higher at 1,857.6.
   The index opened 1.8 points higher and then rose as much as 8.9
points in the late morning before drifting aimlessly lower during
the afternoon.
   Volume was a modest 464.5 million shares, up from Wednesday's
378.0 million.
   The end of the second quarter and the approaching end of the
two-week trading account on Friday brought only very slight buying
and selling, dealers said.
   The exchange divides trading into two-week and three-week
periods for accounting purposes.
   ``A lot of funds are tidying up their books and are not willing
to take new positions,'' said John Sellen, a salesman at Chase
Manhattan Securities in London.
   London equities also dipped after Wall Street failed to provide
any trading stimulus, traders said.
   One London analyst said the market would likely continue to
drift until the Bank of England pushes the commercial banks' base
lending rate up another half percentage point to 10 percent, as the
market widely expects.
   ``July and August are traditionally slow months and until we
have our half-point rise out of the way, no one will put any new
money into this market,'' he said.
   The central bank triggered a half-point increase in the
benchmark lending rate on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
