<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Scotus-Business     06-30 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Business,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Apparently Removes Last Legal Obstacle to Agent Orange
Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Thursday apparently
removed the last legal obstacle to a $180 million settlement
between Vietnam veterans and manufacturers of the herbicide Agent
Orange.
   The court also agreed to consider lawyer advertisements and
alleged race discrimination in Alaskan canneries, let stand a
damages ruling against a major defense contractor, and rejected a
product liability case against an automaker.
   Without commenting on the Agent Orange case, the justices let
stand rulings that dismissed lawsuits by about 300 veterans who
challenged the settlement, in which some 120,000 others are
expected to participate.
   The lawsuit filed by the 300 was dismissed when a federal judge
ruled that the Agent Orange manufacturers were immune from being
sued over the alleged health effects of the herbicide.
   The chemical companies sued over making Agent Orange were
Monsanto, Dow, Uniroyal, Hercules, T.H. Agriculture and Nutrition,
Diamond Shamrock and Thompson.
   The ensuing appeals from that ruling had been pending before the
nation's highest court for months, held until a key decision about
government contractors' legal liability.
   Three days ago, the court ruled that government contractors
cannot be sued over government-approved design defects unless the
contractors failed to notify the government about hazards they knew
about.
   The 300 veterans involved in the cases opted out of a ``class
action'' lawsuit that in 1984 ended in a $180 million settlement.
   James Sparrow, director of Vietnam Veterans Agent Orange Victims
Inc. of Stamford, Conn., said, ``It's a major victory for us. This
means that a 10-year battle has ended today and money will be going
out immediately to families of deceased veterans and veterans who
are 100 percent disabled.''
   Agent Orange was sprayed over Southeast Asia during the 1960s by
the U.S. military, which hoped to deprive communist troops of crops
and cover.
   The herbicide contains the highly toxic dioxin, and veterans
contend that exposure to the defoliant causes cancer, miscarriages
by their wives and birth defects in their children.
   In other action, the court:
   _Let stand a ruling that forced defense contractor Grumman
Aerospace Corp. to pay damages for an on-duty accident involving a
Navy pilot in 1979.
   _Allowed California officials to bar airlines from monitoring
phone calls between their ticket reservation agents and customers.
   _Rejected the appeal of a Minnesota woman severely injured in a
1983 car crash, turning away arguments that her car's manufacturer,
Toyota Motor Corp. and its U.S. subsidiaries, negligently failed to
install airbags.
   _Let stand the way cable television operators pay copyright
royalties for retransmitting broadcast programming.
   _Agreed to decide whether states may ban virtually all lawyer
advertisements featuring testimonials or client endorsements.
   _Refused to become involved in a California dispute over the
power of cities to charge fees to companies that operate oil
pipelines under city streets. The court let stand a ruling that
Santa Monica, Calif., may charge Shell Oil Co. $237,000 a year to
carry crude oil through of underground pipeline within the city.
   _Agreed to study alleged race discrimination in Alaskan salmon
canneries in an appeal by canners Wards Cove Packing Co. Inc. of
Seattle, Wash., and Castle & Cooke Inc. of Astoria, Ore.
</TEXT>
