<HEAD>South Florida Leaders Worried About Eastern's Viability</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: AmeriFirst in 3rd graf is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Florida civic leaders placed full-page
newspaper advertisements calling for a truce in Eastern Airlines'
labor wars after executives of the carrier told them the company's
finances were worsening.
   Eastern, the area's largest private employer, has lost almost $1
billion in the past decade. Federal negotiators are helping mediate
secret contract talks between Eastern and its Machinists union,
which has rejected the company's call for deep pay and benefit cuts.
   AmeriFirst Bank Chairman Thomas Bomar said ads were placed in
The Miami Herald and Miami News on Wednesday in response to Eastern
executives telling business leaders that the company's finances
were slipping.
   ``It is making a lot of us very nervous,'' Bomar said.
   The ads in part read, ``Now is the time to bring disputes at the
bargaining table to a prompt and certain resolution for all,
preferably by forging a fair agreement that will allow Eastern to
become a stable and prosperous company.''
   The businessmen who signed the ad included Knight-Ridder Inc.
Chairman Alvah Chapman Jr., Burger King founder James McLamore,
Southeast Banking Corp. Chairman Charles Zwick and the Greater
Miami Chamber of Commerce.
   Besides seeking cuts from its Machinists union, Eastern is
asking its Air Line Pilots Association to accept a contract that
would save the carrier $65 million.
   Eastern welcomed the ad.
   ``We agree with the tone of the ad,'' said Eastern spokeswoman
Karen Ceremsak.
   But Machinsts local officials were annoyed by it.
   ``We are doing all we can in negotiations to get one (contract).
Of course, we are not going to cave in to their terrible demands,''
said Frank Ortis, vice president of the Machinists local.
