<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Associates-MSA,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Associates Still Wants To Buy MSA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computer Associates International Inc., the
giant software company, still wants to buy Atlanta-based Management
Science America Inc., its president said Thursday.
   ``We generally like to complete what we start,'' said Anthony
Wang, president of Computer Associates, the Garden City, N.Y.-based
company that has grown into the world's biggest independent
software company.
   At its annual shareholders' meeting Monday, Management Science
America said its directors rejected an offer of $11.50 a share, or
$191 million, from Computer Associates.
   Wang said Computer Associates was weighing its options, but
said, ``I think if you look at our track record of acquisitions,
we're not fooling around in the game.''
   Acquisitions are responsible for a large part of the growth that
has made Computer Associates bigger than such better-known
companies as Microsoft Corp. and Lotus Development Corp.
   Management Science adjourned its annual meeting until July 12 to
give shareholders more time to think about some items on its agenda
in light of the offer from Computer Associates.
   Among the items up for a vote is a proposal that would give
directors more latitude in deciding that a potential acquirer was
unsuitable.
   Management Science specializes in financial software packages
for mainframe computers. Computer Associates sells programs for
computers of all sizes, and Wang said Management Science products
would fit well with its product line.
   Management Science reshuffled its top management earlier this
year, leading to the resignation of 12 officers, and reduced
worldwide employment by 350 people, or about 12 percent of its work
force.
   The company earned $2.4 million in the first quarter on $62.9
million in operating revenue. In 1987 it had a narrow loss of
$221,000 on revenue of $258 million.
</TEXT>
