<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that winter wheat is being
harvested, spring wheat is growing, sted reverse; picks up 3rd graf
pvs bg'ng, Indications of ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed
sharply higher Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as rain ended
in the Farm Belt and drought fears held sway in the markets.
   Wheat futures turned in the strongest performance, with most
contracts advancing the expanded 30-cents-a-bushel daily limit. The
rally was driven by concern about further drought damage to the
spring wheat crop in the northern Great Plains and worries that
heavy rain in the central and southern Plains would hamper progress
on the winter wheat harvest, analysts said.
   Indications of new wheat export business also supported wheat
futures, said Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research Department Inc.
in Chicago.
   Some oat and soybean contracts also posted limit gains, and
prices for July delivery of all grains and soybeans were allowed to
soar freely. The exchange removed limits on the July contracts
Wednesday in a routine action linked to their upcoming expiration.
   The National Weather Service's 30-day outlook, issued Wednesday
after the close of trading, was a major bullish factor, analysts
said.
   ``They're calling for almost no rainfall from Illinois east to
Ohio and higher-than-normal temperatures in Iowa, Illinois and
Missouri, the three biggest soybean states,'' Karlin said. ``That's
one area that really needs rain.''
   At the close, wheat was 24{ cents to 34{ cents higher with July
at $3.88 a bushel; corn was 8} cents to 19 cents higher with July
at $3.28 a bushel; oats were 6 cents to 18 cents higher with July
at $3.53 a bushel; soybeans were 35 cents to 69 cents higher with
July at $10 a bushel.
</TEXT>
