<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Monsanto-Emissions     06-30 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Monsanto-Emissions,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Monsanto Announces Plan to Reduce Emissions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Monsanto Co. plans to reduce air emissions from
its worldwide hazardous chemicals operations by 90 percent over the
next five years, the company announced Thursday.
   Monsanto Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Richard J. Mahoney
said at a news conference that the company was making the move even
though its current emission levels are well within safety
guidelines.
   ``The best scientific and medical data available indicate that
the emissions we are reporting (to the Environmental Protection
Agency) do not pose a health risk in our plant communities,''
Mahoney said. ``However, the public expects no less than a maximum
effort to reduce emissions, nor should we.''
   Monsanto has nearly 50 plants worldwide, with 30 of them in the
United States.
   Hal Corbett, Monsanto's senior vice president for safety and
health, said the program's target date for completion is Dec. 31,
1992.
   ``At present,'' Corbett said, ``we have the technology in hand
to achieve a portion of the 1992 target. The rest must come from as
yet undeveloped technologies, which we intend to find and put into
practice.''
   Because the technology does not yet exist, Corbett said, there
was no way to put a price tag on the program.
   ``But right now we are spending $200 million each year'' on
pollution control, he said.
   The company also estimated its three chemical plants in the St.
Louis area combined to produce 4.4 million pounds of air emissions
in 1987. The EPA requires companies to report their emissions
annually by July 1.
   ``The emissions numbers may sound large, since they're being
reported in annual totals,'' said Dr. Barry Friedlander, Monsanto's
director of medical and health sciences. ``But even in the areas
closest to our plants, emissions are well within the limits
considered safe.''
</TEXT>
