<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     06-30 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Fell $1.93 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 440 money market mutual
funds fell $1.93 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The decline, to $264.36 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a revised increase of $923.8 million in the
funds' assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based
mutual fund trade group.
   That increase originally was reported as $908.7 million.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 220 general purpose funds fell $390 million to $81.44
billion, assets of 98 broker-dealer funds fell $689 million to
$112.8 billion, and assets of 122 institutional funds fell $851.3
million to $70.1 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 6.62 percent from 6.56 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 6.52 percent from 6.46 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
35 days, down from 36 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts rose to 5.74 percent as of
Wednesday from 5.73 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.13 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.12
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 7.11 percent
the previous week. Yields were 7.47 percent on 1-year CDs, up from
7.45 percent; 7.84 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 7.83 percent;
and 8.26 percent on 5-year CDs, unchanged.
</TEXT>
