<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed narrowly mixed Thursday in
uneventful trading.
   Gold prices also were mixed. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted gold at $435.10 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down 20 cents
from late Wednesday.
   ``The change (in the dollar) wasn't big enough to matter,'' said
Jim Paul, director of futures research at the investment firm Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago. ``If it lost any ground, it
probably was more a reaction to the sharp gains the dollar has
had.''
   The dollar has spurted higher in recent sessions, and traders
attributed its advance to an increasing perception that the major
industrialized democracies are willing to tolerate a more expensive
U.S. currency.
   In Europe, where the dollar edged downward Wednesday, dealers
said the U.S. currency held its own despite interest rate hikes in
West Germany, Switzerland, Austria, Belgium and the Netherlands.
The increases had been expected and were already discounted,
dealers said.
   The West German central bank again sold dollars in favor of the
mark, dealers said.
   Trading was thin. Dealers noted that because Thursday was the
final day of the first half of the year, many traders had already
closed their books.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7085 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7060 late
Wednesday. In later New York trading, sterling declined against the
dollar, closing at $1.7115, compared with $1.71325 late Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.20 Japanese yen to close at 132.20
yen. Later in London it rose to 133.40 yen. In New York, the dollar
rose to 133.045 yen from 132.935 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York vs. late Wednesday included:
1.8155 West German marks, down from 1.8225; 1.5040 Swiss francs,
down from 1.51175; 6.11625 French francs, down from 6.1375;
1,344.75 Italian lire, down from 1,351.00; and 1.21305 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.21475.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe vs. late Wednesday included:
1.8170 West German marks, down from 1.8290; 1.5060 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5155; 6.1250 French francs, down from 6.1635; 2.0530
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0545; 1,350.38 Italian lire, down from
1,350.75; and 1.2126 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2173.
   Gold fell 40 cents on the Commodity Exchange in New York to
$435.30 a troy ounce.
   In earlier London trading, gold rose to a late bid price of
$436.40 a troy ounce, compared with $433.30 late Wednesday. In
Zurich, gold closed at a bid $436.50, compared with $433.50 late
Wednesday.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell 86 cents to close at a bid $439.18.
   Silver bullion rose on New York's Comex, closing at $6.676 a
troy ounce, up from $6.622 late Wednesday. Silver was unchanged on
the London market at $6.66 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
