<HEAD>Quaker State Names Corn Chief Executive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OIL CITY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quaker State Corp. named Jack W. Corn as
chief executive officer, the company said Thursday.
   Corn replaces Quentin E. Wood, who is retiring as chief
executive officer but continuing as chairman of the board, the
motor oil company said.
   Corn's appointment is in line with the transfer of top
management recommended to the board of directors at the company's
annual meeting in May.
   At that time, Corn was named president and chief operating
officer. Corn will assume his new post Friday and relinquish the
title of chief operating officer, which will no longer be in use.
   On Wednesday Ardshiel Inc., a New York investment firm, said it
withdrew its takeover offer of $695 million, or $26.50 a share, for
Quaker State.
   Dennis McCormick, an Ardshiel senior managing partner, said the
firm reviewed its options and for many reasons decided to withdraw
the offer made April 8.
