<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Coke-Soviet     06-30 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coke-Soviet,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coke Memo Says Internal Investigation Found No Wrongdoing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Co. officials are denying allegations
that the international soft drink company paid bribes to gain
access to markets in the Soviet Union.
   Coca-Cola Chairman Roberto C. Goizueta on Wednesday distributed
a memo to employees saying an internal investigation uncovered no
wrongdoing by Coke workers, said company spokesman Carlton Curtis.
   The same day, President Donald Keough confirmed that Coca-Cola
is being investigated by a federal grand jury for possible
violation of the 1977 Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, which
prohibits American companies or individuals from bribing foreigners
or political parties in order to get or keep business.
   Keough denied the allegations.
   ``The simple fact is _ and you know it _ the Coca-Cola Co. has
not, does not and will not pay bribes to Soviet officials or to
anyone else,'' Keough said in his keynote address Wednesday at an
East-West trade conference in Atlanta sponsored by Coca-Cola.
   He also said the company is ``cooperating fully with appropriate
authorities,'' and he is sure Coca-Cola will be vindicated.
   The Soviet Union's chief trade representative in the United
States, Oleg V. Kozhevnikov, was at the conference. He said he had
informed his government of the investigation but did not know
whether the Soviets would launch their own inquiry.
   Kozhevnikov, who is attached to the Soviet embassy in
Washington, said the investigation will not affect Soviet relations
with Coca-Cola.
   Coca-Cola's argreement with the Soviets calls for the company to
sell soft drink concentrate manufactured at its plant in Drogheda,
Ireland, to the Soviet Union.
   Concentrate is shipped to 11 cities in the Soviet Union where
Coke is bottled and sold, said Coke spokesman Randy Donaldson. The
Soviet Union owns the bottling plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
