<DOCNO> AP880630-0345 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-30-88 1921EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Campeau     06-30 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campeau,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DeBartolo, Campeau Plan New Shopping Centers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto CPT14</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Dollar figures are U.S. unless specified as Canadian</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Edward DeBartolo says that over the
next decade, he and his new partner Robert Campeau could be
spending more than $1 billion annually, opening as many as 10
shopping centers a year in the United States.
   The partnership, which has turned the U.S. retailing and real
estate industries on their ears, foresees the construction of five
to 10 centers a year beginning in about two years, DeBartolo told
Campeau Corp.'s annual meeting Thursday.
   ``I think he's a pretty exciting guy and he's got a lot of
guts,'' DeBartolo said of Campeau after the jam-packed meeting.
   DeBartolo, a new Campeau director, helped the Toronto-based
company complete the biggest takeover in U.S. history outside the
oil industry with the purchase in May of Federated Department
Stores Inc. for $6.6 billion.
   He loaned Campeau about $480 million for the Federated purchase
in return for more than 50 percent of his U.S. holding company,
Campeau Corp. U.S.
   Campeau, who spent part of the meeting fending off concerns
about the company's debt, said later that he and DeBartolo would
share financing for any future shopping center projects in the
United States.
   Although Campeau built his fortune in Canada, he is focusing his
attention on improving profit prospects for Federated and Allied
Stores, bought in 1986 for $3.6 billion.
   In return for a commitment to anchor new shopping malls with
prestige Allied and Federated department stores such as
Bloomingdale's, Campeau can bargain with developers for substantial
equity interests in their malls.
   That gives Campeau and DeBartolo enormous clout in mapping
shopping center development in the United States.
   ``Let's say they're uncomfortable,'' DeBartolo told reporters
when asked how competitors feel about his new partner.
   Meanwhile, the feisty Campeau, sporting a bandage on his left
hand from a squash game mishap, acknowledged that the first quarter
for the retailing industry was not good, but insisted his company's
balance sheet will be in good shape by the end of the year.
   ``We're ready and set to go,'' said a beaming Campeau. ``No one
can stop us now except ourselves.''
   Campeau President Jim Roddy said the sell-off of assets that do
not fit the company's strategy has reduced debt significantly. The
company wants to keep only key strategic properties in high-growth
centers in both the United States and Canada.
   ``It's a debt level we're comfortable with,'' Roddy said.
   The company is saddled with $3.68 billion in long-term debt and
must find ways of paying off an extra $6.2 billion in loans used to
buy Federated.
   Campeau said he expects that the sale of the profitable Ann
Taylor division of Allied Stores should be complete within 90 days,
although a buyer has not emerged.
   Campeau also plans to sell two other Federated specialty chains
_ Children's Place and Main Street _ as well as its Gold Circle
discount store chain.
   The company announced the sale of 37 properties in Ottawa for
about 100 million Canadian dollars to Toronto-based Bramalea Ltd.
this week. Earlier in June, it sold five office buildings and
shopping malls to Laing Property Corp. of Vancouver for 180 million
Canadian dollars.
   However, Campeau said the company doesn't expect to sell any
more assets in Canada. And it won't sell shopping centers in the
United States.
   ``The best part of real estate is shopping centers,'' he noted.
   Campeau sold Allied's Brooks Brothers for $750 million and the
company noted that that represented a pretax gain of $350 million
in a period of 18 months.
   The company has also cut costs by consolidating some operations
and laying off more than 3,500 employees in the United States. Last
year, it sold land holdings in southern California for $100 million.
   The company reported operating profits of $57 million on revenue
of $745 million for the first quarter ended April 30, compared with
$59 million in earnings on sales of $596 million for the three
months ended March 31, 1987.
   However, the company noted that revenue was not comparable
because of the change in the reporting period and the addition of
new stores.
</TEXT>
