<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CarrierContract     06-30 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carrier Contract,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Awards Contracts for Two Aircraft Carriers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy on Thursday announced the award of a
$2.9 billion contract for the construction of two nuclear-powered
Nimitz class aircraft carriers to Newport News Shipbuilding and Dry
Dock Co. of Newport News, Va.
   Completion of the carriers, due before June 1998, would bring
the Navy's fleet of flattops to 15.
   The Navy already is sailing four of the Nimitz class carriers,
which are the largest in the world _ 1,092 feet long and displacing
91,500 tons fully loaded.
   Two other carriers of the class, the Abraham Lincoln and the
George Washington, are under construction. The Lincoln is to be
completed by the end of next year and the Washington by the end of
1991, said Navy spokesman Lt. Brian Cullin.
   One of the two ships contracted for Thursday, the CVN-74, has
been named the John C. Stennis, after the Democratic senator from
Mississippi, and the other is so far known only as the CVN-75,
Cullin said.
   The first carrier of the class, the Nimitz, was commissioned in
1968.
   Cullin said Newport News Shipbuilding is the only shipyard in
the United States that has the capability to construct the carriers
``in the time frame required.''
</TEXT>
