<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HuntReorganization     06-30 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hunt Reorganization,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hunts' Trust Estates, Creditors Agree To $750 Million Repayment
Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The billionair Hunt brothers' estates and creditor
banks have agreed on a $750 million payment plan to settle lawsuits
over bank debts held by the Hunts' Penrod Drilling Co., the estates
announced Thursday.
   In addition, a reorganization plan for the foundation of the
Hunt brothers wealth, Placid Oil Co., ``is just around the
corner,'' according to Tom Whitaker, vice president of Hunt Energy
Corp.
   A bankruptcy reorganization plan filed with U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Harold Abramson's court would resolve all issues surrounding
the loans to Penrod by First Chicago, Citicorp, and Manufacturers
Hanover Trust, said Whitaker.
   It also would bring the Hunt trust estates, which own Penrod in
partnership, out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from creditors.
   Under the agreement, the banks would get a conditional 50
percent ownership interest in Penrod, the world's biggest
independent offshore oil-drilling company, subject to purchase by
the Hunts.
   Penrod and its sister company, Placid Oil Co., sued 23 of their
lenders for fraud and misrepresentation in 1986 after defaulting on
$1.5 billion in bank loans. Two of the banks since have been
dropped from the case.
   The suit alleged that the banks conspired to drive Penrod and
Placid out of business by forcing them to agree to an unreasonable
payment schedule while offering their competitors more favorable
terms.
   In August 1986, the trust estates of William Herbert, Nelson
Bunker and Lamar Hunt filed Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection for
the trust partnership that owns Penrod Drilling. Penrod itself was
not under bankruptcy court protection.
   Placid also is in Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization, and for
now will continue pursuing claims against its 16 banks involving
$773.3 million in loans.
   Under the consensual plan filed Thursday, bank creditors will
receive a $50 million payment and a $500 million secured note from
Penrod Drilling. The banks also will receive a 50 percent interest
in the company, which is subject to purchase by the trust estates.
   In addition, some trust real estate will be transferred to the
banks subject to a $200 million purchase option.
   When the reorganization is complete, the trust estates would be
released from prior liability to their bank creditors. The banks,
trust estates and individual members of the Hunt family also would
drop claims and counter claims stemming from the bank loans.
   ``When approved by the court, this plan by the trust estates and
their bank creditors settles all issues surrounding the bank loans
to Penrod Drilling Corp....'' the Hunt estates said in a statement.
   Whitaker said the agreement would not affect the day-to-day
operation of Penrod.
   Whitaker said there was no timetable to the repayment plan. He
said the plan must gain bankruptcy court approval, but said that
since both sides of the dispute agree to it, he foresees no
difficulties.
   Bank creditors and trustees have been negotiating a plan to
repay the outstanding debt since 1986.
   Penrod employs about 2,300 workers and will have revenue of more
than $250 million this year, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
