<HEAD>Greyhound Sells Two Regional Lines; Completes U.S. Intercity Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greyhound Corp., once the nation's largest
intercity bus company, completed its withdrawal from such U.S.
operations on Thursday with sale of two regional lines, Greyhound
announced.
   Greyhound said it has sold Vermont Transit Co. Inc. and Texas,
New Mexico & Oklahoma Coaches Inc. to GLI Holding Co. of Dallas,
the company that bought Greyhound Lines Inc. last year.
   Terms of the latest transaction weren't disclosed.
   Greyhound continues to operate Greyhound Lines of Canada Ltd.
   Vermont Transit provides service in several New England states.
Texas, Neew Mexico & Oklahoma Coaches provides service over a
3,500-mile route in the Southwest.
