<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     06-30 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allegheny International,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company, Dissidents Reach Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. and a dissident
shareholder group that failed to take control of the company's
13-member board in a proxy fight agreed Thursday to stop their
legal wrangling.
   Attorneys for Allegheny International and Spear Leeds & Kellogg,
a New York brokerage house that led the effort to gain control of
the consumer products company's board, announced the settlement
Thursday to Chief Bankruptcy Judge Joseph Cosetti.
   The agreement came after several hours of negotiations between
Spear Leeds and Allegheny International, which is reorganizing
under Chapter 11 bankruptcy law protection.
   Allegheny International agreed to drop its claim that a comittee
of equity shareholders led by Spear Leeds had no right to engage in
the proxy fight. It also agreed to drop a motion seeking removal of
Spear Leeds from the committee.
   The shareholders committee agreed to drop a motion seeking to
disqualify Buchanan Ingersoll as legal counsel for Allegheny
International over alleged conflicts of interest.
   The settlement was negotiated after it became apparent Allegheny
International retained control of its board, according to
preliminary results released by Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.,
the proxy contest judge.
   Preliminary results indicated the Spear Leeds group won five of
the company's 13 board seats. Two of Allegheny International's
nominees, including Chairman Oliver S. Travers, were elected to the
board. The company's chief operating officer, Thomas Albani, was
not re-elected.
</TEXT>
